text: smells of citrus..and formaldahyde .  pours very dark brown with a large very foamy light brown head that leaves tons of drippy lacing and holds a nice rocky island and cap .  somewhat thin but more close to medium .

no smell , no taste but a little sugar and so heavily carbonated that by the time i finnished i wanted to do a barney gumble-style burp .  appearance & gt ; yellow , lively . lovely .  it is slightly watery on the palate .

i love the smell of this beer ... i smell molasses with hints of toffee ... nice maltiness . mouthfeel is very good . great esb !  impressive looking beer .  m - some carbonation , not much to speak of .

the smell was magnificent , and like i said i wish it had been in a snifter to catch more of these floral and citrusy aromas . outstanding .  a-pitch black , perfect darkness . burnt and bitter , with black licorice .  lowish carbonation and a light , smooth mouthfeel .

smells very sweet , what you 'd expect . perfect for dessert or a nightcap .  beautiful fucking color .  i had this beer at the great waters facility as we stop in often . i try to take notes on the beers i try but sometimes forget . the attack was very smooth and there was a sweet and smooth flavor with faint hops character at the finish . i do n't think i have had any cask beers at great waters that i did n't like .

very very nice . very complex .  in a tulip the beer was near black in color with a light brown head . the head lingered well , and left abundant lace .  m : gritty and more astringent than any brown ale i 've ever tasted , very porterish feel .

it 's a good inviting smell .  from tower liquor a - a deep reddish-copper pour , slightly hazy , with a great fluffy , off-white head with good retention and lacing .  too much carbonation for this style ( -1.0 ) .

smell- figs ! drinkability- deciptively drinkable , i could finish up this bottle in a hurry and then find out that it 's 10 % abv afterward . nice .  a - dark maroon with lots of capuccino colored head .  this beer was purchased at cyclone liquors , in ames , iowa . the beer was very dark in color and tasted very well . i drank the beer warm and i think it was a good beer . i would try this beer again if it was presented to me . it had a very nice sweet taste for a german dunkel , which i am not a huge fan of .

smell was quite nice though , a great mix of wheaty goodness and raspberries .  pours a dark reddish brown with a huge off white head with huge fat lacing .  m-explosive carbonation . tough to gauge the feel over the bubbles . a bit too carbonated for me .

my favorite part of the beer was the aroma . it had this very intense chocolaty smell that while sipping was very pleasing to the senses .  pours a cloudy yellow with amazing white head that stays through out the whole glass .  light copper color with a large head s. malty with a slight resiny hop smell t. more bitter than sweet but well balanced with roasted malt m. a little to acidic and carbonated for my tastes d. a good lighter amber ale that i can heartily recommend

s-couldnt smell much , probably my fault . what i got was a malty caramel like aroma .  a : pitch black , slightly viscous . excellent head formation and nice lacing . this is how an ais should look in the glass .  pretty weak mouthfeel , it 's a bit watery . i 'm enjoying the flavour and aroma quite a bit but the mouthfeel is a bit weak . but lacking in mouthfeel .

s - great smell . dark fruits such as raisins and plums maybe . o - good over all .  pours with an outrageously massive head , a dense , simmering mass of eggshell brown rising over the rim of the goblet like a souffle . what a visual feast !  the feel had decent carbonation , if only it had n't been followed by a lingering metallic feel on the tongue .

wow , one of the best smelling old ales i 've ever smelled . as it warms up so many different smells come out , yet it stays balanced . i thought this beer smelled amazing and was very complex and balanced . while the taste was a step down and a tiny disappointment after the smell , it was still very good . i thought it also had an amazing mouthfeel and while definitely a sipper , the abv is well hidden .  $ 5.00 / 750ml bottle county market grocery store stevens point , wisconsin appearance - a haze of golden yellow to a pale orange with a lasting frothy white head . very much carbonated as a constant flow of tiny bubbles speed to the top if the beer from the side and bottom of the pint glass .  m. a bit acidic d. overall a nice iipa .

the powerful blast of cherry and almond aroma is all i get out of this beer . the beer , sadly , does not live up to the overwhelming cherry aroma .  the pour is beautiful . intense rich brown/black , with a two finger dark brown head .  m/d - a little sticky but the body is still thin and it feels appropriate for the style .

a : pours a cloudy orange color with good frothy white head , good lacing down the glass s : smell is awesome , smells fruity ( apple/pear ) , good spiciness in there as well . m : light to medium bodied , dry finish d : very refreshing , complex smelling and tasting beer .  had a gorgeous impenetrable chestnut coloration , massive amounts of creeping carbonation , and a thick , creamy off-white head that displayed amazing retention .  m & d - the brew is a tiny bit watery , the doughy character is a tiny bit too small , and so the mouthfeel is n't as full as i 'd expect .

beautiful smell of bourbon it 's you first then caramel , vanilla , and a hint of oak .  quite surprising ... not because it 's a great beer from dogfish head ( that 's certainly not surprising ) , but because i have never actually enjoyed a pumpkin ale . seriously ever . appearance & gt ; what a beauty . colour reads from dark honey to a pumpkin orange glow . extremely lively .  mouthfeel is a little too carbonated and light but i still enjoyed the beer in-spite of those tow minor complaints .

the nose on this one is about a mile deep . i get tons of nutmeg , chai tea , cinnamon , vanilla , ginger snap best describes the aroma . i ca n't stop smelling it . most , if not all the aromatic qualities come through on the palate . very creamy and spicey . overall the drinkability is good . great aroma , great flavor and mouthfeel .  poured into a fluted pilsner glass , this czech pils showed an exceptional ability to form a stiff , meringue-like , rocky head of foam . retention was great , lasting for the duration of the glass , leaving irregular clumps of foam on the way down .  and this is a surprisingly warming , earthy-tasting beverage for a `` summer ale '' -- i would n't mind opening up one of these in midwinter either , except in that it lacks body . it 's in the mouthfeel that the summeriness stands out .

smell is amazing ! nice and sweet and very hoppy . very appealing and aromatic . a very good blonde .  pours a hazy golden color , with a huge fluffy white head . what a sight , as the head rose easily above the rim of the glass , and held there like an ice cream cone for a lengthy period of time .  medium bodied and a bit sticky in the mouth .

s : faint toasted grains and earthy heath . t : toasted malts much more pronounced that aroma ; chocolate , lightly burnt toffee and bitter coffee . disappointed in the nose , but a good stout past that .  black as the deepest parts of the ocean with some overcast fluffy 1 inch mocha colored head that fades at a good pace .  the first time i had this beer , i distinctly remember it being among the worst i had ever had . apparently my ba colleagues disagree , so i 'm giving it another try . there is some faint grassy hops , but this beer is mostly about the malt character . overall , this is way better than i remember . i might have to make this a regular part of my beer fridge ! or perhaps they had n't figured things out when the brewery was just getting started . glad that there 's another quality beer in e-town .

stunning rich and assertive peach and banana nose . unfortunately , flavor , character and body do not follow . however , nothing in body , flavors or character could lead one to conclude that aging will help this dull , simple and short flavored beer with a fantastic nose . smell it ; do n't drink it .  tasted june 22nd 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - a clear blood red , one finger tan head and some lacing s - alcohol , wine barrels , sweet dried fruits , earth , oak , french vanilla and more sweet and alcohol t - alcohol , lots of sugar , sweet malts , tons of sweet dried fruit , black cherries , wine barrels , raisins , charred oak , molasses , carmelised brown sugar and vanilla .  more carbonation would go a long way .

s : i thought i died and went to heaven the first time i smelled this beer . caramel and toffee aromas dominate with some hints of berries .  looks perfect . mounds of off white maybe pretty much light tan head , and has a clear dark copper colored body .  s - some grassy hops paired with caramel malt t - slight hop bitterness resolving into some serious roasty malt , but then it 's all gone fairly quickly with just a hint of woody bitterness m - quite light with just a hint of carbonation on the back of the tongue ; the slight bitterness endures for a whlie d - quick drinkable , though the excessive roasty malt will probably get in the way ; little to no alcohol warmth nice drink ; did n't expect it to be as dark as it is - listed as an american porter , but it 's almost a supercharged brown ale .

the smell is truly incredible , and the taste is malty and pleasant .  this is hands down the most beautiful looking beer i have ever seen . the head retention is pretty amazing and the lacing extensive .  m : very smooth , but seems pretty thin in terms of the body of the beer .

a nice white head , great retention and lacing ... the aroma is fantastic , so fresh , just plucked pine needles with pineapples and an assortment of tropical fruits ... taste is equally great , bitting pine and alcohol of a dipa , but muted and so drinkable .  pours a nice bright yellow orange with a massive , almost overflowing white head . head sticks around indefinitely as bubbles continually rise in an energetic fashion .  mouthfeel was average .

s - great smelling ! lots of nice fruit and hoppy deliciousness . overall , a fantastic beer . it 's odd that it 's an amber , as it tastes a lot like an ipa .  pours out a beautiful amber color with a wonderful fluffy white head .  mouthfeel : a bit thin and watery .

wonderful aroma . perfect to style taste : bland .  a- caramel amber beer , nice dark coloration , super huge head with sticky lacing .  i first had this beer a year ago and fell in love . so i was excited to see it appear once again this fall . i find it a very easy beer to drink even for the inexperienced beer drinker . flavorful and rich with malts , a slight hint of hops towards the end . the aroma is sweet but not overpowering , you can definitely smell the sweet malt that went into this brew . i highly recommend this beer . unfortunately its not around year round but it definitely will give you something to look forward to come fall .

s : the nose is awesome . coffee . just so much going on .  bomber bought at total wine a - dark black , 2 fingered head , dissipates slow and leaves a nice lacing .  had to give it the maximum points for appearance , because even out of an imported bottle , it looks just right . comes in with an alcohol bite that 's almost like an imperial . pertty nice taste , though , and if you had some , i would n't refuse .

750ml bottle with cork , like their local series . smells of the local 1 , champagne , cork , lemon meringue or orange marmalade , some tropical fruits or pina colada , wet vegetation . surprisingly , i taste the hop in the flavor more than the aroma . a unique hop . corky . kudos for making a dry and hoppy saison , and getting it to texas ! worth trying .  a - beautiful amber body with intense white huge head and sheets of lacing remaining for an insane amount of time .  this is pretty good , but not up to the level of most other weihenstephaner beers in my book . the aroma is raisiny and alcoholic with grapes , dry grain , hint of bread , honeym , pine , herbs , and hay . the taste is bread , herbs , pine , faint hints of honey , apple and lemon , with a tingly pine-herb flavour and bitterness , along with a faintly rough , thin mineral-water quality . it goes pretty well with food and is fairly easily drinkable , but not great .

* subtle but complex aromas of dark chocolate , ripe cherries , sour fruits , currants , figs , beer bread and burnt sugar . taste is not as complex as the smell , and almost underwhelming with more dark chocolate notes , unripened dark fruits ( plums , grapes ) grain and yeast .  bottle into a pils glass pours a clear , deep copper orange with a one and a half inch off-white head which holds up well throughout from lots of carbonation release . it also leaves some nice looking sheets of lacing down the sides of the glass . ca n't ask for a better looking beer .  this is an excellent pilsner . number three on my list , only behind konig and pilsner urquell . just as crisp and refreshing as both of those , but a little lighter in taste and body . very clean , top quality .

s : holy hops ! strong citrus and pine hop aroma , sweet and fruity , not very bitter smelling . t : follows the nose , tropical fruit and citrus hops dominate , followed by piney flavors . o : this beer gives me a rock-solid .  had this at a recent ba gathering at milly 's , and brought a growler home . this is a beautiful beer : as black as can be , with a thick coffee-colored head .  this is a great light summer ale from pike brewing . this could be a great crossover ale for the bmc drinkers . it is very light yellow and clear . head is white light and fluffy , overall a great light easy drinking als . this is a beer that everyone will like .

aroma is very fruit dominated , and not by any single one . peach , lemon , starfruit , lime , mango ... it 's an intoxicating tropical melange . some contrasting oak and fresh yogurt notes are there too , lending some harmonizing 'wild ' elements without getting too funky . flavor is moderately puckering , tart and verging on lemony sour . hop elements are present though indistinct in the mix , lending some possible leafy orange tea notes , and residual bitterness .  poured black , with clear mahogany highlights , with a large mostly lasting light brown frothy head with good lacing .  smell : uh oh , something is going wrong ... taste : blecchhh . my stomach is starting to turn . what happened to this beer ? simply put , the taste is sour and offensive . beef notes : horrible . what was the thought process when putting this beer out for sale ?

smells wonderful . cloves , banana , caramel , fruitiness . nice comfortable warmth from the alcohol . not something i could see drinking a ton of at a sitting , but delightful as a one off .  a - black , inch and half of tawny head . leaves amazing lacing that should be in a museum as art .  the mouthfeel was a bit watery which could be due to the fact it is only 4.8 % and thus not alot of malt was apparently used , but i think it held up well over time , although i have not tried this fresh so i can not compare .

refreshing , quite complex , and just the right temperate on the citrus .  giant billowing white head . the dense creamy , soapy head leaves giant lacey patches and a tantalizing heavy layer for the duration . color is a thickly hazey amber red with a big old carbonation tornado at the center .  good carb , but feels a bit thin and watered down in general .

it smells awesome , everything works together and you get something else every whiff no issues here t much more booze then the nose , more toffee , smoke , and fruit with some burnt brown sugar , still very nice but without as much balance m enters silky then the bubbles make it feel creamy , quite thick and the flavors linger , the heat lingers too and that 's my only complaint in this area o for a big fresh barley wine i thought it was pretty good , the barrel agings there but not overpowering and its oh so mellow i was hoping this one would suck so i would n't need to buy a couple of them to age , pretty expensive but this would be amazing after some time , pretty mellow considering the 13.8 % fresh i can only imagine this 5 years down the road  2009 vintage a- deep violet , crimson red just a beautiful awe-inspiring color and massive towering head that seems to be independent of the beer and an entity all onto itself .  the carbonation is surprisingly strong for the style .

t- very very nice . lots of chocolate & lots of coffee .  appearance : pours a beautiful hazy dark amber color with a finger of foamy off white head that leaves a little bit of lacing and good retention .  m good medium body , with a lot of carbonation , either takes away from this beer .

s : pumpkin pie baby ! very nice . t : pumpkin spice , clove , nutmeg and caramel from the malts .  pours a very dark reddish brown color with a very nice looking 2 finger slightly tan head that does n't seem to want to go down !  i think that the long trip from greece to williamsburg , va did n't treat this beer too kindly . pours and looks like the standard heine-clone . taste was rather flat .

the nose is beautiful . i get the belgian yeastiness , and something akin to peaches served with a dash of allspice . so far it 's awesome .  appearance - jet black in color with a very nice one finger light tan head that lingers while drinking . perfect for keeping in the flavor and smell of the beer smell - very light on the malt smell , but somewhat heavy on the bitter hops .  the mouth was a bit oily but not unpleasantly so .

( s ) - very aromatic . very dynamic & layered . again , a good taste that followed suit to the smell . great aroma . lends itself more to a better drinkability score due to a lower abv than alot of strong ales out there ; thicker than most too , but it fits it well . this might benefit from further aging , but its great now .  hazy blond in color with a steady stream of bubbles rising from the bottom of the glass to form a huge , thick , rocky white head that lasts for the entire glass .  smooth , nice , a little thin maybe . not a ton of carbonation at the end which leaves it a little watery .

upon opening the bottle you receive a pleasant aroma and on pouring the smell is obviously even more intense . the mouthfeel is actually kind of weak and bitter , surprisingly , given the pleasant look and smell of this beer .  a-pours a slightly clear copper/amber color with lots of thick white head that leaves outstanding lacing .  mouf & gt ; average drinkability & gt ; great ! more beers to add to the breakfast menu at my house .

aroma is the best part . lots of grapefruit and citrus . tons of hop aroma . taste is great . tons of hops . reminds me of hop slam a bit . mouthfeel is good . overall an awesome beer that i 'm going to want another growler of .  appearance : pitch black . very dark head .  good coffee and chocolate and malt ( ate a small piece of oreo birthday cake with this and it was damn near orgasmic ) mouthfeel is surprisingly thin .

s - impressive ! i 've smelled hoppy beers from a few feet away , but this has a spicy malt boozy smell that almost fills a room when the the bottle is uncapped .  pours nicely for a two finger thick tan head , and has a copper colored well filtered body .  smoky , malty and mildy coffee-like . deep black with a thumb thick mocha head . fore is hoppy bitter then roasted barley malt follows . very much in the fullers vein as opposed to the more roasty and coffee/chocolate flavored american porters . very nice brew .

s : the bouquet is quite vibrant , with grapefruit and pineapple jumping out of the glass .  appearance : poured a nice , thick dark tan head which persisted nicely . color is very dark brown -- pretty much opaque .  mouthfeel : thin yet flavorful .

grapefruit ! my favorite aroma in beer and life for some strange reason , but enough about me ... .once i break from my grapefruit coma , i do notice pine and a little lemon rind in the background t - there is that damn grapefruit again , i just ca n't get away from it . immense hop flavor with a surprising amount of malt that finds its way through the hops .  absolutley perfect looking beer .  a bit watery at the start , but , it gradually gains weight as it rolls to the back of the palate .

vanilla , oak , maple leaf , faint rum aroma , and most of all ooey gooey caramel - sort of like a caramello bar . t : bittersweet chocolate layered with oaky and vanilla flavors , a caramel filling , and a coffee finish . i would even go as far to say this was luxurious or elegant .  pours an opaque black with a creamy tan head that retains well and laces the glass .  m - kind of watery , but good carbonation .

not a big fan of this one , but it 's drinkable . i expect more of a fruit profile if the fruit is in the name . sweet and low bitterness , perhaps a bit too sweet .  a - scotch / almond color . beautiful head with great lace .  poured chilled in large ale glass ; bottle courtesy buzzlitebeer a : dark chocolate colored ; good frothy head ; decent carb action s : chicory and ( what ? ) tobacco predominates ; musty coffee t : wow , unusual ; the brown ale is a base for experimentation into coffee and tobacco ; bitter cacao serve this to friends and you 'll definitely have a talking point ; it 's very distinctive

poured into a chimay goblet.. well , the name does n't lie ... this is a pitch black with a creamy but small head ... laces unbelievably though.. this almost has an ris look to it with its perceived thickness.. this has one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced ... it has all of the aspects of a great stout with an added extra of smokiness that reminds me of a nice thick cut bacon ... it 's just wonderful ... it 's loaded with roasted malts and i might even get a little touch of hops here as well.. just magnificent ... very rich roasted flavors here ... loads of dark roasted malts with that smoke that i was getting in the aromas mix wonderfully with a tinge of hops on the finish ( although not much ) ... there 's a thickness to this that belies the export stout style.. i would guess ris or double stout all the way here ... there 's a meatiness here as well that i would assume comes from the smoke.. it 's a nice brew , i know that.. i 'm really digging it ... i 'm very glad i got to enjoy this brew.. it 's loaded with rich dark flavors and the aromas here are ridiculously delicious.. the whole experience was terrific.. very nice export stout.. very drinkable although at 8.5 , it could hurt you quick ...  poured into a tall glass , pours a cloudy almost two tone fire red color . genuinely impressive , that i have never seen something like this before .  m : a little thin on the body , and surprisingly light and spiky with the carbonation .

smell is so awesome . the belgian yeast esters mixed with the hoppyness of the ipa is out of this world . probably one of the nicest beers i have smelled . it smells better than it tastes . it 's a very good beer but i like the smell of it alot better .  this brew pours a very large head of creamy fine light brown bubbles and opaque black brown body .  mouthfeel seemed a bit to lean to me .

smell is beautifully complex & bright , like i just walked into an herb garden : really picking up on the rosemary , floral notes that are big but gentle , something kind of savory like oregano , maybe some basil or mint notes in there . seriously , this is fantastic , i do n't think i 've ever smelled a beer like it .  appearance : great stout , dark brown color with a coffee colored head .  the body is on the thin side , with below-average carbonation .

the aroma is a very nice rich creamy milk chocolate . the best part of this beer is that the aroma is so strong , it is a major component of the beer even while drinking the last swallow . nice feeling coming out of a bottle .  a nice amber color with a thick tan head . lace was thick and copious .  this beer has a flavor i really like m- pretty thin and bubbly , almost reminds me of a bmc feel o- one of my favorite tasting pale ales .

s : wonderful nose . toasted notes with some malt character hiding behind it .  absolutely pitch black from the middle of the fluted part down , with a gorgeous caramel brown cascading head up to the rim . excellent head retention and nice lacing . held directly in front of a bright bulb , no light passed through the pour .  the body of the beer is actually approaching medium and the carbonation is not overly fizzy as many macros are .

the closest thing to bourbon county stout ive ever smelled . a wonderful nose of raisins , oak , vanilla , bourbon , chewy chocolate , cocoa , rum , and god knows what else . it seems there are citrus hops that are mixing without dropping a beer with the malt and creating this rather sweet fruity start . finishing with bourbon and a touch of alcohol bite . overall im pretty happy with this beer . huge thanks to crushedvol for this extra .  as the beer was going down in the glass , it left an incredible , thick creamy lacing all over the glass . appearance was pretty cloudy , light copper color .  the only detraction i can fin is the below average body .

aroma is brilliant and vibrant , full of citrus hops and apricot . nice .  a : forms a nice 1.5 finger frothy head in my sa perfect pint glass with very good retention . it 's a crystal clear beer with varying colors , being auburn orange at the thinner parts and ruby red at the thicker , and a good amount of bubbles floating up from the etch at the bottom . perfect appearance at least .  taste : sweet malt , raisins , a lot of sweet nutty flavors like pecans , sour/tart dark cherry flavor , ending with a nutty malt characters mouthfeel : really light body , low carbonation , pretty basic .

brett funkiness shows its face , but is n't as prominent as in others from similar varieties . like the smell , the brett funkiness is more subtle than others .  poured a slightly cloudy , amber to copper color with . nice frothy two finger off white lasting head . ample lacing cling to the glass .  as readily available as bud , and a whole lot better . a great fall-back session brew , which is good with a meal , or having several at a baseball game .

the smell really impressed me with the strong clove scent like a cooling pie .  heading was awesome , big , white and fluffy , with many tiny air bubbles racing toward the head .  nice carbonation , but this comes off as a little thin . this should be more drinkable considering its thin body , but as this is a stout , the thin body is a bit of a turn off .

the aroma of this beer is amazing ! hops hops and more hops ! very deep and complex . citrus , spice , pine ... but not much of the barley makes it through . wow this is hoppy !  a : bright red with an even keel of carbonation rising to fluffy beige head . gorgeous head does n't waver for a moment .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is quite sharp ; a bit fizzier than i 'd like .

citrus ( grapefruit ) - yes , strong and good , wow . apricot flavor notes .  this is the dead-on look for a pilsner ; pale straw color with steady streams of bubbles heading for the surface . the head is huge and sticky and clings to the side of the glass as if it were a life-or-death matter .  tastes pretty amazing really . watery on the tongue but ends dryish .

granted it does taste better to the good ol ' american bud light ! becks has an awful smell to it !  pours a lager-yellow , huge creamy white head that dissipates down to a film leaving very much lace . nice looking beer .  it was also a little to carbonated for me in the mouth feel category .

fruity nose classic ipa ( not the barleywine as is sometimes said ) .  a bottle exceptionally beautiful . so , for large qualities , almost everything .  a little lighter and less sweet than many `` real '' belgian beers , and a little thinner in the mouthfeel department .

decent lacing left behind . s - wow , great aroma here . immediately there is a lot of pineapple and coconut aroma making it clear that this has been barrel aged . lots of stuff going on here .  ( a great place ) poured a wonderfully rich yellow color . it was cloudy with a half inch of creamy white head . nice lacing with this beer .  mouthfeel was a little thin , that 's my only complaint .

n : this is a beautiful , mouthwatering nose . smells very close to liquid pumpkin pie .  appearance : pours a crystal clear dark orange color with a huge 3 '' + fluffy head that lasts a long time .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and harsh from the acidity and carbonation . also finishes quite dry with little to no bitter .

beer also appeared to be quite carbonated smell : hot-day-amn . the smell of this one is trump tight . the eastern spices are like aroma therapy . those clove-ish spices blend with the hops and a sweet fruit scent to create an enticing aroma . taste : from the second this one hits your lips you just know that this is an `` americanized '' tripel .  visually stunning with a clear red-amber hue , plentiful off-white head and lace , and carbonation bubbles that seem to be in slow motion as they rise to the surface .  an e-mail from the brewery indicated that twins lager is not the same beer as hauenstein , just with a different label . schells tells me that the twins lager uses a different recipe and yeast than the hauenstein , but a side by side comparison leaves me wondering why they would go through the trouble . i have always liked `` cheap '' beers . the beer drinkers of olden days wanted it cold , crisp , and cheap . but for afternoon lazing back and swigging , there is certainly nothing wrong with a cold bottle of twins lager . twins lager might be `` twice as refreshing '' as the label purports , but , boy would it be a treat to drink an original recipe fitgers again !

what struck me first is the aroma , very rich with a mix of floral tones and sweet caramel . lace forms readily on the inside of the glass and a thin layer of head is always prevalent . the mouthfeel is particularly noteworthy , and every swig leaves a viscous coating of robust barley goodness on the tongue . many have complained about the drinkability , but i find that the 9 % abv is well disguised by the complexity of this well-rounded brew . even if you do n't take to this beer as i have , read up on the intriguing history behind the name of this brew , and perhaps convince some die hard minions of mass-marketed swill to see the merits of expecting more from a beer .  pours a rich opaque sable with a fine-bubbled light tan head .  mouthfeel is somewhat disappointing . if we 're talking about banana bread here , then it should be thicker , like bread .

the aroma is skunky with a malt presence that is not pleasant . what it lacks in smell it makes up for in taste .  hopefully since it appears to be bottle conditioned that the beer is still holding up a - poured into goblet an opaque black color . fluffy inch tall light brown head that disapates into a tinner covering that lasts until the end .  it is a bit thin , bordering on watery with adequate to slightly low carbonation .

smells like cooked veggies that were slightly rotten . quite possibly one of the worst smelling beers i 've encountered . light mouthfeel makes this one go down easy , but the smell hurts the drinkability .  pours up a beautiful grapefruit color with a very thin white head .  the mouthfeel was thin with a slightly dry aftertaste .

s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  a : poured perfectly . nice pinkish , beige head with a good retention and very good lacing for this style .  bittersweet finish . kind of think and syrupy on the palate .

just plainly delicious as hell . goddamn , what a insanely alluring nose . on the palate , the dark grains come to the fore , with a rich roasted character , leavening to a light burnt cacao husk note .  a-pours a pitch black color with a finger and a half tan head .  a surprisingly great beer from a brewing giant . it could have been a little less punishing when guzzled , but hey it 's a dark beer and we are not dealing with coors light here . i think the beer is buitiful to look at , and is rather smooth . but the lable and beer fit perfectly ph

s = this had me hoping . smell was very sweet and inviting . nice fruity ( plum , prune maybe ?  the black body of this brew is topped by a medium thick , brown head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  m - a little water , but it goes down smoothly d - this is a really good beer .

it smelled like feet to me , a little bit skunky .  poured a 355 ml bottle , dated 15 nov 2007 , into a tulip . a : poured a massive 1.5 fingered creamy head , in a tulip this appears huge . the color is a glorious tawny . the carbonation is rising nicely in the glass and it seems as if the head is hardly going anywhere .  a little too thick on the tongue , but nice .

s : this smells like heaven . endless raspberries , need i say more . it 's not as good as the legendary new glarus raspberry tart , but this beer is certainly fun and tastes great .  black as the abyss with a dark sticky head .  m : upper light body with high carbonation .

smells wonderful ! t - flavor is a bit subdued , really disappointing after such an amazing nose . more tart cherry , with flavors of brown sugar , vinegar , tobacco , and high quantities of oak .  pours a deep , opaque blood red with a really pretty cotton candy , rosy head that settled into a soapy haze .  in my opinion , flying dog brewery has created a great seasonal , smooth-tasting beer with very little bite or after taste . i would definitely recommend it to any self-respecting beer drinker who might be having an end-of-summer party this or any october .

the aroma was very fresh , like a breeze on a river , ( stunning ! ) floral hops and hints of citrus along with caramel malt ; a sweet and inviting blend . muted orange rind , grapefruit notes and a doughy malt/yeast blend were present but the bitterness that sat atop them i found unpleasant .  a : my antonia pours a lovely straw/amber hue and is marked by a monstrous head of the consistency of whipped egg whites . definitely appealing ... .  mouthfeel is sticky-sweet and dense .

the smell is amazing . it gets me first on the sides of my tongue .  a- pours dark black . one of the prettiest beers i 've seen .  m : mouthfeel is decent , goes down reasonable smooth even with the slight burning sensation .

it had a very beautiful aroma of dried fruit and alcohol . almost wine like to the nose , and was enjoyed by everyone i offered it to .  pours an absolutely gorgeous dark cola body that illuminates to a caramel-amber when held to the light . creamy , light tan bubbles form a sizable froth on top and slowly settle to a thick veil of foam , thanks in part to a vigorous carbonation level .  the mouthfeel is very fizzy due to the ample carbonation .

aroma is exceptional , with a great sweet citrus smell that bursts from the bottle and makes you want to take a huge gulp . this is n't a horrible beer , and if you love bitterness , you should love it .  pours very dark brown color with a 2.5 finger dense tan head with incredible retention , with some very nice lacing on the glass .  4.5 m - lacks body . a bit thin but spritzy carbonation .

aroma of roast , ash , chocolate , dried fruits , vanilla , bourbon , caramel malts , and alcohol . taste of dark fruit , some tropical , sticky molasses , roasted malts , vanilla , and bourbon - alcohol .  glass : chimay goblet temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees bottling date : 04-23-08 pours an exceptional clear golden amber color . minimal head that retains a light lacing all the way down .  m : the body is not as thick as i was expecting . it on the thin side as far as stouts go , but drinks very smoothly . i would have liked a thicker body , but that 's just being picky .

aroma of spruce and tiger lillies . supremely floral . this is not the aroma of your average triple . this beer could be marketed as liquid potpourri , and i 'd be proud to buy a lame plug-in air freshener that smelled like this . certainly , all the qualities are there .  perfect head retention & lacing s : slight hops aroma t : some fruittyness up front .  smell is of old corn/rice and skunk . pew . taste was horrendous . a skunky malt liquor flavor mixed with sweet rice/corn adjunct . maybe it went bad on it 's journey from the carib-bean ? looks like i should have gone for the sam light that was also in the fridge ...

two brothers heavy handed ipa : terrific aroma , very full and noticeable from several feet away . some heavy malt syrup aromas coupled with flowery hops make the aroma very appetizing . slick mouth feel .  the brew itself is a spectacular amber-orange color that is crystal clear . the head dissipates to a constant quarter-finger thickness with excellent lacing all the way down . while it has a fantastic appearance , everything else is only slightly above average ( for microbrews ) .  the palate is average .

wow ... the nose on this is excellent ! tons of roasted malts , coffee beans and dark chocolate . very nice ... the taste is n't quite as profound as the nose , but it holds up well . i am really glad i had the chance to try it ... after all , it has been on my wants list for some time .  browning 's bourbon barrel imperial stout pours a very nice , pitch black into a snifter with a small , light tan head that leaves lots of lacing behing .  its perfectly balanced and not overly done . m very medium , which i find most all stone beers to be and i dont really complain about . the carbonation is present and isnt overly aggressive or submissive .

smells amazing , like the normal version with some oak and bourbon . the smell was amazing to me . i thought the taste was a bit hotter than the normal irs , but that 's to be expected .  a one finger , mocha colored head has supreme retention and some amazing lacing to go along with it . very nice looking .  m : starts off creamy , but i 'm pretty quickly struck by how watery this is . the carbonation is decent , but i find this surprisingly thin .

c : thick and dark h : jet black n : hellllooo cognac ! hints of coffee and roasted malt huge thanks to hopscotch for sharing this barrel aged treat that is good till 2020 ? really ? will the world still be in existence in 2020 ? did you order an imperial stout with your cognac ? this approach is often reversed by brewers , as people like to have the abv hidden in big beers .  a : pours a beautiful bronze with ruby highlights . this beer looks fantastic . s : smell is of juicy citrusy hops , with an abundant dose of pale and caramel malt .  m : a little bit thinner than expected , medium-light bodied with low carbonation , lightly creamy .

aroma is wonderfully thick , gravity holds it in check . flavor collapses the experience , tremendous letdown as the scent gave much promise .  bottle in 16oz.sierra nevada glass leaves a beautiful 3/4 inch head . a-tremendous color , nice floaties , great lacing on the glass .  like cheap malt liquor infused with citrus and nail polish remover .

sn consistantly produces beers w/ amazing hop boutique aromas . t - flavor profile pretty much mimics the nose w/ the malts and biscuit holding the fort down so the trademark sn cascades can do what they do best . mf - creamy , medium body and goes down w/ a slick and oily feel d - balance , balance , balance . highly sessionable .  very attractive beer . massive sticky foamy eggshell colored head rises to 2 fingers and holds there forever .  very well carbonated , but not alot of head . i am thinking its a unique hop that i have not experienced alot of . thoughts - this beer is one of my favs from shiner .

probably one of the more amazing lager aromas , it 's truly crisp and fresh , i could smell it all day . the flavours are light , but the aromas quite amazing . indeed overall this beer is much better than even most european lagers .  a - black is right . the head is a medium brown and standing about three-quarter inches tall before slowly fading to bumpy and frothy top .  ) my only qualm was the the body seemed a little thin .

many `` damn '' s and `` holy s*** '' s could be heard as we sniffed the mercifully small portions in our tasting glasses . tons of whiskey , vanilla , burnt caramel , butterscotch . taste features big woody vanilla along with chocolate , caramel , coffee , and big booze ( how could it not ) . lot of whiskey . some sweetness , but really nowhere near as sweet as i thought it might be . feel is thick and syrupy , but look at what you 're drinking - this is one of those beers you could probably pour over your pancakes .  it pours a rust-colored brown with a roasted 2-3 finger head . this looks as good as any of the big ipas made by stone , smuttynose and company .  this beer poured a dirty blonde color , with a haziness that made me suspect that i would n't enjoy this beer too much . aroma was malty , and flavor was a sweet maltiness with only a hint of hops . this was n't what i was expecting from an american pale ale , and i really did n't enjoy it . i may have gotten an old beer , but there is no date code on this beer , so i have no way of knowing its age and it gets what it gets ... most of this one is going down the drain .

the beer is certainly lighter than i expected with an almost straw color . the nose on this brew is phenomenal ! i 'm immediately transported to magical grapefruit land as the beer screams citrus into my nostrils . there is a piney base note to this smell to that compliments the soaring citrus very well . not on hops of course , as the grapefruity citrus notes yielded to a piney bite on the finish , but rather the malt character . while still a world class ipa , i felt that the backbone of this brew just was n't quite as strong as i would have liked and the huge hop profile was almost overwhelming .  look is beautiful . perfect 1/2 inch head when poured carefully into a surly pint glass .  quenching , medium-light body , citrus-earthy character .

a very intriguing nose , wow , minty , citrusy , lemon-grass , soft licorice notes , very pleasant even with its slight funk of oxidation . this is actually quite nice even with its funk , i could deal with a little less carbonation .  bottle says bottled on 4/16/09 a - pours cloudy orange with huge 3 fingers of pillowy foam that takes forever to die down - lacing is all over the glass . this is one fine looking beer s - very hoppy with a strong grassy aroma - there are so many other aromas also - reminds me of a wine t - bitterness is subdued , bready yeast flavor is present , solid malt backbone m - great creamy mouthfeel - but i wish there was a little more lingering bitterness to this brew d - this is a very sneaky 9 % abv - deceptively drinkable .  mouthfeel is probably the most disappointing aspect of this otherwise excellent beer ; the carbonation promised by the head largely disappeared , leaving a slick , full bodied beer with very light carbonation . a nice , sharp bite of carbonation would have been welcome in this case , drying out the finish nicely , but that does n't happen here .

the aroma is exactly what i expected from an imported beer in a green bottle : skunked grain and nothing else . the flavor has a little bit of skunk , but not as much as in the aroma . i also get some grain and grass notes from the hops .  pours jet black with a thick , luscious brown head .  the overall feel is dry , like it should be , but unfortunately , it 's also a touch chaulky , which is pretty unfortunate .

beautiful aromas of freshly baked banana bread , vanilla coke , toasted candied coconut . definitely will be cracking some more of these open in the future , alcohol is well hidden and i tend to consider rr a bit too hyped but this is a very nice beer .  poured out of a 16.9 oz bottle into a tulip style glass . i held it up to the sun on my patio and admired it for a few seconds . ( cue music ) there were two inches of white head that led to a nice white cap that never dissipated .  my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin .

excellent . t- sharp hop bitterness with a floral blanket overall . slightly sticky d- smooth , smells great and tasts great .  pours black , black black , with a big , dark , thick cloud of a head .  i 'd love to try this on cask , if only to taste it more directly without all the carbonation dancing across my tongue .

wonderful citrus aroma of oranges and grapefruits . the nose is n't just there , it smacks you in the face - and this is a wonderful thing . if i could give higher than a five for aroma on this beer i would . taste - this beer is called hop dragon and consequently is all about hops . great bitter kick that almost goes unnoticed because of all the other great things about this beer .  bottle , a : pours yellow-orange , with a very long-lasting white head , great lacing .  while the carbonation is nice , the overall feel is a bit thin .

smells very sweet , of caramel and spice and a definite alcohol presence on the nose . i love it . one of the best smelling beers i 've put my nose to .  mbc 's big jamoke pours up with a modest carbonation that creates a very creamy beige-khaki brown head that encompasses the very dark brown-mahogany body .  good carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is spicy , yeasty , hints of sweetness that gets buried by the yeast . lingering yeasty aftertaste .

this beer smells incredible . a strong aroma of hops and malts immediately made itself known as soon as the bottle was cracked . excellent lacing .  into a pint glass , it poured a transparent straw/gold ; heavily carbonated , two fingers of bright white , and great head retention and lacing .  m - a little thinner than i thought and more carbonated than i would expect .

s - incredible aromas in this beer . even if is a lambic , the smells are very fine and not off-flavours .  black with a glorious creamy beige head with great retention and lacing .  body is ok , nothing special but not bad . very boozy finish .

smell is delicious ; porter , plus chocolate , plus raspberry . highly encouraging . so wonderful up front , so nasty in the back .  dark mahogany color with a 1 finger , light tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  m- somewhat thin , actually . smooth , clean , but a little more watery than i expected .

smells like delicious ginger snaps , cinnamon and some clove . delicious . it has a medium body with a good amount of carbonation . definitely a sipper , but a very good sipper .  a : red-brown , fluffy off-white head , awesome retention and lace !  m : relatively light though not particularly carbonated .

aroma is wow coffee , rich robust , you want it , it 's here , with a nice dark malt sweetness underneath .  very good lacing & head retention smell : slight malt hints taste : slight caramel followed by malt & fruiityness .  the mouthfeel was a bit unimpressive too light in my opinion .

this smells just terrific . the flavors on the palate generallyh replicate the nose , except they 're not as intense and the brown sugar and chocolate seem to dominate the flavor profile .  the appearance is outstanding ! s : expresso like smell with subtle malty aroma .  reminded me a bit of bmc with a bit of syrup added for sweetness . the taste is more of the same with a quick malty dryness at the end that seems to say , `` ha ! had you fooled..you thought there was about to be something pleasant here , did n't you ? in fact , this may get sacrificed to the kitchen sink . as i always say , in total fairness to the brewer and his ( or her ) intentions , this may have its fans , but it most assuredly is *not* for me ...

aroma is full of floral notes and hoppy sweetness . gummy ... lavender ... spicy ... oh so nice ... smooth on the palate ... a smallish touch of burn on the way down the throat . more balanced than i was expecting ... a nice sweetness up front and a good bitter back-end .  a : orangey amber cloudy beer with a huge 3 finger cappucino head that settles to peaks and valleys veery slowly , great lace throughout .  the mouthfeel is light bodied with a high level of biting carbonation ( the carbonation is the only part of this beer that i 'm not too fond of ) . quite dry due to the high level of carbonation .

very nice aroma ! very nice beer .  a big fluffy ice cream scoop of a head , eventually smooths out to about a quarter inch . for a lager this is a very good looking beer .  a new contender for the worst beer i 've ever tasted . it tasted like a carbonated v8 with sweeteners added .

one of the best smelling beers i have tried .  what a crazy story ... a - a tall pour creates totally huge cascading that ends in a three+ finger head with awesome retention .  m : medium to full body but needs more carbonation .

smell : wow , mazing ! roasty , dark chocolate , very coffee forward , sweetness . taste : very good , nice and roasty . overall : very good beer , i would certainly want to have this again .  looks fantastic ! the head leaves plenty of lace after a couple of minutes .  the mouth feel was hindered a bit , as the bottle had n't been sitting in my refrigerator long enough , the ale could have been a little more carbonated .

when you smell this beer , you know this is a big one . lots of power and lots of liquor , much like rum with some fruity notes to me . it felt like port or a fortified wine in my mouth and the taste was rather like a really , really nice rum .  amazingly slow head cascade action . clear from yeast or other floaties .  does smell a little like `` beer , '' as my wife would say . so sweet on the tongue . slight raspberry tartness but it is like drinking raspberry sorbet after it melts . it is still trying to recover from the sweetness . a good once in a while beer . sorbet beer , i tell ya .

this beer smells so good ! sweet with almost a balsamic vinegar quality . great . tart , sour gets me in the back of the mouth .  great retention and generous lacing . lovely looking porter .  mouthfeel is effervescent , lighter bodied ( almost thin ) , medium carbonation and slightly dry .

s - oh shit . dark chocolate , charcoal , campfire , wet ash , cigar smoke , dark chocolate coated coffee beans , birch bark , cigarettes , and a vague hint of sweet count chocula marshmallow cereal . ridiculous ! cigar smoke , woody campfires , wet firewood outside of an old cabin , gentle hints of sushi with soy sauce , and `` musty ( but pleasant ) old house '' notes if that makes any sense .  appearance is beatiful dark dark black with a fluffy , pale yellow head that laces nicely .  it is a little bit sweet on the tongue . i could stand it to be a little bit more dry .

a : pours a muddy muddy thick black with a little ring of head that sticks around but i was not expecting a head anyways , its just dark and inviting black as night s : smells incredibly sweet , like a sweet port , huge huge nose on this , plums and rum raisins with hints of sweet and dark chocolate . i mean there is not real reason to get more specific it smells pretty much like exactly what is listed here , very luxurious . t/mf : the carbonation is a nice touch here and allows an extremely heavy and creamy body to impart the flavor all across the tongue .  pours a cloudy garnet hue with a thin but persistent head . leaves an incredible lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel : surprisingly thin body , full carbonation , fairly thick coat after the swallow .

incredibly complex aroma , a deep strong dark with dirt , sour grass , tart apple , a cornucopia of spices . perfect touch of the rustic .  bottle : poured a pitch-black color stout with a huge dark brown color ahead with good retention and great lacing .  it was barely palatable : very little carbonation - full of sour , gone-bad notes .

s : great smelling beer . c-hops and american malts . potent nose . d : great beer , absolutely delicious , with the delicate touch of a masterful brewer .  1,000 review a- awesome copper red appearance , great foam and nice head when poured from a bottle .  i got this beer in the beers of the world gift box for christmas . immediate taste is a lil sharp and bready with a hint of citrus in the smell . it was not an out of this world experience , but it is a very light and enjoyable beer for everyday or get togethers .

great chocolate smell as soon as the cap came off , smelled just like a candy bar .  beautiful red orange color . a tan head sits on top for a while . a very pretty beer . we tried it with some honey ham and then some apple pie and it was terrific with both .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with no carbonation .

i 've had a few of these and this one plays up the humidor to 11 . incredible . t. the jai alai flavor is played down a bit to the predominate cedar flavor . the grassy and citrus hops are very nice with a good malt .  a-bronze and brilliantly clear . huge eggshell head .  m- low carbonation , medium-body .

drank it on draft at legacy and at reading country club i have also had three cases of it made for them by the lion in bottles it is smooth favorful light and not biteing , nice head great smell very refreshing to drink it is a amazing product that they have made it is very nice to just sit and drink again and again .  wow , this beer really looks like it was poured from a bar tap ... great body . boddingtons is so unique for being a light-looking golden beer that pours like an irish stout ; those widget things work well .  the mouthfeel i found oddly watery ... but still fairly full bodied at the same time . carbonation was fairly mild - maybe that lended to the `` watery '' sensation .

the aroma was amazing , especially for a beer of such humble stature . chocolatey rich to the extreme . steaming hot fudge instantly came to mind . sweet and creamy with strong notes of vanilla and a touch of oak . dark chocolate came through strong up front . black coffee was noticeable in the center . this was a smooth and tasty beer with an aroma that was to die for . at 5.7 % abv , this porter was surprisingly drinkable .  a-dark ruby to light brown with a huge tan head . clear .  i 'm rather late with this review but i had this on tap at nicholson 's downtown and it reminded me of sierra nevada celebration . in fact at the time the original name was celebration ale . i 've since had a few growlers from jungle jim 's and though it 's a quailty brew i 've experienced some diacetyl like off-flavors when served from the growler . still it 's quite enjoyable and recommended . i wish the best to mike and his future brews !

smell is a tart , floral aroma with crisp , clean edge ; simply put , it 's delightful . this ale 's taste is a crafty hop blen dover a clean , crisp start .  a : vigorous pour yielded a creamy 2 finger light caramel colored head with great retention and outrageous frothy web-like lacing .  carbonation a little higher than i expect in the style but still manages to be exceptionally drinkable .

this is one of my favorites , this is the alt which is available year around at the brewery on tap . the bottle pales in comparison to the tap version . love to spend a rainy afternoon enjoying an alt and the good company at the brewery . when at the berwery , i hope you get to meet nick , one of the last great bartenders - great way to spent a portland afternoon .  appearance- black ! ! ! creamy head .  apricots . hops undetectable above the jaw-clenching , eye-squinching , head-shaking sourness . awful . ugh . otherwise , it defintely seems to be beer , ( if in no way resembling any version of a contemporary pa ) , but with a sour and bitter fruitiness that pervades , annoys , and overwhelms . the originally enticing head cashed in early and diminished to virtual non-existence before i gave up trying to like this one ; very little lacing to wash out of the glass . wo n't drink the other two in the sampler , did n't finish this one , and opened a sn celebration ale to get the taste out of my mouth .

s-what comes through first is a perfect balance of sweet caramel malt and a blast of citrus hops . d- this brew is pretty awesome . brews that emphasize the citrus/spicy hop combo are hard to come by and this one does an excellent job with it .  a : yellow , straw hues , slightly hazy , enormous whipped meringue head , long lasting retention , nice lacing .  m - comes across a tad light on the carbonation , making it a bit watery for my liking .

smell : varies as it warms : bacon , chocolate , hickory , raisin , wood and more ... taste : dope .  pours a two finger cream head that fades slowly leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear ruby/amber color .  mouthfeel is light and carbonation fades to almost flat .

very nice and original beer - more body would have been better but still a great treat from a great brewery .  light copper with a thick , mousse-like , sticky-as-hell head .  the carbonation is ok ; small fresh bubbles at a decent strength .

nose is fantastic ! uniquely fruity , like a cranberry-mango chutney . hops are detectable and make this a complex sniffer , probably the best smelling tripel i have ever laid nostrils upon . fruit levels take on the best from belgium , impressive . very nice brew , might be my favorite that i have had so far from the bruery .  great retention and great lacing .  m - body is a little thin , moderate carbonation .

stalagtites of drippy lace . fantastic barrel aroma , soaked in bourbon and sun-dried , retaining it 's oaky complexity . mouthfeel is smooth and rich , alcohol really only detracts from the taste slightly .  look : dark brown with a good solid 1 inch head with great retention and some spotty lacing smell : smoked pork comes to mind .  mouthfeel was ok ; about the same as urquell .

the smell is amazing , strong coffee aroma , more so than any other coffee stout i 've had , easily the best aspect of this stout . the taste is a bit more reserved with the coffee as it 's hard to beat the strong aroma , but there is a good deal of coffee and roasted malt , hint of chocolate , and a decent bitterness in the end .  brilliant cloudy , fuzzy , bubbly orange appearance with a perfect 1/4 inch puffy head and a pleasant hoppy aroma .  mouthfeel is soft and a little heavy .

the first thing that struck me about this stout was the aroma , very complex , almost sweet , with what i thought could have been vanilla among other things . the # 1 surprise was the texture and consistency of this beer , i was expecting something much thicker , more like guiness , and boy was i surprised , a much smoother , lighter consistency with a great taste and just enough flavor to let you know you are drinking something quality without being over whelming . it took me more time to get a good overall sense of this stout then i would have expected , a compliment to the complexity of the flavor .  a - brilliant copper color with a finger of thick solid off white head .  the mouthfeel was light but a bit chewy .

mmmmm , a smell like none other . besides aroma , this is a mighty tasty beer ; absolutely my newest favorite ipa . i could drink a couple of these at once , but like many highly flavorful beers , not my kind of session brew .  it pours a dark brown to almos black color with a huge fluffy tan to light brown head .  light to medium in body .

the first impression i got when i took a long deep breathe in the the glass was sweet malt and chocolate , oh my god , chocolate ! it seems as though i was sniffing a fresh glass of dark chocolate milk . it just smells creamy and smooth . the taste was roasted malt and grains combined with the chocolate .  reviewed 11/1/2009 ( bottle coded 8899 ) : pours a clear brown color body , with a big tan foamy head , very lasting .  though this is a red ale of stormy garnet and the menu states it is `` brewed with 20 % honey malts for a touch of sourness '' ( honey = sourness ? it is not merely that this red ale tastes bad ; it is absolutely offensive . of the lowest evolutionary order . the entire beer is corrupted by spoilage and should n't be served publicly .

awesome smell , couldnt wait to drink it !  a- poured into an over-sized beer mug , this made for a super robust head . great sticky lacing , a steady stream of carbonation , and an amber/orange body sets this beer up as one of the prettiest looking ipas ive seen in a while . s- i think the full scent has a bit of a hard time breaking through this super dense head !  m- a bit thin for my taste .

for me , this was one of the most appealing scents i 'd smelled in a long time .  bottled 10/31/11 a : pours jet black with a nice finger high layer of dark mocha head that laces the glass nicely .  m : medium mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

lovely aroma of figs , coffee , licorice , lavender , pinesap , chocolate & mint . the dark roasted malts smell so very fresh , almost as if they were right there damp in the palm of your hands .  pours vibrant pale gold with lively streams of carbonation sustaining an impressive large white head and leaivng lovely lacing .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is light , as is the body .

the smell on this one is incredible , and leaves little to be desired . a lot of chocolate hits the nostrils as well as bitter espresso . this is by far the best porter i have ever smelled , thus far . the taste is not quite up to par here .  wow , what a good looking beer . dark dark , dark body and small light brown head ontop .  a - black on the pour with no head whatsoever s - big burnt malt and bittersweet chocolate aroma along with some bourbon , some oak and vanilla in there as well , slight alcohol , as the beer warms up , smells almost like straight bourbon , maybe more like a bourbon and cola t - big bourbon flavor right up front , lots of oak as well , some bittersweet chocolate in the body , finish is more bourbon and oak along with some vanilla , alcohol notes , long finish m - a bit too flat for my taste , full-bodied but totally devoid of any carbonation action in the mouth d - i 'm glad port put this in a 375ml bottle , because this is a sipper , treated this almost like fine bourbon sipping for quite awhile , but i could sip on this all night very interesting beer .

very good . t - starts out quite fruity , sweet and tart with heavy notes of strawberries .  the white head is huge and pillowy and leaves wonderful fuzzy navel lacing .  m - the feel is not terrible .

s : sour cherries are noticeable before the glass reaches my nose . t : the aroma carries well into the taste as the sour dark cherry hits the palate first and then gives way to the sweetness which tastes more like a jolly rancher than sweet tart .  excellent look - copper color with a big slightly off-white head that leaves excellent lacing . looks as good as a rye beer can .  the carbonation does not give this beer a pleasant mouthfeel that i would like .

probably the best aroma of any ale i 've tasted all year . amazing ester profile .  great white head that left a really nice lacing .  cons : the low carbonation level does hurt many factors of the beer , but it is such an exquisitely brewed offering , it 's only a minor issue .

there is a slight hint of malt in aroma , not much else , but it smells like a bock . this is a decent bock with some spiciness .  stellar appearance with this beer . it pours a really nice orange amber color with fine yeast particles suspended in it like stars . very attractive .  this was my first encounter with pumpkin ale . i must confess that i could not finish the bottle . i had the distinct impression that the beer was trying to taste like something and not quite getting there . fearing the latter , i tossed the bottle after about five sips .

i love how the smell changes over time . got ta give 3f props for the phenomenal smell , tho .  pours a very nice amber , just the slightest bit of haze . nice thick , dense , head . excellent lacings .  i always look forward like most do the annual stone anniversary brews.poured a rich deep amber with a tight and sticky one finger off white head , big hops in the nose with a mix pine and herbal/leaf , there is a gummy , fruity-like sweet note as well.the mouthfeel is a bit sharp i will say it crashes down the gullett at first , it does begin to smooth out after a few sips but still seems a bit harsh.no holds barred hops hit the palate up front with big pine and big herbalness , a healthy does of sweeter alcohol gives a slight burn along with a bit of dark fruit.very good but seems like it something that should sit for awhile , still another fine one from stone .

smell is flowery , and very aromatic .  poured from a bottle into a pint - exceptionally clear , copper colored with a one finger head that was almost latte colored , enough carbonation to keep plenty of lacing and a little bit of a head until the end .  drink this on tap at city beverage in durham . i like the color and mouthfeel , though a bit thin for a heavy beer aroma is slightly sweet and complex spices taste is toasted barley , spices , and slight caramel with little head . drinks easy for a heavy beer

amazing , both the most unique and best smell i have in a beer in a good long time . taste- a strong and front malt body .  the color is incredible . i 'm not sure how you give this appearance anything other than a 1 or 5 . excellent retention , settling to a thick film and rings of clumpy lacing .  mouf & gt ; meh . okay . average .

really smells nice . the taste mimicks the nose ... .nice balance between the cloves and banana notes ... also some subtle but enjoyable caramel maltiness .  this settles very slowly to a thin , nearly complete cap and leaving behind amazing lacing . the beer itself is black as night . a small amount of sediment remains in the bottle and the last portion of the pour seemed a little cloudy .  m : medium body with low carb . dry finish . nothing special here .

s- super hoppy and sweet with a mixture of predominant pine flavor and underlying grapefruit notes ... absolutely exquisite . t- taste is very reminiscent of pliny the elder but possibly better balanced .  a- deep black with a giant tan head . retention is awsome and it laces down the entire glass .  a completely black beer with a thin mocha head . boris is a thick , almost to the point of sludgy beer with a roasted malt taste with a noticeable but background hop presences . the oatmeal comes into play as a slight cookie taste . overall it 's a great beer that worthy of a try .

s : the smell is very balanced and i am loving it . mild fruity esters mix with sweet bourbon , vanilla , and coconut to form what is probably the best smelling beer ( non-ipa ) i 've had before . d : fantastic barrel aged barleywine . great job mayflower .  the color of this beer i find just amazing . it 's so dark as it sits in a guinness glass , with it 's beautiful smooth head . are there bubbles finer than these ? in contrast to how heavy it looks , it 's goes down incredibly smooth and fast .  the only thing slightly disappointing about this beer for me was the mouthfeel seemed a bit watery .

smell is movie theater popcorn & maple syrup .  stunning ruby red/black beauty with superb head retention .  mf : the carbonation is n't quite as spritzy as i would hope to go along with the huge sourness , the body is light d : this is a great lambic .

smell is very sexy - pure belgian goodness . taste is very good . this beer is very drinkable . each sip is very nice as you get a great whif of that aroma . belgian yeast is very impressive - the unique flavor qualities never get old ; they are very subtle .  served in a pint glass poured from a 12oz bottle a : pours a deep black color with thick foamy head reminiscent of chocolate milk .  light , decently carbonated , and quenching for the desert dweller .

very enjoyable beer . highly quaffable and deliciously decadent .  huge rocky off-white head with good retention . carbonation bubbles rise to the top which makes the head more active than a tornado in a trailor park . fine looking beer !  a-garnet with small ring of foam s-raisin , pancake syrup , faint vinager t-assertive sour front , sour cherry , some malt sweetness , dates m-medium , with average carbonation d-very tasty !

extremely full smell , very good . t : sweet dark fruits up front then a booze laced chocolate and toffee .  poured from a 750ml bottle into a champagne flute : appearance : pours a beautiful strawberry red/ lavander purple color . huge pink head that has great retention .  flavor is absolutely nothing like an oud bruin .

the yeast notes are exquisite . not very earthy , mostly ripe fruit with a bit of funky complexity .  poured out of a bottle to a beautiful dark color . really a beautiful beer .  the body is surprisingly light with moderate carbonation , helping to make this very drinkable .

this smells amazing . like perfumed hop elephants . but damn ... this smells amazing . i could inhale this all day . which sounds odd .  absolutely beautiful long-lasting cascade and unbelievable merangue-like head .  nice dark brown color with fantnaztic lacing ! smells choclotly with coffee . tastes even and thick with cocoa sweet caramel flavors continuing thru . good for its class this porter represents well , its much better than its younger brother . would drink again .

the aroma is thoroughly enticing , presenting notes of buttered wheat , bubble gum , orange peel , banana creme , vanilla , and a touch of spicy , organic hops . all in all , a satisfyingly complex and tasty wheatwine from the talented terrapin brewers .  pours with a hefty amount of two finger thick light tan head , and has a clear copper colored body .  mouthfeel is a bit thinner than i would have expected .

s : this is seriously the best part of the beer . the smell is a pronounced chorus of woodiness , vanilla , chocolate , and booze . is this nirvana ? t : starts out with a creamy chocolate taste which is followed by a sharp stab of flavor and alcohol burn on the tongue . d : overall a very impressive beer .  summit horizon red : a : appearance is exceptional , great amber-red color to it with exceptional clarity ! nice 1 '' head that develops yet depletes half-way through .  mouthfeel is way more thin than the head and lacing made me think it would be . very quaffable .

hard pour gets a beautiful head to rise up , just a little more than two fingers worth of off-white frothiness . smells phenomenal . a bouquet of citrus hops , with a little bit of floral and maybe piney for good measure . so nicely balanced , just a little bit of bitter and the rest is flavor . the alcohol would probably catch me a buzz after just a couple , but it certainly weighs in a little lower than some comparable ipas , which is nice .  pours a bright orange color , slightly carbonated , with a thick pillowy off-white head .  mouthfeel : this was my one issue with this beer . it loses carbonation quickly , and with not that much to start with , it is kind of a bummer . a little sticky as well but the taste makes up for a bit of this .

the aroma seems to transcend the dopplebock style with a delightful boozy elixier : notes of dark rum , brandy , sherry and the like . currants , produce , fresh grass , and a slight hint of citrusy hops provide a great balance to the smell . this is not a beer for the faint of palate . i 'm not exactly sure how i feel about samichlaus ... one one hand , it 's an exceptionally complex , well-crafted beer that probably deserves its own style .  very bright , very glowing red body . cream-colored head is boisterous and rocky .  tingly in the nose which is common with sour ales but this is n't sour at all t. sweet with dried fruit , malty m. has a biting quality , a bit to carbonated .

s - surprising amount of malt in the nose , and an equally surprising lack of hops .  a very good porter , poured dark ruby brown color with strong tan head that i impatiently dove into smelling its aroma of chocolate , burnt malt , sweet caramels and hops .  mouthfeel : a bit thin the only thing i can say i 'm disappointed about here just seems watery i even recall the original munich formula having more body but hey sturdy carbonation excellent o-fest .

s - the nose on this one is as good as it gets . t - just wonderful - almost as perfect as the nose . this outstanding beer 's only downfall . d - great . tons of booze and heat on this one , but the outstanding vanilla and coconut flavors allow me to drink as much of this as is available !  this brew pours with a deep amber body topped by a medium thick head with lots of lacing .  thin mouthfeel , this is the achilles heel of the beer .

really good . t : milder than the smell , with a taste of mostly apples and cider , creamy caramel , and a mild woody gin finish .  hazy and dark copper-amber in color with a thick cream colored head of super tightly laced foam that left great lacing at it receded at a slow but steady rate ; the head reminds me of an improperly baked cake very slowly losing its leavening .  m : it 's a little thin , but i kind of like it . d : improved because of the thin mouthfeel .
the aromas are very fine and intense i was very impressed ! !  the color is pretty cool to look at .  good carbonation , which i appreciate . minimal complexity to this beer .

i just about busted a nut getting the # $ # cork off in one piece..ahh make that several pieces that did n't fall back into the bottle ... but after a long and arduos process the cork was successfully removed.. poured a dark brown ... relatively clear..absolutely no head ... mouthfeel is very uncarbonated..i love the nose ... molasses ... .brown sugar ... .dark fruits ( plums , dates , even burgandy cherries ) ..a bit of oak ... just an awesome smelling beer.. the flavors are similar to the nose but much more tame ... .dark fruits ... molasses ... oak ... good taste to this ... my biggest complaint is the loose mothfeel ... very uncabonated which gives it almost a watery texture ... seems almost thin ... overall , the nose is great and the taste is very good but the body leaves something to be desired..definitely worth trying ... i wo n't be buying any more though ... .  this beer looks great , clean and clear , good carbonation and head .  the mouthfeel is quite thin , verging on watery .

the color was not as dark as i expected for a stout , but it looked nice , had a nice roasted smell to it .  pours a beautiful dark brown , nearly black , with a tan head of about one finger .  a soft , almost too light mouthfeel and a little weak carbonation , the only appearent downside of this brew in my opinion .

s : strong enticing smell of toffee , vanilla and butterscotch . t : much the same as the smell .  very pretty in the glass , big foam head that would n't quit through the whole bottle . heavy orange color .  mouthfeel : it 's a bit heavy for the style .

aroma is very inviting with apple , pear , and an awesome yeastiness . the taste is n't as fruity and glorious as the incredible aroma but it is nice and earthy . there is a great toastiness to it and great caramel , bread and diacetyl butter flavor .  appearance - crystal clear gold body with a huge white head ( took three goblets to pour this ) . gorgeous .  m - medium to light body , low carbonation , smooth mouthfeel going down , perhaps a bit watery .

smell is incredible : pure piney , grapefruity hops with a veneer of rich malt . and that in itself is amazing ! finishes like an unsweetened soda .  what a shame ... pours a pretty golden-amber color topped by a huge , thick , creamy white head .  the feel is a little odd . it does n't seem to be too carbonated , but the bubbles sting like sprite against your lips .

the head is fluffy , off-white , and responsible , in part , for the best characteristic of this brew : the nose . the nose is a wonderful mix of allspice , nutmeg , and a bit of cinnamon , laid over a warm , inviting sweetness . it 's like sniffing a particularly delicious cookie . this brew goes down quite smoothly , and does not seem as high in alcohol as i thought it would .  a : beautiful clear rich copper color with creamy tan head . m : smooth o : a very aesthetically pleasing beer . really beautiful to look at and smell .  m - extremely light and watery , typical carbonation from a cask .

the nose is very complex with hints of soy sauce and salty taffy .  appearance : slightly hazy , ruby-amber pour with a voluminous ( and tenacious ) , light-tan whipped-cream head . recedes to floating dollops ... lace everywhere !  mouthfeel : there is a lot of bitterness .

i ca n't smell much of anything in this . at least it is n't skunky .  pours a sparkling orange tinged gold , topped with a huge four finger pillowy white head , constant streams of carbonation bubbles , leaves thick puffy webs of lacing .  is this someones idea of a joke ? rotten peaches with a kick of dirty feet is not something i prefer in my beer . sour an nasty , she be . i should have know by the pour , cider apple yellow fizzy white head . cripe , im glad i only got 2 bottles of this overpriced ( $ 2.50 a pop ) sour peach soda geez , only 4.5 % . i would have kicked myself in the sack for buying this , but im no longer that agile .

not a whole lot of smell , there 's a little malt , and i do n't really smell pumpkin .  a : thick and black , dark almond head ( more like a thin disk of residual bubbles ) s : strong note of alcohol , bitter dark chocolate , coffee m : very alcoholic feel ; initial taste of a dark stout followed by the heat of a liquor akin to scotch .  malts help to round it out a little , but that bitterness hangs around for quite a bit m : medium body with typical sa carbonation , slightly oily d/o : well , apparently zeus is known for that intense piney flavor , so it is highlighted well here .

the smell is quite pungent . i can smell the glass from a foot away ! sweet caramel malts are picked up in the nose , but are nothing in comparision to the huge hops assault . it is very hop foward ( understatement ) . this is easily one of the most unique and bitter beers i have ever had . the hops oils make it quite slippery and oily going down .  exceptional head and lace . big , rough , chunky , substantial lace . impressive to look at and earns full points on that count .  m : sharp carbonation is pretty overpowering , and any refreshing aspects of the smell and taste are lost .

the smell was bourbon and caramel . sometimes these things can taste like beer with a shot of liquor - not so with this one . all in all , quite excellent .  wow ... what a head !  mouthfeel is on the light end .

perfect fruit scent . clean , pleasant , and wonderful . almost erotic , even - i want this beer to have my abortion .  came out a murky amber-gold with a good inch 's worth of head on it . great retention , and perfect lacing rings after each sip . beautiful .  the mouthfeel starts off kind of watery since this seems to be a light to medium bodied brew and leaves a dry , but sticky feel to the lips .
