there is also a nice toffee and molasses sweetness to keep the aroma balanced . there are also hints of dark berries : to me it smelled like blueberry and raspberry . it is a very enticing aroma . taste : more roasted glory , and the first sip was a shock of burnt bitterness ; the overpowering intensity , though , passed after a couple sips .  beautiful box package , dated 2004 , opens to reveal a classy looking bottle , numbered 85352 . this pours into a tukip a dark amber/light brown , with a thin head .  a little thin .

a- pours a light amber with a quickly dissipating head s- wow , this smells incredible ! it smells like cinnamon , nutmeg , graham cracker , pumpkin , and brown sugar . d- it 's highly drinkable , however the alcohol is not as well-hidden as in some other st imperials .  it has a very deep black color and tan head that make it beautiful to pour .  i always drink my high life out of cans ! it looks like beer , smells like beer , and tastes like beer ... to keep it simple . this is my go-to macro , and will always be as long as miller keeps it the same ! prost !

it smells great . t : the taste didnt exactly match the smell but the taste was good too .  a - pours black with a nice light-tan head . looks great . sticks fairly well to the side , just about as good as a porter could .  mf- raw resinous and sticky , becoming oily , medium carbonation , slightly astringent , dry and grainy in the finish d- well rounded ipa , but not the best around .

the smell is amazing . like i stated above , i 'm not big into coffee , but even this is appealing , and impressive to pull off . this porter does nothing but give off an intense and clean cafe au lait aroma , straight to the point . it 's greatest attribute is the aroma however , that is really phenomenal .  a- gorgeous . deep gold with hints of orange .  m : medium body but the finish is not as crisp nor as clean as it could be .

the smell was amazing -- probably the highlight of the beer . it got better as the temp increased . overall , it 's a pretty solid novelty beer .  pours a very nice looking dark ruby with a thick tan head which remains forever and leaves sticky lacing in my delirium glass . a beautiful beer , i wish they all looked like this .  m- average medium bodied beer o- great take on a saison style beer .
actually pretty bad .  great looking beer !  the flavor is a bit harsh and a bit watery , but not too much .

wonderful nose on this beast . but it is n't very rich . its kind of one dimensional . has big hop character , big malt character , roasty , chocolate , caramel , but that 's about it .  this looked wonderful ! ! !  mouthfeel & drinkability : lighter bodied and less bitter than most other ipas , which makes for quite easy drinking .

tallboy can @ 4.9 % and $ 1.85 . we can all agree this is n't fancy stuff , but it 's special none the less . it does n't smell good . heck , it does n't really smell at all .  a - pours a gorgeous bright and translucent dark copper color with some nice golden and slight amber hints . very good retention . almost perfect looking beer .  m - a little harsh , not as smooth as other ipas .

the nose of this beer is simply amazing . pure fresh cherries , almost like a top notch but soft lambic . some light caramel and hops could be smelled as well , but mostly fresh fresh soft cherries . light caramel tone , but just very clean and malty . the bottle is a little disapointing to be honest , but on tap this beer is simply amazing . fresh cherries and soft clean crisp malt .  a- pretty beautiful . a reddish amber color , just glowing .  poured from bottle to tulip glass a : brilliantly clear pale yellow color with huge 3+ finger head that fades very slowly n : nose of a light belgian type wit with some light malts , touch of spices , toasted quality , touch of yeast t : starts with more malts and toasted quality , pretty light otherwise , a touch of light fruits and banana , slight earthy marzen quality , no spices m : very light and somewhat watery f : finishes dry and very crisp with a fading earthy marzen taste , would make a good session beer final thoughts : its a very light tasting oktoberfest/marzen .

aroma is unusual and very pleasant : something akin to meadowland following a spring shower blended with a peatiness and cooked vine fruits .  pours an opaque darkness with a huge stiff dark brown head that decomposes like an ice cream sundae , massive 3d lacing present .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but thats a minor complaint .

no cloves ... aroma is very sweet and smells like sugar , a touch of diacetyl , and apple juice ... not remotely close to the style , and pretty horrible smelling despite this .  ) pitch black colour , moderate brown head . the appearance is top notch , a very fine and lasting brown head .  the rye is evident , as is a tangy almost sour note along with the bread . a little over-carbonated ... i found it slightly distracting and that it may have affected my enjoyment of the beer 's complexity . light-bodied and very refreshing . while i have little to no experience with beers of this style , i enjoyed this one and i believe that its a great refresher during the summer months .

smell : ah ... it 's been a while since i smelled something so interesting , so refreshing . sour concord grape juice , light farmy funk , an undercurrent of yogurty lactic tang , nutty sherry , and oaky port . really , a great nose . taste : sour through-and-through , with a spicy , envigorating tartness that swells in intensity as you hold it on your palate , then dissipates slightly before a clean , bracingly tart finish . very good , very bright , and very refreshing , but i do wish there were a bit more depth in the malt profile . this is exceptionally flavorful , interesting , and drinkable , especially at only 6 % abv .  a- pours orange-amber with a massive , foamy and creamy head that retains amazingly , gives duvel a run for its money . the cloud is as big as the head of others .  mouthfeel is poor due to the overdone carbonation .

robust cherry smell that is fantastic . taste is almost all cherry , wheaty malt underneath .  i absolutely loved this bottle .  medium bodied with carbonation that was a little too high and too coarse for my liking , but it did n't turn me off completely . my only issue was the carbonation .

incredibly pungent and tropical aroma . the distinct nelson hops really shine here . one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced from any dipa . an absolutely wonderful dipa . honestly , i never expected a dipa this good to come from karl strauss -- count me in as very pleasantly surprised .  pours to a beautiful deep dark brown body with a hint of ruby red when held to light . hosts a decent 1 and a half inch rich tan head , leaving some lace as it fades .  m - surprisingly , its a bit thin and lacks carbonation .

smell is very floral and fragrant , wow , fantastic . as it warms , you get more classic nw hops , pine and citrus .  a : one of the most gorgeous beer i 've ever seen . head is tan and very very strong .  medium bodied fairly low carbonation .

the aroma of it is amazing , almost a pumpkin cider type smell .  but not rahr and son 's w.w. from the get go the pour was great a beautiful reddish brown with a head that stuck around for awhile . and lacing that covered the glass throughout the few minutes it took for me to gobble this one down and lots of sediment in the bottle .  light bodied for what i was expecting , but then it does n't claim to be a porter or stout .

what struck me first was the phenomenally fresh smell . the roasted malt and slightly bitter hops hits your nose and just stays there , begging you to take a sip . while the beer is great , the taste did n't quite live up to the smell . a bit thinner than expected and a bit less complex than i had hoped .  pours with a beautiful amber body topped by a thick lasting head with a good amount of lace left on the glass .  mouthfeel : a little watery , but not terrible .

the spices really compliment the berry smell . very unique and inviting . the highlight of this beer is the incredible aroma . t - not quite as impressive as the nose leads to believe .  appearance : black as the abyssal depths topped by a hearty dark brown head that 's thick , frothy and slightly rocky . it sticks around for quite some time before settling down to a smallish layer of foam and then finally a ring of bubbles .  m : lighter than it should be and very creamy and smooth , decent carbonation . f : long creamy chocolate vanilla smoothness .

very strong perfume , somewhere between musky cologne and rose water they use in middle-eastern desserts . very dynamic and evolutive aroma , good stuff indeed ! taste : lively , robust carbonation - another shocker for me , considering 13 % abv and a swig-top bottle - but it pushed the fruit flavor really hard , a pleasant sour raspberry then mingled with a round , caramel toffee malt richness .  pours amberish black . nice pillowy head . retention and lacing are nice apples , chocolate in the nose .  heavy hops , but not totally unbalanced . very quenching .

the wheat wine here seemed to me to be just like a regular barley wine to me and my friend who split the bottle . i was thinking that it would be a nice lighter strong beer before the dinner we had but it was heavy and boozie . i have n't been able to see much of a difference between wheat and barley wines .  i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . great head , fine bubbles that stuck to the glass the whole way down .  my first tripel style beer , i spit it on my counter . the flavors of fruit combined with a bitter aftertaste left one bottle down the drain , and three still sitting in their case . anyone near me is welcome to the other three . while i am confident in the quality of this product , this style is definitely not for me .

330ml bottle served into an snifter glass.enjoyed on sep11.pours intense orangish copper in color , chill haze appearance.crowned by a creamy light yellowish off-white thick layer froth.brief retention leaving some spotty lacing.yeast & intense caramel malt aromas . buttery bread , toffee hints & slightly fruity -apricot & peach- notes to the nose.spicy , orange zest & subtle coriander flavors.gentle warming alcohol.sweet bitterness in the middle.medium but intense body.soft carbonation.dry bitter finish.smooth fruity aftertaste.a beer for a long & paused drink.a nice warming beer .  makes an impressive appearance , a nice red amber color with a large foamy pale head that lingers in the chalice with some sticking .  the body is medium with decent carbonation .

huge pepper aroma and a very pronounced and balanced flavor . thanks to the lovely folks at elysian fields today , very gracious hosts .  a nearly perfect pour . smells and tastes of the usual hefe spicy , peppery yeast , clove and banana , with a touch of citrus ( maybe lemon ) sourness .  spritely carbonated and fairly aqueous . very good but i would like a little more body .

this beer smells amazing . t : very roasty , lots of coffee , lots of chocolate , some sweetness in the background .  appearance - black with murky auburn brown edges . nice semi tan head with great retention and lacing . super sticky on the sides , just beautiful .  actually thought it might be bad but when i drank it there was plenty of carbonation . smell : a toasted malty smell with an almost cardboard smell . taste : very strong toasted smell but more of a bitterness then a sweetness . note : no date on the bottle but wondering if this beer had gone bad . will try another attempt at it but not really looking forward to it .

the nose was spectacular . sweet tar , coffee , chocolate , sappy wood all leap from the glass . molasses and brown sugar are buried within the beautiful , rich nose . overwhelming loads of flavors battling for attention .  poured a hazy straw colored hue with a fluffy three finger head . the retention was beyond excellent as was the very stick lacing . by the time i got to the bottom of my hefe glass , there was still nearly a finger of fluffy head remaining .  mouthfeel : light/ medium body with excessive carbonation that somewhat hinders the flavor .

this reminds me a bit of pte with that ridiculously great aroma and bitterness but not quite having the citric hop flavor that i would normally want in a dipa . this beer is incredibly bitter on the back end and the hot alcohol make this beer difficult to session .  drank on-tap at hot tomato 's , new haven , ct poured a hazy amber with a two-finger , bubbly , white head that left huge ridges of lacing all the way down the glass .  the body is thin and slightly anemic . a little more carbonation and body would carry this really unique beer into the stratosphere .

viscous notes , along with minimal head retention & lacing s : orchard fruit , grainyness , & pineapple t : peaches , pineapple , honey , boozey grain & a kiss of estery yeast & mushroom like funk .  incredible whipped retention and lacing everywhere . this is an awesome looking beer !  mouth- thin ? it 's a little thin , it lacks depth , and too much raisin for my taste .

smell was outstanding . malts , and dried fruits , raisins , prunes , etc , very complex and really builds the base for the beer . very , very nice . no bitterness to speak of and a lingering toffee sweetness at the end . overall an excellent doppelbock , right up there in my top 3 .  sediment floats about in a strange vapor-like form . just the head by itself is more complex than most beers , sits on top the whole time , slowly getting all awesome and chunky looking and leaving good lacing .  very low carbonation , strong , hoppy with lingering after taste , a very typical english bitter but not my cup of tea .

s - coffee . geez .  beautiful looking beer to be sure , dark , dark brown with a very attractive frothy tan head . just looks so good in the glass .  lightly bodied , perhaps overly so , with a passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

i found the smell a bit lacking , i was a little stuffed up but very little by way of smell especially considering this beer fantastic taste . sweet , creamy , hoppy , with a slight bitterness to chase .  the three-finger beige head displayed great retention as a fluffy cap . eventually the cap became rocky and left little islands of foam floating atop the liquid . the lacing was also excellent , in curtains ; top marks for appearance .  the mouthfeel is the only thing i think could be improved here and it very well may just be that i am having it from a growler .

it smells wonderfully of coffee bean and dark chocolate . the taste is just a little bit dry at the finish for me , but very rich and complex roasted flavors going on here .  comes out of the tap a rich opaque warm sable with a thick , fine-bubbled , almost guinness-like light tan head that leaves some good lacing .  the palate is somewhat thin for the style but it 's still smooth .

the smell is outstanding - i was salivating from the roasty nutty goodness .  a : attractive drink on the pour , looks like a lighter , creamier guinness pint from a good tap . huge head and flowing bubbles .  mouthfeel was not particularly big , enough that you knew you were drinking something real but not a facefull .

head stays for a good while s- smells identical to apple pie .  tasted nov. 21rst 2011 ( from notes ) tulip a - very nice translucent blood red , 1/4 finger off white fizzy head and minimum lacing s - peat , smoke , nuts , alcohol , slight wine , lots of yeast and oak t - so much peat , wow ! sap , wood , lemon , citrus , alcohol , sauvignon blanc , more peat , some nice hops and the peat kind of peats ( haha ) out all the other flavors m - medium body , medium acidity , low complexity , not balanced and very long finish d - while at first few sips the peat is overwhelming and almost nasty , after a bit the peat is more in the background of a smokey , citrus , alcoholic ale .  the mouthfeel was about what i expected going in , but i thought it might a little over-carbonated . the aggressiveness of the carbonation was a little distracting .

smell is hops - straight , beautiful hop smell . seriously , smells awesome . okay , taste is lagging behind a ways .  thick brown head with moderate retention . excellent lacing throughout .  it was bland and the stout portion was overpowering . yet , for reason 's i do n't understand , the people i know from philadelphia all seem to love this beer .

pours with a fat thumb head , with decent stout lacing ... smell is amazing , lots of sweet bourbon and chocolate plum ... lots of bourbon upfront but it really is remarkable how enjoyable it is , despite the fact that its like sipping straight bourbon ... this beer would age soooo beautifully ! a wonderful beer that i was honored to have tried at a really fun event , but that open bar kicked my butt in the end ! !  poured a beautiful amber color . wonderful lacing . just a beautiful beer .  m : thin , but with a bit of sparkle .

the smell is very fresh , crisp and clean ; truly wonderful . lots of citrus and pine aroma coming off immediately , mostly grapefruit with some floral grassiness as well , with some biscuity malt in the background . i could smell this a mile away and loved it . t : taste follows nose for the most part , leading off with citrus-pine hops with a sweet biscuity background . it 's fairly bitter , but the malt sweetness balances it just enough to keep it extremely pleasant and crisp . the taste was very fresh and very clean , ending as it began with a gentle , bitter , floral hop bite . the smell is exquisite , and the taste is juicy and not as dry as many similarly citrusy-bitter ipas , making it a bit more drinkable . with all the smaller breweries popping up in boston , and many focusing on more boutique styles , it 's great to see a new , local ipa that seems to be doing everything right without reinventing the wheel .  a - it 's impossible to score higher , beautiful beer ... thick fluffy white head that resembles the frothed milk of a latte , dark gold to light copper , carbonation rains towards the head ... such a beautiful looking beer .  body is fairly thin , but that is expected for the modest abv .

dipas aroma 's are awesomely hard to describe .  pours a perfect cloudy gold with a big fluffy head .  wow this has to be one of the worst ideas in beer history . trying to cross a pale ale with a belgian and what you got is something that is a distant cousin to both . instead of leveraging the style 's strengths this beer doubles down on their worst attributes . a very hoppy tatse that fights like a strong ale . not a fun beer and a true shame that it might discredit weyerbacher 's other great beers .

the best thing about this beer is the aroma imo . awesome , very awesome . beer is thin and falls flat on the flavors at first . its a good beer , just not my favorite .  appearance : darkest , thickest brown head i 've seen , even a notch above rogue 's shakespeare stout . pitch black even when directly on top of a 60w lamp . tall head , intense lacing .  flavour is better than expected- a little woody and slightly spicy , with a thick strong maltiness . i 'd like the hearty body on this one , were it not for the turbocharged carbonation .

the aroma is really great . big hop presence and a flavor profile that screams west coast .  pours a deep murky brown with a nice frothy light-tan head that lasts and leaves great lacing .  feel is thin bodied overall , but well bodied for the style .

nose is `` oh my fucking god '' chocolate . this smells like a combination of the greatest cup of pure milk chocolate , chocolate milk or hot chocolate with touches of espresso , coffee , dark burnt coffee beans and pure vanilla beans .  appearance- beer pours clear and golden with a half finger of creamy white head with ample lacing on the sides of the glass . carbonation rises from the bottom of the glass as if this were a pilsner . very nice on looks at least .  taste is weak but odd at the same time with a mild rice-sweetness . this is the kind of beer you can share with your friends because most do n't appreciate the imports anyway . i drank plenty of this is my younger days ... when you look up headache in the dictionary it reads `` drink 12 budweisers and take a nap .

s : big yeast smell right up front . the yeast and hops work really well together . excellent nose . t : wow . d : very nice beer . still excellent beer all around .  exquisite in appearance !  the mouthfeel is light carbonation , somewhat on the watery side , but very drinkable .

s - a lot going on but still well balanced . smells of citrus ( maybe orange ) and pine , along with some winter `` spices .  a perfect pour into an oversized wine glass with rich deep amber body a tightly formed thick white head , i could not find any reason to not give a perfect score.tropical fruity hops in the nose with a little boozy and caramel sweetness , overripe mango and pineapple on the palate with again some sweetish booze , the malt base is quite dry underneath the hops and sweet booze.a nice dipa , one of the best pours for me ... ever .  i have had ipas that went down a bit smoother but this one is n't bad it still goes down good but with just a little more carbonation and bite .

the smell is very potent . vanilla , cocoa , brown sugar , port wine . rich , sweet vanilla mixed with tart flavor that almost resembles a lambic ( kinda like ommegang 's three philosophers 2 % cherry lambic effects the overall pallet of that beer ) .  this beer is absolutely stunning in appearance .  the mouthfeel however is slightly taut . body is clear red copper with sustained carbonation .

pretty tasty with a great aroma .  first of all this is an amazing looking beer . a nice pale orange , hazy , with a huge rocky white head . great retention and that belgian lace that i love .  as with several anchor offerings , i feel the carbonation is a bit overdone , but is n't powerful enough to be overly distracting .

smell is on the sweet side but hoppy as well , sweet bubblegum scent , weed , juicy citrus and a malt punch , great scent . taste is enjoyable , alot of different things balancing sweet and hoppy in that order with the above mentioned scents going into the taste without the weed .  pours black with virtually no light around the edges . towering cap of light brown foam that grew on the pour like one of those ash-growing snake things from a fireworks stand . retention is great , as is the lacing .  very carbonated feel on the tongue .

the smell- incredible . at first , very sweet smelling- hints of pineapple . for such a strong beer , it finishes very abruptly , leaving you with just a tad of malt . overall , incredible .  the beer pours beautiful . great head and retention .  m - a little thin for my liking . the body is quite thin , almost watery .

s- smells almost exactly like a liqueur-filled chocolate . chocolate covered raisins . a little marshmallow .  pours a clear dark brown with superior side lacing and a copious tan head with very good retention . appearance is exceptional .  the feel is the only drawback here . it was rather light in body , and thin feeling . carbonation was adequate , but it just lacked that `` near medium '' that i would expect from a dipa .

great hop bouquet -- sweet and juicy , with citrus highlights laid over a smooth backbone of stonefruit ( mostly red ; think cherries , plums , grapes ) , and a little oak . i really like the aroma this beer puts out . the body of the beer is a lovely dark amber color that tinges toward straw around the edges of the glass .  bottle holiday wine cellar escondido , ca black as can be with a thick , persistent light brown head . perfection !  ) i would like a little more bready/chewiness as the mouthful feels a tad more thin than what i 'd prefer for this style .

not much in the way of smell except a little sweetness .  this brew is quite hazy with a golden orange body . the head produced is massive and bright white .  the mouthfeel , i was not so impressed with .

s : the aroma is fantastic . natural lemon scent and orange zest , mostly lemon .  11.2 oz , 2007 bottle a : deep brown , not quite black under a nice sized tan head . excellent lace and retention .  mouthfeel if very alive and crisp at first sip . maybe a bit overpowering on the carbonation .

murky , fluffy smells ... well , wheaty and sweety ! the perfect hefe .  poured into a chalice a- huge huge huge frothy merangue like , sand colored head rises way above the rim of the glass . it has incredible stay with incredible lacing . the beer is a murky and clouded dark brown/umber .  m : average , nothing of note .

s - toasted leather , dark malts , smoked peat , sorghum , liquid smoke , iron minerals , strange herb perfume aroma , hickory wood chips . t - watered down liquid smoke , roasted malts , toasted sugars , unknown fruit character barely sneaks out among the savory smoked meat flavor .  i 'm very impressed with this beers look .  the largest macro beer in the country is very disappointing . the feel of this beer is somewhat thin but i liked the bock feel that it had .

smell is rather striking and unique . slight hints of spice most likely from the chilles , with a really sweet grainy hop note .  bourbon colored with an excellent 3 finger head that rises a good 1/4 inch above the glass . very foamy head that last a long , long time .  the beer feels light but not watery . there is a little prickle on the tongue at the swallow .

a-pours a cloudy orange ... i 'm docking points because pilsner 's should have good clarity ... also excessive head ... s-outstanding aroma ... spicy , floral and somewhat fruity ... very inviting and the type of beer you could sit and smell all day long . but i found it an exciting , and tasting brew ... .one of the best smelling beers i have ever experienced .  firstly , i dont know if the nitro can should be listed alongside the on-tap version , because they are completely different , as the on tap version is far superior than the widget-can . anyway , if kept well , the pour is the classic we have all come to know and love .  somewhat smooth feel , moderate-medium body for amber , but still feels a little thin .

aroma : heavenly . roasted malt , chocolate , a hint of coffee , and i detected a hint of whiskey aroma that was very pleasant . taste and mouthfeel : slightly chewy but not quite creamy .  served in a pilsner glass a : pours a deep mahogany color that looks thick . pours with very thick white head and leaves considerable lacing s : very sweet smelling brew possibly of cherries .  m : crisp feel at first , mellows gradually before eventually becoming a little sticky/gummy . light-medium body .

smells creamy/milky with rich , almost sweet coffee , chocolate , kaluha , cocoa , and a touch of green hops . absolutely divine . the flavor is roasty with burnt/charred malts , coffee , chocolate , and a medium bitterness .  a - two fingers of off-white head slowly fade on top of a gorgeous translucent amber beer with bubbles rising steadily through it s - smell is a juicy blend of citrus and apricot , grapefruit is most prominent but plenty of orange zest comes through , apricot is muted and there 's a little bit of mint and pine in there too , do n't get too much aroma from the malts , a touch of toffee maybe t - flavor is far too muted considering that the beer is so appealing to the eyes and the nose , a touch of sweetness , a lot of hop bitterness , some grapefruit and orange , some apricot , but so subdued m - nice tongue coating from the hops but the carbonation is a little prickly , not as smooth as it could be o - not a bad ipa , not a great ipa .  mouthfeel is a little lacking ; like i said , this bottle had very little to no carbonation , so i might need to try again . overall , though , a very tasty sweet high abv winter seasonal that i wo n't mind drinking again to `` research the carbonation .

smell is fantastic ! nothing but chocolate covered toffee in the nose , the lightest bit of roastiness , and a hint of nuttiness . i love it .  a- damn sexy looking in my pilsner glass . it sits atop a slightly hazed , deep red almost apple cider colored body .  the mouthfeel was lowly carbonated .

a special cask tapped last night at the j. clyde . s : an absolute explosion of floral and citrus hop aromas -- it smelled dipa-esque . a rich crackery malt backbone is evident , as well . a solid offering , and if gpbc decided to make the aroma of this beer into a car air freshener , i 'd be all over that .  beautiful pour . bits of sediment floating around . nice creamy tan head that remained throughout with gorgeous lacing .  mouthfeel : medium body and a finish that is a bit dry . this beer almost flat .

the aroma is nothing short of amazing . it immediately presents with big raisin , molasses , strawberry , and bubblegum . i have had most of the unibroue beers , but this was really outstanding even for them .  dark chocolate brown with a nice , thick , creamy , khaki head atop .  m - the reason i dinged it on mouthfeel is because it actually left some of that nasty coffee-mouth feeling in my gullet .

huge pumpkin aroma with a bit of spice not unlike pumpkin pie ( which i was eating with it ! ) . my wife loves pumpkin and is not much of a beer drinker and really liked this beer .  this brew pours out a deep , hazy red amber color crested with a massive head that retains very well and leaves huge , sticky lacing .  lighter body than i thought it would be with with very low carbonation..the weakest point of the brew . easy drinker for the abv and ignoring the mouth feel , a nice brew .
s - mild lemon and yeast .  great amber apperance with thick ass head that will not stop clinging to the glass .  the mouthfeel is light with a decent amount of carbonation .

pumpkin pie spice is felt throughout and makes it absolutely wonderful . absolutely amazing . going into this , i knew that southern tier made some great beers . i had no idea this would be one of their best !  glassware - imperial pint appearance - dark amber/red in color , which makes sense . nice two finger white head that leaves a lot of really great lacing on the glass .  brownish gold beer straight out of a 40 ounce bottle . sugary sweet flavors of corn and grain . it 's not something i 'll buy very often . milwaukee 's best 40s are cheaper and taste better , even if they do n't have that signature bottle shape .

aromas were fantastic : bready , citrus-fruit and cloves were wonderfully balanced . it was not too strong , but the aromas were apparent .  poured - beautiful dark color .  it is astringent and medicicnal .

the nose on this thing is awesome . complex sweet fruits , sultanas and figs , some ginger , brown sugar , earth and alcohol .  pours a beautiful slightly hazy amber color with a large two inch off white head . excellent retention and some great lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied to me . could be a little thicker on the tongue .

really delicious . 5 t : malty chocolate with some tangy fruit character from the blueberry .  a careful pour produces a robust , sandy colored , three-finger head with excellent retention and lacing .  m - a little on the thin side .

( s ) - a ridiculously rich aroma . awesome whiffs of oaky bourbon with sweet toffee and caramel with an even more glorious smell of cocoa covered dark cherries behind it . its strong , but smells really stinking good .  but wow , this one looks amazing ! a gorgeous burgundy with beautiful creamy froth on top .  nice floral hops and malt starchiness in the finish . it 's a drinkable beer . heavy in the stomach .

pale golden body that 's slightly hazy . aroma : pale malty grain , light , vegetal hoppiness with a little tart citrus ( lemon ) in play . kinda mild . drinkability : decent , cold use a few more complexities in the mouth and nose , particularly in the malt bill .  this looks absolutely beautiful .  the only complaint i have is that the texture left much to be offered . overall i great beer .

'' -- review from the growler ... .dark brown color with a small tan head ... .awesome aroma of fresh picked and mashed blueberries along with a sweet chocolate aroma ... the nose it top notch ... body is a bit light ... not horribly so but i wish it had a bit more meat to it ... taste is a bit acidic from the blueberries..the cocoa complements nicely but is definitely secondary ... .  this beer poured a black body with a thick dark tan/black head . a beautiful sight to see .  the taste was very light and highly carbonated . overall i 'm really surprised at all the negative reviews of this beer . maybe it 's just the fact i had it on tap , or that it was fresh .

above average head retention & lacing s : lemony with white pepper & orange peel t : follows the nose , also some breadyness & candi sugar , apple peels & general spiceyness up front . finishes with apple peel , lemony & herbal hops & a lovely spiceyness & just a bit of grapefruit at the apex mf : medium bodied , lively carbonation , very nice balance superb drinkabilty i could stay on this all night !  black with reddish tints if you look hard enough . looks really good . fluffy foam settles to a thick , dense mass .  mouthfeel is decent , this beer seems to foam up in your mouth .

exceptional aroma . very hoppy , and you get it at the first sip , then the sweetness , finishes bitter , with all the hops of an ipa but more subdued .  a toasted head has great retention and lace .  the beer seems to thin a bit in the mouthfeel . very clean beer for a triple , slightly thin in the mouthfeel , but that helps give this beer a nice clean dry finish .

smells amazing . the pine and citra form a wave of hoppy goodness .  perfect head retention and plenty of lacing left behind in the glass .  the middle is kind of hoppy , but somewhat thin . the finish is dry and quite hoppy . a decent light beer .

this is quite possibly the sweetest smelling beer i 've ever sniffed .  hopback pours a beautiful cloudy dark copper with an ample beige head .  t - again , bicuit and nut . nice and malty , virtually no hop bite , but tasty none the less . d - i have had this a ton in the past , but i only just got around to getting another one for the purposes of reviewing .

quite delicious , but not quite as good as the nose led me to believe . m. thin with a good level of carbonation d. i was a bit disappointed with the taste after the incredible smell , but the mouthfeel is really what let me down here .  amazing looking beer .  a- blackness with a espresso colored head s- coffee beans ground soaked in licorice coffee and dark chocolate really bold t- straight up coffee and espresso with bitter chocolate and a slight tang finish m- medium carbonation and a bit watery for the style d- i drink 3 cup of coffee a day who am i to judge ?

man this was incredible . citrusy herbal if i had to put some words on it .  a- glourious golden yellow with a fluffy and foamy white head that retains well in the tulip glass . dies to a fluffy ring and nice cloud that leaves thick lace all along the glass .  body is perhaps the one less thanexcellent area , as its a little too light and i would have preferred something heavier and slicker ( more like the maui offering ) .

complex and strong aroma of wild flowers , banana , orange and coriander .  makes a great looking beer for sure .  it may not be for everyone but i think this is a beautiful product . flavor is far less sweet than the smell and look might hint , in fact this is gobs of sour black cherry . it 's an instant classic and one of only a handful of lambics i 've liked so far .

the smell is lovely grapefruit essence from the hops , and a small malt offset ; what an anticipatory aroma ! the malt influence is quite mild ; this is all about the hops , which i 've come to learn is n't always a grand thing .  huge four fingers of bright white , soapy head .  the mouth is a tiny bit like flat soda which was the only off-putting part of this beer .

it smells awesome and makes my mouth water just anticipating the first taste !  poured black with a thick brown head . the retention was great . very creamy and capuccino like looking head .  mouthfeel : the body is oddly thin , and crisp .

i 'll tell you that the smell is freaking awesome . have n't tasted the beer yet , but smells of good things to come ... here we go . s - freaking awesome . especially since i considered this some bland , flavored light beer t - nice .  the beer poured a hazy golden color with a massive white head .  mouth feel was pretty average , smooth , not very complex so i expected a little more from it in that department .

very hoppy taste . right away you can smell the cascade hops which it smells like its been dry hopped . hopefully i bought an older six pack  the appearence is exceptional . pours a stout lovers favorite color , motor oil black . less than a finger of head , but it is a very dark brown .  m : the thinnest , lightest imperial i can remember , but the intensity doesnt have to be overpowering .

smells ... bad . for a lambic , offensive smells dominate the currant .  a - gigantic frothy head that is the color of latte foam . the head lingers for an eternity and leaves a mountain of foam in the middle after it has dissipated to constant level . top notch look for a red . looks good though .  more watery flavored than i expected from this ... very light mouthfeel .

the smell is aggressive , and with high standard , quite classic . a vanilla character from the oak treatment adds nicely to the vibrant sweet malty caramel butterscotch toffee brown sugar molasses notes . really nice ! ! the flavor is quite nice as it reflects the nose yet has a surprisingly black licorice thing going on , especially in the really enjoyable aftertaste .  a- looks perfect . ruby amber with a one inch head that only fades after drinking and leaves some nice lacing .  this is very malty at the opening with a twinge of caramel . upon downing it , the taste resembles a very dark beer . very malty with heavy caramel presence that makes it a bit sweet . it also gives a bitter character that mellows into a sweetened deal . i 'll have to try it from the mug in the near future . it may turn out differently due to more carbonization released , making it less bitter , dare i venture to say . but , straight from the bottle , it is easier to imbibe if you 're used to dark , bitter ales .

amazingly complex . taste follows nose and begins with dark malts and honey sweetness .  looks like a magazine beer ad . beautiful clear , light , orange-amber color .  taste was pretty balanced with a bit of malt sweetness . overall i liked this one . this is the first beer i have tried from boulder . based on this one , i 'll have to try some of the others that we can get in ct . the website says that a secret spice is added , but i can not really taste any spice . maybe i 'll figure it out by the time i finish the six . good brew .

s - toffee , cocoa powder , nutty , then as it warms sweet citrus oil , green pine needles . slabs of caramel mix with alcohol vapors and fill the glass with a robust sweetness . t - starts with a mix of semi/sweet chocolate , sweet toffee malt , then an undertow of hops rush in with mint and citrus . the aroma is so good it 's hard to explain .  a - caramel-butterscotch gold with a thick off-white head , very nice looking .  m : slick mouthfeel with a medium amount of carbonation that can be prickly at times . body is medium and has a bit of resiny stickiness to it .

the aroma was quite exceptional . never before have i whiffed this nose of smoke in a beer .  great `` belgian '' lacing & very good head retention smell : sourness & then woody , lactic notes .  it feels very thin in the mouth , close to water .

if you like hops , you 'll like this . it is overloaded with hops , but very very tasty .  based on notes poured into a thistle glass with an effervescent amber with 4 fingers of rocky eggshell colored head . great lacing & head retention s : ever-so slight sweet berry smell t : malty , fruittyness , a hint of warming boozeyness up front .  it has little to no head on it with a soft pour . this beer has a good balance of spices that is not overpowering . the aftertaste is mellow . this is one of the darker ales that i have drank but all in all i would give it another try . especially on a snowy winter day .

the smell is fruity and funky sweet . tons going on here in addition to the funkiness of the brett .  pouring a deep black with ruby tinting around the edges , out of bounds also has a creamy , tan head which gives way to an attractive , spotted lacing .  like chocolate carbonated corn syrup . body is light and watery ... good carbonation level helps it feel thicker than it is and hints at being creamy .

flower essence , hop oil , a touch of malt balances out the smell nicely . taste and mouthfeel- much of the same that is in the smell is evident in the taste as well .  this alt looked fantastic ! has a rich , deep , clear chestnut color , with a very fine light tan head topping off at about 1 '' . the head dissipates at a very slow rate , and leaves top-shelf lacing .  the body was only medium , this was not unexpected as it is an ipa style , but i though it could have done with a bit extra .

down to my last g'knight so i felt the need to review this beauty and hopefully it wo n't be long before i can get more . i 'll never forget the first time i popped one of these open , the smell was amazing , i could drink it straight from the can . pure sweetness in the nose , a bit of resiny hops , caramel , cake , so sweet you can taste it .  this beer pours exceptionally well for a three finger thick cranium in a light tan color .  the mouthfeel is medium , slightly watery .

smell is excellent and unique . predominate smell i get is apricot .  a : nice brown body with a fluffy 1+ finger head that lasted forever .  incredibly light with cereal grains , very grainy taste , hops are nowhere in site . there are way better summer beers out there .
no aroma at all , as with most shed beers .  beautiful , beautiful honey color with a thick , but not creamy , head .  m : a touch thin .

s - wow , what a blast of aromas : floral notes , pine and citrus smack you in the face . t - it tasted of spicy , piney hops with a sweet , burnt toast maltiness . it is extremely hoppy and fairly easy drinking considering the high abv .  huge sticky head alone has a personality all its own . gorgeous golden haze pour that has no room for improvement , while in a class all its own .  md-light body and sharp moderate carbonation . foamed pretty good going down the drain .

aroma was ridiculously appealing - sweet malt , caramel , maple , vanilla , oak , some dark fruit , and alcohol . wow . d - this was a sipper , but drinkability benefited from the fact that it tasted so damn good .  dissipates slowly and exhibits great retention with beautiful lacing .  ) it has very low carbonation witch makes the mouthfell very average with about that of a tap bud lite , only a little tingle from the carbonation .

aroma : coffee and chocolate malt meld accented by a whiff of hops and a touch of smoke . nice complexity and balance leads to a very appealing invitation . overall impression : thick and creamy with a wonderful nose . unfortunately the taste just didnt live up to the billing .  frickin ' a beautiful . deep and black , medium head of nice and tight dark tan bubbles . no effort required to get it and even going vigorously on the pour it seems like there 's not a crazy amount of head . beautiful .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too syrupy , though it does n't detract much at all from the enjoyment of the beer .

smell & gt ; sweet and resiny . a perfect balance of the two scents without much alcohol heat .  the head poured out at 1.5 fingers and stays that way forever in a rocky , creamy form that just refuses to recede . gorgeous appearance .  smell was sweet , with a citrus hint and strong english ale smell . initial taste was interesting , and i was n't sure about whether i would like it . by the end of the bottle , it had become one of the best beers i 've tasted . i would n't recommend it for any parties , but in small groups of like minded people i would say good call . very drinkable beer . looking forward to trying more from the brewery ( if i can find it )

extremely fruit-fillled aromatics - pungent apple sauce notes lead the way into a more diverse array of stone-fruit esters . lush oaky notes with a touch of bergamot in the finish - complexity grows as the beer warms . i 'm still impressed that the base beer can be improved upon by soaking up the best characteristics of the barrels it is aged in , but these special editions of harvest ale have certainly `` matured '' more than simply `` aged .  excellent lacing . great looking ipa .  taste is dominating by anis with some candi sugar . body was above average and alcohol was well hidden .

s : nice sweet smell , but not too complex .  body was black as night with a tan head .  the beer is somewhat oxidized , but still highly drinkable very light bodied bitter , true to the the style . this is a prime candidate for a session beer . at 3.8 % abv , it 's alcohol content makes this a clear choice for something that could literally be consumed all day long , starting with your pancakes !

this is , to date , the finest smelling pilsner i 've had .  poured from the bottle into a sam adams sensory glass . a : a beautiful pillowy head sits atop a clear , deep brownish copper , with great carbonation . perfect and appetizing .  nothing special here .

s - smell is terrific and pops way more than a lot of nitro beers i 've had .  a - very nice lacing left by a frothy white head with strong stamina on top of a copper colored and translucent body . i even witnessed the bartender pouring some head away .  medium-bodied , maybe just a little bit thin .
nose : mulled apple cider . sweet and fruity .  appearance : pitch black with a thick foamy lasting head that laces nicely .  mouthful : somewhat over-carbonated but generally decent mouthfeel .

body was cloudy and amber aroma was outstanding . moderate hoppiness and perfume .  a : beautiful pour from this 440ml nitro can . bright copper with a thick , creamy white head . great lacing left behind .  drinks a little heavy because of all the sediment but feels watery and thin on the palate . adequate carbonation but not incredible lively .

very rich and interesting smells . tastes almost apple-y with more spices from the nose continuing .  a beautiful site setting in the glass , this blackberry to almost brown elixir of life , the head gargantuan in size , creamy in texture , the color a light chocolate brown , the residual lace a thick clinging sheet .  boosting the carbonation would help .

the aroma of berry funk with a hint of crust that smells delicious . the appearance is rich pinot wine color with a white head and tons of berry sediment floating on top .  looks beautiful and inviting !  very light bodied , but carbonation seems too low to me .

pours q light clear bmc ylliw . nose is plain of rice and malt . light and malty it 's very and bad worth skippng and bland skip it !  the appearance is amazing . it pours really really dark brown , safe to say black . it leaves a thick lacing around the glass that is very very intimidating .  m - a little thin , sickly-sweet finish .

smell has an odd soy sauce present , missing the dark fruit aroma and roasted malt that is usually a part of it .  into a tulip . pours the closest to motor oil i 've ever seen in a beer , dark crimson/brown head , dense retention and heavy legs .  mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .

very nice nose . sipping is quite sweet . however , this was much more than i was expecting ; very nice .  it has a gold cloudy body with a beautiful head and just the right amount of carbonation from an aesthetic point of view . it is a simply picture perfect beer .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin , spicy , moderately dry , and has a distinct saison flavor in the aftertaste .

s - about 0.2 seconds after the cork popped , the air was almost filled with a rich , dry oak smell . lots of brett in there as well .  pour was exceptional . the head rose faster than expected , and shot over the top of the mug - but it did n't overflow .  smooth and to the point , bit of a sweet aftertaste in the sweet sticky beer way .

the smell is exceptional . it smells like candy the mouthfeel is really smooth , and not very thick .  1-fingered extremely light tan head with very impressive retention , leaves rings of lace all the way down the glass .  mouthfeel - a little gritty , though a light body to it .

the smell is utterly fantastic , easily one of the best smelling beers i 've ever come across .  appearance : pours the color of a tripel ; that burnt golden orange appearance . head is gigantic and rocky which dissipates slowly into a thick rocky soapy lacing that clings to the glass tenaciously and refuses to let go . it even have yeast in the bottle which i found out on the last pour of my bomber . so really proper looking for an imperial ipa and the color of a tripel . i 'm giving this a 5 ! its a beautiful beer smell : this a very hoppy beer .  mouthfeel : a little slick , thinner on the palate than i expected drinkability : a fine porter , would definitely drink again .

taste is a bit of a let down compared to the amazing aroma . a really good ipa .  drinking it in a pint glass poured from a 12 oz bottle ... huge , thick head . awesome . beer is opaque and black .  m : medium to light bodied . feels a touch watery .

aroma is wonderful . incredibly intense malt tones and a nice sweetness detected .  appearance - pours dark enough to block out all light . a big bubbled mocha head springs up and i have to quell the pour a bit to calm things down . it caps off and forms a nice creamy cover with large spacious bubbles of foam below it .  mouthfeel : medium body , a bit chalky , tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

s- nice nutty aromas , butterscotch , caramel , high end rum notes . this makes me smile . t- starts out a nice light dry chocolate , some nutty notes , light caramel , and some light dry hoppiness on the clean finish .  pours a ruby brown with a creamy beige head . excellent lacing and retention .  m - medium body , with moderate to high carbonation . a bit too carbonated for my liking . slightly thin , would like a bigger body from a stout . the mouthfeel is lacking , and sweet flavors of vanilla and chocolate make it too much like a dessert beer , one is all you need .

this was strange beer for me , i could taste all kinds of hops , but little evidence of hops smell , i checked my nose against some other household items ( soap , candle & pepper they all checked out normal ) , so here goes : appearance : thick white fluffy head , with great head retention . smell : presence of malt and honey and lurking way in the background , some hops . mouthfeel : optimum carbonation combined great hops and malt balance very drinkable , i still recommend this one despite the hops aroma being awol  appearance - pours with a nice , clear golden head , some dark reddish hues provide a little tint . two fingers of whity rocky head with a crusty top and lots of good stick .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and resinous , this is really the only fault i can find .

unbelievable . taste , too has a very pronounced graham cracker taste in it , along with pumpkin , of course .  say what you will about guinness ; yes , i know they 're a bunch of gimmick happy corporate whores , but one thing is undeniable ... there is no other beer on the planet , that looks , smells , or tastes , like a guinness on tap . the cascading effect is awesome . for the first third of the glass it leaves a solid wall of lace all the way around without a break in it . held to the light it 's surprisingly clear and reveals a fiery red hue .  for the mouthfeel , i found this stout almost watery in consistency .

a - very good , very light golden orange - pretty decent head retention s - the most unique citrus nose of any dipa i 've ever encountered . upfront dried fruit basket and grapefruit blast to the senses . i can pick out the citra hops , that for sure . bitter dry , crisp finish . very , very good beer .  big firm plush head , one of the most impressive i have ever seen . opaque black hue as expected .  m : full bodied and creamy , the slightest touch of carbonation and a smooth , somewhat watery finish .

very vibrant fruity/floral aroma with a hint of peat , grain and sweet caramel malt . all these blend perfectly together to make a fantastic aroma . certainly the best aspect of this beer . it tastes very much like the aroma - fruity berry , white grape flavors with a little herbal spiciness . the flavors are n't as rich as the aroma would suggest . a really nice beer overall . i genuinely enjoyed it , but i only with the flavors were richer .  a - pours nice black and huge heavy sticky head .  do not know if this was an aberation , but this caused a lower score in mouthfeel .

the aromas promise a dandy ; juicy dark fruit ester , roasted coffee , pineapple , chocolate powder and molasses , and hints of bubble gum . a silky mouthfeel , slightly oily , and a sharp carbonation that does n't bite too hard is quite enjoyable . dark fruits , plum , sweet tobacco notes and some coffee and cocoa but not like the nose indicated .  solid finger of brown , almost black head . incredibly dark body with nice lace . darkest head i 've seen .  i 've always liked this beer , and if they beefed up the abv and gave it a little more body , it would be the perfect porter . why grant 's beers share these characteristics i do n't know , but if they ever did beef 'em up a little , they could truly be a contender .
really great nose !  dark brown pour with a solid tan head .  mouthfeel is rather thin and average .

it smells distinctly like pineapple cake . i mean you get the sweet pineapple and a really bready smell underneath . probably my favorite smell in a beer ever , different than the norm for an apa . definitely does n't live up to the smell but i enjoy it . the carbonation level is good and there is n't really a harsh aftertaste . there certainly is n't anything off-putting , and i would recommend it to anyone , at least for the sake of smelling it .  a : what a great looking stout . deep brown color with an extremly silkey 1/2 '' head that slowly disipates into lacing s : roasted malt t : grain sweet ness and roasted malts m & d : mouth feel was medium and dry .  seems a bit thin , with very soft carbonation .

incredibly clean , with absolutely no imperfections in the malting or hops . extremely delicate . the flavor is incredibly clean .  this one pours a dark muddy brown that shows some ruby highlights when held to light . the beer is topped by a nice frothy khaki head that lasts and leaves beautiful lacing .  m : thinner than i expected , pretty fair amount of carbonation , once again a little more reminiscent of a porter than a stout .

small amount of lace around the edges s : roasted coffee and dark chocolate hit the nose first . very sweet smelling , as well as the presence of alcohol t : initially it was more bitter then i expected from the aroma .  great pour , huge amount of foam , thins out to lace the outer edge of the beer . dark brown in color , yet the beer itself is light , meaning not as thick as you would expect it .  body is a little thin .

s : a very sweet and complex nose here . lots of caramel , toffee , dates , figs , raisins , and wood . t : not quite as impressive as the nose , but still damn good . lots of caramel , bourbon , oak , and apple .  a - a mildly assertive pour yields a bubbly two-finger head with decent retention and frothy lacing down the glass . really a nice looking beer .  it was pretty smooth for stout and for for the alcohol content . i tried it with a few other beers .

mesmerizing , really .  pours a glorious deep , garnet-tinged amber color , with a thick , creamy , sticky , cream-colored head on top .  trying to think of a sweet red wine , not one i can place , but its defintely tannic , bitter and sweet ... the taste is super interesting , not say its good , but interesting . chocolate wine comes to mine , light feel though . what i do know is that 8 months is too long as it totally changes the beer into something new losing almost all stout character .

s - the spicy , phenolic aroma hit me as soon as i opened the bottle , and once the beer has a chance to open up in the glass it expands into notes of chocolate , dark cherries , raisins , almonds , pepper , cinnamon , and lots of clove . d - very complex beer that manages to avoid being overbearing despite the high alcohol and big flavors . the smell is absolutely spectacular , reminds me of samichlaus , but more interesting . the flavor is quite interesting as well , and i really like the way it finishes , but there is something about the initial sweetness or phenolic character that i find a little cloying .  appearance : cloudy golden yellow with an amazing , big , billowy head that last all the way through the beer , incredible lacing too which sticks all over the glass . the best looking tripel i 've ever seen .  its a bit thicker on the palate than american crap beer , but it 's your basic `` serve cold , swill it down , catch a buzz '' beer for the masses .

the smell was exceptional and exciting , with a remarkable variety of spicy tones that are too complex to describe . with great anticipation , i tried the first sip , which was heavenly . and then it happened ... a nasty aftertaste that i could n't quite place but did n't like .  pours to a bright copper color with thick white head that lingers throughout , and slowly diminishes to a white foam cap with excellent lacing .  again , dried dark fruit seems to be the dominating taste , and as it warms , a sweet cherry-like flavor comes in m : at first i found this beer a bit too prickly and highly carbonated for my liking ; i purposely agitated the beer by swirling and enjoyed it a bit more when carbonation was less severe great beer that i would drink anytime i needed a belgian fix .

its smell is its best characteristic -- floral hops , malty , a hint of wheat -- really beautiful . the taste is sweety & malty , as well as bitter .  brillient , copper penny colored pour with a full , thick head of near white froth that retains and laces very nicely . just the way i want my ipa to look .  m - a little thin-bodied and watery and a little low on the carbonation .

no real discernible nose , slight slight hops .  presentation : it poured beautifully into an oversized wine glass . coming out of the bottle it was an amber color , but in the glass it turned to a deep , dark maroon .  m - the hops lingered a bit too long and had a metallic feel at times .

s : coffee ice cream cones ? like a joy ice cream cone , and a mild coffee . only beer yet to give me that . m : creamy , creamy and creamy . imperial anyone ? t : i 'll start with a heavy dark chocolate to start .  appearance this beer is absolutely gorgeous . the body is a dark , orangish-brown and murky with lots of carbonation and had a bountiful , brownish-white head that was full without exploding and pitted well on top of the liquid leaving some awesome , shaving cream foam around the edges of my pint glass .  mouthfeel is a little too tingly for me with the carbonation .

s : a rich citrus , piney hop aroma is released when you open the bottle and once in the glass that 's all you can smell . sweet grapefruit - fantastic smell . t : unfortunately the smell seems more powerful than the taste which seems a bit on the light side .  22oz bottle ... a : a deep very dark ruby colored with a huge 2+ inch tan head that fades at a decent pace .  it was an average imperial stout with a thin mouthfeel made exciting with some fruit .

no aroma whatsoever , even right up under my nose .  the appearance is truly exceptional . rediculously dark . not even allowing for the amber edges that many stouts boast when backlit , this one is impenetrable to light . a gorgeous head that ranges in color between milk and dark chocolate .  a bit thin , but a very good stout flavor develops in the mouth . i 'd have preferred a bit fuller body .

absolutely amazing grapefruit , lemon , and orange aroma . also has a touch of sweet toffee and vanilla . this was a beautiful hazy golden pour , with typical cask frothy head . very well balanced flavor , then a wonderful dry bitter finish . this is an amazing brew , and the cask only adds to it .  2011 batch 1 - 750ml bottle poured into a cbs snifter a : black as night . gorgeous finger-and-a-half dark brown head that leaves a nice full cap throughout consumption .  m - fairly zesty and zingy carbonation that left me feeling a touch bloated after a third of a glass . medium-light body that also has a bit of grain character .

this has to be one of the most interesting beers on the nose ~ lots of malty rye mixing it up with a bready note , lots of spice ( a mild chai cocktail - mostly clove ) , some green spruce notes ( probably juniper berries ) and gobs of orange and lemon zest . overall a beer that really smells great , tastes pretty good , and finishes nicely .  a : beautiful head about 2 fingers thick that never goes below a half finger thick , ever . golden/amber in color , looks like honey . honestly , one of the best looking ipas ever .  the mouthfeel is a little lacking in carbonation too .

s- jeepers creepers there 's some bugs in there . super sour and funky with lots of acidity in the nose . t- so sour and tart with tons of acidity . bright brilliant sour cherries , strawberries and underipe plums .  this beer pours an inky black with a dark brown head .  like drinking sour grass , probably the best way to put it m - low carbonation , slightly astringent d - not very drinakble , i had to leave a third of it

smell : piney hops , citrus ( grapefruit , peach and pineapple ) . overall : the aroma was out of this world . it 's very much like an ipa . just did n't seemed very well balanced .  a : black on top , fades to reddish/brown at the bottom when held up to the light . nice lacing . a real gem .  mouthfeel is not too bad , sharpness coming more from the carbonation than hops .

aroma : incredibly aromatic , rich bitter chocolate , fresh roasted coffee beans , smoked oak chips , burnt caramel , woody .  a 1/2 '' medium brown head takes a very long time to fade to a thick film . lacing is impressive , lots of thick , clingy curtains stick around for a while and eventually fade to thin strings that were still there when i went to wash the glass off .  out of all of the blueberry beers i have had i would have to say this is probably my favorite . very fruity with a somewhat dry finish to it . the blueberries are definitely the star of the show . overall this is a very drinkable beer and makes a great summer brew .

s : smell is awesome . so complex for a stout which are normally one dimensional . coffee and dark unsweetened cocoa powder , whiskey/bourbon and even some woody notes that are muted .  found this one at julios randomly ... a : awesome look .  mouthfeel was medium with a bite in front and back and made the roof of my mouth tickle ( odd ) .

5.0 s : this is my absolute favorite type of dipa , i can tell already . it has a malt bill that can stand up to the hops in flavor and complexity . hops are citrusy with emphasis on orange and grapefruit . malts are full of caramel flavor and dark fruitiness like a barleywine . i did n't know what the hell i was tasting . the malts were a big disappointment as it was n't as complex as i would have liked . mainly just has the caramel flavor . 4.5 d : i would definitely like to have this been again , but not too often since it 's quite expensive .  it poured a beautiful copper color with lots of bubbles coming up from the bottom of my beer-clean glass . the beer had abundant head that agressively stuck to the side of my glass and slowly and inconsistently faded , starting from the middle of my glass . this beer really was quite attractive .  i can feel it in my cheeks . it does n't have any off aromas specifically , but it definitely has the acidity for it . undrinkable , i 'm pouring it out .

aroma is mostly complex stages of hops , it 's easy to believe there are 10 varieties , there 's the big american c hops character combined with the refined english ones . very relaxing to sniff on and ultra-complex , like a touch of vanilla on fresh citrus ( grapefruit ) . in mouth this dances on the tongue , nice effervescence , creamy , full-bodied , complex malt sweetness and an obvious balancing yeastiness . this is a delicious big generous beer . tasting this with my buddy martint , we came to the conclusion that given the choice to pick only 2 beers from a same brewery to have an infinite supply of , hotd with fred and adam would probably win over quite anyone .  it has a deep , copper/mahogany color with stunning clarity and a beautiful head . such a nice looking brew !  m : carbonation is a little weak ( especially since i poured moderately , and received an aggressive head ) leaving a mouthfeel thatis not strong enough for me to consider it cask-like . a little watery ... d : all things considered , i really enjoyed this beer .

a - typical brown color that comes with this type of beer ; little to no head retention s - wonderful aroma ; slight caramel and hops ; this is what a brown ale should smell like !  this beer is beautiful . red/amber color with a thick rocky head that clings to the side of the glass . head disappears fast though .  the mouthfeel is larger light with a very , very slight fizz .

the aroma is exceptional ! it has a beautiful array of floral hops which penetrate along with a solid malt scent . the aroma is awesome along with a really good hop and malt flavor .  yeti pours out like the darkest of used motor oils , thick and smooth with a monstrous billowing head that never goes away .  the mouthfeel was medium bodied with adequate carbonation .

the aroma was spectacular , one of the best i have ever been privy to . though the look could use a touch of tinkering , the amazing aroma and depth of flavors more than made up for it . a unique and enjoyable offering unlike any other saison i 've ever had .  it settles slowly in a dramatically lumpy fashion leaving a tremendous amount of chunky and webby lace .  it goes down smooth .

the smell is funky lemon and a hint of the pepper corns .  the beer pours a nice 2-3 finger beige head with great retention and a lot of beautiful lacing on the glass .  best as it warmed , when the malt flavors of chocolale and toffee become a bit more complex and the mouthfeel seems fuller .

it smelled terrible !  a : pours a dark black with a massively thick mocha head that seems to last forever ... excellent lacing throughout .  the only fault is that its a little thin bodied but that 's what makes this brew dangerous .

s - lively lemon oil aroma , very fresh and unique . lots of spicy wheat and slightly fruity yeast . the aroma is spectacular , it smells like oil squeezed out of a fresh lemon peel , though the flavor is not quite as good .  reviewed 1/8/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a golden somewhat cloudy yellowish color . big foamy frothy white head with good lacing .  this beer poured nicely with a creamy white head , giving off nice citrus aromas . the flavor was shocking , however , reminding me of kool-aid orange flavor , and with almost as much sweetness . i could n't distinguish any hop bitterness , though it could have used some to balance out the excessive sweetness . this beer tastes as though all the yeast were filtered out , and then orange kool-aid added post-fermentation

a great aroma greets the nose , with soft cherry fruits and lots of toffee sweetness . a hint of floral & piny hops lingers in the background -- -very barleywine-line , which i enjoy . the flavor has the typical wee heavy malt profile boosted by a vinous barrel note . overall , a great special release from real ale , and probably one of their best beers i 've had to date .  looks really good- reddish amber body , nice pock-marked cream-white head , and active carbonation .  m - moderate carbonation , medium bodied .

y'all can beat me up for it if you like , but for an american macro this is the stuff . i would choose coors over the other two , ab and miller any day . because this macro actually has a little flavor as opposed to the taste of rice or corn . overall , if i was in a bar and had to choose any of the american macros i 'd pick this one .  lovely looking beer , and very similar in appearance to the classic guinness look , with a large creamy tan head on top of a dark body .  the mouthfeel was medium with a syrupy sweetness on the palate .

took a trip down to colorado springs last week , mainly to visit this brewery . aromas of passion fruit , grapefruit and tangerine . medium bodied , and not at all bitter , with flavors of oak , booze and sweet malt .  nice white , foamy head with great retention .  medium bodied , it seems a little flat at the beginning , but there 's sharp carbonation at the finish , which is a little watery and silty .

s- as only a good british beer can smell , luscious . very complex . t/m- ok , the taste lets down a bit after the luscious aroma . a good beer but disappointed that it is n't a great beer .  this beer is excellent , from the moment you open it till the las drop i have tried this beer on tap as well and it is good , the 22 ounce bottle for some reason does not taste the same in my opinion as its 12 ounce brother .  mouthfeel is pretty typical , and if anything is a little undercarbonated or slick .

smell- huge pine , bitter citrus , terpentine ? love it ! big aromas have me very excited about this beer . taste- the pine needle flavor instantly greets me , along with a nice bittersweet malt finish . there is a lot going on here , and i can taste a duality of hops types playing here .  bottled in feb. 2009 , batch # 9 ... appearance : pours a very pretty deep orange , copper ; very clear with tiny bubbles and a huge sticky white head . this is a great looking beer !  the expected lactose or creaminess is absent in the flavor as well as the mouth feel given that this is a milk stout . the carbonation , again , is more soda-like in the mouth instead of frothy or creamy . the drinkability and mouthfeel improved with time as the intensely carbonated head withered away .
this beer actually does n't smell very good . grainy . it tastes much better than the smell .  the appearance made it look superbly delicious .  the mouthfeel is a bit too light for my liking .

this has got to be one the best smelling ipa 's out there . the fruity and hoppy flavours balance out perfectly to leave a tasty , dry , almost graperuit-esque finish which is just fantastic . this beer packs a mighty punch .  first i have to say the appearance is exceptional . the red color is as someone said very similiar to the color of the label .  pretty average mouthfeel overall .

pours dark orangey brown , slightly hazy at first , then extremely cloudy as i pour in some of the yeast dregs . the aroma is huge - sweet brown sugar and honey with floral notes , alcohol and some breadiness . flavors are very aggressive in this fresh form - a huge honey presence meets with the aggressive bittering hops and some dark fruit sherry notes . excellent barley wine , both in its fresh and aged form - a testament to the value of bottle conditioning and cellarable beers .  this beer looks amazing in the glass . extremely rich orangish-copper hue .  the body was light and there was not enough carbonation .

this is a powerfully aromatic ale it hits you the moment you open it . there is a strong candied fruit smell here . candy dates , pineapple , cherry , and a raw tobacco scent . about the most aromatic beer i have smelled in at least a year , maybe more . pliny the younger and three floyds dreadnaught are the only two on the same level of complexity . mouthfeel is good . drinkability is ok .  appearance- 3/4 inch full dirty brown head . dark brown , maybe and off black colored pour . full length lacing sheets plaster the glass . lovely sight .  long , super bitter piney bitterness , aftertaste almost of pine-sol but i love the hop attack . problem is that it 's too sweet and slightly syrupy , especially evident in the middle . a little harsh and unbalanced overall , big beer and it shows .

smells of grains and malts hint of cinnamon .  pours black with a dark brown creamy head . very nice beer to look at .  in the glass , the elderberry dominates . the taste just off , sour in a nasty way , more like rotten fruit than any sort of pleasant tartness which might be expected from the berries . we gave this a decent try to see if it would get better , but in the end just could n't drink it .

the nose of this beer was amazing - grapefruit , orange , mango , and pineapple and pine . the taste is just about as good . wow . mouthfeel was medium and mildly carbonated .  this beer looks perfect . theres not as much smell to this one as others like it .  mouthfeel - a bit too carbonated which overrides the wonderful taste at first .

smell is of bourbon barrels , alcohol and some deep plum and cherry/chocolate on the nose . taste follows with notes of the barrel and a very lingering close ... nice.. good feel and the drinkability is extravagant given the potency , as the alcohol is present on the nose but not on the tongue .  reviewed 11/16/2008 ( tap @ the stables , st. louis , mo ) : very cool presentation in a kasteel glass with a castle on the stem of the goblet-like glass . pours a very dark blood red body , with a lasting frothy pink head .  4.5/5 m : crisp , medium body .

s - wow , really fresh pine aroma . pine needles are also big . the finish is bitter , yet fragrant sap . overall this is very well done .  this one pours a beautiful orange copper color with 3/4 '' off-white head .  picked up a few of these `` oil cans '' at a local liquor mart . this is the only place i 've seen them . i like the regular fosters occasionally , and have fond memories of it from various parties and times in life . after looking at the color , noticed that the can said `` caramel coloring added , '' so nothing real to go by there . i liked this , i guess , but the drinkablility was hampered by a fakey sort of bitterness that did n't hold a candle to the fuller 's and young 's of the world . kind of caught in my throat . i pick up the regular if it 's on special , but for a real bitter , this ai n't it .

really really strong nose - very sweet with notes of baking spices , vanilla , vanilla cake batter , pumpkin . there is also something about it that i 'm not sure i 've ever smelled before ... and i love it . t : lives up to the smell .  liquid is a dark amber topped with a thick finger of brown foam and dense and substantial lacing . carbonation is also very prevalent , making this model stand out much more than previous years . visually stunning .  m - lots of carbonation maybe bordering on too much .

the aroma is awesome , with a big black cherry and dark fruit scent coupled with typical bourbon aromas : vanilla , oak , maple syrup . a very well-crafted beer and a real pleasure .  simply beautiful cascading action that lasts for over a minute ! superb tan head retention that is not going away at all !  mouthfeel : medium and semi-smooth . bottom line : this is one of the most bland beers i 've ever had .

aroma of a quad / stout mix with the figs , plums and spices plus a hint of grape hi-c infused vanilla . full bodied , viscous without being cloying , chewy . the alcohol is amazingly restrained , not even the inherent warmth you 'd expect at this abv level .  the body of hop head poured an absolutly beautiful copper-orange color , with a sizable custard head . retention and lacing were both excellent , thanks to a constant supply of carbonation from below .  the palate is thinner than expected but not bad .

aroma is crisp blend of citrus and hops slightly sweet , wonderful . best part of the beer do do n't drink this on out of the bottle pour it or you will miss out .  the head is big , small bubbles below , big ones in the middle and a nice cream dome on top .  s- smoky wood and scotch , one of the more interesting noses on this beer t- malts , with some nice roasted flavors that come through and then a hit of alcohol m- lighter bodied than expected d- a very interesting and drinkable beer , but one i need to be in the mood for

smell has a great malty dark fig aroma . very warm smell . taste is also very malty .  it 's one of the prettiest beers i 've ever seen ! deep , dark brown with a hint of ruby when held up to strong light . a tan frothy and foamy lasts and lasts , leaving waves of sticky lace on the side of the glass ( artful ) .  an amazing brew . medium strength carbonation with a wonderful complex flavor of hops barley and corn . somewhat similar to pbr , but upper canada has an after taste that pbt ca n't compare with . usually i do n't care for beers to have much of an after taste , but with this brew it 's all good . i would recommend this beer to anyone who can get their hand on it .

with the smell of opening a brand-new gar of rasberry jam . it has a powerful rasberry flavor that overpowers pretty much all the malt flavor .  this beer pours a semi-cloudy pale orange color . the head is an impressive two and a half inches in height , and recedes very slowly into thick , chunky lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and is a bit watery .

very nice scent , potent citrus and floral hops .  a very nice brew that started with an absolutely great black color with an outstanding head and lacing .  it was creamy with an average carbonation level and also average alcoholic strength ( 6.0 % abv ) . overall : awful .

forgot to mention , i hate the bottle a - sweet grassy aroma , grainy biscuts , the subtle sweet is throwing me off , not much of a hop aroma .  looks great ! great color , small head .  mouthfeel is a bit too thin , especially in view of the heavenly head and ample lacing .

smell is sweet molases , carmel , and the like . the taste is ... meh .  looks like a perfect ris : pitch black with barely no brown around the edges , even when held up to a bright light . an incredibly creamy , frothy and sticky dark khaki head forms and sticks around for quite a bit . impeccable .  mouthfeel is a bit thin for my liking .

it 's very drinkable and has a pleasant , subtle mix of grain , hops , and english yeast . the aroma is very muted , even for this style , i just get a little grain dust , but the taste holds lightly caramel barely and gentle , spicy hops that finish the beer out . overall , a great session beer and a rare locally-brewed example of the style .  pours deep burgundy/ with 3 fingers+ of sand/tan colored head . superior lacing & head retention s : chocolate & coffee ( ?  sweet caramel and an herbal bitterness m- clean , but a bit watery with mediocre carbonation d- i do like to drink this beer every now and then .
