a - pours a nice deep inky dark color befitting a proper russian imp stout . s - dry biting hops come through with a dark roasted malt earthiness and just a touch of currant or other earthy dried fruit . not too complex or strong of a smell , though . d - incredibly well-balanced beer whose hops and malt come together in unison .  a rich gold hue with white one-finger head , laces astonishingly well . looks like a good beer .  m - not as thick as i 'd like it to taste considering how rich the smell is . d - very drinkable , with the lighter mouthfeel it 's easier to forget how much you 've had .

anyhow , when you have a need for hops , this one certainly takes care of the fix . aroma , yes , just like it should be- huge citrus , flowers , grapefruit rind , oranges , probably lemons and limes if i was n't diving in so fast . this beer has a nice solid body holding in a creamy , milky nectar thats very smooth . the finish is bitter but smooth , maybe a little woody from all the hops . it only lacks a little malt complexity in the flavor , the malt seems a bit basic but does hold up well to the hop explosion .  opaque black chocolate under a tall creamy mocha head .  the only downside of this beer was the mouthfeel , which was fairly flat and watery , probably due in part to the low % abv .

big fluffy two finger head that wafts the hop aromas well , tons of lace and excellent carbonation . color is a kind of murky dark amber . smells great . i love it , the quintessential california hop heaven . tons of grapefruit cascade , melon , guava , apples , cherries- all with a subtle fresh-cut woodsy pine backbone and soothing aroma of fresh mountain air .  the beer looks really good with a thick brown creamy head , tons of lacing , and a very nice head that lasts and lasts .  m : light to medium bodied and highly carbonated .

smell : absolutely delicious . the hops really fused well with the cedar in this case . love it . taste : it is a very sharp flavor .  pours out a lowly brown and sits a dark crimson-orange in the glass with a large off-white head , great lacings up and down , excellent head retention . sharp as a tack and bright as the sun ; looks great in a tuliped glass ( what does n't ?  m. a little too sticky , it feels syrupy , but without a sweeter taste it fells a little off .

the aroma , which was really the high point of this beer , was quite terrific -- roasty malt with hints of chocolate and black cherries .  2006 appearance , great head and retention . easy to create head .  very basic but very good m= average carbonation and average weight .

s : chocolate covered cherries , vanilla , mocha , amazing ! t : huge vanilla ( a little much for me ) , oak , bakers chocolate , mocha .  l : never seen such a perfect look ; two fingers , lasting foam ; s : pear , citrus , smells like the corsendonk agnus , but with a bit of caramel and celery ; t : as an agnus-addict this taste was a little disappointment ; good , but no more than that ; a bit too sweet and too short of hops/bitterness to complete the taste .  m : finish stays around for quite a while , almost too long , really coats the mouth .

this is good , but it 's a little overrated here . it 's tasty and it smells fantastic . i know real porters have sour ale , but usually that sour ale adds creaminess , here it almost has a coors light sourness ( acrid-overdrive ) to it thats off-putting .  this brew poured a medium head of fine bubbles and left behind a nice lacing as it receded . it has a dark cloudy red brown body and a malty aroma .  m : mouthfeel is a bit thin , considering how robust the initial flavor is .

an isabelline crown persists and leaves luxurious cascades of sandy lacing - those bubbles that stick rest atop viscous legs suggesting snow dusted mountain peaks . aroma is highly potent - it hits you from the moment the seal is popped . brown sugar , high quality aged sherry , vanilla , coconut , dense brown bread , faint clove ... the list goes on . the flavor profile closely follows the aromatics , but everything is present in a lesser degree . lots of flavors come and go - abbreviated tastes of bread crusts , licorice , and dried tropical fruit . the finish is quite nutty and hints at leather as well . almost like an armagnac it is a beer well suited to contemplation . the oak notes contribute a great deal without becoming overwhelming ( brandy barrel angel 's share i 'm lookin ' at you ) . definitely worth seeking out and sticking in the cellar ...  a very appealing looking brew .  if you closed your eyes and smelled this you would think your smelling a good octoberfest beer due to the scent of carmalized malt and faint hops . has a carmel toasted nut flavor on the tounge and finished dry . i like the fact that this irish red is a little more bitter than most red ales but still not overpowering . tongiht i will be reviewing 4 of hook and ladder beers as i bought a gift pack that came with 3 bottles of 4 different beers . the beers i got were backdraft brown golden ale pipe and drum irish red ember amber ( a type of black and tan made with their backdraft brown ale and golden ale ) . try these beers if u can find them they are good

this beers saving grace is a fantastic odor .  have had this a couple times at churchkey and paradiso in dc & gt ; a : a very sudsy pub cask like look to this one with sticky lacing , a beautiful finger of fluffy head and a darker orange body . great start .  definitely a little too carbonated for my taste - the mouthfeel was a little too creamy , masking the flavor .

exceptional smell of toffee , caramel , nutty . wanted to eat something that smelled like this . slightly bitter note on the nose . sweet with a more bitter nutty taste .  appearance : dark black color , with big chocolate brown head , medium carb smell : chocolate , with malts , and some wood taste : bitter dark chocolate , coffee , alcohol , and roasted malt mouthfeel : dry , slightly bitter , rich full body drinkability : a drinkable imperial stout , the high abv is moderately masked .  smell is cocoa , touch of coffee , licorice , slight vanilla , a whiff of smoke . taste is thick creamy , dark and bakers chocolate , touch of espresso , end is dry and slightly bitter , a woody aftertaste .

nose : oaky vanilla , caramel/toffee and apple skins dominate this so-called imperial ipa . insanely sweet and syrupy like most of dfh 's `` super beers '' ( ww stout , raison d'extra ) .  a : this pours an entirely transluscent orange color with red hues and a finger and a half of slightly off-white head that laces better than any beer i have ever seen .  m- the weakness of the beer - moderately light body feels a little weak to me . light carbonation does n't add much .

aroma of malted grains , hops , very nutty and sort of citrusy .  this is one great looking brew ... . both big and small bubbles and what appears to be a layer a grease on the head .  body was medium with med/high carbonation and a dry finish .

i actually smell this beer about 2 feet away when opening . very citrusy and piney , a small amount of orange juice sweetness is present . a very nice extreme beer , i may be afraid to try fresh .  this beer has probably the best head i 've ever seen on a saison . saison de lente pours a massive 3 finger white head that has almost a pancake batter like consistency . the head retention is fantastic . the lacing is just magical . a thick french lacing accompanies the glass even when then the glass is empty .  mouthfeel : i 'm a bit disappointed by the mouthfeel .

aroma vomits forth ripe , rich fruits . raisin paste and juicy plum notes jump out of the glass from a distance . the slightest hint of raw cocoa beans top off this exotic nasal medley . still , tastewise , there are better dubbels . it 's no 12 , but it 's a solid beer wrapped in an exquisite package . worth a try , glad i did .  gorgeous , classy looking beer .  mouthfeel , i would like it have been a bit more carbonated , but it did fine .

smell was amazing , coffee , toffee , bitter chocolate , sugar , fruit .  pours a deep copper color with a big creamy tan head that lasts forever and leaves a great looking lace all the way down the sides of the glass .  magic hat usually disappoints me , not that their brews are n't good , it 's that some of them just are n't tasty- till now . magic hats roxy rolles is right up there with ithaca 's cascazilla and troegs hopback amber . a definite seasonal must have for me . great ! ! !

s - from the first crack of this beer , the smell is great . fruits are in the forefront , with a bit of bitterness . great smell , i do n't think it gets a whole lot better than this . this is still a phenomenal tasting beer , but comparing it to the smell , it lacks a bit . m - mouthfeel is good , slightly syrupy and the bitterness fades at a good rate . overall , this beer is great . i 've had it several times and i have found that if you let it sit for a while , the bitterness dies out a bit , but the fruitiness goes with it .  the classic appearance is the widget induced/nitro-draft style , which produces a paler , more uniform head with typical nitro bubbles ( tighter ) . it was almost foamy and left a nice lacing on the glass from the four pulls i took . this is what a stout beer should look like , imho . perfect . the dark , almost black , appearance of the guinness is beautiful .  under carbonated .

aroma is whoa grapefruit ! nice brew , maybe a bit over the top , but for an anniversary brew , you do what you have to .  pours hazy copper amber color with a very nice dense 2 finger off white head with fantastic retention , that reduces to a thick lacing cap that lasts till the end of the glass . some fairly nice glass lacing is present around the entire glass .  this one is a bit light and watery but does have a decent taste .

smell is super fruity sweetness , excellent complexities including wood , vanilla and a bit of alcohol . taste is an explosion of goodness . i love that barleywines come in 12oz bottles** , as that 's the size that i 'd prefer to have this style of beer in .  poured a gorgeous amber pink , with a thick white fluffy head . plenty of lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit overcarbonated for the stle but not bad .

smell : the wonderful aroma starts with the smell of concord grapes . holy hell , this liquid smells amazing . its like a huge fruit salad mixed with brandy and raisins ! taste : so does it taste as good as it smells ? well , the taste is of plums , raisins , and maybe prunes .  bottle from the lcbo the 2008 vintage has held its own agaist the 2007. black with a lovely tan head .  this is the least impressive quad from the trappist breweries ... do n't get me wrong , it has a similar taste profile , although not that perfect as a westy 12 or a rochefort 10 , dark fruit , plums , candy sugar , but i did n't like the mouthfeel on this one . too much sparkling going on ... pretty funny thing is i just absolutely endlessly adore the la trappe quadrupel oak aged batch 1 version ... so so so much better then the regular one , especially when the oak aged version , bottled this summer , is coming around fantastic ! i like their dubbel more too .

the aromas were of blood oranges , honey and moist , fleshy herbs ( ie . basil , bluegrass , cress , sorrel , epazote , etc . ) on the palate these images were joined by flavors of toasted , dry biscuits . it was vermouth-like in its exotic spicing and dreary , liqueurish texture ( blame the poor handling ! ) yet its bracing , raw , and complex extraction of herb overcame even this `` flaw '' . can a great ipa arise by accident ?  looks nearly black with about a 3/8 '' caramel colored head from a vigorous pour .  it smells of rotten banana peels , rotten apples , and molding compost . the flavors are very sweet and kind of medicinal . it leaves a clove laiden aftertaste behind , making you think you just had an artificial banana milkshake . i just do n't understand what two brothers was going for on this one .

the aroma is absolutely wonderful ... full of freshly crushed green , leafy and sweet hops . nice . the carbonation is mild to moderate . pleasantly surprised by this one..i thought this was going to be another average pale ale , but this very enjoyable .  opague black extremely heavy coffee colored heading . that leaves excellent lacing and keeps a nice collar all the way down to the last gulp .  m - somewhat lacking in mouthfeel .

smell - not a whole lot of aroma , maybe a bit of malt and a little bit of caramel , but not much taste - the taste matches the smell quite well .  crystal clear straw hue with a two finger dense and frothy head that slowly settles to a thick cap , leaving a solid wall of lacing in its place .  nothing to write home about when it comes to mouthfeel . kind of a club-soda feel to the beer , tingly . though there seems to be a strange `` romanian roulette '' effect where every sixth beer is kinda soapy .

very promising . and then : the taste is a bit disappointing after that great smell . good , but not exceptional .  i also love the brownish patina imparted to the deep red colour as it sits in a chalice .  i can see why the word peat was used before in a review the mouthfeel was medium to light i will agree it needs some more body to it this is a good brew and with a little tweaking it could become world class .

but the immediate punky aroma lets me know that this is an ale with intrusive yeast esters - one whose yeasts feel compelled to dominate rather than delegate .  honestly one of the most impressive looking ipa 's i 've encountered .  shockingly light carbonation feel . i think the mouthfeel is off from what it should be .

i smell fresh cat piss , pine , grapefruit peel , fresh , fresh fresh hops ! ! ! ! still hard to live up to the smell . the mouthfeel is good and i have to say that if this beer was on tap i would stop for a pint or three every day .  pours from the bottle to a reddish orange with medium off-white head that lingers , and excellent lacing .  i feel that it felt a little light on the tongue after it went down .

the smell is fantastic sweet very floral and an under tone of citrus .  a : pours to a frothey tan head with a deep and beautiful copper body . excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin and watery side though .

i just had a hop devil and that leaves me with only one more hop devil and one troeg 's pale ale , so i decided to save those for another day and steal one of these from my sister . something sweet like candy with a touch of an adjunct ... corn maybe ? maybe a banana like runt t : pretty much follows the smell .  pours dark black - thick brown foam , long retention and heavy lacing .  come and drink this corn syrup !

amazing nose of peach with a high , frothy , long lasting head with an almost soapy mouthfeel .  a : moderate pour yields 1.25 fingers dense tan head with superb retention . a beauty .  cake/nutty malt up front with a huge , thick spiced tea hop flavor headbutt with the swallow . not just season 's best , but saranac 's best . i usually find them to be just an average brewery but this stuff is nice .

typical of the wheat and carapils . s - pineapple , mango , apricot , piney hops balance with the carapils aroma . all in all , good balance . m - smooth medium body with soft carbonation . d - well , i ca n't really detect any alcohol , it drinks really fast , and it 's delicious .  the appearance was quite impressive .  m - decent body with a bit more carbonation than i 'd like from this style .

s - the aroma is pretty impressive , and accurately captures the smells and intricacies of apple pie .  my bottle looks different than the picture ; guess they changed the label . appearance : clear light amber with a big frothy head of light tan .  mouthfeel : hoppy and rough , but a bit fuzzy .

awesome . the taste is again huge with cherry flavor without sweetness , cherry pits , a decent amount of sourness , with a good lactic tartness on the finish .  a - poured a completely black with a gigantic 3 finger head .  malty and corny .

smell : the best part of this beer in my opinion . extremely complex ! i smell the chocolate and coffee but i am also overwhelmed by the super sweet heavenly smell of vanilla . taste : i was so happy that the taste was so refined , understated , elegant and smooth . drinkability : love it love it .  this one gushed out an extremely creamy , frothy off-white head with a suprisingly long and stable retention . the bottom was also very appealing , golden orange-yellow hue that was opaque and reflective .  m -- slightly too watery , does n't really coat the mouth like i would hope but it washes down clean with no bad lingering tastes d -- this is it here , i think this is the beer i would use to introduce someone new to ipa 's .

s. pears on the nose once i open the bottle . i 'm excited to take a sip . not a great representation of the style , but a surprisingly champagne-like beer : they hit the bottle 's stated target on the mark , but i 'm still disappointed that all of the wonderful scents did n't fully transition into the taste .  appearance : pours a motor oil black with a 1 finger creamy milk chocolate brown head . excellent lacing . like all the other yetis , this one looks perfect .  this is a very good pumpkin beer . picked a 6 pack up at the local market , came home on a chilly night here in rural mi , and my girlfriend and i finished the whole six pack . lots of pumpkin taste , beautiful color , and an overall great seasonal choice . i would n't drink it in warm weather , but on this cool fall night , it hit the spot . i could see picking this up in the future to bring to a bon fire , or to enjoy while i hand out candy on halloween . cheers !

a fantastic aroma if you ask me ! great stuff !  drank on-tap at atwood 's tavern , cambridge , ma served in a stemmed glass gorgeous appearance . thick , lasting rings of lacing coated the glass .  mouthfeel : tingly and not quite substantial enough . seems to be the only point where this beer loses some ground .

smell is pure oranges and very faint hops but the smell is amazing . taste did n't lead up to the smell kind of a big build up and then aahh .  the beer poured beautifully into the glass : a bronze-brownish coloured pint with a thick off white head . the main thing i noticed throughout the duration of the pint was the excellent retention and lacing that the head left .  the taste is also fresh but a with bit of watery mouthfeel .

heat is starting to mellow with a year on it , and the fruity development of the nose compliments the flavor beautifully . freshness indicated that this beer needs some time , and boy was i right .  poured from a 750ml bottle bottled on november 10 , 2011 into a tulip . a : pitch black with a 1 finger foam head . exactly how a stout should look .  m-its a little undercarbonated but the balance of the sweetness with the malt and subtle hops make for a relitivly complex october beer . d-easy to drink and very nice to have this time of year , easy to session .

a very complex and inviting aroma . the taste really follows the nose , with a sweet melange of spices careening across the tongue . it 's very complex , but unfortunately does n't smell quite as good as it tastes .  a- a perfect golden look in the glass . looks great .  mouthfeel was my only complaint .

s : this beer smells great . a very nice balance of booze with piney/citrusey hops . was slightly underwhelmed by the flavor after experiencing such tantalizing aroma smelling the beer . it is still a hearty and satisfying , flavorful brew .  a beautiful looking beer with at least a two-finger head that lasts for a while before fading to a nice cap that remains to the end .  perhaps a little watery , fuzzy . quite drinkable but somewhat sweet .

nose is superb -- very much pumpkin pie . delicious and a new pumpkin ale favorite !  opaque pitch black , moderate brown head . '' apart from the looks and the aroma : very disappointing .  its sucks to know that in a different format this could be so much more . body and carb is okay , but by this point i 'm already at the meh stage .

very nice start of a semi-grainy and fully malted pilsner barley . delicious .  12 oz bottle poured into a snifter - best before oct. 19th 2007 appearance : harsh pouring reveals a generous 2 '' head that lasts quite a long time . the head is tan with tiny bubbles that leaves a bit of lace behind .  flavor is very light malt with a slightly sour pucker at the end . finishes clean with minimal bitterness . overall , this is a very good summer beer . it 's light , refreshing and mild , so it 's a good intro beer for those that are n't into intense beers . however , it has enough of a belgian twist to keep more advanced beer drinkers interested . versatile enough to enjoy one with a meal or multiple at the lake or playing cornhole .

this is a really great nose . tastes not quite as good as it smells , but still solid . smells great and is solid all around - worth a shot .  visually it 's perfect . nice copper color with a fully creamy head .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts as sour apples becomes more sour like lemon juice , dry finish ; easily the least enjoyed belgian i have had . 750ml bottle - gift from vintage cellars blacksburg , va .

sour cherries , fresh-pressed apple cider , mild marble rye , yeasty esters and a faint touch of alcohol . complex and rewarding . effervecent and envigorating without overwhelming the tongue . much lighter than the appearance would lead you to believe and it resembles many other belgian-style ales in this regard . maybe not everyone 's cup of tea but i find it to be immensely drinkable and the alcohol is hardly noticable . quite good .  poured from 22oz bottle into `` balloon '' glass the darkest ebony color in the body with a rocky massive foamy/sticky dark tan colored head .  i thought the mouthfeel was a touch watery but the whole packaged seem very much an alluring strong-lawnmower , early evening session beer .

another great beer from denmark , this little country is no slouch in craft beer world.poured into an imperial nonic a near jet black except from some chocolate brown highlights when held to the light , a large blooming lighter mocha colored head atop.to me the aromas couldnt get any better , a fantastic display of chocolate and resiny hop , maybe the best aroma of any stout i have come across , if you like the hops no matter the style its spot on.the mouthfeel is a little sharp and not as full on as i would have liked.bitter chocolate , dark fruit , and a healthy dose of resiny hop make for a well rounded flavor profile , if that mouthfeel was just a little more smooth ! a really good beer that is close to being great , love the hop play going on .  poured a brilliant gold hue with a completely hazed clarity .  mf : relatively light body with medium to high carbonation . would like a little more body , but the flavor more than makes up for it .

nose seems thoroughly disjointed ; a myriad of different scents that simply do n't co-exist all that well .  a : pours a light golden with a couple fingers of dense white head that reduced very slowly into a thick frothy head . beautiful rings/sheets of lacing left with every sip .  mouthfeel lots of fizzy carbonation , lighter bodied , finishes dry . the high carbonation combined with a thinner than usual mouthfeel really did throw off the beer making the flavors less prominent than i feel they could have been had the aforementioned two things been toned down a bit .

s : as soon as i popped this one , i loved the smell of it . i was hoping after the great smell , it would have a taste i loved , but unfortunately not a taste that suits me .  11.2oz bottle poured into a chalice pours a murky , deep brown with a thick , one-finger head that has awesome staying power and leaves rings of lacing down my glass .  an american classic . good fall back beer , or one to enjoy when a less complex brew is desired .

smell is of bourbon , wood , malt , brown sugar , toffee , and dark fruits . overall , this is a fantastic beer with very complex aromas and flavors . i am really glad i was able to try this one .  think imperial irish dry stout instead of russian imperial stout ... a : bottle opens with a 'gunshot pop '' and pours a dark black with a monstrous 2.5 '' dark tan head . fantastic retention .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with medium to high carbonation .

smell : this beer smells amazing . getting chocolate , coffee , and a little dark fruit . definitely follows the nose . chocolate and coffee , maybe a little raisin .  appearance is flawless . it 's a very dark ruby with a billowing pillow of foam and great lacing .  spicy and yeasty on the finish , this beer is medium-light on the palate with a high level of carbonation , much higher than i care for , really foaming up in my mouth .

big aroma full of treacle , vanilla , oak , and hints of raisins and bourbon . an acquired taste , but very good .  pours into my new belgium globe with very dark brown body that looks almost black in the glass . thick creamy tan head tops the beer and looks stable enough to stick around for the duration .  m : the body is medium and so is the carbonation .

aroma was an incredible with scents of spicy dark bread .  ths one poured a dream , you shoulda seen it , looked like a photo from a beer book . billowy head sticking out of the glass all proud and boastful , very cool .  mouthfeel : thin body and medium carbonation overall : a nice geuze , a bit too watery for my liking though .

this is just perfect . pine and citrus are both detectable . but ... ahhh , it smells so good !  thought this beer had a really nice color . an excellent color . i 'm thinking mahogony , but i 'm not sure exactly what color that ... but i 'm thinking like a deep deep wood varnish color ... really nice .  m - exceedingly bitter . needs to be a little creamier for this style d - not a session beer .

wonderful tropical fruit and floral aroma that from my experiences is ever present . the centennial hops are very distinctive as they come out in the aroma and flavor .  pours out like chocolate syrup , fills the glass pitch black with a very dark tan head . billowing foam despite a very cold serving temperature , thick chunks of lace , crazy retention .  mouth feel is sharp and crisp , with a high carbonation level .

the aroma is intoxicating , deep and bold arabica coffee notes upfront that is fruity and intense . high quality cacao , molasses , pepper , cherry wood and a wallop of alcohol ... really outstanding . the flavor is a letdown from the aroma , with a broad sweetness that kind of smothers the coffee and roasted notes , some cherry and plum notes in the background and an alcohol bite finishes things off . an incredible aroma almost makes up for the cloying sweetness .  nice downward bubbles on pour ... dark brown to black with a slight ruby edge , a tan creamy nitro head , and lace like wallpaper .  i think i 'm a bit parial to this beer for 2 reasons . it 's not by any means a `` specialty '' beer , it 's your typical lager and since it 's been around since before any of us were born it 's got a nostalgic feel . excellent beer in my books , average for most .

a : dark brown with yeast particles s : could be the strongest smelling dark fruit belgian style beer ever .  pours black with off-white/brownish head in one finger thickness that lasts for very long time , generous lacing . perfect .  t- roasty , sweet malts , coffee and dark chocolate m- starts off nice and creamy and full , then towards the middle loses a bit of it 's body and seems to get watery , only to return with a solid finish .

smell : good malt presence , but ca'nt smell any hops .  ruby and brown shades with decent clarity , a beautiful 1/2 inch head of white foam sits atop with solid retention .  mouthfeel - the one noticeable drawback to this offering is the lack of carbonation . otherwise it felt very good in the mouth .

as it warmed , it ran the gamut of aromas from root beer , estery banana , and authentic wet vanilla sticks . it starts off offering complex flavours and aromas , but the alcohol comes through more as it warms up , and the nuances become more muted .  poured an opaque brown , as expected from a stout , with thick , pillowy tan head and excellent lacing .  this beer has a lot of flavor for a light . too bad its not a good flavor ! nothing impressive at all here . i 'm not sure what they are putting in this beer but its not worth the 7.99 they are charging for a six pack . i would recommend pabst blue ribbion over this any day !

either is the rye . i sought out rye as i chose it to pair with an herbed chicken . the smoke is light as well so i suppose i could call it a bock . the hops , as expected , were n't pronounced .  this was poured from the bottle into a consendonk tulip glass . a - clear light golden straw color with a thick foamy , ice cream-like head that is very well retained s - sweet malt and fruity yeast aroma with a slight hop spiciness t - like aroma , sweet malt up front with fruit-like notes and a very slight amount of hops on the finish m - medium body with high carbonation d - this is a decent , well-made beer .  the nose is caramely and very malty . a little too carbinated for a traditional barleywine but lines ones gut like the best of the bunch ! being a sucker for barleywines i have to give this beer high remarks .

it 's sitting across the table but throwing great scents my way hazy amber orange with some sudsy head juicyfruit aromas : immense , zesty citrus , mint . not much pine , which is a nice change from the norm . good , robust , woody bitterness ( it really hangs on the tongue ) with excellent hop depth . mint .  great retention and lacing .  it 's a black colored beer with ruby edges . fairly nice nose , with a variety of dark fruits , as well as a bit of chocolate and coffee . really nice nose . flavor is fully packed , loaded with dark fruits ( blackberry , plum , cherry and currant ) , as well as some notes of dark chocolate , coffee and a light hint of alcohol . i like it .

the nose ? wow ! intense citrus and definite grape fruit aroma is almost overwhelming , but in a very , very good way . never had anything like it taste : as i go for the 1st sip , i 'm almost squinting my eyes , expecting to drink a form of carbonated grapefruit juice .  pours a dark , opaque mahogany tone with a solid finger and a half of a beige-colored head . decent retention , good lacing , and a lasting cap .  light bodied though , almost watery . in a way this is an ipa-light - some similar desirable flavors and aromas , but less bitterness , less alcohol , and lighter bodied .

huge hop aroma , a nice scottish style malt presnece behind the agresive hop bitterenes .  a : a stunning deep brown near black with cranberry highlights . a inch of toasted head comes after a medium pour . the head slowly fades to an impressive 1/3 inch . lacing on a dark beer ?  this review is from notes in my `` travel journal . '' obviously the beer is now `` retired . there is some berry in the attack . the flavor smoothes out to leave a clean finish . it is a very drinkable beer , but not what i normally seek out .

aroma is fabulous , even at this temperature . delicious . well worth the $ 6 canadian that i paid for it .  produced a huge rocky head that lasts & lasts and when subsides leaves half its mass on the side of the glass ( i did n't mean for that to rhyme , it just worked out that way . ) the aroma is ok , its floral like perfume but not particularly citrusy or piney or any of those typically american hop descriptors .  the only real flaw for me with this beer is that it 's a bit thin , but that 's a bit nit-picky and did n't detract at all for me from this wonderful beer .

just great . t : similar to the smell but with bit of smokiness .  a brilliant tan head rose quickly to three-fingers and lowered very slowly leaving brilliantly thick patchy lace on the glass .  crisp taste - not heavy as expected ... hints of smokey , woody flavors - has the appeal of a coffee porter ... mouthfeel is average .

s - a fantastic aroma of lemony citrus and wheat with pale malts and a light bouquet of floral hops . the thing that totally makes the aroma is the wonderful funk from the brett yeast . tiny fruit esters of mango and pineapple from the yeast also play a small but delicious role . very complex and inviting . t - a bright sour funk bursts across the tongue right away bringing with it that barnyard and horse-blanket that is so good . it 's definitely a lively beer . d - i 'm really happy i 'm sharing this cause a 750 ml to myself would be devastating for two reasons ; a ) to my sobriety , and b ) to my taste-buds .  nitro-tap , nice pour into a pint glass at henry 's 12th street tavern in portland . color is brownish-black , thick tan head has excellent retention all the way to the end .  mouthfeel can be too fizzy if you do n't make sure to pour high for tall head . when i 'm drinking more than one beer , this is my favorite second or third , as it 's got enough hops to satisfy , is not highly alcoholic , and sells for a real good price where i live .

smell : complex nose boasts belgian yeast with a sweet apricot note and some underlying white pepper spice . complexities abound . taste : a well balanced tripel with a nice peppery spice and undistinguishable fruit presence . overall : solid , solid tripel . very fine beer .  a - truly unique looking beer . a black beer almost dark purple looking at times .  dare i say it seems a bit on the thin side . the meatiness in the flavor is not backed up by the body . not bad , but just a little disappointing ... this is a fine stout .

this is a light caramel colored beer . the smell of this bear makes me eager to drink it . it 's a combination of peach , apricot , and orange . this is a nice light ( in color and mouthfeel ) beer that will be great going into spring .  captain lawrence st. vincent 's dubbel is a great looking dubbel that tastes pretty good . a : red orange colour and a great 2 cm head that lasts very well . highly carbonated .  feels quite creamy at first , almost in a draft-stout kind of way , which struck me as odd . would rather it be crisper and a bit more carbonated , though .
fantastic stuff .  the appearance is beautiful . a bit darker than i 'd expect a golden ale to be , but it looked great .  carbonation is ample but the body lacks a little texture .

seriously this is really closed , clean smelling , trying some big whiff perhaps a faint malt . really not impressed .  the bottle popped furiously , and poured with a full head and glowing color .  the body is sufficient to carry the 10 percent alcohol which is impressive by itself . some spicy notes and an effervescent type of feel to it .

wheat smell , with a sickly sweet remainder , not exactly pleasant .  pours a cloudy golden/orange color with a two finger frothy head that has really good retention and leaves lots of sticky lacing .  m : light-medium body with an oily mouthfeel , and a dry and resiny fade overall , not a bad beer , though it does stray from traditional belgian dubbels in a few aspects : not as sweet or yeasty as the classic belgian examples , a little hoppy for the style , and its too light .

a bit of lacing & zero head retention , really dragged this score down s : pumpkins & pumpkin pie spices , cinnamon , allspice , & nutmeg t : pumpkin , cinnamon , nutmeg , dryness & brown sugar up front . spices start to dominate as this warms , cinnamon & nutmeg especially , plus some squashy/pumpkin notes as well . finishes warming with nutmeg & cinnamon mf : medium bodied , fairly low carbonation & a nice warming sensation , expected a bit more malt depth though drinks pretty easy , the abv is well hidden , but lacks the total package of say , an ichabod , but i would certainly grab a sixer of this during the fall every year  poured from a 11.6oz brown bottle with a white cap marked `` bottl 2006* 12 % '' into a tulip glass . easily one of the longest lasting , largest frothy heads of foam i have ever seen on any beer . appearance is a rusty yellowish orange color , cloudy and semi-translucent .  m- seems a little thin , but nicely carbonated .

the smell is the best part of this beer . it ' sweet and refreshing , almost like woodchips or taking a walk in the woods on a brisk fall afternoon . upon first drink , the extreme hops and alcohol content are apparent . the alcohol is not yet well incorporated into the beer and combined with the hops makes this very difficult to drink .  pours the color of any other well crafted imperial stout , pitch black but with an impressive mocha colored inch of foam on top . the head displayed some excellent retention and a creamy layer of bubbles from the cask treatment .  medium-high carbonation .

smell : wow ... i was n't expecting this at all . incredibly hoppy , honey , almost strawberry jam sticky hop smell . taste : i found it a little too watery at first , which was a dissapointment . another intriguing brew with an awful label from ray mcneil .  pours an almost transparent golden/light copper with an amazingly fluffy 3 finger head from an extremely gentle pour .  mouthfeel : i 've always thought this was a little off ... not quite enough spine to offset the sweetness .

smell : a deep and delightful warm caress to the nostrils . chocolate , molasses , brandy , and oak joint together for an exquisite amalgamation . wonderfully sugary , earthy , and effervescent .  pours cloudy yellow orange with thick creamy foam indefatgiable white foam .  this has the syrupy goodness of the 90-minute , but with an added syrupiness ... robust and smooth , like a desert sauce , you could pour this over a bowl of vanilla ice cream instead of a caramel sauce , with its own french vanilla creaminess ... the only thing that detracts here is an odd light metallic twinge at the finish that didnt seem to fit . otherwise , this is a beaut of a big beer with a light profile .

just flat out wonderful , this is just an exceptional nose here . the nose on this is just flat out fantastic .  biggish , crusty , light tan head leaves lots of hard , sticky lacing . very pretty .  surprisingly light mouthfeel makes it a fairly easy drinker for a 9 % er

no head retention or lacing huge oaky , fruitty boozey nose , beautiful t : dryness , raisins , dates , & breadyness with a slight booze presence up front .  650ml bottle poured into tulip july2 2010 a clear deep amber with a massive light beige head that has great retention eventually forming a brain like island leaving plenty of lace all the way down the glass s big grapefruit hops with a fair bit of sweet malt t again loads of hops but with an unexpected mild nutty chocolate a little different but pretty good m slightly sticky with enough carbonation to give it a slightly creamy feel d a 4.25 option would have come in to play once or twice with this one so i drop the 4.5 here , for a strong ale it 's very drinkable and i would drink it again without thinking twice unique beer with no doubt , nice flavors from the hops and lots of malt character .  the mouthfeel was the only thing that detracted from the beer in my opinion , as i found it to be a little to watery for my personal preference .

smell : this beer has an exceptional aroma of toffee leather tobacco cocoa , burnt caramel and coffee .  poured into an imperial pint , formed a 1 1/2 '' dense beige head above the slightly cloudy orangey amber brew . head falls way slowly , leaving a tall monolith of froth in the center , and thick coating all down the glass walls .  i 'm not getting much in the way of bitterness anywhere here , which combines with a medium thin body to provide very little in the way of a finish .

the aroma is fantastic , sweet , sour , chocolate malt all blending to a wonderful bouquet . taste is a bit too spicy , but otherwise very pleasantly complex . mouthfeel is dry and acrid , not as smooth as some others .  poured a very deep brown with a massive brown head and tons of carbonation .  quite watery for the big flavor this one tastes and smells different from the main stream craft ipas , which is a pretty new category i 'll give it that .

wonderful aroma . warm and oaky , molasses . almost get a bbq sauce scent , very spicey like a worcester sauce . very interesting tastes in this one , unusual .  it is as black as pitch . a nice , pillowy thick 2 finger head formed and stayed for the whole beer .  if you aerate the beer in your mouth , it really releases the co2 . it would do well as a beer to server with medium to strong cheese .

s- totally amazing smell . just like pumkin pie .  served up a breathtaking deep copper amber that is crystal clear . the head is slightly off-white and looks superb with tightly packed , shiny bubbles that stick around forever and leave near perfect lace . if this beer tastes nearly as good as it looks i will be most happy .  very nice m : medium bodied-a bit thicker than i expect from an ipa or a dipa , but it works well with the oaky sweetness of this beer .

outstanding imo . a : normal , yellowish/orange .  pours a deep chestnut brown , with a layer of foamy white goodness on top . laces amazingly . the more beers i try from this brewery the more i realize they sure know how to make a beer look good .  little fruityness . light to medium body , oily , light carbonation . could be a little more carbonated .

huge sweet and bready malts rise to the nose upon an initial whiff .  appearance : this one pours a very dark mohogany with an incredible red hue . great head rentention very frothy .  this is a man 's beer . none of this flowery wine swilling critique lingo . light color , smell and mouth feel , who really cares . outstanding dry & hoppy flavor without sweetness . when bought in the 30 pack , cost is about 50 cents each . the best macro being produced !

solid macrobrew beer . sometimes you just need to kick back and enjoy something fresh , and heineken delivers . if you are cutting calories go light , they taste the same .  the pour is jet black with a nice two finger head on it . the head is a nice mocha color with tiny bubbles holding some of the best retention and lacing i 've ever seen in an impy stout .  too carbonated , the mouthful of liquid seems to almost crumble right away .

d : nice big i.p.a. , best smelling i have had yet , very flavorful and the malt has been kept in check and the hops can come right through .  head is enormous and really nicely laces . retention is amazing .  m : still a bit watered down , but again , it 's better .

in my opinion , racer 5 is one of the best smelling beers on the market . one whiff revels a cascade of piney and citrus hops aroma . it 's the quintessential west coast ipa aroma . for a beer topping out at 7.0 % , racer 5 is ridiculously drinkable .  appearance : very , very deep clear gold , head on this one is one for the ages , really spectacular . huge , dense , pure white and a bit slick ; looks a bit like whipped egg whites .  m : a lighter body with good carbonation which yields a sensation akin to chewing on a cloud .

really loved the nose .  a : pours a bright light amber with a large dense head that reduced into a delightfully thick dense foam dollop that floated on top of the beer . very active carbonation and fantastic lacing . head stayed forever with very impressive retention .  this was followed up by a sweet , orangish tang on the tongue , followed by a sweet finish , especially in comparison to the berliner wiesse , which i tried earlier . the introduction of the lemon slice to the beer increases the dryness , especially at the finish . a good , summery beer with a name that invokes `` the simpsons . ''

appearance is nice , dark but that red cherry goodness shines . smell is the winner here with loads of cherries and chocolate . taste is good , and hits big with cherries , a little dark smoke and chocolate .  great , great look .  mouthfeel too prickly and astringent but medium body is appropriate for style .

smells great . huge floral and citrus hop aromas with a bready malt that asserts itself more as the beer warms .  a light orange marmalade cropped with a white , creamy top , it looks damn delicious !  a good beer . comes in a .33ml brown bottle , part of a 6 pack sampler from brouwerij van steenberge . a sweet and dark beer , where hops has taken a back seat to the malt profile . not light , but not heavy either . give it a try .

super sweet citrus tingle with a fresh evergreen aroma . a fitting caramel malt finds its way in the nose as well . wonderful exotic hop scents all the way through with this one . scary good drinkability for the style .  poured a very nice deep copper with fantastic head and nice lacing .  t : wood chips , obviously , tastes like a sauna smells , charcoal , molasses , savory like breakfast sausage , soy sauce , real sharp sweetness that 's broken down by hops lurking in the background and that 's absent at the finish m : medium body , very low carbonation , i 'm surprised this was n't the cask ( it was n't but they did have it ) , dry bitter charcoal finish . the mouthfeel was a big drawback for me , it was very flat , considering this was the draft veraion .

very nice . the taste is quite good , mostly dominated by malts .  this beer was a very nice , deep red/brown color , and it had a very nice and thick head .  the carbonation is interesting , but a little too fizzy for me , i feel like this beer has a watery quality to it which i do n't particularly like in a porter . it starts out watery , then the carbonation kicks in .

the aromas is astonishing , this is the most coffee like of any coffee beers that i 've tasted . excellent .  a : big creamy tan head , very dark body s : roasted coffee , cherry , chocolate milk t : chocolate , chocolate , chocolate .  drank in a chalice from a bottle in brussels at delirium cafe.. this is very good lambic . it smells great very sweet with cherries . the beer has a beautiful red/brown color with a white head , not a lot lacing . it tastes sweet with cherries dominating but has a nice sour kick too .

awesomely complex . taste : chocolate , chocolate malt , coffee , chocolate syrup .  thanks for the opportunity ... poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1/4 '' dark brown ( almost purply black ) head above the opaque black brew . head hangs on , with average lace , which actually is pretty good for the style .  m : smooth on the palate .

the nose had a very fresh floral hop aroma .  poured a dark golden orange to light amber in the glass ... yes , almost the color of the jewel amber . lots of beautiful bubbles in the pour reminding me of a guinness that end up creating a full 2 finger craggy beige head that melts to sticky lace .  mouthfeel is the only real negative to this one , medium bodied and a bit thinner than i 'd like .

pretty much light yellow water . i definitely do n't get any hops from it at all . the main/only part of the taste is probably corn . there is n't really much of anything to consider while drinking it , it is easy to drink , and it 's cheap .  black to extremely dark brown in color of the body . huge rocky head that is coffee color .  the colour is a light straw , probably the weakest colour i have seen in a pale lager , the head is very pleasent and has some serious glass cling ... the aroma is very skunky when first opened but quickly disappears and the taste is highly sweet malts on a thin body , very nice for dining , not a stadium brew ... i first reviewed this brew in march of 03 , approx 10 monthes ago .

the smell is great . as a chocolate lover , i really like this . smells like straight up melted chocolate . but this is really good if you like chocolate . next time i will pair it with some raspberries or strawberries , or make a damn milkshake out of it .  a : poured a dark clear ( filtered ) chocolatey amber color with a rich white foamy head .  mouthfeel is bubbly crisp and slightly creamy , but overall rather watery .

s - nice ! grapefruit aroma with some hints of pine fill my nose . very attractive flowery hops , with some bready biscuity malt hidden along the way . nice co2 .  poured into a pint glass a : pours very black with a large tan colored head . looks amazing . s : get a slight hop kick up front which gives way to some roasted grain .  carbonation is a little light though .

very sweet , but extremely complex . awesome . taste is intense sourness and bitterness , which tapers off to not much else .  pours out very clear straw color with plenty of carbonation and a rich frothy white head that lingers and laces , truly beautiful .  easy drinking but it has a different mouthfeel , it almost leaves a film in my mouth .

huge hop and malt aroma , very typical of stone .  appearance there 's pretty much no flaw to how this beer looks . its a deep , thick black , capped with a super rich , creamy tan head . great retention and solid lacing .  mouthfeel : a bit thin in body but makes up with an even overall texture not much carbonation very wine like with each sip .

this has one of the best aromas of an ipa that i 've ever had . sticky , piney , resiny aroma . i find this to be a very drinkable ipa .  black color , pitch black .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery .

been a while since i 've had a stout . burnt roasty smell with coffee , cocoa , and cream ... a smokey , woody , hot cocoa almost .  2003 : nice heavy white head tops the cloudy golden hue .  parching on the tongue . almost no flavor : slight sweetness up front , trace of bitterness on finish . really .

has a clean fresh smell . very soothing . makes me think of lazy walks through a hop field in the belgian countryside .  this beer looks wonderful . a beautiful mahogany red , cloudy and rich topped with two and a half fingers of rich foam . the beer leaves textbook rings down the glass as you drink it ( rather quickly ) .  on tap this poured as a golden straw colored ale , clear and bright with less than an inch of head . there is an apparent hoppy aroma that followed with a similarly dominant slight-hoppy taste followed by the expected bitters - very tasty . i stopped with one . not to discount its drink-ability , there are just several others i wish to try .

s : this smells amazing . raspberry and strawberry jam with bread and peanut butter . unbelievable , the aroma could n't be better . impressive . m : lower medium body with upper moderate carbonation . overall : the flavor is good , but the aroma is unreal . i could n't take my nose out of the glass .  growler the bruery placentia , ca a clear light golden with a big and thick foaming white head . the head sticks around for quite a while and eventually leaves thick and sticky lacing all down the glass .  lively carbonation is a bit excessive , but the body is quite smooth .

the nose is heavy on the rye malt- showing a more pure breadiness with fruity tones of buttery apples , white raisin , faint cinnamon , light brown sugar , plum . the parallels to rye whiskey are awesome in this . the medium bodied palate is caramelly sweet up front with a mild bitterness that ushers in the rye maltiness- drying and spicy with lots of fruity tones .  pours an effervescent honey color with3+ fingers of cream colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : grapefruit & lemon , fades a bit as this warms t : follows the nose , plus pineyness , slight breadyness & a touch of leafy hops & dryness hiding behind a ton of grapefruit up front .  the body was a bit too thin for my tastes in this style .

smell of dark rich chocolate , coffee and molassas , having some dark fruity earthiness to it . taste is again rich as in the above aromas with some roastiness and having alchohol present , but not overwhelming .  the humble brown has rarely looked so good .  m- medium body that was slightly under-carbonated . with more carbonation , all the flavors would bite that much more .

location cellar 70 serving 22oz the scent of this piva is spot on and really is inviting . i have n't had any other coffee stouts , so i am by far means an expert .  pours a truly awesome blood orange reddish tan color with a tan head .  m : the feel is creamy and medium bodied . rather light for a ris and that really detracts from the beer in my opinion . the mouthfeel is lighter than what i come to think of when i thik of a ris .

medium lacing smell : lacking . no malt , hop , or roast aromas present taste : smooth , sweet , lightly roased flavor . drinkability : very drinkable nice schwarzbier .  head retention was excellent , melting down to a slightly less huge frothy , rocky head . lacing was thick and plentiful ... .a beautiful looking beer .  the nose of the beer is strong and gives off a nice floral hop aroma . the flavor is sweet and semi-tart with fruity tastes . behind the sweet fruit , there is a slight but smooth alcohol presence . the earthy hop bitterness comes in at the end and fades away with the semi-dry finish .

nice hop aroma right off the bat . very piney and resiney .  as pretty as beer poured out of a can into a glass can be .  taste/mouthfeel : this beer is slightly oily , with a very limited carbonation .

had this on 2010-08-21 at the sizzling tandor restaurant in santa rosa , ca where their menu claims this ipa is made for them by firestone to compliment indian food . s - slight citrus and yeast t - medium roasted malt , caramel , orange citrus that changes more towards lemon as it warms .  pours beautiful dark brown with red edges , almost black with a huge tan head that sticks around and leaves walls of creamy lace .  m : a light-medium feel to it and kind of syrupy .

aroma is incredibly full and delicious . very very nice aroma . the flavor is just as incredible as the aroma . cherries , both sweet and sour are here in abundance , as well as a bit of graininess , and almost a thin flaky pastry flavor .  pours a fluffy , thick , white , three-fingered head , fades very slowly and leaves gobs of lace .  mouthfeel is ok. fairly light body , more than i 'd think it should be at this abv .

aroma is powerful , though not overbearing . piney/resiny hops are dominant , yet there is also a good helping of pineapple , tropical fruit and caramel .  i fricking love the way this beer looks . huge foamy white head , brilliant dark golden color with a cascade of carbonation bubbling up the side .  i sent it back thinking it had gone bad , but the bartender tried it and assured me it was ok. m - average for a macro lager .

the aroma is of peat , caramel , nuts , and chocolate . i really like the uniqueness of this aroma . the taste has more caramel than the aroma . overall , this is a really , really good scotch ale .  that 's an outstanding looking brew - steady head , chunky like snowfall on fence posts from the beginning , but it melts down a bit to only ring the glass . like deep brown bricks , with hints of orange around the edges - strong looking beer .  mouthfeel- medium body with very little carbonation .

s - huge pine aroma that is quickly and easily enjoyable . massively beautiful from the get-go , with underlying citrus notes . a perfect , varied aroma that promises wonderful delights within t - slight pine taste , bit of grapefruit , pure hops abound . d - very nice , but perhaps lacking a bit of malt balance making this a bit more difficult to enjoy .  appearance- beer pours a wonderful looking amber golden with a thin wispy head one finger high of whipped cream foam . this is about the most perfect appearance i 've seen for a marzen . very impressive from an impressive brewery .  m : medium bodied with not much creaminess or silkiness to talk about .

it has the wonderful spicy aroma that the style should always have . slight phenols , cloves , a sweet bready malt and a beautiful underlying fruitiness are all there . it finishes very very clean and does n't linger at all .  this beer was poured a very dark rich chocolate brown with a thin tan head . with this beer being pushed nitrogen , it had a ton of lacing and the head lasted the entire beer .  body is medium , mouthfeel is oily/creamy , carbonation is low but adequate .

that bright yellow can is like a delicious beacon calling to me at the supermarket . the taste i 'll admit is n't hoppy , or even very stong but rather subtle and beautifully simple , zen if you will . a real guzzler that 'll quench your thirst without fucking you up too bad .  excellent head duration to boot , with the dollop of foam in the middle arranged like a hurricane taking shape ; stellar looking beer .  color and mouthfeel are average for the style and fine .

looks good , smells amazing , but the taste is very underwhelming .  a : pours a deep dark brown that is almost black in appearance .  but it has quite a few pros : this beer is intended to be consumed with food . if you want to have chinese food with a light drink then this one is just what you are looking for ! it 's a typical lager : crystal-clear blonde , discreet taste and weak aroma . i usually do n't drink lager beers but this one i can have by the barrels while there 's food on the table . this beer is what you want to drink when you do n't want to drink !

smell was delicious . nutmeg , cinnamon , holiday cheer ... everything a holiday ale should smell like . overall this beer was good . i would definitely try the 2012 redition .  pours almost black , with tan 2 finger head .  this is an enjoyable , smooth but tasty strong polish lager . the aroma is fresh , toasty sweet bread , hint of lemon , pine , and rather nice . it has a bit of a czech lager taste to it and the alcohol is essentially unnoticeable . the taste is clearly alcholic , but very smoothly so , with nothing rough opr unpleasant . it has a light caramel quality , bread , and nice , warm spiciness , it 's a bit rasiniy , sweet and spicy with a light bitterness coming to the fore in the finish . it does not taste quite as strong as it is .

s : chocolate , peanut , fruit , raisin . rich , but it took me a while to pinpoint exactly what this reminded me of , then it hit me - hazelnut !  bomber picked up from the brewery , opened after some months aging into goblet : a : quite nice hazy light-golden orange color with a substantial , creamy , lasting head .  medium-full bodied mouthfeel with below average carbonation , the latter being ( beside the appearance ) one of my few criticisms .

there was a mild earthy aroma that lends nothing to the beer .  appearance : pours a clear orange color with a big 3 '' head that lasts quite a while .  this is n't the fault of the brewer so maby it had great head . the main problem with this beer was infection . i 'm sure it was an infection because when i sniffed it i thought for a second maybe i was at the movies about to dig into a 12 dollar medium popcorn . past the buttery flavor i could taste blueberry almost which i 'm sure was n't intended either . it 'd be interesting to taste one from a different batch .

massively nutty aroma , packed with roasted peanut butter , walnut brownies , and nuttella - very inviting . not terribly smoky ( more roasty ) , just a mild edge of charcoal that also lends a hint of toasted marshmallow . plenty of coffee notes as well - this is just about perfect , exactly what i want in the style . strangely , there is not a hint of alcohol in this beer - which makes this dangerously drinkable , but still , not exactly a lawnmower beer !  what a great looking beer .  medium bodied with medium carbonation . i only wish this average mouthfeel was supporting an average taste .

this is beautiful , and refined . man , the nose really had me going , but the taste did n't follow through .  a - this beer pours black in color . this is a beautiful looking beer .  m : surprisingly thin , slightly sticky body with low carbonation . a little weak .

this smelled like the kitchen while my mom bakes banana bread .  abv 5 % pours a brilliant , perfectly clear , golden color with a fluffy three finger white head . picture perfect of a pils .  mouthfeel is a bit of a problem for me . the carbonation level is also a factor , making it hard to enjoy in gulps .

the aromas are magnificent ! espresso coffee as if fresh brewed .  sampled on 4-7-09 pours a clear deep red/brown , with a huge , foamy , clingy , off-white head that leaves crazy thick lacing .  feel is kinda harsh .

intresting , very intens smell , very nice hop aroma , tons of hops , citrus flavour , very similar to pliny the elder , i want to taste this one t : similar to the nose but not that strong , wheat , tons of hops , citrus , sweet malts , nice slightly bitter finish , this could be the little brother of pliny the elder , but this is softer , not so strong , m : very smooth , very well balanced , d : very drinkable , alcohol is well hidden , i could drink this all day long , yammy , well done struise .  dark gold , lightly cloudy , with a very big creamy off-white head slowly shrinking to a puffy , rocky smaller head and foamy lace .  carbonation seems spot on .

smells fucking amazing . this is the best-smelling beer i 've ever had . it smells like exotic , spiced , fresh-roasted coffee , like you 're standing in [ trendy east side coffee shop ] . really good , but not quite on the same transcendent level as the nose .  pours black with a long lasting brown head that leaves plenty of lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit light , to me , for the style , though it seems appropriate for the flavors that this beer brings to the palate .

wow . thick bourbon and aforementioned flavors , mostly caramel . lovely beer , quite exceptional .  the foam was wheat in color , bubbly , thick , smooth and left a ring around the glass til the end . the color was a dark burgandy/all most black with an orange red highlight in the light .  mouthfeel is a little bit thin .

s- this beer smells great , typical ipa smells ; pine mandarin , pineapple , grapefruit .  a - pours a thick 2 fingers of tan head that sticks around for quite some time .  m : okay , mostly wet and satisfyingly quaffable , but with a noticeable alcohol presence in the finish .

aroma : sublime ! super sweet , rich dark ripe fruits coupled with notes of chocolate . an all organic ale , not the best dubbel , but respectable .  a= pours a beautiful dark brown almost black color with a great two finger perfectly toasty looking head on it that holds awesome retention and wonderful lacing on the glass .  not sure if our north american brethren appreciate this but this is , as far as i can tell the first fairly widely available american style ipa brewed in the uk . the american craft brewing industry which has been accused of being derivative is really starting to influence europe which is great . i am all for my uk brewing industry but i do get a little board of the vast variety of often samey real ale bitters populating manypubs . we definitely have a shortage of hopheads brewing in the uk ! and before anyone shoots me down , greene king ipa is not an ipa ! ! !

very nice . the taste is very unique .  it produced a nice , soapy , white head at about 2-fingers . decent retention that left some seriously clumpy lacing behind . this is a vibrant and inviting looking beer .  a bit on the light side of medium in body , with a dryish spicy finish . aftertaste seems watery .

smells like halloween ! very welcoming . it sure is an imperial . very crisp , sexy beer . spices are rounded , clove , cinnamon , vanilla bean , and most importantly , fresh pumpkin .  i enjoy just about everything this beer has to offer .  m - felt a bit thin to me .

this nose is so unique and amazing . as i take first sip i wasnt ready for the electric sour rush that attacks the tongue .  that little widget in the can sure does the trick : a majestic light tan head formed in my pint glass atop a layer of mesmerizing , cascading bubbles and a dark brown body .  mouthfeel is a little thin and aftertaste is a little too much ... like the brew has gone stale , although i know it has n't .

smells great ! you go the same whitepepper honey spice wheatishness of duvel only with a wonderfully crisp , weedy background . tastes very nearly as good as it smells . big nodes of weeds , pollen , and wild flowers backing up a spicy , crisp , lightly lemony belgian pale .  color was a little hard to see as it was fairly dark in the bar but appeared to be a very deep red , that while really dark was no opaque . slightly off-white head that left excellent lacing on the glass . not sure if it was the branded oversized wine glass or what but this was probably the second best looking beer i 've ever seen .  a very special thanks to zeke at the speakeasy for sharing a bottle of this 1995 treat . it still had carbonation in it which was crazy . the beer was very dry at this point . the spiciness of this beer has been cut down from the aging .

the smell is really quite wonderful ; nearly perfect . the roast and sweetness are the perfect marriage of complimentary elements .  a= at fridge temp , this ale poured a dark but clear mahogany brown color with a nice reddish glow . the first pour produced a light tan head that was only 1/4 '' but retained very well . retention was incredible and the stickage on my glass looked like emulsified foam ... beautiful .  feel is smooth and well-carbonated though a bit on the thin and watery side . medium-full body , not too heavy . leaves a nice sticky coating around the mouth . a bit thicker and less bitter and it 'd be great .

lovely , bright cherry red color ... head is large at first , simmers down quickly ... aroma : mmmmm ... .complex ! quite a rich and invigorating aroma , i postpone consumption to prolong my time drinking it deep into the nose ... really nice !  the head is a huge and fluffy 3 fingers high cloud puff with great retention and excellent lace .  the mouth feel is heavy with a decent amount of carbonation .

does n't quite live up to the smell , but still very pleasant and highly sessionable .  looks fantastic ! s : hoppy ( pine-ish ) with some malt- smelled fairly balanced and inoffensive for a high-gravity offering .  had this during o'briens wet hop festival . pours clear orange with a white ring of bubbles . lots of caramel with some tropical hops in the nose . kind of like a fruitcake . earthy , yet citrusy in the taste . bit sweeter than your normal ipa . grapefruit and blood orange . good stuff .

a - deep gold color s- amazing , citrus , grapefruit , & bubblegum aromas t- bitter hops ( grapefruit-like ) with fruity undertones . m - dry to the finish o- i was impressed that brewers were able to capture strong complexity for such a bitter , hoppy brew . overall i felt that the bitterness was way overpowering , leaving my mouth dried out .  pours into a pint glass a translucent straw yellow with a billowing white head and and amazing lacing that last throughout the drink .  m : over carbonated - fizzy .

mmmm , that head really released a lot of wonderful aromas . pine and citrus predominate and , man , it smells good . very 'merry christmas ' , but not in the tinsel-and-cookies kinda way , but the 'i 'm some crank wandering around in a pine forest and i 'm giving presents to strangers ' kinda way . it definately ai n't normal , but it sure is delicious .  a : damn near perfect in my book . nicely hazy , radiant golden orange color . it 's got a big , soapy head that settles into a cap and leaves big sheets of lacing . so far so good .  mouthfeel- light-moderate mouthfeel . carbonation is moderate-high .

) extremely unique . outstanding ! t - sweet sugary honey and vanilla flavors up front , followed by strong herbal flavors , mint , anise , and a bit of tangy hop . m - medium bodied and slick , with a course , gritty , dry finish .  pours a amber ale color with a super looking coffee colored head with tight tiny bubbles that also remits some great lacing .  creamy , light toffee . very mild bitterness . mild carbonation and foamation , could be a little more vigorous .

while really good , not as good as aroma . overall : really good . would have liked the flavor to measure up to the aroma but you still ca n't go wrong with this one .  appearance- deep brown-caramel colored pour . leaves wonderful lace streaks and patches . almost the entire glass was caked with lace after i was finished .  i purchased this beer in a mix and match pack at the recommendation of the guy working at the liquor store = error . the look of the beer was clear and it drank smooth , but it was accompanied by the 'sour beer face . ' the taste was a combination of failure and shame ( with a hint of fruit ) all leading to the grand finale of a quick pour into the drain .

the smell is exactly like a cafe mocha -- dark chocolate , buttery , and quality roasted coffee . the taste is very intense on the chocolate but the roasted coffee malts come through nicely too .  '01-'02 : starts by pouring a jet black , your unable to see through it , with a nice dark tan head that settles with deep fluffy pockets .  m - this one finished a little dry , too much so for my liking , but the carbonation was nicely balanced , making it very smooth .

s : the smell is quite amazing and complex in my opinion . there are some light hops initially noticed . overall , it is very pleasant . t : after the very satisfying smell , the taste was sort of a let down .  12 oz bottle into pilsner glass a : beautiful ! crystal clear yellow body topped off by one inch of white creamy foam .  mouf & gt ; easy , average .

s : bold and healthy hop aroma . perfect ipa smell . t : dry and hoppy .  a : the perfect clear orange color . great retention .  rich , almost like chicken soup broth , and very low carbonation . in the world of bocks , this could be a new favorite of mine .

the nose on this one is very strong . some pineapple , orange zest , and grapefruit along with some floral and piney notes . if this tastes as good as it smells , i 'm in for a sweet , citrusy treat . the taste is , unfortunately , not as juicy as the nose might suggest .  attractive looking brew here .  my first taste of it was great , however it lacks in the balance of the malts , and has sort of a over roasted taste . altogether though , this beer in my opinion is the best of the coors brand and i would recommend for something new . not a everyday beer though .
a truly profound smell . has all the plums and figs of a dickens novel .  insanely sticky , a spectacular pour .  this one was surprisingly thin in body .

very very unique beer , the nose right off the bat informs you of it . rich aroma of the carmel malts used , very heavy scent , but goes along nicely with the character of the porter . really good on a cold day in warm house kind of beer .  the stream of beer coming out of the bottle even looked impressive ! semi-firm tan head , tight bubbles , settles to a sheer cap .  even with the earthy malt flavor , the overall feel stays on the thin side .

aroma is spot-on.. lite roased barley and dark roasted malts and chocolate overtones ... even smells creamy .  absolutely beautiful orange red body with a thin white head .  mouthfeel works just fine , but is a little watery . highly drinkable .

i can smell this beer from the other side of the room ! this is one of the best smelling sours out there ! flavor is good ... but not as crazy as i expected . a good sour , but does n't stand out like i wanted it to . the obvious sour/tart funk is right on key ... and very clean and crisp . overall , a very solid sour from captain lawrence ... a must try !  a 330ml bottle fills a duvel tulip with garnet elixir topped with lots and lots of creamy head .  m/d - mouthfeel is nothing special , the steely hop bite takes a bit away .

aroma is wow ! bacon .  pours an impossibly crystal-clear straw color . the bubbles are as fine as you will find in a beer , crazy lacing on the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel is lightly carbonated , a little thick ( like a dark lager ... blech ) , and generally mediocre .

very pleasant and layered . t - very hoppy at first , but the finish balances that out with a mild and sweet maltiness .  16 ounce can , best by sept. 29 , 2011 . pours extremely hazy orange amber color with a 1 finger fairly dense off white head with good retention that reduces to a thin lacing cap that lasts .  m- thin to medium in body . highly attenuated with a soft carbonation .

a floral citrus smell hits you hard with a smell of some sweetness to it that seems to be hiding in this hoppy beer . mouthfeel- a good amount of carbonation to it between medium to heavy in its feel , about average in my opionion drinkability-is n't the best but with conditioning you can become very use to it and then it becomes very appealing . just brilliant .  young 's double chocolate stout pours super dark with an excellent thick tan head that remains until the beer is gone .  a bit more body would 've made this an excellent brew .

definitely a woodsy component going on , and i 'm thinking rosemary bark or dried thyme . not much funk , really , but the acid backbone is there making for a quite enjoyable drink on its own . phenomenal .  pours with a deep red-brown body topped by a medium thick lasting head with good lace .  medium bodied , highly carbonated .

s : wonderful fruity belgian goodness . caramel malty dubbel is a smell warms me up even on a hot evening . allagash has some of the nicest smelling belgians that come to mind .  a - black as night with a thick frothy brown head . fades slowly leaving a thin solid layer of foam on the beer with excellent lacing .  unfortunately , it is basically flat , with a heavy mouthfeel . overall , this beer would be unbelievable with good carbonation .

an immense hop punch to the nose . extremely fresh , bitter hops practically leap out of the glass . further in i get notes of orange and citrus , wrapped into a pleasing sweet malty undercurrent . superb nose . t. alas , after such a superlative smell , how could the taste hold up ? it 's a fantastic smelling , `` lite '' double ipa that is easy to put down .  appearance- pours a crystal clear brownish red , almost cognac , with four fingers of beautifully structured soapy bubbles . the head peaks well above the rim of my glass , and compacts to a creamy , hefeweizen-like consistency . outstanding lacing leaves sheets behind . excellent .  m : very very mild carbonation .

a huge aroma of starbucks mocha frappuccino jumps out of the glass . sweet chocolate and nice roasty smell mix in for quite a nose pleasing aroma . cappuccino leads the way in the flavor of this brew .  22-oz bottle opened at local beer tasting ( underground bluz ) . a beautiful brew . this beer can do some damage because you wo n't want to stop drinking it !  the mouthfeel is a little off , too light and thin .

very interesting . concrete and ginger . refreshing and smooth but a bit more bland than i expected based on the wonderful aroma . nicely mellow and subtle .  exceptional appearance with enormous meringue-like dark brown head , opaque black body , and gobs of lace as the beer goes down .  heavy mouthfeel .

aroma is rich and complex : sweet , sticky maltiness rich in caramel , accompanied by a ripe fruitiness and a good deal of citrusy hops . i do n't detect any oakiness .  still a bit of haze but not anything like a hefe . the beer looks great in this glass !  mouthfeel is slightly thin for the style or maybe just thin for how much is going on there ... .like you are expecting more of a stout mouthfeel .

very enticing . taste has quite a bit of belgian yeast and spice .  poured this puppy into a duvel tulip , which helped to bring about an ample 4 finger thick fluffy and off white head . the body is very murky and peach in color . head retention is great , as well as the lacing .  if i had to log a complaint , it would be that this stout is too thin and less of a cream offering . however , it is full of flavor and easy to drink despite being 6.5 % abv .

a : orange copper color , almost no head s : floral hops , not much else but thats ok with me . i love the way this beer smells ! t : tastes like it smells .  this beer is so dark that it makes the glass appear as if it 's jet black . it 's beautiful . no head , no carbonation , just black .  this is about my only complaint of this beer-too much carbonation ! carbonation gives a foamy/frothy mouthfeel .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever tried . good amount of pumpkin . clean and delicious . lighter side of medium in body . not sure if this is a drastic improvement from regular pumking , but this is surely tasty .  great black appearance with cascade of bubbles when poured that lasted a minute , leaving 1/2 inch tan head that stayed until the glass was empty .  very good light lager . hints of barley and hops , with a smooth slightly dry aftertaste . this brew had a short lived white foamy head and lower than normal carbonation . i would highly recommend this to any light beer drinker .

very powerful sweet aroma . overall : fantastic beer , will definitely get again .  pours a deep , rich plummy color topped by a lively head of sloppy , sticky looking foam . this has a very healthy head that sticks around and laces majestically .  carbonation is n't bad , with fairly good activity after each drink . mouth-feel is a bit dry .

i am smelling a creme brulee desert right now ... i do n't think i could tell the difference from the real thing . exceptional . there is a touch of courseness in the back of the throat from the abv and bitterness .  a deep amber reddish beer with a mother of pearl head . the head on this brew is large fluffy , lasting and pungent .  m-a bit watery for my tastes but the taste makes you forget about it being slightly thin .

delicious citrus fruits with resin-y sweetness in the background -heavenly . d : a little too off-balance to be gulp-able , but certainly a yummy beer .  dugana pours beautifully for a 2.5 finger thick off white head , with great retention .  it has constantly proved itself to be my favorite local utah brew ( this use to be called the 2002 unofficial ale ) . if the pour makes your mouth literally water , you know it 's good . damn good beer ,

nice maple , nice cognac pipe tobacco aroma going on as well as some nice syrup smell . great . t- initially , some nice matliness , caramel/maple , then some dry hops .  pours a dark copper with a large , foamy white head that hung around forever . large amounts of thick lacing left on the glass surface . this is one beautiful beer .  rated as a stout the mouthfeel is a bit thin , the carbonation is a bit high , and the finish is a bit less than one would expect .

the aroma is amazing . major chocolate aroma with a dose of roasted malts , vanilla , toffee and cocoa . sort of a letdown on the taste .  a beautiful appearance , two thick fingers of creamy light coco head with spectacular lacing coating the glass .  the mouthfeel has a strange little zing that seems inappropriate for the style .
the aroma is pretty muffled by the head .  a- dark brown with an off white creamy one finger head that laces nicely to the last drop .  mouthfeel is a bit light .

this is one of the nicest smelling beers i 've had .  anyways , into the erdinger glass ... a - really impressed with this head .  mouthfeel is fairly carbonated , a bit sour , finishing dry and crisp .
smells like garbage .  spectacular retention and thick , chunky lace .  m : meh . disappointingly flat . i 'd like more carbonation .
