aroma is powerfully sour and very champagney . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .  pour revelaed an extremely thick and long lasting creamy white head.as it reduced it left rings of lace in the glass.the color presented was orange and somewhat cloudy.mouthfeel wasnt very crisp and seemed a bit watery.the finish left a sharp sweet or tart twist that dissapeared real quick.a bit bitter in the back of the throat with a wheaty grain taste.a spicy aroma thats not too strong but is there.tastes of oranges , lemon , cloves , corriander , and honey are noted.overall good with a medium body .  taste : a bit thin for a porter , almost to the point of being slightly watery .

smells fantastic ! fruity , citrus , & some serious hops . one of the better smelling beers i 've had .  this brew pours into the glass with a black body topped by a thick creamy , light brown head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  medium to thick body , light almost too light level of carbonation with a sweet almost sticky mouthfeel .

the aroma is honeysuckle and dark fruit , complex , tropic , and soothing . mouthfeel is brighter than i would have expected , but leaves a slightly gritty film on the teeth . the taste is not nearly as complex or abundant as the smell and alcohol does not feature much part in it .  look : bright golden color , white head of creamy foam with 2 fingers thick , very good lacing , has a sticker that say it was the best beer in the world in 2002 , let see if it 's true ; smell : biscuity malts and fruit essences ; taste : pine and spicy hops , molasses , some biscuity malts , alcohol and sugars at the finish ; mouthfeel : dry and very bitter , bittersweet and spicy finish , the body is creamy and thick ; drinkability : the first time i try the `` tripel '' style , very spicy .  ginger is one of my favorite flavors . this beer has a wonderful ginger taste , which is exactly what i would expect from a beer with this name . further , there is a decent bitterness & a slight sweetness as well . i 'm not a huge fan of spiced beers normally , but this one is really nice . recommended .

aroma is just perfect . a slice of pumpkin pie in a bottle is what this beer is . picture perfect . easy to drink with good mouthfeel .  the retention was downright insane and it essentially sat there like whipped cream . beautiful looking beer .  a really really long aftertaste in the nose .

richer . the sweetness comes through much more . i highly recommend storing one of these away to turn a very good experience into a great one .  a : orange colour and a huge 4 cm head that sticks around due to the high carbonation .  lowish carbonation and a slightly thin mouthfeel .

very nice presentation . aroma is forresty ( real word ? ) with grassy , herbal , piney , sprucy hop notes along with citrus notes of grapefruit and lemon rind .  amazing retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel of the beer was , like most porter and ale styles , very average . however , the mouthfeel did not detract from the overall feel of the beer .

the smell of this 2 year old beer is so rich and strong . it smells of sweet fruits and a little bit of alcohol .  almost impossible to open due to the stupid wax coating covering the whole swing top . lightly hazed bronze color with a nice full pillowy light beige head , nice active carbonation , and nice lace sheets .  the mouthfeel was medium/light bodied with a fine , prickly carbonation .

nose is simply stunning . soaring sour limeade with an intense barnyard element , a good smack of leather , and just a hint of very sweet malt .  there is lots retention and great lacing . it might be best lacing i 've vere seen .  s : candied pineapple , yeast , and hops well balanced t : a typical ipa taste with accents of pineapple ; yeasts and hops , well balanced m/d a bit thin , carbonation too small and too much , abv on the high side and quite noticeable good beer

the aroma , however , is a-one , outstanding , and really well captured in the wineglass : nice , fresh pumpkin accompanied by strong notes of cinnamon , nutmeg , clove , maybe some ginger ... wow , this is the smell i look for in my pumpkin ales - imo they nailed it . that said , i feel the flavor takes a step back ; maybe the nose raised expectations too high ... still very nice , with the pumpkin and spices pulling through , but perhaps not as robustly as the nose had led me to believe ; there 's also a not entirely pleasant though subtle bitterness to it , as well as a bit a boozy bite to the finish .  bottle poured into a tulip glass . brilliant clarity . thick white crop of foam with good retention and moderate lacing .  i wish the carbonation was a little more noticeable in the mouth .

s- very large coffee smell . great complexity . t- taste starts with sweet fruits and a little bit of chocolate then is balance excellently by fresh bitter coffee .  almost black with a cream colored head measuring maybe one finger . i love pouring it out of the gan into a pint glass and watching it mix and cascade turning from the color of mud to the color of .  could use both more body and carbonation .

this beer gives you a great looking glass ... smell- ... and a great smell ! incredible smell , might be the best smelling ipa i 've had so far . really nice batch . smells like a field of flowers and with its distinct flowery smell that might remind some of opening a pot of honey .  a : jet black with a nice dark mocha head that sits just barely above the beer . perfect for the style s : has a very nice mellow scotch smell that is not too harsh along side a slight sweetness of vanilla and honey .  thin body ample carbonation overall : this is slightly better than bud light but still not really worth drinking

the aroma was quite lax , nothing really going on in the nose , it smelled a little spicey and nutty , but that 's all i got ? the taste is solid ; nice mix of unique spices and a grea tmalt taste with a sweet tone as well , i found it hard to grasp what exactly was in here but it was dispersed throughout very well .  a- really nice big belgian-style head on top of a fizzy , slightly hazy , light straw colored body . looks lovely in a belgian tulip glass .  taste is more of the same ... some wild floral flavors , hints of citrus ... seems like the dominant flavors have switched from the citrus to the floral characteristics . i like it , for sure , but could use some balance . i 'm not a big fan of the bitter taste left in the mouth ... but it 's still plenty drinkable . a definitely above-average ale , but not the best .

the smell of this thing is very lively , wow , its all over the place , funky as hell , smokey banana and smoked salmon or bacon , dull lemon , musty horse blanket , soft rubber , and feet .  full black color with a thick , creamy head .  m - thought it was a little flat , but not bad .

a little unusual too . overall , a unique and very enjoyable iipa .  deep brown pour with a gigantic , rocky , tan head .  the beer poured hard but the carbonation ended up being low and the mouthfeel medium .
aroma is simply heavenly , with strong molasses overtone and some burnt hints .  pitch black with a full dark amber head that settles to very thick sticky lacing .  the body is rather thin though .

light malt and grainy presence upfront with nice floral hop notes and undertones of grassy hops . overall , quite flavorful and easy drinking , tasted fresh despite the freshness date being about 3 weeks past .  almost black colour , with a very good head .  palate : medium body , thinner than expected actually , but goes down smooth .

tons of chocolate malt , coffee , anise , plums , raisons a fruit blender of aromas . it really needed more hops to balance this bad boy out .  this beer poured a cloudy deep gold that bordered on light amber . it 's pure white head was thick and rich , solid lacing adorned the glass .  pours a three finger light tan head that fades quickly to a ring leaving a little lace . dark cloudy amber color . light carbonation and light bodied . caramel nose . starts balanced but then a caramel flavor that stays to a clean finish . a tasty wheat . $ 2.49 for a 500ml bottle from john 's grocery iowa city , ia .

amazing . t : sweet malt that has plenty of peat flavors that i love so much in scottish ales .  i was first impressed with the color - almost black ! big , creamy , frothy head .  mouthfeel was avg ; like a nice dark beer .

smell : fantastic , lots of citrus , pine and bubble gum . it is decently balanced but could use some more malt backbone .  just an absolutely pitch black beer that poured like motor oil and had one of the darkest , longest lasting heads i have seen on an imperial stout .  the mouth is a little lighter than years past .

strong vanilla notes , sugar , and faint chocolate aroma..southern tier really has a knack for completely nailing the nose on their brews t - do n't know if i could drink any more than the 9oz i was poured . this is incredibly sweet , and extremely rich . a perfect dessert beer .  looks picture perfect . despite my allergies , i can actually smell floral hops .  mouthfeel is fine - it 's a very light lager .

appealing . t : dirty orange peel , fringe fruit esters that do n't ring distinctly and ca n't be identified , and full barley .  it pours a thick , viscous black with a large dark tan hea that slowly recedes .  m : um . it was carbonated and did n't leave any odd off flavours on the palate .

a : dark but not black - can see through it up to the light - pour was unimpressive - really no head to speak of from a bottle - no lace - nothing - looks like coke in a glass s : chocolate , vanilla , malt , milk t : very strong bitter in here with the malt , vanilla - seems like they put too many hops in this for it to be a milk/sweet stout .  bottled april 22 , 2009 poured into a pint glass amber with a very thick white head . very good retention and lacing .  m- light in body and light to medium in carbonation .

sweet and sugary , but delicious and unique . alcohol is absolutely brutal on this bitch as the heat slaps you in the face with the force of 10,000 fighting japanese midget minnow farmers .  dark copper with a 2 finger off-white head from a 22 into a pint glass . i drink slower , so i poured the remainder almost 30 minutes later and it still formed a 2 finger head . this is much lighter in the smoke than any rauch that most people have had .  sprecher brewing company is one of milwaukee 's first micro 's and in fact its the one that really got me into quality beer tasting and home brewing . this is one of my favorite octoberfest beers as far as drink-ability as many octo 's are a bit overly heavy for me . this one really leaves your palate refreshed and ready for more . i lived in germany for two years and never found a beer at a octoberfest there that was like american octoberfest style of brews but thats why i like them they are unique even if maybe they are n't trying to be .

a : pours a pale yellowish amber color with frothy white head and lots of lacing on the glass s : smells like major hops , citrus , grapefruit , some pine ... the usual great dipa scents t : tastes just like the smell , but the hops are less prevalent that i expected .  pours a pretty deep black with dark tan head that clings to the glass . looking quite appealing .  3.0 m : medium body . smooth , but not creamy .

earthy , weedy , hoppy , piney ! a real west coast ipa . love it ! not for the faint of heart hop haters , but awesome for hop lovers ! definitely interesting with tropical fruit hints in this one . mouthfeel : deliciously crisp and oily .  a - a beautiful pour . deep amber with an inch of off-white head . as the head slowly goes away it leaves great lace and ends up in a creamy , bumpy layer on top of the brew .  mouthfeel is a little thin , though .

the smell is sweet , spicy , almost vinous , and very complex . each time i think i have an aroma captured it changes into something else .  a : an outstanding looking beer . dark plum color with a pinch of tannish head and amazing coating lacing . stunning .  my only gripe with this beer was the mouthfeel . it was rather thin and watery with a mild yet large bubbled effervescence .

amazingly strong - smells of syrupy semi-sweet chocolate and very deep roasty and toasty malts ; smells like very fresh brewed espresso ... actually , the `` freshness '' of the smell is really quite intense . taste : very burnt and roasty malt characteristics that are reminiscent of fresh brewed espresso and grounds ; faint flavors of semi-sweet baking chocolate ; i have to admit , this would be an amazing morning drink .  bomber poured a clear dark reddish brown nearly black with a lasting brown head .  m : somewhat thin body , slightly watery ; could do with more carbonation also .

head is a bright off white , watery and light , not much retention or lacing ... outstanding aroma , very funky floral muskyness , some nice brett ... taste has some nice things going , this is a musky sour brett saison , not sweetness , makes no bones about it . crushable musky saison , well worth trying .  - served at cellar temperature appearance : sort of hazy ( unfiltered beer ) golden color with orange highlights . the head is off white and bubbly , like a champagne . cakey top part of the head and lots of sticky lace left on the sides of the glass .  m- low carbonation and very low mouthfeel .

pours a hazy amber/orange color with a small white to light yellow head , very bubbly . nose is amazing , fresh and fruity , mango , grapefruit , pine and sweet fruit juice . taste is much less fruity than the nose , but it 's still top notch , for a regular ipa it sure packs a hop punch , very bitter and palate tingling . a really nice addition to lawson 's hoppy line up !  on tap o'brien 's pub san diego , ca black with a lot of visible carbonation and a thin brown head . regular , lined lacing down the glass . very attractive and perfect for a black ipa . roasted malts and pine aromas combine , though i would suggest that the roast is fairly dominant .  a delightful golden color graced by a pale yellow head . i did n't get much lacing , but i believe that was due to a freshly-washed glass ( served at a bar ) . nice hops come through in this one . it is a little bitter and spicy , but also has some good vanilla and tones of malt . not the most fantastic example of its style , but tasty and very drinkable .

smell is downright incredible , with lots of oily hops , citrus , and a complexity i ca n't describe .  appearance : looks beautiful . jet black stout , brown creamy head pours thick with a thin half finger head .  mouf & gt ; nice , nothing special drinkability & gt ; sure thing

s : not much going on hear , some toffee and yeast t : very malty , toffee sweetness , some spice .  wow , orange , slightly reddish , as it let 's the light pass through ... it 's beautiful . such a strong head , off-white .  there is a very little carbonation factor in this beer .

aroma is amazing - brandy , caramel , brown sugar , dark fruits , vanilla , and oak . bummer i 'll probably never have it again , as rare as it is .  a : beautiful beer ! it 's a perfectly clear light amber color topped by a big-bubble , thin but foamy head . lacing is alright , but the beer looks so good it makes up for that in other areas .  perhaps a bit thin for the style , which i suppose makes it a good pale ale for summertime quaffing .

s : best nose on a dipa i 've ever experienced . the alcohol is actually a complement to the hop aroma , however . this is one of those `` i wish this was an air freshener '' aromas . t & m : flavor is interesting -- some herbal and grassy hops , some notes of citrus , and a good smattering of pine . it does n't seem to be as balanced as stone ipa , but it 's still pretty tasty . the mouthfeel is very nice -- a sticky , full , and lasting feel with a long finish .  this beer pours beautifully , glowing , hazed apricot amber in color with 3 fingers of fluffy froth topped by rocky peaks . retention is epic and lace coats my maredsous goblet .  slight hint of the hop flower but the malt dominates , sweet , crisp , fresh and pleasing to the senses with the start lightly sweet , satisfactory malt presence , and top light to middling in feel . this is a style where i like the lighter body , as it lets the flavoring hops shine through , quite quaffable , a damn fine session beer me thinks , and i thank royalt for this bottle .

the mystery beer in my joe 's garage variety pack , poured a deep brown with dark near crimson hue when held up to the light with a large 2 finger mocha colored head.perfect 5 for me aroma wise its american big on the fruity , piney hop mixed with chocolate and earth just fantastic love the big hop profile.the same goes for the flavors big piney drier hop profile intertwined with bitter chocolate with a earthy raw nut lingering finish.a little prickly on the mouth but nothing to take away from the great flavors of the beer , damn i wish there more porters like this it is the most hoppedup version i think i have had to date .  this beer was so pretty that i had to stop and take a picture . a beautiful translucent golden color with a billowing white head .  m - at times , a bit of a metallic feel to the beer .

aromas of lots of different berries ( strawberies , blueberries , blackberries , and raspberries ) . i would get a different berry every time i sniffed . the berries were done nice ! good thing i like all the types of berries in this one .  a- looks awesome . pours a crytal clear light brassy orange , with a massive white oamy , fluffy head that slowly shrinks down leaving behind all kinds of webbing lace .  no sediment at all when bought fresh . this really brought out flavors you could not taste beforehand . a wedge of orange or lemon is a nice touch also . best served a little warmer than most beers . goes really well with food . a beer you could drink all night especially during a good bar-b-que .

crazy amount of hops , smells awesome . t - tastes of citrus hops , pine , grapefruit , smooth fruity malts . d - this is definitely a very good black ipa .  a - very dark murky brown pour , extremely large ( 4-finger ) head . really beautiful .  mouthfeel is carbonated , but creamy and smooth . lacks the dry bite that i look for in a dipa .

2008 vintage a- almost stout-like in appearance , no head , fizzy swirl of carb in the middle of a color-devoid structure ... s-vanilla , cherry , oak , intense , strong , amazing smells ... .omg ... .there is n't a single hint of sour beer behind this nose . simply smooth vanilla and cherry ... awesome ... .ca n't remember a better nose on a sour ... . t- starts off smooth , nothing much going on *served at 39 degrees f.* then spice , phenols , tartness , tanginess , oh man ... this is great ... . m- solid brick of a mouthfeel , with a few glimmers of carbonation ... nothing exceptionally nasty about the 'brick ' that i speak of , but it is different ... .all together a different beer but for mouthfeel , i 'd expect something flat to taste like this , but in all it provides the right amount of carbonation ! duchesse on crack ...  appearance- deeper colored golden pour with a full inch plus rocky head with a good 1/4 inch of staying power . great looking beer .  feels thin .

really delicious smell t : very tannic finish ... almost too much . not as sour as the smell suggests , but very nice . lots of flavor going on !  a : a medium amber color with a very robust creamy white head . it has a very creamy and milky head . lacing is incredible . s : it smells of citrus ( orange or grapefruit ) with floral notes .  much like the ingredient list on the back , there are scent of malted barley , malted wheat , hops , and yeast which gives it an almost caramel scent . starts out making you think this will be a heavy tasting beer with its malted ingredients like a stout but instead it finishes rather light . drinks rather smooth as the malted ingredients really hit the taste buds . finishes rather clean smooth . a decent beer with a rather interesting drinking experience .

aroma is awesome . yeast .  tasted in mid-may 2009. nearly opaque , black/brown , with reddish brown on the edges under the light . great lacing , forming curtains in the latter half of the glass .  had some fruity and clove flavors but was covered up due way too many hops for the style - not to mention that it was bitter . i barely finished it . other reviewers liked this beer and seemed to have a much different experience than i did which leaves me to believe that they have consistency problems or maybe they use different formulas for each location ? btw this one was sampled at the brewpub near the fleet center .

aromas are awesome . i can smell this for a couple of feet away .  poured into duvel tulip glass , half beer half very thick foamy head . very solid beer .  mouthfeel is a little thin , but not offensively so .

the nose is extremely complex -- clay soil , caramel , butter , farmland , and fresh aromatic hops are all in there , along with some more elusive intangibles that are conjuring up all sorts of images of rural europe for me . on the tongue , the caramel sings out with a spritzy edge , the hops keep it interesting , and the butter moves to the forefront , but what really does it for me is a slight sour twist towards the end -- reminiscent of those flemish ales that ive recently fallen in love with ( such as duchesse de bourgogne ) . this says to me , `` drink with food !  brown 33cl bottle with an artsy looking label . pours a peach orange-honey -very murky with a big 1inch + cap and holds very well down to 1 finger after a few minutes . very fluffy and fresh-looking lace which leaves thick puffs on glass . the head holds so well it is similar to egg-whites with very soft peaks .  just the right amount of hops . even though you can taste the fruits and spice , you can also taste the high alc % . drinkability : very drinkable , but if you more than one in a session , watch out : ) overall : a better than average tripel .

smell- unbelievable aroma ! overall- has a great aroma but falls short with the taste .  got a single of this the other day , and poured it into my mug and the appearance is beautiful . hazy straw color , best looking ive seen in a hefe .  leaves you breathless -- groping for words to describe what is one of the worst beers i 've ever tasted . i have had enough bacterial beers to recognize the usual flavors .

750ml bottle into duvel tulip a : golden/almost straw color with 3 '' thick , white whipped-cream like foam s : mango ! tropical fruit . smell of a very `` sticky '' and sweet fruit . once the foam dissipated , i can smell some `` yogurty '' belgian yeast . t : low-medium , maltiness with some husky ( tannin ) character upfront . noticed a very clean belgian yeast flavor after my palate got used to the beer . d : highly drinkable .  poured a translucent mustard/straw yellow with a huge , rocky , white head that faded into clumps of white froth . beautiful lacing .  m- a bit over carbonated for me , but other than the crisp nature of most kiwi beers , nice malty and dry .

s- huge floral hop aroma escapes from the glass . t- extremely flavorful , very hoppy with a hoppy grapefruit finish . d- exceptionally drinkable .  made a great appearance , poured a classic beer golden with a very large creamy foamy white head with a lot of sticking .  m - moderate carbonation-almost too much , dry finish , medium bodied due to the carbonation .

anyways always seem to go with styles not fitting to the season and well we are in the mist of june and i 'm loving me some barley wines at the moment ! smell , well imagine a bowl of uncooked fruit cake batter . rum , raisins , dark fruits and figs , dates sweet molasses and soft belgium brown sugar . taste ; velvety fruit cake batter , more of the same from the nose . this beer is deliciously smooth and creamy . such a dessert evening sipper for sure . although they are great beers it just seems to me they dont fit in well with the style of barley wines . the hour passed and it might of been the alcohol but i could of had another 12 oz .  looks great on a goblet . amazing retention and lacing .  m : surprisingly on the more carbonated side with a slight fizzy mouthfeel .

spicy and compliments the smell . m - thin and smooth , carbonation does not come in to play which may be from the age . d - this beer is very drinkable .  highly envigorated light brown head of fine bubbles that left behind a nice lacing on the pour .  a light- to moderate mouthfeel , hints of sour flavor linger at the back of the tongue after the swallow . i do n't pick up much of a hint of carbonation in the mouthfeel .

unfortunately , the smell does n't measure up to the appearance . it 's ok , but nothing spectacular . well , the taste certainly is nice . complex , malty sweet , and again , i taste the cherries . for 8 % , this is extremely smooth and drinkable .  bottle to a tulip pours a clear red body , and by red i mean excellent vibrant red . has a fizzy white head that doesnt stay for the party .  mouthfeel medium body for the style with sharp carbonation .

aromas are just awesome ... deep rich fruits , candy sugar , plenty of oak barrel , dark bread-like yeast character , and some orange peel in the back . maple and molasses in the sweetness , with just a touch of citrus rhind hops in the finish . not overly chewy , which was nice for this strength of beer .  a tawny amber gem in the glass , champagne bubbles like fireworks , and an incredible mountainous head .  the mouthfeel is thiner but still good .

aroma is unable to be discerned in this sitting , it 's quite faint .  a-amber with sediment and good frothy head . the color an intense head gives this one high scores .  there is little ( hardly any ) carbonation here , and the mouthfeel really does n't pack a punch at all .

4.0 s : nice aroma . it smells like a tripel meets saison . for the most part , the goofy ingredients get lost in the mix .  the colour is pitch-black ; the two finger head is pale beige , airy and uneven . massive amounts of lacing .  m : light bodied and well carbonated .

smell : awesome . juicy citrus hop hit the nose hard . taste : does n't quite live up to the smell , but still very good . the hops are more herbal with some citrus in there as well . still very good and really glad to have tried this .  pours a big white head that takes up half a tulip glass , then settles to a half inch of meringue . body is dark yellow with some wit-like cloudiness .  mouth feel : a bit thin on the palet , or maybe the aroma and taste make you expect more in the way of mouth feel .

very strong smells of pineapple and pirate beers waft away from the glass . there is caramel , yeast and citrus along with the sea , like the belgian pirate-themed beers i have tried . cold weather seems to encourage the brewing gene ... slainte .  on-tap at beachwood bbq , on to the beer : the head retention is great on top this coal black beer . great , thick lacing sticks to the glass .  m : very carbonated .

the second the cap is popped , the aromas come rushing out and literally fill the room . it smells like i 'm chopping up fresh oranges and pineapples as i pour this beer ; remarkable ! this beer takes me longer to finish than most dipas this drinkable because i stop to sniff this beer before every sip ! it is not exceptionally bitter but a rather sweet and citrusy ipa . there is n't a lot of malt getting in the way of the hops , hops , hops . a superbly drinkable dipa .  much better than guinness off the nitro-keg , but not as good as a regular quality stout . very imposing solid black brew with a giant head .  mouthfeel suffers a little bit as i feel a higher abv would 've left this coating the tongue a little better . it seemed a little too thin to match its flavor profile .

it 's an awesome smelling stout !  a pint of the black stuff , or the priest , looks as good as ever , enjoyable to watch it settle over a minute or so .  a little less carbonation and this probably enters `` special '' territory .

not faux-bacos as many low-end rauschbiers often are ... but honest to god bacon . once you get through the scent , there is a wonderfully salty and sweet beer underneath , that makes you want to keep drinking .  appearance is beautiful . pours an oaky golden light brown . leaving a dense one finger head on top of the beer .  the carbonation is heavy and it adds harshness to the palate . medium-full body .

smell : strong coffee notes over roasted malt . fairly straight forward but the limited dimensions it offers are good in their own right . taste : fairly waterly coffee rinds .  on-cask at the brewpub : hazyish copper tinted hay color with a puffy topping of oatmeal cream . keeps its cap for a great length and laces well across the glass in small curtains and spots .  take this beer for what it is ... a nice `` treat . '' it 's not something you will want to drink all night long . but for a nightcap , or change of pace this beer fits the bill . the vanilla taste is not overpowering , it 's there , but not so bold and overpowering that it seems fake .

beautiful hop smell : floral , grass , the smell of spring basically . a little bit of bread & cracker smell . very aromatic , but not overwhelming , a smooth & even hop character . the lovely hop character is forward in the taste , but again not overwhelming or destructive to the tastebuds .  pours a nice amber color with a white head and excellent lacing .  thin to medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

smell is heavenly , with the almost overpowering aroma of peaches . there is a slight coating of sweet , sticky phlegm in the back of my throat , but it is sort of pleasing . over all this was a great journey and the buzz is just what i needed .  pours a deep brown with ruby highlights into a tulip . creamy off-white/light khaki head leaves excellent lacing and retention .  mouthfeel was a bit heavy and undercarbonated , but that may have been more of the fault of the bar i was at , and not the beer its self .

smooth , creamy taste , easy to drink with mild to medium body . cloudy , yellow-amber color . compatible with multiple foods . the first i have had of this style .  pours deep brown with a stiff egg custard-colored head that fades slowly .  the mouth fell was a little thin for stout .

s- very complex with sweet milk chocolate predominating mixed with a good amount of raisin , smells like a raisin candy bar in a good way . t- not as complex as the nose but still tasty . lots of chocolate with a finish of the whipped cream , the other flavors seem lost in the mix .  poured into a new belgium snifter a - a beautiful clear dusk sunset color , 2 finger head that lingered and lacing through and through and awesome tiny bubbles for days s - pine , citrus , malt , floral , cotton , sweet , grains and maybe a bit toasty t - very nice bitter sweet , pine , orange , melon , pineapple , very hoppy and yet super bitter sweet malty m - coats the mouth a bit with some super bitter sweet lingering .  m/t : light to medium body , watery and a good amount of carbonation . however with the light body , low bitterness and virtually zero aftertaste , i could session this beer .

this beer smell awesome ! ! ! as i drink it , the problem is , what flavors match up with these aromas ? the beer has a great london/english fruity estery taste with christmas ale type flavors of nutmeg and cinimmon . i wish i had more than one of these to review beacuse its a really complex ale that i would like to clone . a very drinkable ale with a great nutty spicey fruity finish .  it has a great thick fluffy dark mocha colored head perched upon a jet black body . the head was still present a good 5 minutes after pouring .  the body was medium to medium light .

smell- that of very fresh raspberries . not the fake sugared and candied scent , but a kind of smell you may catch at jamba juice when you order a smoothie . taste- a tad sour and tart at first , which turns to a nice sweet flavor . not as fresh as the scent was . tasted a bit like jolly ranchers .  perfect appearence for an ipa , with a strong , full foaming head that lasts .  mouthfeel : slighty watery good .

quite a nice and pleasant aroma with qualities of banana , slight clove , a little phenol and a general light ( and sweet ) fruitiness with a backing of wheat . overall , a great aroma and appearance otherwise average , at best .  gorgeous . a few streamers feed the head , which retains ok and leaves nice lacing .  mouthfeel : typical red stickyness drinkability : i love this beer .

very resilient aromatics , wonderful . taste - a brief sweet malt start goes nowhere before some serious hops kick in .  a - pours a very dark brown - almost black - with a two-finger , well-carbonated , beige head that slowly dissipates to a 1 cm head . very attractive drink , as well as bottle which is slightly shorter and wider than most 12 oz bottles .  mouthfeel is high carbonated foamy and slightly mouthcoating .

it pours a cloudy golden orange color and smells delicious . the nose had hints of orange peel , coriander , hops and light caramel . drinkability was a little low though due to the over carbonation and the sweetness of the beer overall , but very good . will buy again  the appearance is simply beautiful . a rich brown that seems to be characteristic of most trappist ales . this actually sort of reminds me of the way eku 28 eisbock smells , which is odd for a trappist .  tart and dry feel , but not overly so . lower carbonation detracts a little , really the only flaw in my mind .

coffee and lemon aromas , very rich and inviting . thick , thick , thick mouthfeel ... molasses , some coffee , and a dense and vaguely cherry flavor . bitter as all get out .  poured into a standard snifter at about 55 degrees f , 1-inch head , light lacing , deep beautiful cloudy magenta .  mouthfeel is light , and carbonation is set at medium .

smell only needs one word : raspberries . lots of raspberries . also smells a bit tart and kind of like juice . very sweet and tart at the same time .  bottle : poured a clear golden color ale with a big foamy head with good retention and good lacing .  thin bodied , and just sufficient carbonation , but i suspect the growler is at fault much more than the beer .

oh , man ... the aroma on this is , perhaps as the name implies , heavenly . almost a perfect balance in the nose -- fruity , pine needles , grapefruit . and this one goes through three `` hoppings , '' kettle , hop back , and dry hopping ... awesome . the flavor is just about perfect . a fine balance of hop flavors , including a nice grapefruit bitterness and a light bready undertone . but , as a whole , this is a very drinkable beer ... and quite delicious .  bottle : poured a deep pitch-black stout with a motor oil consistency and a small foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  m - crisp and bitey , high carbonation - the bottle overflowed when i opened it .

smell - smells absolutely delicious ! ! lots of fruit/wheat and some toasty nuts ... yumm , 5 for sure .  has my favorite froth for this style , thick and sticky , goes nowhere fast and the color looks bread .  the motuhfeel is moderately carbonated and slightly watery .

the aroma - mango , pineapple , & exotic flowers - is delightful . smells like hawaii in a bottle ! not as grapefruity as i usually like , but i did n't mind the lack at all ; a very pleasant surprise .  `` mad bitch '' has an great look . upon pouring it creates a beautiful white head that lasts for the duration of the drink . the beer is an opaque , honey color that is incredibly appetizing .  mouthfeel is on the thin side for a stout .

smell : lovely aroma of toasted fresh bread with earthy hints of nuts , vanilla , and molasses . drinkability : starts off with a great aroma , but the taste slips just a bit .  a : pours a hazy golden with a thick bubbly white head that slowly faded into a thick film that lasted the whole beer through and left an incredible fuzzy sheet of solid lacing down the glass . beautiful .  nice aroma of hops but i would hope for a bit more being a hops lover . the celebration ale , from the same company , seems to hit the spot more than this beer but still worthy of a place in the fridge and still better than many micro beer ipa ii . sierra nevada seems to me to be the only mass beer company that brews excellent beer for `` mass beer '' prices .

it smells like when i picked hops and stuck my head into a box of them . it smells so fresh it 's wonderful . the taste was rather assertive in hoppiness .  a - black ... cool s - nutty and fresh with some fruits behind but not really much of a scent t - tastes like an oil mixed with dirt .  mouthfeel was ok , not too thin , right amount of carbonation .

the smell was everything you would expect from a beer as hoppy as this . the smell of hop oil was big .  a - murky apple juice with and incredible pillow head ... slow to leave , chunky lace left .  the carbonation is around medium . there is a watery texture to the beer which is not pleasant .

the aroma was underwhelming but neutral grainy .  appearance - black with no light passing through . good tan head on top . looks like a very nice stout or porter . nice amount of head but with even less lacing then their other beers .  guest two usually drinks michalob ultra , coors light , or busch light . since this is my girlfriends dad he knows about my passion for quality beer so i 'll often encourage him to sample what i am drinking . he rarely enjoys any of them and most of the time makes a look of disgust after the first sip . he drank two bitburgers in about a half hour without one little peep about the taste . i noticed these reactions before i had the opportunity to sample this beer myself . later in the evening , after the music was turned down and the midnight snacks were partaken of , i tried one . they were right , this beer sucks over a year later i have grown to like this beer alot .

smell : delicious and complex . truly a melange of different aromas . coffee bean , caramel , toffee , chocolate . wonderfully palatable . drinkability : very drinkable . excellent complexity of flavors .  has a really nice fluffy one finger tan head that sticks around . lacing covers a huge portion of the glass .  m : very carbonated - almost too much .

hops are juicy smelling . very complex and citrus-fruity aroma . t : mmmm ! d : this is a tasty beer on the verge of being terrific . a solid offering , i would have a few of these .  the appearance was a perfect deep color with a incredible head .  m - fairly thin body and medium carbonation . nothing special on the mouthfeel .

malty aroma , mostly caramel and crackery , but there 's a light hop and fruit component as well . i really liked the aroma , but once i took a sip things went downhill .  nitro-can encouraged frothy tan head , superb retention , some lace , almost opaque hue .  the taste is sweet and smooth , with a hint of hops but the most prevalent taste is of lemon . finishes with a very refreshing aftertaste . i would defiantly suggest this beer to even non craft beer drinkers .

a harmonious aroma of raisins and rosemary , dominating . dates and caramel , intoxicating sugars . wow , taste is right there too . it 's just alluring .  bottle into an english pint glass appearance - dark brown/red hue reminds me of high grade saddle leather . a very handsome brew , sir .  the flavor too is ever so slight wine barrel aging with a weird and awkward type sour . it 's really off putting . this barrel aging was awful . this beer is weak and severely overrated . it was awful both times .

the smell is wonderful , definitely loved the smell of this one . very balanced beer .  pours a completely opaque pitch black . light brown head with some big bubbles around the edges .  m : not too bad , there was a little bit of body .

the smell is a complete disappointment . it smells like a good ipa , just not a wet hopped ipa .  poured from the 22oz bomber into a belgian duvel glass . appearance- beer pours a clear brown with red hues with a finger thick cap of irish cream foam .  this feels thin for some reason . carbonation is good and proper .

i smell a fruity and floral characteristic along with a strong citrusy hop overtone . this is a classic ipa and the brewers knew what they were doing with this batch .  this amber ale pours with a clear amber body topped by a thick head with lots of lacing left on the glass .  mouthful mouthful is okay . has decent carbonation , but i 've had better as far as carbonation goes .

some lacing & no head retention smell ; huge oaky & sherry notes taste : super sweet up front , followed by raisin , vanilla , treacle/honey and tangerine notes . very complex , but a little too sweet for my tastes mf : syruppy , oily , undercarbonated , & slightly out of balance .  beautiful nitro thick creamy tan head over a black body . has a lovely way of settling to a creamy solid chunk that wo n't spill out of the glass if you tilt it .  despite the nearly opaque black color , the flavor of this one is surprisingly light . there are sweet malt notes , a delicious fruitiness and some fairly rich yeasty , estery notes . i keep over-looking this brewery , but every time i try one of their beers im usually pretty impressed . this particular beer is tasty , refined and very drinkable . recommended .
smells great ! ! !  nice tight eggshell head . nearly brilliantly clear .  mouthfeel is ok. a litte too dry for my liking though .

pours a deep amber ruby body with a nice modest off white head . smells of a massive combination of strong barley wine and oak . there 's flavors of raisons , plums and caramel on the nose with lots of vanilla and toasted notes from the oak . bourbon and dark fruit play out initially .  pours a cloudy amber brown into a wine glass with two fingers worth of frothy , white head . the lacing clings to the inside of the glass for dear life , and is quite exquisite .  very ashy , very charred , and it really lacks some body and sweetness to back up the astringency . feel is very light , a shame , because a thick , chewy , silky body is a necessity in the style .

sweet tropical notes , mainly mango accompany a major amount of hops in the scent . there was a lot i liked but overall very good .  this poured out a rich golden color with a lovely red-orange glow that danced reflective light off my fingertips . a rush of tiny bubbles formed a thick white head that dissipated at an average pace , leaving foamy crystals that clung to the sides of my tulip glass . superb !  it was my first fruity beer . it kinda tasted like an apricot . i was expecting most of a fruit taste like wine , but no . and i liked the picture on the bottle . and since it came ithaca i just had to try it . over all the beer was worth it . it 's good . : )

heavy caramels , bourbon , dark fruits , a fruity sweetness and a touch of tobacco.. this is really a fantastic smelling barleywine . i 'd dare to say it is one of the best smelling barleywines that i 've had to date . kudos to a great bouquet . plenty of caramel malt to provide a creamy mouthfeel , king henry takes off with sweetness but not cloyingly so .  poured into michelob celebrate glassware ; awesome head retention for several minutes . fantastic lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and syrupy with a bit of sharp carbonation .

this may be the best smelling pilsener i 've ever experienced . lovely complex , floral hop aroma . pleasant light grained malt in the background . overall , a superior beer .  looks really viscous and is extremely dark . excellent cascading head .  mouthfeel - very enjoyable borderline complex character .

the smell of tangerine jumps right out at you the moment you free this beer from the bottle . tangerine just fills the room . this is a unique ipa . fruit fresh from the tropics start this beer off . mango maybe ? the flavor actually kind of mutes itself in the middle and the hops kick in during the finish and stay . the hops are very citrus in nature and somewhat floral . i do n't detect the piney nature of a lot of ipa 's .  this brew poured a medium creamy long lasting dark brown head of small to large sized bubbles .  taste : mirrors the smell , but the flavors are weaker than their aroma counterparts because of a thin mouthfeel .

smell is a wonderful grapefruit burst .  impressive looking ale..bright clear golden yellow , with a rich , thick , creamy head and literally walls of lacing .  mouthfeel is fullbodied , and slightly cloying .

s- has a typical macro lager aroma ... .that of skunked dry grains , followed by some sweet malt . it has better flavor than most american macros and i think i 'll probably buy this again at some point .  a : this pours pitch black . a large tan head ( over two fingers forms ) with great retention .  the only thing i felt was it could use a little more carbonation to balance the tart flavor and make it more perky .

a-dark brown/black s-nice blend of cocoa and leafy hops..really impresses on the nose . t-hops are a little more forward on the taste ... .interesting hop dimensions ... some bright citrus ... .and some grungy pine and weed like notes ... roasted malts ... .also some darker cocoa ... m-rich ... fuller bodied ... .feels bigger than a regular black ipa ... body fits ... o-top notch effort .  very pretty two-finger head .  body is on the thin side of medium and the finish is both mildly astringent and slightly bitter .

the beer has massive yeasty bready smells . the beer has a very good combination of fruity ( apples , grapes , pears , plums ) jelly smells . oddly enough the smells of this beer bring back memories of my grandmothers kitchen smell .  pours an opaque , oil-slick jet black with a big , durable tan head that never completely goes away .  mouthfeel : bubbly and light body . the mouthfeel is a little peculiar and affects my experience .

the aroma on this beer was exceptional . cinnamon and plum came across strongly , along with hints of ethanol and orange rind . it had a nice bitter finish , but i struggled for awhile to get a handle on the sweet , fruit flavors that seemed to stay with the beer for the duration . i was thinking cherry with a few orange notes , it seemed very familiar , and then i finally put my finger on what it was reminding me of : cough syrup .  pours a lovely , crystal clear dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' tan head that persists all the way down , coating the entire glass with heavy lacing . the best looking ipa i 've ever seen .  the mouthfeel is decent , but could be a bit more robust to support the flavors .

a very attractive beer . powerful aroma . moist , sweet raisins at the forefront , with bitter chocolate , roasted malt , soy sauce and sweet sherry behind .  the head of foam was nothing short of exceptional . it had a 1 1/2 inch creamy head of tan colored foam that looked good enough to eat .  muted roastiness and chocolate malt notes . deep black body with a decently firm and lasting thumb thick head . roasted coffee beans int he fore followed by toasted and burnt bread and some mild chocolate notes int he finish . finish is dry and coffee tinged great classic porter .

this is a phenomenal aroma i ca n't get enough of ! t - sharp rye comes out in the flavor much more so than the aroma lets on . it actually overwhelms most everything else . d - very good take on the saison style that 's completely unique .  the pour was very good and this is easily one of the best looking beers i have ever seen with its excelent head , color and champagne like bubbles .  m - a little strong on the carbonation for my taste .

one of the best aromas to come around in a while for me . very decadent chocolate here ... sweet , silky ... you can really smell the cocoa nibs here . a slight hint of hop bitterness as well but this is a very chocolatey aroma . the body is a bit light , and the taste is certainly full of chocolate , but is more of a mix between a sweeter chocolate and a bitter , roasted chocolate . this marriage keeps it from becoming cloying or just being too bitter . what was a pretty sweet and rich beer on the nose was n't quite so on the tongue .  pours pitch black and thick , and makes a milk chocolaty looking huge amount of foam .  mouthfeel - rather bubbly , fairly thin .

the smell was n't all it should be , but average . the taste above average , in fact , very good , but no top shelf kind of beer taste .  a deep mocha head emerges from the bottom of the glass to form a nice half inch layer . exactly the appearance a big stout should uphold ; textbook .  decent palate , a little thin like the others in the series , but fairly smooth .

the grapes come through again from the aroma but the flavour depth is n't as good as the nose . a decent ipa with lots of great aroma but lacking a bit of flavour . a really nice showcase of the nelson sauvin hop and a great idea from mikkeller .  beautiful , clear dark copper color . excellent clarity here . a moderate cap of light whipped cream , tiny bubbles mostly , sits at the top . this is as pretty as an ipa can be .  it has a pretty high carbonation .

this smells real delicious . t - balanced malt hop mix up front with a hint of the fruity taste the smell indicated .  tremendous head and a deep , dark brown body . the lowly brown ale usually isnt going to win beauty contests , but this is about as good as one will look .  im augustus gloop : ) m - carb a little low , a little on the sweet side .

extremely muted nose , i can really only pick up a faint whiff of raisin bread and excruciatingly faint generic vinous and woody notes . i just wish i could smell more of what is delivered to the palate in the nose .  perfect appearance . really smooth 2 finger ashy cocobutter brown head . dark black balled body that looks beautiful in my snifter .  not too many micro 's that come out with a light ale . hats off to them for bringing this to market to allow folks who are used to drinking american mass producted swill to move into a easy drinking michigan micro brew . lighter than sam adams but more flavor then the bud and miller 's of the world .

smell : weak smell overall , but mostly buttery malt and some grains . i would n't buy this normally , but this is a beer i 'd definitely be willing to drink again on a budget .  this beer poured black with a large tan creamy head , that lasted through out the beer .  nice flavors , with a nice two-row malty sweetness and a huge piney and slight citrusy hop flavor that is very much in front ; good overall , but very unbalanced , even considering the style . goes down fine , but there is quite a bit of hop scratchiness .

s : holy hops , batman ! intense , complex , and amazing . t : starts off with citrus and herbal hops , then transitions to a bit of caramel malt before finishing with a wave of piney bitterness . delicious . m : medium bodied with a good dose of initially spiky , finally smooth carbonation .  a : pours a clear golden with a massive frothy , rocky head with great sustain .  m : a bit overcarbonated , dry , thin , light-medium bodied .

aroma exhibited a very nice floral hop bouquet . light and sweet with a hint of spiciness . this beer smells excellent and is not overpowered by the hops .  pours a luscious and very tempting opaque sable with a thick , frothy tan head that leaves a fair amount of lacing .  it 's sort of smokey but in an artificial way . rubber and alcohol . the rubber turned into a slightly smokey malt flavor but still lingered in there . alcohol dominated any sort of flavors coming through . i just did n't enjoy this beer at all . if i ever cross paths again with this beer i 'll re-review it .

nose speaks of a wonderful sweetness , malty , yeasty , and fruity , but most of all carries a unique candy-like scent . excellent . taste is malty and semi-sweet initially , with some spicy hints lingering and a bit of hop dryness .  an agressive pour was neither necessary nor desired to result in a glass 1/3 full of beer and 2/3 dense , off-white foam . robust carbonation , with many small bubbles .  the mouthfeel is light , but hey , its a light beer ! for drinkability , again , one of the beers that could probably never offend me .

a truly wonderful bouquet . taste accents of hops and light fruits , again pineapple , with a delayed afterthought of hops bitterness at the back of the throat . a tasty and sexy organic brew .  nice retention and very good lacing . clear amber color makes this an all around great looking brew .  the palate is bland , sweet , and clean . the strongest aspect of this beer is its mouthfeel , it is medium , sturdy carbonation , very basic but appropriate .

as soon as i opened the bottle , i was smacked with a heavy hoppy smell , easily reminded me it 's an ipa i 'm dealing with . s : an amazing combination of hops , pine , citrus , maybe some grape . t : interesting , with the token ipa hoppiness being the most notable aspect of it all . d : daunting at first , especially for me , not a huge fan of ipas , but i have to respect this beer . the dynamic flavor-smell combinations are remarkable , and though it 's not my favorite , the never-departing flavor may be the reminder that it is something to be reckoned with .  pours a bright , clear gold , with a three finger high column of dimpled white head . good head retention too . really it is absolutely gorgeous . i do n't think a saison could look any better ... the aroma has a bit of citrus ( lemon ) , slight grass , and mild pepper .  mouthfeel is a bit fizzy , and another beer where bottle-conditioning would have a positive impact .

the smell is probably the best part of this beer . sweet and herbal with a touch of honey , hazelnut , citrus of some kind . the finish is very dry . pretty cool beer .  pours a dark brown-black with a huge creamy tan head that retains well and laces the glass .  i like a little heavier of a mouthfeel than this offers , but the lighter feel is not surprising considering the crystal appearance .

on the nose , fresh fruits , cherries , peaches , green apples , pears , simply amazing . a bit twangy and just on the border of being chewy , but not quite . dry and a bit laid back ; decent yeasty body with some reserved sugar , candy cane offerings . sticky as it warms , sort of a bubble gum palate and a bit rustic .  a - extremely dark brown body with a dark brown head to go along with it . the thick and frothy head started out at about 4 inches and ever so slowly faded down leaving a thick humocky topography .  carbonation is fizzy on the tongue where it should be soft and creamy .

this beer has the most incredible smell in the world . '' the big wafts of vanilla , caramel , and butterscotch fill the nose and is absolutely delectable . i could enjoy the aroma of this beer for hours . one bomber was enough for me , and i was pleasantly surprised .  this is a real doppelbock that is rich in flavor . the smell is that of over ripe fruit . i love all bock beers especially doppelbock so i can say with out a doubt this beer is going into my top 10 .  slightly under carbonated for my taste but not really a flaw .

pours a opaque black no light showing thru this bad boy with a thinner mocha colored head , wow the aromas damn where to begin heavy on the dark roast coffee , bitter chocolate a hint of almond extract as well just awesome.flavors are heavy in the coffee department for some it maybe to much dark roast coffee and chocolate malt flavors with a malted milk type flavor , nice creamy , silky mouthfeel glides down pretty easily.if you like strong coffee and bitter chocolate you 'll love this beer .  glass : snifter temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees this is perfect appearance for a stout . it 's as black as black can be . the head takes a long while to recede to a nice thick surface covering , over an 1/8th of an inch thick . visually , this is quite an impressive beer .  but there are hints of dark fruits that seem to disintegrate on your tongue , slight astringent alcohol tate/smelll this is defiantly a very drinkable brew .

smell is phenomenal , sweeter , spicy , floral hops , fruity esters , just very appealing to me , lots of aroma without overpowering . perhaps if the aroma was so appealing to me , the taste would seem better , as there 's really nothing wrong with it , pretty standard witte . drinkability is pretty good , if only for the aroma .  apperance - this beer poured from the tap thick and creamy . it was bright golden yellow once the body cleared up from the nitrogen . nice thumb thick head .  feel seems to be about medium in body , but slightly watery , with a lingering semi-bitter dark unsweetened chocolate/coffee bean aftertaste .

brewery states they did pick up some brett recently , popped the cork off ... corked talked about brett to me , more fruit than funk . hops stay modest . mild tartness , infancy of the brett ? it does have a ghost-like funk within . sweet roasted finish , pretty much burnt sugar . not a hair short of being great , the brewery admits to some funk ... wish i had another bottle to see where it goes .  the color is a deep , very pretty dark amber . this is a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel was ok .

smells just a bit of honey , not much scent to it really . first taste is ... thin .  pours a golden-yellow with a huge white head . lace is all over the glass . beautiful .  feel is a bit coarse , but just a bit .

very sessionable , but only an adequate porter with the exception of the nose which is amazing .  let 's start with first impressions : this big beer makes a big impression on appearance . dark and sinister looking , the rough-textured mocha-colored head sits atop the black body like a russian fur cap . lacing is full and sticky .  perhaps another way to explain the feeling would be a textured shandy . noting the high praise this saison received , i have trouble fathoming such a bad experience .

probably the best smelling brown ale i 've experienced yet . t- almost porter-like at first , with up-front dark malt , lots of nuttiness , a bit of dark roasted grain , and a slightly metallic finish .  great retention and lacing !  very pleasant indeed . great hop character . this is a fairly balanced ipa . hard to say , it might just be because this particular bottle is more on the room temp side , but i would like more effervescence . a good beer all in all . i will be sure to drink it again , only a little colder and faster . more drinking , less typing ... .

smells absolutely wonderful ... pungent aroma of hops all the way ... piney , citrusy hops and i 'm loving it ... i want to smell this all night ... terrific blend of piney/grapefuit hops and sweet malts.. thought this was going to be a hop bomb all the way which would have been fine but i 'm surprised at the balance on this one .  pours out a slightly chill-hazed brassy tangerine with a wealth of tiny bubbles making their way to the head . head is massive , foamy , and almost spills over the top . leaves some near solid lacing on the glass .  smell is a cross between musty and estery at first , then just corn . tastes like corn , but considerably worse than a typical macro . it has some off flavors , that i ca n't really identify . bad .

overwhelmingly the finest ipa i 've ever sniffed . perfect . m - very good . nice carbonation and appropriate chewiness without being syrupy .  reddish copper in color , impressive head with incredible retention and massive lacing down the sides of my pub glass .  on the thin side , and i dont get much carbonation .

s - beautiful wet hopped aroma with a citrusy and piney profile that is extremely fresh . there 's also a bit of bread and caramel malt present .  a : pale straw , great carbonation , crystal clear , and a lovely full head .  wonderful flavor , with deep malt tones , a great smokiness , hints of peat , and a touch of caramel . goes down quite smoothly , but it does have an odd , almost generic , flavor on the tongue at the very end .

a - black with a huge coffee colored head s - smells delicious - very sweet , chocolate malts . the most balanced smell to a stout i have had the pleasure of knowing .  the color was hazy lemon yellow with two fingers of rocky , yellow-tinted head . the cap retained itself beautifully and the lacing was in solid bands .  s : slightly citrus , faint banana t : citrus & yeast & candy sugar m : bit thin , but not uncommon for a triple o : i am sure age did this one well reading the prior reviews ... think i paid $ 3.50 for it , well worth the price and a good brown bagger at a tasting .

smell : oh baby can you say citrus hop bomb ? loads of grapefruit and a touch of lemon .  pours almost a coffee brown with a hint of amber red in the bottom of the glass . nice 2 fingers of off white bubbles tops the glass .  it is medium-bodied with soft carbonation and seems perhaps more watery than i 'd expect . it leaves the mouth feeling a bit astringent .

interesting blueberry aroma with something pungent in the background , not sure what , maybe some yeast .  pours to a very dark brown , only slightly ruby colored liquid with a massive fluffy white head that coats the entire circumference of the glass in a perfect frilly victoria 's secret crotchless panty-style lacing . she really is quite sexy looking .  mouthfeel is somewhere between ultra clean and a little soapy - if that makes sense .

s- strong aroma of banana , clove , yeast , pear , bubblegum , wheat , nuttiness , and spice . complex and aromatic . t- banana , clove , pear , lots of spice , and the alcohol was surprisingly prominent , some warming . m- pretty high carbonation , crisp , finishes dry , drinks smooth o- first weizenbock i have ever had .  head holds well making this an incredibly good looking beer .  mouthfeel is a little light for a beer this big , but that would likely improve with age . carbonation is a tad too prickly for my personal tastes .

5.0 s : lots of oatmeal is apparent . this may be the most oatmeal laden beer i 've had . awesome balance between sweet and roasted flavors . 4.0 t : the taste is just about as good as the nose , but the mouthfeel is too distracting for me to enjoy it .  the way the carbonation and creamy foam mixes with the super dark body of the beer is gorgeous . through the glass , it looked like the bubbles were cascading like a waterfall , only upwards . anyway , the body is opaque and the head is super creamy and tan in apprearance . the head stuck around for a long time and left decent lacing .  being from the adirondacks i quickly likened this to adirondack brewery 's bear naked ale , yet a lager version , and a bit more wheat-filled . the mouth-feel is nice , but nothing special ( not flat , not too bubbly ) . in short , its a dandy brew- we all enjoyed it and thought it was pretty cool to have something that is only currently available in growlers from the brewery ( spring seasonal ) , drink up !

s : grapefruit and evergreen needles . you can smell the aroma of bold hops from yards away . t : simcoe , welcome aboard .  from the nitro-can , started as a full glass of thick , creamy foam . slowly the foam turned over from bottom to top revealing a deep yellow beer with a steady half-inch foamy white cap .  it seems to light and over carbonated for a stout .

i can also catch a slight nose of peaty scotch if i catch it the right way . fantastic aroma here .  got this one in trade , thanks eric ... a : perfect look . thick 1 and 1/2 inch off-white head that slowly fades leaving nice lacing around the glass .  my only complaint is that i wish the mouthfeel was thicker . it was smooth , but a bit watery to me .

strong malty smell , along with some dark fruits soaked in alcohol ... cherries or plums .  pours a pitch black color with a tan colored head that fades slowly , leaving a thin layer of foam and some heavy lacing .  the carbonation is mild ; there are almost no bubbles at all .

big sweet malty aroma . caramel , candied walnuts , raisins .  appearance , beer pours a red golden with a huge pillowy off tan head that lingers and clings to the sides of the glass thickly . big bubbles and small bubbles intermingle making this beer look alive on the pour . the red gold color is more of a ruby when held to the light , this is one impressive looking barleywine .  yack ! i 've had this lots over the years , but this time it got a major problem with butterscotch . aroma smacks me down wth that butterscotch - ugh . but , somewhere in there is some malt and a little chocolate , good malt . flavor is butterscotch - blaaahh . ca n't finish it . draft lines are clean here too . no more , pleeeeze

smells great ( but nothing like a gumball imo ) . incredible . very bitter for a pale ale , or pale wheat ale , whatever . it certainly smelled good , but nothing more than the typical tropical fruit-heavy pale/ipa .  appearance : as poured the beer is a nice lightly hazed golden apricot color with a 1 fluffy off white head that leaves rings , legs and small patches of lacing as it recedes .  carbonation is a bit low for the style .

from notes a - good dark black body with a medium brown head s - delicious sweet chocolaty bourbon t - dry smoky bourbon and vanilla . o ( d ) - tasty , great smelling . a 6 oz bottle split 4 ways can make it difficult to judge . but very enjoyable  pours a dark brown with a healthy sandy light tan head that lingers at a fairly thick level and laces the glass heavily .  m - it drys out in the mouth a little too quickly for me .

do n't be turned off by the little green specks floating around as they are chucks of hops leftover from fermentation and help accentuate the huge hoppy aromas . pours a nice creamy golden color with slight greenish hue to foamy head . aromas of malts and hops give way to dried fruit .  this beer has a frothy , three finger thick , almost rocky pale white head that sits atop a body that is brilliantly clear and a pale straw color . the color is about perfect and the head is one of the longest lasting and best ones i have seen on a macro-lager .  mouthfeel medium full for the style with carbonation that is a bit too strong for my taste .

suprising considering the spiced nature of this beer . it smells lagery to me ... .a bit musty . there is not very much of the pumpkin and spice aromas that i was expecting . smells slightly sweet ... maybe some caramel . the taste is somewhat more powerfull than the weak smell . it does n't really taste like pumpkins , spices , or ale for that matter .  some of shakespeare 's stuff is pretty dark , but shakespeare stout a nihilistic black , with a big head the color of creamy coffee . the little black bubbles peppering the head make it look alluringly like a chocolate chip cookie .  too cloudy and not nearly enough hop profile . at first i wondered if the waitress had given me the wrong beer . i would have characterized it as a weak summer wheat beer had they not told me it was a plisner . there was nothing objectionable about the beer itself . i drank it all . it just was n't what a pilsner should be .

the hop aroma on this beer is outstanding . a wonderful mix of pine and citrus hop smells great your nose as you lift the glass . the mild pale ale flavor , which is never low in bitterness , is surprising after that much aroma but fits well to the style . i think if it has a little better mouthfeel and just a touch more malt flavor this would be a perfect beer .  a - has two full fingers of ultra-fine reddish-tan head . what a beauty !  medium carbonation .

the smell is wonderful . tannin , grapes , apples , apple peels , raisins , caramel , touch of cocoa , and a hint of alcohol .  pours crystal clear orange-amber color with a dense 2 finger off white head with great retention that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts the entire glass .  m- the mouth feel is a bit overly carbonated , yet not thin .

very nice aroma here -- spot on for the style -- as notes of fresh orange peel combine with soft coriander spice and a hint of lemon .  probably the most impressive head i have ever seen on a beer .  mouthfeel is medium with more carbonation that i expected due to no head showing up .

exquisite nose has brandy , oak , vanilla , dark pitted fruits , candy malts , port wine and whiskey . taste does not hold the same complexity . some tart cherries , plums , caramel , toffee , wood , vanilla , wine grapes and cognac . past prime for sure , but still an interesting beer .  i really enjoyed this one . perfect copper looking beer .  m : thin , do n't take that the wrong way though but easy drinking .

horribly skunky , so much so that it blocks out any discernible beer aroma . the taste follows the aroma -- horribly skunky .  appearance : beautiful deep gold color , a lushous two-fingered layer of white foam , lots of rising bubbles , good head retention , flecks of lace aroma : dusty , cinnamony , malty , honey-like sweetness , floral hops , plummy fruitiness , perfumy ( sage and roses ?  light to medium bodied , carbonation seems to be at the right level .

appearance - very rich amber/red colors with a nice 1/2 '' - 3/4 '' head smell - slightly hoppy but not a very strong smell taste - sweet and smooth with no bitterness mouthfell - very smooth and pleasant . drinkability - this stuff is very easy to guzzle . everyone sitting with me at my table tried this and everyone ( non-beer drinkers included ) was very impressed .  pours a deep , opaque mahogany , almost black . there 's a 3-finger cafe au lait head with a moderate amount of layered lacing .  m : the mouthfeel was a bit thin compared with other sours , although this did not detract from the overall enjoyment of the beer .

wonderful , rich , and inviting aroma consisting of bourbon , oak , roasted malt , vanilla sweetness , and some chocolate and coffee . a complete aroma if i ever smelled one , without being over the top or too powerful with bourbon and alcohol sting . subtle , yet rich and complex . a fine tasting beer with a mellow bourbon and vanilla accent throughout , though the base beer still shines through : a rich , chocolatey , somewhat smoky porter . smooth drinking , though full and rich , subtle yet delicious -- really a standout .  beautiful 3 finger head , caramel , frothy and persistent , reddish mahogany nice stream of bubbles , good lacing ; if this did n't look so inviting i would put it on a shelf and leave it there forever !  the last 2/3 of my beer was a bit thin , but this was quite refresing and very easy to drink .

looks less viscous then i had expected smell is bourbon all the way . probably the most bourbon i have ever smelled in a ba beer . the smell prepares you for a very chewy brew but the mouthfeel isnt so .  a- pours a brownish color with red hues noted against a white background . the clear nature of the beer allows me to see the carbonation , which is modest looking at best . the head is plentiful and puffy looking , retaining well and leaving behind a thick film of dense foam on the glass .  m- actually the mouthfeel is n't that bad but it was really hard to focus on that while i was drinking joan rivers perfume .

s : a great big whiff of piney , citrus , and florally goodness hits the olfactory receptors . i 'm expecting a decent malt backbone here . o : this was only my fourth offering from 3 floyds ( alpha king , apocalypse cow , arctic panzer wolf ) and i 've been impressed with most .  the head is quite impressive , off white in color , composed of thousands and thousands of tiny bubbles .  mouthfeel is too thin for my liking .

tasted june 25th 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - deep copper , one finger off white head and some lacing s - lots of alcohol , very hoppy , pineapple , pine , grass , very yeasty , sweet malt , sugar , high octane everything , flowers , grass and tons of everything awesome t - really sweet up front and than a wall of bitter . this is a great ipa . i am starting to be a big fan of yulesmith final thought - 8 % + abv and only $ 7 a bottle . this one is worth it and if you find this on tap somewhere , please email me  i poured this one from a 12oz brown bottle into a tulip pint glass . a= this stout poured black as night with zero light penetration . with a very aggressive pour , the dark tan head rose a full 2 '' and took a long time to settle to a thin cap .  mouthfeel : both the carbonation and body are on the higher end of the light range .

smells great . big , overripe tropical fruit and citrus with a little bit of grass underneath . i actually coughed and spilled some while pouring and thought , `` man , that smells awesome ! '' while cleaning it up . still good , just a letdown after the nose .  it lasts forever and settles to a nice pillow . usually old ales have no head at all . i 'm amazed this looks so good .  mouthfeel is okay , no carbonation to speak of .

awesome aroma . on the buds , some more bong resin , pineapple and rind characteristics . the bitterness is fairly clean and enjoyable . underneath all the hop activities lies an unassuming caramel and toffee base .  there is a magical cascading effect within the beer as it settles . a beautiful off white head remains perfect throughout the experience lacing is awesome .  mouthfeel - foam is scarce and small bubbles and light caramel that fades quickly . slightly thin .

s - big aroma of cherry juice , some apple juice , molasses , malts , just a great smell . t - a nice balance of molasses , licorice , malts , some cherry .  dark brown/black body with a dense chocolaty head . a thick cap remained throughout .  slightly sour , a bit thin , highly carbonated . quite drinkable .

overall a fantastic beer .  into a pint glass , pours a kind of honey amber copper , with a heaping huge off-white head , settling down to a thick foam , lots and lots of lacing in rings and spiderwebs and bubbles down the glass . and upon second pour , the head swells again to two inches of foamy delight , a great big mustache is my reward .  mouthfeel is medium-light , and carbonation is medium-light .

below average head retention , but the aroma more than makes up for a lackluster appearance as it brims with bold espresso and sweet chocolate notes . one of the best-smelling coffee beers i 've had recently , and the malt backbone is nothing to scoff at , either . overall , brewhouse coffee stout is amazingly aromatic , but could use a few tweaks here and there with regards to the appearance and mouthfeel .  a : pours a cloudy , medium brown color with two fingers of billowy , pale tan head . exceptional retention and lace , vigorous carbonation .  average feel for the genre i 'd say . it 's pleasant in sips and gulps and a few of em would be just as enjoyable as one .

half inch head and thick head retention s : straight dole pineapple orange juice or something like it ! phenomenally citrusy . t : more dole juice ! crisp bite at the front before smooth finish . o : delicious ! very unique . probably could n't have more than one but very enjoyable . the fruit juice character is pretty interesting , that 's for sure .  pours dark mahogany with a thick tan head .  mouthfeel the beer is slick on the tongue with strong carbonation . the body is a little lacking , medium-light .

but overall still a nice dipa and one you could drink a couple of .  served in the `` new '' sam adams lager pint glass , the beer pours dark , dark brown ( might as well be black ) with an inch frothy brown head . head retention and lacing are both pretty good .  bought this over a month to two months a go and decided to give it a go . it is an ipa so it does have a nice bright orange to copper color . the taste and the smell are sweet and fruity , the only bad thing i have to to say about it , is the taste of tea is very lacking . i cant pick it up but , other than that i wish that stone , ishii and baird made this more as a yearly offering , cause its really good

s. tons of beautiful hop aroma - a spring day in a can .  poured into my duvel tulip a - pours a dark reddish-brown color with a huge pillowy tan head . this is absolutely beautiful , and took a good 3 minutes to recede enough for me to drink it !  average body and carbonation .

the aroma is so spot-on for the style that it makes me wonder how skull coast did it ... how do you get that much non-artificial-smelling watermelon aroma into a beer ? just exceptional , with juicy , fruity 'melon notes backed by a hint of wheat and hops .  appearance : extremely voluptuous head , almost overflowing , with lots of carbonation and bubbles . color is pitch black , no nuances there .  it 's got a little bit of a piney finish that 's quite refreshing . maybe closer to watery , but not bad . d- very drinkable esb .

i prefered the tap version as the apricots were so intense in the aroma as the bottle had more funk and barnyard . apricot , lemon and peach flavors . moderate acidity for a cantillon . the palate could be drier and the carbonation more lively but this a stellar offering by cantillon once again .  pours a beautiful clear golden orange with a plentiful fluffy head and excellent sticky lacing .  had this today on tap @ hibernia in boston . diacetyl ? in an ipa ? and what 's with the low hop profile and mega-sweetness of this beer ? my pint was quite cloudy too . beer drinkers of the world ... this is not an ipa , and it 's a pretty crappy beer to boot .

the aroma is fantastic ; a huge hit of lemony citrus and grass with undertones of pale malt and yeast . excellent ; the best pilsner i 've tried .  a : pours absolutely perfect ! cloudy , creamy orange body with a glorious mountain of head that fills just to the edge of the glass and hangs around until the glass is empty .  m - it 's a bit thin for the style .

full and rich , with dried fruits overtaking the nose . lots of vanilla in here , as well as some caramel and licorice . t : quite a lot going on in this brew . nothing too special here . d : so scarily drinkable . at 11.5 % , i feel that i could sip this all night .  appearance - this beer arrived in a tall , branded pilsner style glass and was yellow-orange with a offwhite , two finger head exhibiting good retention and heavy lacing . impressive carbonation showed off the whole time .  this beer is not awful but it is not good either . if use to be better , i think , back in the days before aluminum cans and pull up tabs . beer is fizzy and gives a good head and that is about the only good quality it has .

big hop aroma -- a bit sugary , citric and piney . lots and lots going on just in the scent , and i can feel the back of my tongue tingling already .  you get the beautiful nitrogen show and then it settles with a dark brown , almost black , body with a nice light tan head .  maybe a touch too much carbonation .

a - perfectly clear , fresh honey golden color . s - wow . piney citrus . loads of hop aroma . with the nose , i expected a haymaker of hop bitterness , but it was actually fairly subtle to me . m - medium-bodied , nice feel .  a - huge head , really fluffy . beautiful amber color with appealing haziness .  mouthfeel is pretty thin and wine like tbh the beer has more wine qualities than beer , carbonation is also a bit high .
