i definitely smell some sweet notes . t- tons of stuff in this one .  bear republic tribute ale is a very clear , very lively , deep crimson brown berr with a huge , lumpy , beige head .  mouthfeel is silky smooth , really nice . body fairly full and the beer leaves an impression all the way over the tongue .

foam looks like insulation foam.. smells okay , not a whole lot going on , mostly dark malts .  excellent lacing . a great looking beer .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible for a milk stout .

s : moderate hop aroma slight malt . t : initial sweetness followed by strong hop bitterness .  a : this beer pours a beautiful hazy red color with a fluffy off white head . the color of this beer is amazing .  full bodied with creamy carbonation and a lingering sweet licorice finish .
there was a faint earth and citrus aroma but nothing really pronounced .  a pretty good looking beer .  mouthfeel : perfect , just like champagne .

the aroma is slight clove , some bubblegum , but that 's about it . taste is rounded and smooth , with the clovey and bubblegum from the aroma , but also with alcohol warming and candy sugar flavors . medium bodied and drinkable , it 's good but not really a first class beer , and not worth $ 6.29 a bottle ( 22oz , john 's marketplace , portland or ) .  a : fantastic clarity , golden , and a relentless head , a 3 millimeter head is still visible after 20 minutes , leaving rings of lace in its wake .  m : lovely . sort of creamy , without being too heavy .

pretty bland and not really what i was expecting .  pours into 't hofbrouwerijke chalice a deep dark chocolate brown with a huge , i mean huge , light brown head . this is a head that just wo n't quit . it 's stunning .  the mouth feel is the richest and thickest i have ever tasted in a beer !
aroma of chocolaty mocha and alcohol .  pours a clear golden color with a thick , fluffy , off-white head .  mouthfeel is the star here . it 's plush , velvety ... is nice .

smell : a bit musty , some hints of banana in there , but not as appealing in the glass smell-wise as it was when i cracked the bottle . quite nice .  while it pours beautifully with a deep copper color and wonderful head , this brew is all looks and no personality .  the taste starts with a slight carbonation . the carbonation builds to reveal a sweet velvet feel . a milk chocolate flavor with a roasted finisht showcases a great mouth on this beer .

the nose is n't prominent at all . all i can pick up is some muted honey cream and some pale malt sweetness with perhaps some clove . despite the short list of adjectives i used to describe the flavors , it 's actually very , very good for the style . this is a very good belgian strong pale and worth trying .  a- clear dark reddish copper hue with a billowy tan head that last forever and leaves tons of sticky lacing on the glass . edit : holy shit , this beer is so hoppy it turns your tongue yellow !  mouthfeel ; very tight and lively carbonation , slick and creamy in the finish , pretty complex and admirable .

s ; has a mild roasted malt aroma with a good bit of sweetness mixed in .  22 oz bomber pours copper to orange with a 4 fingers+ offwhite head with effervesence . great lacing & head retention s : fruit & oak-like notes taste : apricot & oakey notes up front .  fairly crisp in the mouth , with an exceptional smoothness going down .

the smell is malty , very mild . mouthfeel is thick , rich , almost creamy .  damm , skippy , now thats what a stout should look like ! deep , cream black pour . an absolutely beautiful , thick and fluffy brown head , clings to the side of the glass endlessly .  outstanding mouthfeel ! very drinkable .

a-golden in color , completely translucent in clarity , about a fingers worth of white head n-not really what i was expecting at all , the nose is more grass and citrus than any funk , some hints of oak and white wine but nothing crazy t-the funk is a little more pronounced , flavor actually reminds me of squatter 's fifth element , there is light green apple , grape , and malt m-light and refreshing with an almost champagne about of carbonation d-not as memorable as the first time i had it , but still a notable american sour , as i noted in the taste , this beer reminds me a lot of squatter 's fifth element , would like to see some age and additional sourness on this  pours a huge head with crazy retention that wo n't leave the glass .  mouthfeel : fantastic . great carbonation , no real aftertaste and washes easily over the palate .

wonderful . just the perfect amount of fruit mixed with the belgian wheat goodness .  the most delicate looking head i 've ever seen , pillowy and white , thick and longlasting . beautiful .  mouthfeel is outstanding . super thick and syrupy , that flavor coats the palate forever .

the smell is weak but nice and beery .  a great effort from smutty ; this bp pours a saturated opaque espresso brown , leaving a rich dark bronzed brown head . very well bittered and rounded in the mouth with sweet roasted malts , carob and tongue tingling acids .  mouthfeel is creamy smooth , thick body , low carbonation .

hay and some sweetness give this beer a fairly simple aroma . grainy flavored beer with some faint pale malt sweetness .  pours a dramatic thundercloud of head , beige/tan and mountainous , rocky .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , as it should be fir a beer of this strength .

s - chocolate , cocoa . d - the beer itself looked beautiful , but its flavor and aroma were really weak .  the pour is black with a billowing light brown head with some very nice lace .  the rich , smooth , roasted chocolate flavor works well with the silky body . this is definitely highly recommended , as the beers tend to be from great lakes brewing company .

a bit light on the nose . pleasant and fresh , but not ultra complex .  a busty foamy cap on top ... head is monstrous ! not only is the head big its retention is just as good . head was a soft tan ( cappuccino ) color with craters , mounds , and dense chunks forming all the while leaving a bleary coating of lace . a very good look to this one s : i am having a bit of trouble grasping this one but had no problem realizing this one is sweet and rich .  m : really a standout porter . carbonation is perfectly dialed in and gives a very subtle tingle on the tongue .

it smells like a basic macro .  pours liquid gold and with a huge porcelain head .  it 's wonderful . alcohol tingles a little in the mouth and it 's certainly present in the aroma but buried 'neath the fruity yeast . expertly woven into the beery fabric of this brew .

i do n't usually like fruity beers especially one 's involving raspberries , in fact only apricots are a fruit that i liked in my beer . the smell is not overwhelming but the taste is perfectly mixed with a beer and raspberries .  pours black and thick . substantial tan head that forms of a billion tiny bubbles then morphs into a very slow fading creamy foam .  mouthfeel- damn , this sh*t is creamy ! smooth , medium carbonation , but goes down super smooth . nice light bitterness in the aftertaste .

i do not like coffee i love the smell but the taste is lost on me , but this should not be feared by non coffee lovers .  a - golden and slightly hazed with coppery highlights and a foamy , cushiony head that jets to the surface and clings to the glass like glue as it subsides . head retention is fantastic , and would be even without the aid of the etching at the bottom of the glass . fantastic .  m. just perfect for what it is . very smooth and thick .

it smells of mild biscuit grain , light piney hops , a bit woody , and some funky floral hops .  this is one of the most distinctive brews i 've ever had ; the 400 pounds of peaches they throw in really show through . beer had a very pale golden coloration that i didnt think fit it to well .  slick mouthfeel with perfect level of carbonation .

smell - pumpkin , nutmeg , cinnamon , malts , brown sugar , spices . smells like liquid pumpkin pie . rather smooth and easy drinking .  pours near flat . no head , no lacing .  mouthfeel/overall : this beer is every bit of full bodied ; thick , chewy and creamy . everything an imperial stout should be . overall , a very good imperial stout that i 'd love to have full time access to .

s - sweet , malty nose with strong notes of molasses . smelling this blind i would not have guessed ipa .  '' pours to a slightly hazy dark orange-caramel with a small white head and just ok retention and minimal lacing .  not the stunner i was hoping for m- beautiful mouth feel . i sure hope this is not the `` great sculpin '' i 've been waiting for for that past few years .
it had a bitter smell like that of fermented raisins .  directly from the fridge , after pouring there was almost no head .  mouthfeel : very thick and very very smooth , wonderful mouthfeel .

t : this beer has a little malty but mostly hops , actually more hops than expected . m : reasonably full d : very good , i had a second pint  pours a clear amber with a smallish head that quickly settles to a thin cap . moderate amounts of lacing is left on the glass .  a faint bit of tannins in the middle of the tongue starts the finish , which is incredibly long with trailing , vineous notes of chocolate and spiced orange peel . ya it 's a bit like those warheads candies , but it 's tucked in such an incredible silky richness .

i like the haziness of this one-but it is a bit more pale than most ipas i have come across . s-the nose is pretty great . piny hops are the main character with some grapefruit and other citrus coming through as well .  a : this beer poured a nice , brown-red colour . i was glad that the colour was nice to look at because the head barely bothered to make an appearance .  it is exceptionally smooth and drinks perfectly for the style .
smell-mild citrus aroma with a hint of malts in the background .  a - pitch black with a thin mocha-colored head . so-so retention and poor lacing .  mouth-feel was velvety smooth and creamy .

the smell is pretty faint .  pours with about a quarter inch of medium colored head which recedes very quickly to a film .  mouthfeel : thick and chewy , yet not syrupy . carbonation is low and appropriate . in other words , spot on .

it smells nothing special really , typically acoholic smell really , a bit like whiskey .  the beer pours dark , not much head exists but enough to know the beer has bubbles .  m : medium in body with a really smooth and creamy feel on the tongue .

s- light sweet malt and some mild chocolate . pretty mild overall .  not much in terms of head , and what is sits atop a body of dark ruby . ahhh , lifts the nostrils into the heavens and beyond into the great void of ecstasy .  still i thought the aroma was alittle weak , but once it hits your mouth it is amazing .

smells surprisingly good . the berry aroma really stands out here and is not what i would call subtle like the label implies . i was really pleased with the aroma , but this is just way too much .  served in a 12oz goblet , darkly translucent but very close to opaque . dark dark brown color with reddish appearance at the edges , thin tan head that disippates to nothing but the thinnest of rings around the glass .  super thick dark chocolate flavor , light coffee flavors , good coffee bitterness near the finish super creamy , heavier in body , extremely smooth and hopefully i 've mentioned the creaminess overall , i love this stout , give me more

all are very light scents .  a : tried to entice a head , but it came out like oil and left a thin deep brown head that lasted for a few minutes .  it is a full bodied beer with perfect carbonation .

presentation - poured into my chimay goblet appearance - a golden body with a very thick white head reminiscent of snow covered mountains smell - very hoppy , but a little bit of skunk , due to the ( green bottle ) being exposed to light .  orange amber color was semi clear . head was well formed but disapated fairly quickly , lacing was scarce .  typical stone excellent mouthfeel .

light chocolate , clean aroma . one finger dark beige head . big chocolate flavor . reminds me of the hershey 's cocoa powder form .  planet porter is a lightweight porter with a sienna brown color .  the mouth feel was excellent and one could tell the cask was being maintained properly .

deep black in color-nice slight tan head that lingers down the glass.subtle aroma of malt.slight chocolate smell.roasted flavor dominates.hints of licorice.very subtle sourness in the backround.full bodied mouthfeel.a very drinkable beer-comes off more as a stout then old ale to me.very enjoyable none the less .  got a nice 1 finger head on the pour but the coloring of the body is fairly weak . very light orange almost the shade of a pilsner which is not a good look for an ipa . smell is very juicy sweet pineapple with the expected belgian yeast twang of clove and banana .  full bodied , super creamy and smooth . very nice .

hoppy scent is medium to intense , with a nice mix of fresh citrus and toasted , darker hop bitters . malt figures its way in to create a staggeringly intense aroma for an irish red .  a : pours dark black , looks thick , very thin head on all glasses poured .  mouthfeel is fabulous with an amazing carbonation . it 's perfect .

s : airy toast is diluted by the thick carbon dioxide presence . hops are weakly piney , not really able to register . t : begins dry , with moderate pale malt that definitely brings more toast than in the smell , as well as some caramel .  this -bal barleywine pours with almost zero head .  mouthfeel is quite amazing , therefore the 5 .

this is mouthwatering and powerful . t : follows the nose . though it is not as powerful as the nose imo . m/d : a full body that is low on the carbonation end .  appearance : the beer is a slightly cloudy beer . with good head retention . the beer has a thick white head when pourd and reduces to a thin lacy head .  visibly effervescent , the mouth feel is perfect ... classic rich micro bubbles lend a smooth creamy texture .

smell : just a simple beer smell hops barley a bit floral . a little floral like th smell .  pours dark brown , small tan head quickly fizzes away to a thin ring .  the hop particles make it sticky as hell , the rim of my glass is sticky , my lips are sticky , and the mouthfeel is outstanding ! as far as double ipas go ( which let 's face it this is really comparable to an ipa ) , i still prefer either pliny or any of the alpine ipas , but this is a nice change of pace .

smell is very faint - a little bit of strawberry , and not much else . the taste , however , is just fantastic . the wheat beer flavor is at the forefront , but the strawberry smooths it out wonderfully .  dark-brown and cloudy in appearance , the pint glass i was handed had been pre-poured , so i ca n't say a lot about the head . the sweetness up front balanced nicely with the beer 's hops , and in combination with an enjoyable , full body , the pint drank easily while sitting outside the brewery on a beautiful march day .  m- the first thing i notice with this is how smooth and creamy it is . d- a very enjoyable english barleywine . tasty .

smells neutral at first , then smells a bit sour . starts a bit sweet then gets tart .  a : pours a black body with a small , tan head with no real retention and minimal lacing .  m : thick , full-bodied , and very creamy . low to moderate carbonation .
the scent is excellent and strong , with a bouquet of citrus .  looks pretty limp .  mouthfeel was full , thick , and creamy with a rich sweetness on the tongue .

overall the aromas seem slightly restrained .  the beer pours a dark brown with an off-white head ... small with not a lot of lacing or retention .  mouthfeel was phenomenal - silky smooth and with a slight hops bite on the tongue , giving 'way on the finish to a great caramel sweetness .

pours a 2 '' tan head and looks a standard coffee brown in the glass . flavor itself was pretty mild but what is cool with this beer is it has the flavor and feel of drinking a mild mocha malt . i found it thoroughly satisfying like a kid at a malt shop slowly draining his glass .  bomber , a : pours mahogany with a small off-white head , fair retention , light lace .  this is a big , complex , full bodied beer . the huge amounts of malts in this thing are chewy and even feel like they stick to the teeth some .

the smell was not too intense but definitely of apricots . my first apricot beer , and i was n't disappointed .  a decent sized white head that dissipates quickly over a macro-brew-looking yellow-clearish beer . not a great appearance . but i really , really enjoyed this one despite its underwhelming appearance .  m - this is one of my favorite parts so far about this brew . moderate amounts of carbonation that whirls around your tounge and warms it in the process .

decent german pils a- clear golden color with a nice fluffly head that leaves great lacing s- floral , medicinal , and metallic smells coming from this .  a- golden straw color with a tiny little thin white head . nothing much to the appearance here .  the mouthfeel was silky smooth , and i think it was the best feeling oatmeal stout i have ever had . the low carbonation perfectly complemented the medium body , and the smoothness from the oatmeal made it a joy to drink .

s - not bad , vinous with a touch of vinegar . some fruitiness there as well . t - fruit vinegar and a touch of funk there .  a dark orange body with a swiftly descending head that leaves no trace -- semi-opaque ... solid malt aroma with hints of fruitiness to develop a sense of complexity.. slightly effervescent , with a mellow , medium body that is pleasantly fulfilling ... smooth , malty presence in the back of the mouth ; little hops to speak of , but at this refreshing a taste , they 'd only get in the way !  mouthfeel is thick as hell and creamy , perfect for a big ris this is smooth as hell , much smoother than beers with this much ash flavor usually are .

aroma is surprisingly mild with light roasted malt and espresso scents a hit of grassy hops mixed in too .  once you get past the weird label , you find a decent ipa .  smooth creamy mouthfeel that keeps you wanting another drink .
smell is pretty mild with just a hint of roast malt and caramel .  appearance - cloudy yellow color , with small head that faded out .  f : wonderfully thick .

smell : sweet malt , floral hop , light brown sugar , light bread , light whiff of dark fruits . the nose was a little light and the beer itself is more hop forward then what i would consider perfect for a esb , but on the whole a very simple but good brew .  a really dark brown with barely any head at all . at first glance this beer looks thin .  super thick mouthfeel .

truly great drinkability , malty and full-bodied . in what concerns oktoberfest beer , i found this to be a very good one : smooth taste , good looks and very , very drinkable . definetely worth a try .  almost a stout feel , but smoother . i wish i had poured in a glass to see what it looked like .  the best part of the rwanda gatsinga coffee stout is in my opinion the mouthfeel which is extremely smooth and leaves a pleasant malty coffee-dominated aftertaste and a smile on your face .

the nose on the beer is very good with a nice orange burst type hop presence . i just wish the taste followed suit . the beer is overly bitter , with a very pungent tangy hop bite , and not enough of the enjoyable orangey citrus hop and estery juices that i was expecting from the aroma .  bottle poured into pint glass appearance : nothing to write home about . light lacing , amber-gold in color .  huge bodied and full ( again , suggesting iipa classification ) . this is a beauty on cask .

on cask at glouster arms in oxon . the aroma was subdued but featured some malt notes , rasin and a bit of esters on warming .  possibly the worse beer i have ever had..sickeningly sweet..i let it sit for a week in my fridge and it still bubbled over with head . tastes like sugar and the 1st beer i 've ever simply poured down the drain..is there a quality control problem here or is this standard for the beer ?  however , it tastes great and feels great in the mouth .

s : yeast hops and some sweetness from the malt . not really that great a nose on this . definitely it 's weak point . t : sweetness from the malt , citrus from the hops , the yeast adds a slight spiciness .  appearance was ligter than i expected and had virtually no head .  the taste is initially of a very light porter and with a clean aftertaste that becomes a fruit sensation on the palate . the hop/malt balance is the real achievement here and it really contributes to the supreme drinkability . the smell upon opening the bottle is not an effective contrival of the taste that this beer is hiding as it only gives you an idea of the rooted flavor that is to be unleashed , the supreme balance and sublime flavor . great bier .

s : musky and earth aromas . burnt cherry and very malty . farly nondescript as far as i am concerned . i did not know what to expect , but this is an exceptional beer . though , to fully appreciate this , i need to be more familiar with the style .  small white head , has pretty much no retention or lacing .  the mouthfeel was amazing . nearly full-bodied .

to me , boddingtons is the `` caramel '' version of the `` chocolate '' guinness if that makes sense . it 's a smooth and very drinkable beer that you can just put down without even realizing . not much of a nose , which would probably be its biggest problem . it 's a staple , not something that pushes the boundaries , and it should be appreciated as such . it 's best on draught and pairs well with many deserts .  12oz brown bottle with no freshness date . pours a medium brown with some amber , a 1 finger head and decent lace .  awesome . drinkability : the mouthfeel is the star here , and not detecting most of the alcohol only helps .

overall : 3.85 appearance : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | mouthfeel : 3.5 | drinkability : 4 740  a - pours a chestnut brown s - toffee , caramelized brown sugar , toasted wheat bread , maple , toasted nuts . t - lots of nutty malt , some light sorghum , notes of caramel , vanilla , dry bread sprinkle with a dash of cocoa powder , hints of over-ripened blueberry . finishes with nutty dry bread aftertaste . very good beer . way better than expected . a standout beer in it 's class .  great full and luxurious mouthfeel , witha soft , albeit intense carbonation that really lifts the brew .

s : smelled like your average macro . maybe a little burnt corn . t : ok this stuff tastes great . overall : great , cheap evreryday beer especially in this economy .  2004 vintage pours cloudy light brown with a few bubbles , but no head retention to speak of .  perfect example for a ris , and probably my favorite mouthfeel amongst them all .

nice grapefruit citrus taste . a nice malty front with the citrus and slight sweetness undertones .  2009 vintage pours a very effervescent straw color with 3 fingers of fluffy ivory colored head . hazes a bit a the bottom , duh ... average head retention & lacing s : grassy with apple peels , plus lemons t : apple peels , white grape , lemony hops & a wee bit of dirt & tartness up front .  m/d : a full , silky smooth brew with low ( perfect ) carbonation .

the original yuengling lagar ( which is good ) brought me to this beer and i was very impressed .  pours a dark brown almost black with very minimal thin head s : great aromas going on here . was disappointed with the lack of head so the appearance took a knock on points but overall a wonderful offering from brau brothers !  in my mind , this is the perfect feel for an imperial stout .

thin head with clingy lacing and a very thin smell for such a strong brew in the mouth . very malty , explosion of carbonation and citrus on the palate , with a strong , `` snappy '' kick of bitter hops . floral and herb-laden , this brew finishes well and is surprisingly light in the mouth , despite the powerful malt body .  this beer poured a light yellow-orange with only about a one-finger head , and not much lacing . the smooth carbonation level and the dry finish made this a very drinkable beer .  taste again where do i start ... sweet , spicy dark fruits soaked in alcohol ( raisins , currents , dates ) , toasted caramel notes , bready , some brandy / rum traces , biscuity , warming alcohol , spicy hop bitterness forces itself through the sweet maltiness , light madeira wine hints ... feel - so silky smooth ... rich and creamy ... light viscousness.. low drinkablilty for this one - a beer for savouring and sipping slowly ... overall - a phenomenal beer ... highly recommended .

simple light pilsner smell .  growler poured into a weizen glass . an aggressive pour at that , but the 3 fingers of foam reduces to a skim in short order . lazy streaks of lacing here and there .  m- feel is exceptionally clean and smooth .

i really miss schlitz . schlitz has more of a hops flavor than any other american lager that i 've tried . but i think that schlitz is the best american adjunct lager out there today .  extremely dark with no head at all and no visible carbonation .  nice caramel aftertaste held on the tongue by the thick mouthfeel . creamy thick mouthfeel and modest carbonation .

s - slightly sweet and caramelized with a non-specific bitter balance and a bit of minerality . t - lots of mineral flavor , some sweetness , and a sharp grassy bitterness that lingers on the finish .  this beer poured a-not-too-shiny copper red with a good amount of head which quickly faded to a thin lace .  m - absolutely creamy and delectable ! the amazing , tiny bubbled froth envelopes and contains any alcohol sharpness that would otherwise make this 8.0 % beer a bit fiery in the swallow . superb . d - the mouthfeel makes this otherwise straight-up scotch ale an incredibly drinkable beverage . but be careful ! at 8 % , this beer is like getting a two-for-one special in each pint !

s-the nose is light , nutty roasted malts with hints of herbal ester in the back . t-the taste is more full , lots of nutty flavors up front , roasted bread rolls , notes of dough , lightly roasted malt , faint herbal hop in the back .  kerberos is a tangerine orange , pretty cloudy . the head was small after a pretty vigorous pour , and did n't last too long . a small web of lace stuck to the snifter .  considering the abv , the mouthfeel is perfect . d - at 12 % , you obviously ca n't have that many .
smells of caramel and ... pepper ? very faint .  this beer looks a bit too light for an english ipa .  m : outstanding mouthfeel , is very smoothe and refreshing .

appearance : straw color , effervenscence , good head , awesome lacing smell : this is blasphemy but it smelled sorta like mgd .  pours cloudy and warm chestnut under a diminutive cap of slightly pink foam that receeds to a film suddenly and quickly .  mouthfeel is intensely smooth and velvety , creamy and luscious . lactic milk sugar contributes a boatload of palate-smudging heft . although it 's not one for sessioning , it has a sublime quality that makes you savor every sip .

loads of burp from a very clean , light golden fizz and a nice hopped edge on the aftertaste . certainly wo n't stand up to serious beer for beer competition but this is the type of refreshing hot summer beer that 's best served very cold for thirst quenching . like i say this is the best choice for a breakfast bar beer - nothing else .  a : poured a orangish copper color with good carbonation and a small white head s : rye , caramel , citrus t : wow .  the texture is just flat-out perfect and this is about as easy to drink as you can want .

smell was odd ... something seemed off ... unbelievable the difference between smell and taste ... the taste was great..sweet on the front , rounding into a tartness and a very nice overtone of alcohol . drinkability is very good for the high abv ... very easy to drink .  i poured this one from a 12oz brown bottle into a shaker pint glass . a= this ale poured a very clear golden color ( filtered i would say ) with a fairly low carbonation release and a 1/2 '' white head . the head dropped to zero very quickly and did not leave any lacing behind .  the mouth feel is perfect - not watery , not syrupy , well carbonated , and very refreshing .

s : i was a unprepared for the smell , as the malts had a big impact . if i was pressed for details ( i suppose that 's the point here ) i could pinpoint some caramel . t : i think the flavor of this beer is gorgeous . do n't let that push you away though , because it is n't a kriek by any means . kudos to the widmer brothers .  12oz bottle poured into an oversized wine glass pours a murky brown colour with just a thin head and a light lacing on the top .  mouthfeel is full and round .

nose is kinda weak . a little bit of caramel malt and resin .  the appearance is nothing special -dark purple-black -- some ruby elements at the top part of the glass .  the alcohol burns just a bit in the back of my throat , but overall the mouthfeel on this is amazing . d- wow !

the smell is pretty light , but its of roasted malts .  the serving glass and size might have affected the appearance negatively . appearance 3/5 deep amber , slightly hazy , with a moderate off white head , poor head retention and some lacing .  the mouthfeel is right on and this one is immensely drinkable .

the smell was really subtle for me and i could n't detect anything more than a slight sweetness like burnt caramel .  poured a pale godlen orange , witha white head that fades to some bubbles which ultimately disappear . leaves behind no retention or lace .  very light carbonation and a perfect body for a porter , combined with what i have already mentioned , makes this a very drinkable proposition .

smells a little citrusy and and a little wheaty - nothing impressive . a very lemon-like taste that finishes a little bitter and a little like cherries .  appearance : thin and inattentive off white lace that barely stays around . this ale is very clear with a bright shaded orangey copper hue .  the mouthfeel was spot on and the taste was close behind .

smell - light and hoppy with a moderate aroma of malt .  shared a 6 pack with some friends ( peacebone116 and his wife and my wife ) , sadly didnt have the option to get an appearance since we drank them from the bottles on a picnic . a n/a since it wasnt poured into a glass , so ill go middle of the road with a 3 .  m - big bodied , thick , and viscous as hell . middling carbonation fades to a really dry and herbal finish like green tea . wicks all moisture from my mouth !

smell is rather subtle actually , for the hop taste i would would expect more however i would never hold it against this beer .  pours a deep dark black with hints of brown around the edges . the very thin half-finger brown head did n't last very long .  m- full body in the mouth and sticky on the lips .

aroma is quite light some dark malt and hop but too light and not nearly as aromatic as the bottle . all the key flavors are certainly present with same complexity as bottle-brown , scotch ale & ipa .  poured from a 12oz bottle a - looks more like a hefeweizen than an ipa . very cloudy , unfiltered , with lots of floating yeast .  the mouth-feel was what was remarkable to me , very thick and creamy , i would liken it to a stout milkshake , really satisfying and enjoyable to drink .

aroma is very soft a little bready malt , and pumpkiny but hard to bring forth . the flavor is nice definately my favorite sam seasonal .  appearance- poured a cherry , dark brown color with almost no head ! strange .  sweet flavor that i ca n't put my mind on ... m - excellent presentation , really enjoyable to the senses .

no discernable aroma at all - kind of weird .  without any lace or head , but certainly had adequate carbonation . highly drinkable beer that grew on my palate .  a - opaque for sure ; not quite black , but very dark brown ; 1/2 '' tan/light brown , creamy head that diminishes to a thin layer pretty quickly ; lacing here and there , around the glass s - very nice aroma going on here ; notes of roasty malts , dark chocolate , hints of milky sweetness , and nice qualities of gingerbread too t - dark chocolate , vanilla , cinnamon , and ginger come first ; milky sweetness lasts from start to finish that is reminiscent of espresso ; slight bitter finish with roasted coffee beans and ginger as well m - medium to full bodied ; slight dry finish ; some carbonation that feels nice on the tongue ; can feel some warmth from the 9.2 % abv ; texture is very milky , creamy , velvety smooth o - i just ca n't get over how exceptionally smooth this beer really is .

amber brown , with a thin light tan head and a scant malty aroma . full mouth , light chocolate start progressing to caramel with some spice .  pours a murky orange with a thin , clingy head . nothing special in this regard .  the mouthfeel is luxurious , thick , and chewy . amazing . i am impressed with this brew . flavors are great and the mouthfeel is unearthly .

the nose is doughy soapy water and yeast . spicy hops hit first chased by metallic sweetness with a soft-baked quality .  12oz bottle poured into a pint glass pours a copper-straw with obvious carbonation bubbles rising to the surface . any head quickly fades to nothing .  taste & mouthfeel : smoothness is impeccable within the moderate body , big doughy biscuity malt flavour is the showcase of this brew .
the smell was uneventful , with hints of honey and orange .  hazy , reddish brown color with a sparse ring of head .  m : very creamy feeling , small bubbles , not too sticky .

omg , the hops . maybe that was the garlic potatoes . but i want to get back to my beer .  it 's what purple haze wants to be when it grows up .  i keep tasting chocolate ice cream ... dry chocolate ice cream ... not cloy at all ... very fantastic finish and mouthfeel ... german beer ftw will buy again !
smell : gentle hoppy smell .  appearance : chestnut color , low head retention .  mouthfeel : delightfully creamy and full-bodied . very pleasant .

the head really has some large pillows in it and it just sits high the whole way down ... one of the more impressive looking pale ales ive experienced . the nose is very very subtle ; biscuity malt , pine and citrus , but very subdued , i had to stick my nose down in it for a minute to really draw everything out .  bottled 08.09.11 looks like a cloudy white wine . golden yellow ... virtually no head .  appearance : amber , clear carbonated , medium head smell : alcohol , grapefruit , and citrus taste : alcohol , grapefruit , malts , hops , and slight caramel mouthfeel : smooth , slightly hard finish , can feel the carbonation ... it is amazing how smooth and unbitter this beer is for a beer with its abv drinkability : i will have this again , but may be one of the few that prefer the 60 minute ipa .

not much aroma at all to speak of , which is fairly common among the tripel 's , largely due to the clear candy 's which do n't impart much of a smell . great flavor , a creamy , full body full of a chewy malt and some fruit notes , yet clean with the clear candy .  a- pours a very pale straw yellow with a pretty white head that quickly dissipates .  the mouth feel is amazing on this beer .

the aroma is a lovely `` double '' chocolate with lots of heavy roasted malts muted amongst the rich chocolate aroma .  im not a beer enthusiast , i just love the taste of beer , i dont care how it looks , or anything like that i just drink the stuff , i tried this beer today being a fan of the ofallon wheat and gold , and i was surprised . its like a porter light . its listed as a bock ale , but i say is a porter light. , just enough chocolate .  mouth is extremely crisp , clean with tremendous carbonation and a nice light body .

this was a wonderful helles , with the crisp maltiness one would expect from german lager . sparingly hopped , but enought to balance well . show this to a lover of the macros and they might convernt yet ! i wish however , that they were in brown bottles , because i got that slight skunkyness from uv reaction .  pours a hazy gold with a small off-white head .  interesting effervescent mouthfeel makes it a pleasure to savor .

this poured a typical pilsener pale yellow with a decent head that quickly subsided , smell is a tad skunky but not terrible . this one makes up for that really quickly in the flavor department , bitter in the initial flavor , finishing with a beautiful aromatic barley malt finish .  i was not dissappointed though . it does n't pour with much head or lace but is still evident of a very good beer ; even after poured it has a residual head-in the bottle nonetheless .  a - bright golden orange color with some chill haze present , two fingers of white frothy head that leaves thick froth-lace s - not too much rye here , just hints ... hops and bready malt t - hop bitterness up front , sweet bready malts in the back , only a hint of rye in the middle ... the malt backing is about as significant as it gets ... taste 's more like a straight up ipa than most rye beers i 've had m - hops tingle the tongue and give way to very thick , chewy malts that slide down nicely ... full-bodied and very enjoyable d - this is a reeeally well-balanced beer , i just wanted more rye flavor .

aroma is mild but some chocolate and roasted malt but surprisingly no raspberry really shows up here .  light golden color ; a little lighter than expected . smells hoppy ( citric , very grapefruit-like ) with an underlying sweetness . hops are very flavorful ( citric ) and also bring a decent bitterness , but are never harsh at any point . very tasty and drinkable beer that packs a punch .  mouthfeel is very good , a light bodied beer with excellent carbonation ; it dances on the tongue and finishes smooth .

very subtle , nothing spectacular . t - light initial wheat flavor that follows with a sweet/citrus aftertaste .  poured into a piraat tulip glass , creating about an inch head that faded 5 minutes later to a lingering ring . the color is auburn with more orange higlights around the edges , very hazy .  great mouthfeel .

strong hoppy aroma with a floral hint .  not like motor oil , more like tobacco water . it 's damn near a hop bomb . very drinkable . i get a real dry finish from porters , maybe it 's relative to the color , but that dryness coupled with the hops makes me want more & more each sip i take .  mouthfeel- this is an exceptionally smooth saison , with the mouthfeel rivaling that of the saison dupont , my favorite of the style and one of my favorite beers . the tank 7 is definitely a thicker beer , very complimentary to the flavors .

s- very sour and thick . smells nothing like it tastes . d- incredible summer beer . this beer is the best witbier i have had .  the beer doesn & # 8217 ; t really produce an impressive head : thin with some large bubbles .  perfect . d : great taste , but a bit rich to drink in volume .

nice light smell of roasted nuts and dark caramel .  very drinkable.it is refreshing to have a microbrewey beer , that is not that bitter , and very drinkable.gets you very drunk.be careful because the alcohol creeps up on you with this beer.tasted citrus.i also tasted a bit of nutmeg in the aftertaste.this beer is very easy to drink.exceptional drinkability . this is the quintessential summer ale.a light , very drinkable , however , complex enough to be a microbrewery beer.i highly recommend this beer . this is a good recommendation to the general public.inasmuch as this beer is drinkable and light , many people will enjoy this . moreover , what is cool about recommending this beer , is that many people are not aware of this beer and micro beer 's in general.this was a perfect find on a june saturday , great beer to have at a high school or college graduation party.this is a great party beer , and will generate conversation at a graduation party , because numerous people have not heard of brooklyn , even suprisingly , in new york .  mouthfeel- light palate with great carbonation that tickles the senses nicely .

'' love the mouthfeel .

) aroma is mostly malt but not very impressive overall .  big malt aroma ( munich-type , sort of crystal but with a light roasty component ) with some grainy cereal notes . seems a little light colored for the style , just barely off gold , with a touch of haziness . smallish head that fades after a little while . very nice malty profile . hop bitterness is well in balance but still very subtle . clean fermentation .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is a perfect beer to sip on on a lazy pm with no kids in sight !

dunkels ; pours a clear , deep copper-brown w/ a thin light tan head which dissipates quickly leaving a moderate lacing in my pils glass ; a subtle smell , cereal grain , toasted nuts , and hints of dark fruits and noble hops ; a crisp , malty flavor , nutty w/ a caramel-like undertone , faint fig/date-like notes as well , an excellent finish ; very dry and light bodied with plenty of co2 , this beer feels like it evaporates off your tongue ; a very drinkable beer , i 'm def .  nice oily sheen to this ; some head retention & above average lacing s : plums & other dark fruit , a bit of leafy hops t : boozey plums , dark cherry , woody hops , dryness & a bit of cakeyness up front .  it 's as smooth as silk - perfectly suited as a dinner and desert sipper and easily the best porter i 've had the pleasure of tasting .

when inhaling deeply i manage to smell a lavender soap aroma with some malt and spicy hop .  i have to admit i do n't usually spring for hefes , but i noticed this on the shelves locally and recalled it was highly thought of by the ba crowd , so i picked up a 16oz bottle and cracked it open over dinner just to see what the fuss was about . i 'm glad i did , because this was a very solid beer . the first thing that hit me upon pouring this unfiltered , tan beer was the lovely smells dancing on the top of the fluffy head . cloves , cinnamon , yeast , lemon , banana ... just an explosion of wonderful scents . it 's quite drinkable and relatively cheap for what you 're getting .  the smoothness of the beer is very impressive , exceptional smoothness in what has to be a rather potent brew .

smell : very , very faint smell of malt and floral hops . taste : very smooth , creamy , slightly sweet , with good balance and a nice hop finish . fairly hopped for this class .  pale orange like an unripe loquat . smells just like a pumpkin pie . taste like a pumpkin pie with a lot of spices .  the best thing about this brew is the mouthfeel , which is thick and expands as it moves across the tongue to the back of the mouth . modestly drinkable , but with this great thick mouthfeel , it 's one to be savored slowly .

appearance - was excellent , as dark and opaque as any stout , very little head with no visible carbonation . smell - some mild sweetness from the malt with a hint of that coffee taste associated with dark beers .  respectable cover of off white tiny bubbles that slowly collars and disappears leaving a few wisps of lace .  mouthfeel is absurdly rich and creamy , silky smooth and slurpalicious . ) it 's the best feature of this brew . i mean , i like the taste , love the mouthfeel , and would enjoy having two or three of these , but that abv is on the high end .

this brew poured a very beautiful dark brown color with some nice red flecks . the aroma on this brew has a bit of caramel and some faint malts . not a whole lot of aroma coming from it . as it sits a bit , there is a little bit of a nutty aroma . there is n't much else . though there was a bit of lack in the aroma department , this brew makes up for it in the flavor of the brew . it begins with a wonderful blend pale malts , which is quickly followed with a nice punch of caramel and cocoa . it was exceptionally good . i enjoyed it very much this is a great drink .  very carbonated , a light and bubbly beer . the head fluffs up and then dies down , a shame . the color is a golden white , a bit of a haze .  extreme balance and smoothness in this beer , its quite good . big full body with a champaign like fizzyness . im impressed .

as far as smell goes , uh ... .there was n't much to mention . i could smell some hop fragrance but it really did n't stand out as exceptional to me .  pours a murky brown-fuschia with an odd colored pink/brown head . not exactly a looker .  first sip reveals a soft creamy texture with mild rolling carbonation .

s- the smell was very subtle . there was some sweet maltiness and some mild floral characteristics noted .  a : pours red-brown , with slight haze and a light haze that quickly drops to nothing .  mouthfeel : exceptionally smooth and silky as can be .

insanely tart notes of lemon zest , white grape rinds , and dry oak barrels . so incredibly tart ; for me , the only comparable wild ale is batch 2 beatification ( in terms of sheer sourness ) . fantastic beer .  somewhat amber color for an ipa . a very interesting ipa , and probably the best beer from magic hat in awhile .  thick with just a little bit of slickness and just enough carbonation . sly fox oatmeal stout is a solid beer with a fantastic mouthfeel ; probably something i would order again .

there is the light smell of caramel along with a whiff of alcohol ( which is a surprise considering the abv is not terribly high ) .  pours a nice rich brown , not much head .  mouthfeel- medium bodied ale for sure and had small amount of carbonation . very creamy , and left a easy feel on the tongue .

coarse , earthy hop aroma ; slightly catty . toasted bread and dry leaves .  oh , it looks like a euro pils , and to some extent , smells like a pilsner .  the aroma speaks strongly of roasted grains , as you would expect from a stout , while on the tongue the beer has tremendous body .

s : sweet malty smell of molasses . t : the smell is very accurate to the taste ; sweet heaviness with a clear taste of dark molasses . i would have expected more in the way of aroma but that is n't necessarily a bad thing .  pours a beautiful deep brown , very little head quickly recedes- no lacing .  regular boris has the most incredible smooth palate and this follows suit . so silky smooth from the oatmeal . definitely an interest beer for this alone .

feeling inside the neck , it is totally smooth so i have no reservation about the safety of the beer , but the carbonation is another thing ... aroma - roasted grain , kind of woody , a touch of coffee beans .  pours a copper color with what starts out as a nice creamy head but almost instantly recedes into a thin film . minimal lacing left behind .  m : the feel is exactly how i like my imperial stouts . there is a decent amount of carbonation in there as well .

aroma of mild citrus . it was hard to smell . had to stick my nose right down over the glass .  aroma : malt base with some mild floral hop notes appearance : deep gold that looks too light for a bock in my opinion . nice white head , even from the 3rd or 4th pour from the growler , and nice rocky lace .  one of the best mouthfuls ever !

aromas include coffee , some cocoa , and some berries . it 's not highly intense , leaving very little of a mark . overall , this is a highly drinkable , highly refined porter .  some froth and lace .  mouthfeel is really impressive . very gradual on the tongue and extraordinarily balanced .

the aroma is slight but hoppy , with some pine to it . the flavor is surprisingly light , with piny hops and a tinge of bready malt .  a- pours a jet black color . oily slickness on the sides of the glass but no lacing at all .  great bubbly mouthfeel , no aftertaste at all .

nose is kind of small and basic . mild green apple , sense of sweet malts and candi . not very big or noticeable or even complex .  a : pours almost pitch black with some deep ruby highlights around the edges , capped by a thin layer of mocha-colored head . retention is poor as the head dissipates almost immediately , leaving scant lacing .  m- really interesting . a dry feeling on the sides of the tongue and a sweet feeling in the back . really well done .

smells of some heavy brown malts , some toast , a bit of spiciness underlined with a hint of booze . overall , a fantastic and robust offering from a favorite producer . puts countless other pas to shame and raises the bar in an excellent way .  poured rather hazy in the glass with minimal head after a vigorous dispense .  finishes dry with nice mocha notes & a touch of charred grain mf : very oily & smooth as all hell with low carbonation & nice stickyness .

there is not much in the way of aroma , slightly sweet with no hop aroma . the beer is full bodied , smooth across the tongue .  cloudy caramel colour with little to no head .  moderate body , excellent smoothness .

the smell is the highlight of this beer- nutmeg , pumpkin , vanilla , cinnamon and a gram cracker crust smell that emerges as it warms up . tastes like pumpkin pie spices with a hop kick up front with a delicious carmelized sugar like on top of the pie in the middle , delicious . unfortunately , the finish and aftertaste is so dominant of nutmeg that all other flavors are lost . drinkability up front is exceptional but the negative finish makes it average . if they could balance out that nutmeg finish , this would be the best pumpkin beer i 've had .  acloudy reddish brown with a thin tan sheet of foam on top , no head to speak of , but laced well as i drank it down sspicy , raison , plum , apricot , pear , lots of fruity smells here tnot much like the smell , buttery toffee flavor , maybe some mild fruit tones , flavor is very mild and enjoyable if you like mild ales msmooth and velvetish , medium bodied , not much for carbonation dvery differentthe smell really threw me on this one ; i expected the taste to be more fruity .  the carbonation is just right here .

appearance : pours into a sam adams glass a clear pale yellow with a loose-bubbled white head on top . smell : quite sweet with indications of wheat and lemony citrus .  pours a clear orange-y amber with an initially large white head , which reduces to a thin haze .  the mouthfeel was awesome - very creamy and full bodied .

not much in the nose -- just some faint grassy notes . the taste was outstanding for a pilsner , which is not my favorite style -- especially for an american pils . tremendously drinkable -- the ultimate lawnmower beer . interesting and well-crafted enough to please my beer geek friends , even the ones who crave a cellar-temperature russian imperial stout on an 85-degree day , but accessible enough to please those who usually shy away from anything more complex than bud or mgd .  pours a light amber with a cloud and a small head that dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel - smooth , evenly carbonated , and a perfectly solid body .

s- dull smelling dry hops , wheat malt . well balanced with bitter dry hop nose , complex wheat malt finish . the nose lacks however .  a : pours a bit cloudy .  super creamy mouthfeel w/o any overcarbed bite .

s- smells of grain , faint hops . relatively clean .  pours orangey yellow ... not spectacular . poured too cold , but strong lacing nonetheless .  mouthfeel is medium-thick but amazingly silky . carbonation is moderate .

mild roasted malt aroma .  rusty , deep brown . thin , big-bubbled tan head recedes quickly and leaves negligable lace .  m- mouthfeel on this is incredible . medium to full bodied , chewy and creamy , moist , and not a hint of alcoholic bite .

smell was alcohol and burnt malt .  pours murky burnished copper , bit of brown seeping in , with a thin , soapy tan head on top , that at least lasts for quite awhile on its own .  m/d : a full body that is creamy and velvety smooth .

this notes of grapefruit and pineapple . just thick hop notes here so ripe and fresh it was like heaven just smelling this . smooth and mellow delivery of the flavor , though not as strong as the aroma would have led me to believe . light alcohol notes as well and a really good medium feel to it . something i would love to try again as the aroma itself was worth the price . this was damn nice  from notes ... had this on tap in prague at a chinese restaurant off of hastalska street a : dark copper colored beer with a small but lasting head s : not much , but some malt and hops ... t : much more filling and thick than a traditional pils m : smoother and thicker , but still crisp d : very good beer , a nice change of pace from the pils abound in prague .  m= perfect dryness and crispness .

not much at all in there .  an apple ale , this has a nice golden hue , but with no head or lacing to speak of . huge apple aromas !  m : full-bodied and lightly carbonated with a soft and creamy texture . alcohol noticable in a nice warming effect .

the aroma is surprisingly weak and consists of a vague smell of roasted coffee .  pours typical saison ... hazy golden straw , filled with hints of brown highlights .  m - creamy and rich . the carbonation is very laidback ... almost feels as if it floats on the tongue . very soft ... puffy , in a way .

s : aroma is somewhat muted , with notes of raisins , cinnamon , and nutmeg .  from a growler into a frosty mason-jar mug at purv 's beer and more in peckville , pa lighter in appearance than i had expected . smell was of straight cocoa powder and a little bit of spice from the chili pepper mouthfeel was very nice considering the light color .  m - amazing . low to moderate carbonation ( expected ) and full bodied .

nose is tangy wheat with a bit of a roasted flavor and a touch of herbal hops . good overall and interesting as this is my first dunkel .  poured with a little head , but after the initial head was gone , could n't get it back . no lacing at all .  a very smooth , luxurious malt backbone enhances the mouthfeel , but a bitter smack of hops reminds me that i 'm drinking an ipa . quite enjoyable .

i found little to know aroma at all .  here it goes : looks kind of like filtered apple cider . maybe a little more orange . more inviting than most , but it does have some funk to it .  feels wonderful on the tongue , perfect for a summer or spring day .

s : hay , citrus zest with light fruits on the background . crackery malts come through more as it warms .  cloudy , deep amber-straw . almost half a finger of bubbly white head that does n't last long .  loved the residual stickiness . d- it 's remarkable how fff can make such big beers and hide the alcohol so well .

s : not much of a smell , some malt and some burnt notes . t : tastes like guinness extra stout up front but finishes with a sweeter chocolate taste .  pours out a thick , browny , sludge ( hah ) with a little bit of thin head , which completely dissipitates to just a mild lacing around the edges of the glass . a huge whiff of toffee notes , rock candy , and what seems to be raspberry twists . this ca n't be an american beer , where are the hops ? for what it is , it is incredibly good to drink slowly .  m : as expected it has a wonderful feel to it that only a belgian can give . thick and creamy with a medium weight that gives way to an extremely crisp finish .

smells of burnt toast , nuts and vodka . fortunately the taste is so very much more than the smell .  picked this up at the biergarten in jenks : pours an effervescent apricot/caramel with 2 fingers of cream colored head . average head retention & lacing s : orchard fruit in abundance , burnt candi-sugar , peaches , green apple peels & honey , almost pulled a 4.5 t : persimmons , pears , white grapes , candi-sugar , a touch of brown sugar & dryness up front , some lemons & grassyness there as well .  medium bodied , excellent mouthfeel .

aroma is basic , clean and crisp .  a- pours a nice shade of a light amber/orange with a paper thin white head that immediately fades . looks good , but the head situation is greatly disappointing .  mouthfeel is where this beer really shines , and makes one understand why some folks are such lager fans . the balance in this beer is amazing , with everything seemingly in the right preportion .
s - it has a firm soap scent but a hint of caramel can be picked up .  it 's dark brown in appearance with no head .  m- great mouthfeel .

the aroma is very subtle but you can pick up on the yeasts used , and sweet grain .  a - poured very little head , and left very little lacing.. and i know my glass is clean . looks like an ipa ... nice orangey-amber glow .  starts with roasted coffee flavor , mouthfeel is incredible smooth .

she loves scotch ales/scottish ales and when i ca n't turn up something new/local for her to enjoy i fall back on the classic imports . the nose is mildly malty .  kind of goofy throw back ( 50 's ) look bottle ( works well with the duke ellington i am listening to at the moment ... ) eyeballs ... straw with a brownish tinge , nice head , withstanding well , solid carbonation , nothing fancy nothing rancid nose ... bready , almost belgian esque but a bit breifer.. malt and subdued hops like honeysuckle rather than a full on bouquet.. pleasant enough mouth action ... a nice fullness without being heavy in the least , fills the mouth amply without over carbonation , the feel is excellent across the whole pallette , this reminds me of what a `` mild '' fullers esb would tast like , quite enjoyable , nothing overwhelming , just a nice malt ( not too sweet ) start and bare bones hops that finishes dry enough to not drown out the wonderfull mouthfell verdict : an excellent session beer , not as agressive as say long trail ale in america but similar in its ease of sip and nice full feel across the whole mouth .  m- very , very thick and chewy . also quite heavy .

some dms , malt , toffee and something nutty on the nose . flavour - intriguing mix of caramel , toffee , chocolate , nut and something hard to pin down .  slightly lighter than i would expect . fizzy beige head of .5 cm fades quickly to nothing . first sip reveals an average body with fine rolling carbonation and smooth silky texture .  the mouthfeel is outstanding . substantial , but not quite so thick as to confuse it with a stout .

the brew is a clear amber , looking a lot like a munich oktoberfest . aroma is mild , with little indication of the beer 's hoppy palate . wisconsin amber has a lot of the drinking characteristics of a pilsner jazzed up with some medium-roasted malts .  pours a thin a off white head that rapidly dissipates into the ethers . body is deep brown-black . the oakiness becomes a bit more pronounced ion the flavor along with some of the accompanying bourbon . new hollands crown jewel indeed . i drank this around cellar temperature which really seemed to bring out its full character .  mouth feel is incredible with some good champagne bubbling going on .

appearance-golden bright yellow color , very white head grows to three fingers settles down at two and stays there . smell-malt appears in the form of dried bread , also light grassiness and the lightest bit of hop flavor , clean of any alcohol . overall-a very successful kolsch , easy to drink . a great first try for this beer style .  looks pretty average for an american double .  mouthfeel very full and smooth .

as soon as i put the beer to my nose i get a lot of boozy scents , alcohol and such . faint hits of tobacco and grape juice , or maybe a cheap franzia wine ... definitely blushberry . nice and complex , a lot better than the smell which is n't too pleasant to me .  pours a thick deep black with a very thin tan head . no retention , no lace .  extremely smooth tasting beer . bodied is so full its nearly chewable . mouthfeel is full and round . finish is clean and very smooth .

s : here 's my one complaint : light citric hops , light caramel malt . good , but way too light . my nose was wet before i picked up anything .  had this on-tap at ccb 's tasting room during the hunahpu release even on september 24 , 2011 . a : very dark brown , almost black body with a superficial tanned coffee head that dissipated quick . no lacing present . o : it was a good way to start the evening with this beer , which definitely starts shining after it warms up a bit .  m- extremely smooth with the right amount of carbonation d- this one goes down too easily .

smell - smells of soured cider . so far , both the appearance and smell remind me of damnation . slight hints of citrus , brett and funk are also noticeable . very funky and delicious .  a- murky brown amber , wispy head .  matches perfectly with the thickness of the body .

mostly amber ale aroma with hint of spice .  appearance : tawny brown , quite hazy , thinnish layer of tan frothy foam , ok head retention aroma : rich malty caramel , tangerine , woodsy hops , raisins flavor : smooth malt sweetness with hints of orange marmalade , stewed prunes , hazelnuts , and herbally hops ; finishes semisweet with a brief fruity aftertaste mouthfeel : medium body , gentle carbonation , smooth and soft texture , slight warmth in the throat other comments : quite a scrumptious bitter .  super easy going down with a perfect dry finish .

my poured stubby elicited little smell , but the initial flavour was a rounded coffee chocolate.the flavour fell away though , to a minimalist charcoal toast it felt smooth and soft , perhaps too soft in the mouth . this is a strongish brew at 6.8 % and the coffee chocolate predominance makes it an enjoyable stout but one for moderation  it was hard to judge appearance since it was in a brown bottle , but it seems to be a little cloudy with just a bit of foam .  in the mouth , the tiny bubbles announce and incredibly smooth and balanced beer , with a roasted , slightly sweet flavor .

so-so lacing and at least for me no real aroma detected . however this beer tasted great and i am at a loss on how to describe the taste .  there is a decent amount of head but it dies down quickly .  great palate , though . even when it gets warm , great warmth and sliky smooth syrups .

smell was milder than i expected ( also could be due to the allergies/cold i have ) . malts and alcohol primarily . coffee aroma appeared much later , as it warmed .  very small , quickly evaporating head and absolutely no lacing .  the carbonation is spot on and helps bring the subtle notes of roast to the front . this also makes this beer one of the best feeling brews i 've ever had .

really nice aroma . smells of pecans , buttery crust , vanilla and dark fruit .  a : pitch black color , no head , no lacing s : raisins , figs , sweet woodiness t : sweet oak , raisins , figs , smoky chocolate ; finishes with a nice smoky wood bitterness m : medium-thick , lightly carbonated , velvety smooth o : this did n't quite live up to the enormous hype , but it 's still a world-class beer nonetheless .  the first thing i noticed actually was the incredible mouthfeel .

it does n't really have any overpowering aromas . both the hops and malt are pretty subtle . it 's very drinkable , especially for a pale .  drank from a bottle the taste was that of really good choclete and hints of coffe . no real bitter taste had a light smell of choclete to it over all etremelly drinkable and refreshing . alsohada light carbination not too much or little justenough to givethe right amount of fizz this beer is in my opinon up there as far as import beers farsuppour to a guiness wich is overlly bitter .  m - thick , very smooth and very viscous with little carbonation .

the aroma was nice , but nothing special .  extremely cloudy , almost milky thick pale orange golden color .  perhaps there is similar inconsistency here , and i will be wowed by the bottles i brought home sometime in the future ... mouthfeel is by far the best characteristic , supple , creamy and light .

aroma is non descript ... maybe a hint of chocolate .  bought a michelob mixed sampler 12 pack for $ 9.99 wow , big surprise here ! i may be a spring chicken when it comes to beer drinking but this was one of the better hefe 's i 've had and to think it comes from ab .  big , viscous mouthfeel does great things for this beer , transmitting a pretty large package ( 10 % , significant ibu count ) into an easy-to-sip package .

first of all , i am very dissapointed to hear that warbird brewing company has closed . warbird has produced a very drinkable red ale .  pours a caramel to reddish color with a lightly colored head . the head is not very impressive looking .  the mouthfeel is light , with excellent particulates that roam the mouth . a most excellent brew that i would n't hesitate to try again .

s - malt aroma accented by hops .  a : pours a rather hazy , blonde yellowish colour . disturbing the settled yeast added a good amount of sediment to the pour .  bordering on chewy as you work toward swallowing . carbonation was excellent on tap , just enough to contribute to a dry and clean finish despite the initial sweetness of the beer .

s : hints of breadyness mf : medium bodied , slick & very well balanced great drinkability , such a well crafted dubbel ! although the lack of nose is a let down .  appearance- the color reminds me of cedar wood an earthy dark amber/red . mouthfeel- light on palate and definetly lends itself to match with food nicely like breaded shrimp .  mouthfeel is full but not too heavy .

the scent is a malty mix of grains and corn . very wheaty smell with a very slight hint of hops .  got this beer on tap at the flying saucer . pours a yellowish amber body with finger width white head .  m : rich and creamy . very chewy and thick . little carbonation .

aroma is tart and a bit earthy .  i love marin brewing co. beers and this is a well made ale . i just do n't think it 's my style . looked like a lager which was a bit surprising as i expected something darker .  perfect carbonation to it .
s - light citrus hop aroma . not much else .  pours a deep orange amber with a light tan head that lingers for a while .  m - huge , thick , syrupy , creamy , perfect carbonation .

smells are light too , and crisp . nothing sweet or piny to note .  really a weird pour as it comes out a very nice hazelnut color but with no head at all to speak of .  perfectly constructed mouthfeel for a schwarzbier .

the aroma can only be described as terrible . harsh , grainy , and metallic , with an emphasis on metallic .  white head is foamy and small , with little retention . leaves very little lace . like a pils on steroids .  the mouthfeel on this ale was great , and i think the mouthfeel of just about any beer is enhanced by cask conditioning . it had a nice thick feel on the tongue .
however , the nose is pretty muted overall .  pours a crystal-clear straw-yellow body with a quickly dissipating off-white head .  palate duration is excellent . medium body .

s : bouquet is faint , but notes of smoke , bananas , and butter make it through nicely . t : smokey upfront with a hefty dose of walnuts .  from a bottle provided by doublej , thanks jon , a : pours a lightly hazy gold with a spotty light white head , average head retention , some lace .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

smell is average , not a lot comes through other than coriander and other spices .  poured into my duvel tulip . appearance- cognac colored pour..i guess caramel , maybe ruby caramel . 1/2 inch head on pour which is gone before you can say doppelbock . no lacing at all .  m- great mouth feel . very smooth and not over-carbonated .

yummy ... pours a heady white-over-bronze trophy , some modest lacing which arches around delightfully un-predictable shapes ... i think i see a war-elephent trumpeting hannibal 's decent from the alps ... smell was somewhat subdued , i did n't have any good glassware handy , i used a big wine glass . smell was suggestive of good things to come , but nothing terribly fancy . this is where the fun really starts .  a coppery orange with minimal head that leaves a thin lacing around the glass .  t- the taste is starts out very smooth and creamy from the mouthfeel with some of roasted malts quickly followed by a nice bitter finish . m- the mouthfeel is silky smooth from the oatmeal with a moderate amount of carbonation . d- very good stuff , and not too boozy for a 9 % beer even though you can feel the warmth .

now , i 'm an ale lover , so to be greeted by a lager was less than exciting . it goes down smoothly with a light aftertaste . i hope they are n't disappointed when i leave town .  pours to a thin white head and clear darkish gold color . good for the hot summer .  mild-medium carbonation just enough to excite the palate . to me , this is almost the perfect mouthfeel .

leaves some real nice lacing on the way down . i smell the hops , but nothing too disctinct .  a- pours black in color . not a oil black , but its still black . there is very little head and minimal lacing left .  the feel is big and thick .

smell : some bready caramel malt sweetness . not a ton going on here . overall : a solid irish red .  a : pours black with a finger of tan head that recedes into a thin ring with no lacing .  smooth , airy , luscious , divine mouthfeel . tremendous ! a wonderful bsda .

the nose comprises chocolate syrup , roasted malts , dark chocolate powder , molasses , and a touch of vanilla bean . the taste holds notes of darkly-roasted malts , very bitter dark chocolate ( the kind you 'd bake with , rather than eat straight-up ) , vinyl , anise , rubbing alcohol , charcoal , and molasses .  halfway through and the head is gone , with nary a speck of lacing .  mouthfeel is just perfect . the way this thing finishes it has a slight peppery aspect but it is dry and clean .

groggy hazy brown color in the body . a little sour , but the malt comes through in the aroma . flavor is a superbly sweet caramel malt , but with a kick of almond .  the head is a moderate-lived cocoa-colored affair that recedes into a floating patch of film on top of the brew . a few rings here and there , but generally no lacing .  mouthfeel is heavy and smooth with a small amount of carbonation , very nice .

s : some malt characters , bread and toffee mostly . after that not to much going on in the nose . very subtle hints of hops but that 's reaching for it . d : very drinkable beer !  god , that sounds so snobby and like such b/s ... nonetheless , it pours a very nice orange/beige and again had no head mainly because i believe that i poured it wrong . damnit , that 's two meals for me .  mouthfeel is probably the best part of this beer .

smell is subtle and surprisingly fruity . overall an outstanding example of the style .  little head accompanied a dark clear golden colour . little cardination and some lacing .  mouthfeel : thick and smooth in every sense of the words -- a very pleasant experience indeed !

aroma : sweet , grainy wheat accompanied with apple , citrus , and a slight hint of floral hops taste : sharp lemon and apple over a tasty and grainy wheat backbone . drinkability : excellent , as you 'd expect from any wheat beer worth a damn . verdict : saint arnold has created a solid wheat beer , perfect for a summer 's day here in texas .  12 oz bottle , pours a hazy amber with very little head , even with pouring into the middle of the glass .  mouthfeel is so big thick and creamy .
s- not a whole lot going on here . some sweet hops and a touch of hops .  pours a somewhat cloudy red mahogany , with minimal head .  beautiful .

s - not much going on smell wise , reserved , yet some hints of dark roast , fresh mulled grains .  bottle to sniffer appearance : pours with a small brown head that quickly dissipates , looks of black coffee the carbonation barley able to keep the head alive .  m- awesome thick mouthfeel on this seasonal .

smell : i 'm really not getting much aroma off this . perhaps a hint of grasses , but barely . taste : nice malt taste with a light bit of citrus ( lemon ) and grasses .  the beer pours a hazy golden orange with a small amount of head .  the body is just fantastic : full , creamy and smooth .

slight malty nose . starts mellow with some sweetness , finish is more malt than hop with no aftertaste .  poured deep copper , clear with not a lot of head . and what did foam up went away somewhat quickly . almost no lacing .  mouthfeel is perfect . not too thick and good carbonation .

this was by far , the worst `` beer '' i 've ever tasted . if this bottle was n't infected , and was supposed to taste like that , i 'm downright confused .  a-light amber/reddish color with a small head nothing much else s- smells of spices coriander and pumpkin , smells just like fall in my humble opinion t- tastes just like it smells full of pumpkin with heavy spices .  full bodied and silky .
i really enjoyed this beer . it really did not have an aroma .  pours an orangish-amber into a pint glass with very little foam .  very full body that stretches the cheeks . just such chewy hops .

think of a nice malt being toasted . keep toasting it until it is black and almost burnt or charcoal and make guinness . when you make this beer do everything exactly the same just change how much you toast the malt . to me i like the dark toast flavor and color of kilkenny the best . the taps for kilkenny say it is brewed by guinness .  i was a bit apprehensive with my first sip of the saranac black and tan because it poured almost no head ( at first i thought i had gotten a bad one ) .  m : the carbonation on this one is perfect . perfect mouthfeel .

the day after i review the bottle : i walk into my local and it 's on a cask hand pull , what a lovely surprise . the smell was , like the bottled one , it 's weakest part and although there were hop and malt esters they did n't excite or bother the nose at all . the last paragraph is almost the same as my bottle review : really liked the mouthfeel and taste , good blend of ingredients to produce a fine beer .  pours dark brown with very little head .  m : very viscous and full . smooth carbonation and a nice stickyness make the mouthfeel very complimenting to the taste .

the aroma was very strange and not at all appetising for me . the aroma was disappointing but that is one of the nicest beers i have ever tasted .  golden amber color , thin white head that dissipates very quickly . extremely drinkable , with a lot of flavor while it is in your mouth but no aftertaste , so it begs for the next sip .  m : very soft , finely carbonated medium body .

the aroma is a variety of differnet malts with a very slight spicy scent that i could n't identufy .  pours a clear dark brown with slight beige head .  mouthfeel is perfect -- light but not watery , highly carbonated ... perfect for the style .

surprisingly malty aroma from the fresh pour . hop aromas are very muted , particularly for the style . while appealing , this does n't produce the tradition ipa smell . like the smell , more malty than the style suggests , but it is still delicious .  this pours a nice dark brown with an off white head . little retention and virtually no lacing .  the first thing one notices , upon pouring , is the consistency : this beer appears thicker than most , and may or may not have legs , likely a contributing factor to this beers exceptional mouthfeel .

my first beer with agave added . smell : hints of honey and orange blossom , slightly muted .  a - pours very dark brown in color with some light that is able to make it through around the edges revealing some ruby highlights . the tan head was quite minimal showing very little retention and leaving very little lace .  smells like a smoke beer ... .i get a little chocolate in the nose ... but the roasted smell is overpowering ... taste is sweet on the front end ... and an overall smooth taste ... .with a little bitterness on the back end ... very nice feel ... .creamy and smooth perfect for the style ... .velvet like smoothness ... drinkability is not bad ... although it is a stout and it weighs you down ...

appearance : pour is a pale golden/yellow straw color ; starts with a one finger white meringue-like head with solid retention ; body is very clear and shows very strong and fast carbonation ; fair and dry looking washes of lacing hold on to the sides of the glass . smell : some dry , toasty grains . nose is very faint and not much coming out of it .  exceptionally fizzy cloudy and golden appearance .  solid mouthfeel , smooth and dense with animated carbonation .

a : transparent light amber colored beer , that has a good head to start off with , but it dissipates fast . s : hoopy but nothing special , not that potent . t : overall good . mild hops taste with hints of citrus , and a bit of a bitter aftertaste , but nothing overwhelming . very much so torn between 3.5 and 4 .  poured chilled in tall pilsner glass a : little carbonation ; minimal head ; clear , solid yellow s : clove , yeast ; inviting aroma t : dry , spiced , medium hops ; light on the belgian side of things ( e.g. , bottle conditioning ) ; not very intense flavor overall , a good solid beer , drawing sound inspiration from the belgians .  the alcohol is kept well in check allowing the finish to cascade over the palate with a ton of character and wonderful texture . strong , long finish .

i had never had a real irish red ale so when i found out this was contract brewed in holland i was little disappointed . the smell was odd at first , not inviting at all .  the off-white head is modest in size and quickly recedes to a ring and an island of foam . what little head is left behind manages to leave some scattered lacing .  the mouthfeel is a true hallmark of this beer .

s : nose rather faint , tones that i picked up mostly chocolate . t & m : creamy textures throughout with some smokiness mixed in .  12oz bottle poured into imperial pint glass a - pours a very cloudy , orangish/brown bark color with a 3/4 inch light tan head . lacing is moderate when tipped , and head rests at a thin layer .  initially the softness of the carbonation and the sweetness of the fruity flavors makes it like a sweet soda ( can anyone remember tahitian treat ? again with the yeast character and the near rancid presence ( the brett i presume ) , yet the overall soft flavors and soft feel are greatly appealing and enjoyable . the light , fine and bubbly carbonation brings an element of childhood fun to the drink ( how about fizzies , anyone remember that ) as it brings a tickle to the nose and tongue . light overall feel and great softness . soft and light and tasty ( again in a soda pop manner ) .

it smelled much like a chocolate stout should .  medium amber with little head .  a big sturdy body on this one ... no doubt held up by some quality malts used , gives way to a sublime smooth and velvety mouthfeel that has a slight crispness in the end . about perfect in every sense .

smell : the alcohol is very evident , a sweet syrupy smell and raisins are the only other aromas i pick out . taste : the flavor profile is dominated by raisins and syrup , with warming alcohol in the finish . overall : one dimensional , and cloyingly sweet .  pours a pleasant amber/red with a huge head of foam , yet virtually no lace .  perfect ris mouthfeel .
