not a whole lot of aroma with this one but the sweet , milky , creamy taste more than makes up for it . and this thing is sweet ... .just what you would expect from a sweet milk stout .  a- vigorous pour yields a thin layer of tan head sitting atop an opaque beer . no lacing is apparent as what little head there was dissipated rather quickly . nice job shorts !  m - perfect . exactly how a dipa should be .

s : the nose generally lacks aroma . some grainy bread notes emerge but the hops offer nary a scent . t : a sip makes up for the lackluster nose , lots of flavor jumps out from the get-go .  even with a center pour not much of a head , thin coating of cream white with no real staying power nor lacing .  solid body , creamy mouthfeel .

i first enjoyed yuengling traditional lager on a cold winter day after a snow storm passed i was helping my dad cut some firewood . this beer was very delightful with a mild flavor . and the price is great , yuengling has become my everyday drink .  pours a deep amber from the bottle , off-white head that dissipates quickly leaving thin lacing .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is outstanding . it sparkles just enough to give the palate a good tickle , but not so much that it scrapes away all of its flavor .

s - huge chocolate nose akin to hershey 's chocolate syrup or even a tootsie roll . the aroma is simply amazing . very solid chocolate stout with an 11 % abv that hides behind a wall of bittersweet chocolate goodness .  pours an amber brownish tint that holds an inch thick white cap .  mouthfeel is very syrupy and very rich with a dense body .
similarly , there was lots of malt in the nose though not a complex aroma .  demon fish , 750 ml bottle .  so creamy and smooth it 's almost not a beer ...

light aromas of sweet fruit and a hint of chocolate ... but it is very faint !  growler , half inch whit head that fades quickly to some foam around the top and a ring . color is a little boring , clear copper ish .  sour , some cherries , but most of all very tart and bone dry ; element of french cheese in it ( brie ) , some cream ; m : lovely alcohol , nice tartness , very drinkable ; o : not too complex but but very good kriek , which i will buy whenever i see it .

aroma - a pretty grainy first whiff , light roasted malt and a bit of chocolate come out on setup . fades a lot and does well to maintain some faint roasty aroma . taste - sweet , fully roasted malt and milk chocolate malt .  pours a murky brown with a thin ring , not the most attractive beer at this point .  mouthfeel is heavy and smooth with a nice small bite of carbonation , wonderful .

lightest and sweetest helles yet -- perhaps even paler than a us macro . i like jason 's grape skin description . sidenote : bit of a clinical , soapy scent in the glass .  bottle poured into a snifter a- yellow with a white two finger head . looks like a light beer not a double ipa .  a great take on belgium ale ; apples , pears , lemons , apricot and orange flavors nustle their way thru a carbonated full bodied swig .

aroma - limited nose , a fairly standard pilsener aroma .  pours a very hazy , dark golden apricot/brown color with a half finger white head that quickly fades into a thin lasting ring . minimal spots of lacing left behind .  the texture is rich and creamy and coasts your mouth in deliciousness .
bit of smoke in the nose , but overall subdued .  12oz bottle poured into a nb tulip glass . a : pours a dark black . no head .  perfect . d- a very unique pumpkin ale .

mild bakers ' chocolate with a roasted toffee smell . nothing exciting ; expected .  a - poured a dark copper with no visible carbonation , no head as it was poured all the way to the top , no lacing and no retention .  mouthfeel was great , it was very rich and smooth with little carbonation but it fit the stout just right .

s : bouquet is faint for how strong of a beer this is . molasses , vanilla , and chocolate are all detected .  incredibly drinkable , leaves the drinker craving another ! typically , i prefer a beer that hits the total of the palette , but this beer is an excellent example of its style .  only lightly effervescent , making the mouthfeel of this beer fantastic . i could n't picture the mouthfeel of this beer being any better . the amazing mouthfeel coupled with the well developed and super tasty character of this beer make it an easy drinker .

very grassy on the nose with a touch of pine and skunk . also a bit of a musty smell , and a hint of smoky sweet malts .  12oz can - & gt ; nondescript pint a ~ steady pour reveals very red body with pretty good sized head . appearance is not the highlight of this brew though .  the mouthfeel is perfect for the style ; adequately carbonated and finished silky and creamy .

smells like burnt , lightly smokey malt with no real hop or yeast profile . tastes firmer than it smells . smokiness presides over a rich , very dark malt profile of nuts , peat , and burnt grain .  color is a deep garnet with amber highlights . gave me a thin cap of tan head and very little lacing .  mouthfeel is great . just the right level of thickness here .

s - heavy horse has a classic aroma of toasted malt with notes of caramel , toffee , and a pinch of nuttiness but is hindered by a dry , strong mineral finish .  i have no idea how fresh this bottle was . the best before date was very faint and hardly ledgible . light amber/gold , airy head disappated quickly but did leave decent lacing . top rating for drinkability comes from the fact that it was pretty darn good despite my doubts about the age .  very full in the mouth , coating , oily bitterness lingering and alcohol warmth continues to expand over my palate , throat , stomach as i enjoy this beer .

i was actually pleasantly surprised by this beer . i acquired it in the winter variety case and finally got to it . very nice red hue to the beer . very carbonated , of course , and more than a hint of cranberry .  poured into a piraat tulip glass . has a 1cm golden head with but does n't linger with some mild lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , very smooth and creamy . overall this is pretty damn good .

s : dried apple skins , a little banana and some bubble gum on the nose , although even as the beer warms it does not release much aroma . t : on the palate one finds freshly baked bread , some apple and pear , and a bit of spice . its flavor and aroma profile is on the milder side .  good initial head , but it dissipates to a single layer . the lace is spotty and light .  unbelievably smooth . feel is so outstanding for a heavy dark lager .

s : light and hoppy , but i think maybe my glass smells a bit wierd .  clear yellowish golden color with a surprisingly fluffy white head .  taste- for a double ipa , this beer is not on a mission to wreck the palate ... with so much flavor i 'm surprised that the malts weigh in so heavily . solid . it 's sudsy ( the name of my beloved late parakeet ) and sublime . drinkability- one real attribute about this bruiser of a beer is that the abv ( 10 % ) is completely hidden ... it 's nowhere in any of the above categories . this is more like a nectar , thick and juicy , garnering respect for each sip .

smell is quite clean . hints of wild yeast , but in no way as powerful as most lambics and particularly weak for a cantillon .  poured into a weizen style glass that creates very little head atop a golden-straw colored body .  the mouthfeel is great , nice and thick and perfectly carbonated .

sidenote : waitress tells me this name of this beer was chosen because a song by the same name was being played while it was brewed . aroma is toasted malt and caramel .  besides the color ( pale yellow with a tinge of orange ) , everything else is amazing .  mouthfeel is lucious : creamy and oily , rich in the mouth , but smooth enough to want more and more .

really raw nasty cheap grain smell .  22 oz bottle poured into a tulip glass a-pours a deep reddish brown with a half finger white head that dissipates nearly as quickly as it forms . a few scant bubbles and a ring around the glass is all that remains after a half minute .  the moutfeel is exceptional - full bodied and thick with appropriate carbonation .

the aroma is a pretty subtle combination of lemony and herbal notes .  the beer pours a translucent dark red color with no head at all .  the carbonation is fantastic -- beer feels creamy and smooth- almost velvety .

smell : it 's kind of a let-down smell wise actually . some slightly sour hops and some nutty malts . does n't really smell that great to be honest .  gold color capped by a thin head . it does n't look as bright as i expected so i take a closer glance . i see a fine haze of tiny particles in the glass , though i only poured in half the bottle .  mouthfeel : a smooth sugary viscous mouthfeel that is balanced nicely by the carbonation .

faint clean scent the malty base swiftly gives way to a spicy resin that lingers so long you can get lost in its subtle piney suggestions of cinnamon and nutmeg .  honey amber color , light thin head .  exceptional mouthfeel and drinkability .

the aroma was very subtle with a floral haze .  a - poured a hazy amber color with some cloudiness and sediment visible . head was decent , lacing was minimal .  m : a great , great medium body , that grazes you at the tail with sharp carbonation .

s : herbaceous and slightly spicy , with some suggestion of lime citrus and fresh berry fruit . overall intensity of the smell is weak , giving an impression of vacancy . t : begins off-dry , with pithy grapefruit peel and crackery pilsner malt .  appears a light gold with a dense 1 finger white head that lasts for a minute .  m-grand canyon deep and gordian knot complex . amazingly tantalizing on the palate . while it looks still in the glass it bursts with palate stimulating carbonation with each sip . like an amusement park in your mouth ! this is a highly enjoyable and palate stimulating sipper . a mighty fine drinking brew .

smell- notes of citrus and rice , what one would expect .  look : brown color with ruby shades , very thin foamy head ( maybe because of the glass ) .  like other fine belgian beers the carbonation produces a surreal creamy consistency that serves to deliver maximum taste .

roasted aroma of chocolate , sweet coffee and a slight cinnamon bun finish . oxidation . whoa !  from the growler the beer pours a murky orangish brown color . the head was n't all that great , but that could be due to a dirty growler , glass or the fact that i 've had it in the growler for four days . because of the aforementioned ( i assume ) lacing is also lacking .  really coats the mouth for an excellent mouthfeel .

s - some malt , but you need to inhale deeply . it also smells somewhat sweet to me , perhaps a bit corny .  a - pretty darned black , minimal mocha head that ends fast , lacing thin and unimpressive .  mouthfeel is very delicious with some creamy notes but some nice crisps and sharp grassy hop notes .

aroma is soft , but of coarse hops , but for the most part rather clean . medium in body , and smooth .  very little head and no lacing or retention .  the feeling in your mouth , however is gorgeous ! smooth , silky , incredible.. so incredibly good that i actually said 'incredible ' in a french accent because it deserved such smoothness ... i 'm not going to lie , as for drinkability.. i 'm not as into this as anchor 's or even sierra nevada 's , christmas offerings this year , but it is still very drinkable to this lass .

smell : lots of grainy and bready malts in the nose . medium in strength and quite nice for the style . taste : not nearly as good as the nose . bready malts and some grassy hops through the middle , but honestly a little watery through and through .  a - poured out a clear , dark burgundy color with a very small , thin head of off-white foam .  body is medium-full for style , and this is just about perfect on the way down .

smell : yeasty wheat , dry and straightforward , expect for a slight strofoamish hint in the background .  a : pours a deep brown with dark ruby highlights around the edges . about a half finger of foam fades quickly leaving almost nothing on top and no lacing . kinda looks like a coke or root beer .  mouthfeel is just perfect - thick , rich , and creamy , with a slightly oily sheen that coats the mouth and throat .

mild aroma in a black body with an energetic head of light brown fine bubbles . it is a very nice smooth stout that i found myself liking more and more after each taste .  pours hazy copper with a creamy 1 finger tan head that faded about average time ; good lacing that clings to the glass and leaves rings .  very palatable and no alcohol taste at all m - silky smooth , great carbonation .

pours a ridiculous , impenetrable , thick black . the aroma has some vinous fruit characteristics , heavy malt , maple syrup , some sourness , and a bit of oxidation . no perceivable alcohol , at least in the smell and taste , i 'm sure i 'll be feeling it by the end of my glass . not quite as good as it is on tap as it stands right now , but still a formidable , thick stout and obviously pretty damn good .  sampled at the bbf a - pours a nice slightly hazy pale light gold almost orange with a very light head that fades quickly leaving minimal lacing .  it 's thick , creamy , rich , and robust .

the aroma is very weak though .  a : semi copper and clear . thin , tan head that dissipates quickly . two , despite the heavy graham and pumpkin , you never lose the fact that this is indeed a beer .  the mouthfeel is great on this one too , effervescent and full at the same time .

smell of alcohol and malts . color was bodacious . mouthfeel was like heavenly night blooming jasmine with a hint of mirliitons and cypress buds .  a - poured a dark copper with a one finger khaki head and no visible carbonation . no retention and slight lacing .  mouth is rich and sticky yet wonderfully smooth .

slight fruity aroma but nothing stands out here .  who needs a lemon in a wheat beer when you can have some apricot instead ? on to the beer : yellow to orange in color that 's cloudy .  this brew is a tremendously creamy medium-body with a tantalizing , light bite about the tongue what can i say !

although it had little aroma , it had a very good taste .  appearance- slightly hazy , bright orange color with 1.5 finger eggshell white , foamy head . head settles rather quickly but leaves some residual lacing .  m - perfect for a porter .
pretty nice ; once i got used to it i really started to like it .  small amount of head but it dissipated almost completely .  mouthfeel is super creamy and silky smooth .

very faint smell . medium body , medium carbonation . easy to drink for such a dark and strong ale .  i do n't actually know what it looked like because i had it poured in a cinema that was very dark . no head , though , i know that .  ( not a huge coffee stout fan ) ( blasphemous i know ) the greatest thing about this beer is the smooth creamy texture that is present while drinking .

smell is nothing exceptional : some obvious coffee and a touch of dark chocolate .  i 'd never seen any in my neck of the woods , but a close friend brought me a bottle back from oakland , on the basis of me being a huge zappa fan and beer nut . the only thing that put me off a little was the huge amount of yeast floaties that came with it , although they did nothing to detract from it 's flavor .  while there was no head , the carbonation is just right ; the body is no thinner or heavier than it should be .

( s ) - a dry , yet floral-like citrus . a damp wood-like pine . ( t ) - a fresh & crisp floral citrus of lemon , pineapple , grapefruit , and lime . has everything you would expect from the style .  pours a hazy golden color with a one fingered head that quickly fades to a barely noticeable cap .  perfect . d- a remarkably smooth beer , although a bit mild .

as a long time drinker and former hamms beer route salesman this is still a beer that holds up well.ca n't count the cases of this that has passed my lips but wish i could find it in the bottle . now if they would only bring back hamms preferred stock ... we 'd be back in hog heaven . for the money its a real drinkable beer .  amber brown , perfectly clear , with a single finger of soapy white pilsner-like head that settles to a ring quickly .  m- the mouthfeel is full bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

ok , twist my arm ... pours an absolutely clear pale golden colour , with a few fingers of thick foamy white head , which leaves consistent lacing around the glass . the aroma is of cereal grain , the malt being the only thing coming through , until it warmed a bit , and then a bit of floral hoppiness was detectable .  the beer poured black , with a tan head that had low retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is exceptional ! this beer is smooth , silky , creamy .

s - roasted malt and faint molasses and hot chocolate notes . t - roasted malts , bakers chocolate , coffee and a faint sour note that i ca n't place , but it 's not unpleasant .  a ) 1/4 a head . quickly disappeared . looks like medium carbonation .  mouthfeel was creamy and exceptional . i was surprised to be able to drink the whole thing since i am not a fan of coffee at all , but this was a pleasant change of pace for me .

s : weaker aroma than i expected but i might have hyped the wet hops in my mind . floral hops and citrus `` dominate '' but the nose is still weak .  it comes with about a fingers worth of off white head . little to no retention , no lacing left on the glass .  the mouthfeel of this beer might be its most remarkable consistency ; velvety , silken slickness .

s - fairly dissapointing . for having lots of fuggles and goldings i was expecting a good hop smell . smell improves after drinking and warming also m - a little zippy with the carbonation but still well bodied .  a - raspberry/brown color , not head nor lace .  m- creamy and full-bodied . what else would you expect from the style ?

s : roasted malts and cocoa dominate the faint air . there is a little old leather chair smell and it 's comforting . dark nuts , coffee , and some sweet hershey 's round it out .  poured into a snifter on 7/5/10 many thanks to pdxhops dark brown in color , settling black in the glass . in fact all foam disappears save a ring . no lace .  mouthfeel is full bodied and smooth that feels pretty creamy on the tongue .

on its incredibly smart looking clear bottle it even claims to be a bitter ! best compared to the very similar budweiser and millers from the us .  absolutely no head on the pour .  m - perfect carbonation . awesome smoothness . dry .

smell - rosey , very subdued , but a little too much so . just would have expected a bit more out of it , in terms of aroma . taste - this reminds me of a barleywine . there were lots of hops in this , but it was very smooth . you can taste the alcohol . not what i would have expected out of the winter warmer style , but enjoyable none the less . feel - extremely smooth with a nice mouthcovering .  a - pours with a thin fizzy white head that dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel is astonishingly smooth and creamy for such a rich , complex ale .

dare i say , nearly perfect ? grainy and corny aroma with a hint of dishwater and dirty sponge .  poured from 750ml cork and caged bottle into a long stem tulip glass around 40~45 f. nose : dark fruit , plums , maple syrup , clove and other spices . appearance : dark red/brown with small but persistent ring of bubbles .  the mouthfeel is oh so smooth and creamy , just perfect !

despite my usual preference for ales , i really enjoy this lager . if the macros produced lagers like this one ( and i 'm sure they could do so ) , american beers would be looked at quite differently by the world of beer experts .  bottled 08 04 2008 a- nice amber bronze with decent but short lived head that laces .  m : the mouthfeel is what really sold me on this beer .

the nose is entirely too one dimensional though . it smells almost like straight up cold coffee , with just barely a appreciable hint of dark chocolate .  appearance : light golden brown , slightly cloudy with decent head retention on the white head aroma : definate piney notes , with some sharp citrusy grapefruit in the aroma .  t- pretty solid all around . very smooth , robust , and thick .

the nose was lightly malty with a slight fruitiness accompanying the sweetness . the finish was bittersweet and extremely pleasant .  visual : pale straw , gold in color . no head .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , substantial and even sticky .

smells of citrus and ginger , very faint cloves & cinnamon there as well , very nice . the taste is very clean .  the body pours quite a pale yellow , with a moderate haze and thinnish bone-white head .  mouthfeel : perfection . the bead is neither too large nor too small .

smells of smoke and burnt coffee .  looking forward to this evem after the disappointing eipa and apa a- very hazy , milky even , brown . white head looks like warm milk froth . lots of stuff floating about .  mouthfeel is a heavy but perfect . heavy with lots of lactose , light but fizzi carbonation .

s- i get some modest hops here . while the smell is lighter , i get the full range , oily-hops oders , a lot of earthiness and pine-notes , even a little citrus . a nice surprise i did not remember is how balanced this guy is .  pours a burgandy color with no head or lace .  this beer 's greatest attrubite is , in fact , its spectacualrly creamy mouthfeel .

smell - pretty faint but hints of floral hops and sweet bready malt . a well produced pa but smell lets it down .  pours a deep red/brown with no head at all .  the mouthfeel is , in a word , glorious . smooth on the tip of the tongue , then seeming to evaporate off your tongue leaving a crisp , somewhat spicy finish .

a little bit of fruit gone bad on the nose , this might be due to the aging , it is n't too strong but still noticeable . rich malts and still some hops in the bg .  beer arrived with almost no head at all . color was very dark , almost appearing black at first .  so very soft on the palette - really a unique mouthfeel , just velvety smooth .

smells ok ... ca n't exactly put my finger on what is wrong ... but it may have something to do with the `` party pig '' it came from .  lacing is okay , head is minimal , not much retention..leaves barely anything on top aroma : sweet and fruity , hops ( citrus ) taste : malts come in well and finish off with a citrus hop finish .  it is very creamy and very smooth . it 's like chocolate silk . very delicious .

smell- bready with a light banana clove aroma . taste- light malt balanced with wheat/ yeast .  appearance : really cloudy , reminds me of a wit . pours yellow with an orange tint .  what i really loved was the mouthfeel . very good for a lager style beer .

s : i got virtually no scent until it warmed up and i got chocolate and nice coffee but mostly roast and alc . t : great taste , smooth high gravity , the coffee taste is great .  the color is a pale straw yellow with a nice white head .  the mouthfeel is fucking perfect : it 's thick and creamy .

i was n't able to pick up a great deal of aroma , only slight hints of malt .  growler from firehouse saloon in rochester ny a- a pretty standard deep brown/black with a 1/4 '' head of soapy mocha bubbles .  my favorite thing about this obviously the sweet rich malt character which adds to a very nice body for a beer of this alcohol content .

the smell was sweet , malty , and smokey , which i really liked .  love the bottle , too bad the price is so high . a : pours a dark ruby/brown color with a small off-white head forms , comprised of rather large bubbles , and dissipates rather quickly . very thin lacing forms , but does not last .  the mouthfeel on this beer is great , so creamy with just enough bubbles that make it not to syrupy .

s : very feint smell , chocolate note , but a bit of roasty malt as well .  pours mahogany with 3+ fingers of mocha head . average lacing & head retention s : roasty malt & chocolate , plus a slight iron scent t : chocolate , roasty malt , & some dryness up front .  full effervescent body , huge amounts of carbonation . an unusual beer that 's quite good .

the nose was the least offensive part of this beer : ripe fruits , some bitter chocolate the taste on this beer was absolutely horrid . rotten fruit mixed with tobacco and cardboard . new holland produces some fantastic beers , this just happens to not be one .  a - opaque black ( as a black cauldron ) . a thin khaki ring of head remains for a few minutes , then is gone forever .  mouthfeel : has a great mouthfeel . it has exceptional smoothness .

the smell is a little off putting , but once you take the first sip it is very easy to get over the smell .  pours an effervescent crimson/caramel with 2+ fingers of sand colored head . average lacing & head retention s : cherry juice by the ton , some tartness & woody notes t : cherry juice with some booze warmth & not much else up front , maybe a touch of tartness .  this was the first belgian i ever had . it has a very creamy smoothness that i really love . finishes long and dry with more fruityness .

aroma is malty and estery , nothing to write home about .  orange in color and cloudy . a pretty color to be sure but otherwise not outstanding . lots of sediment in the bottle , so pour carefully .  the feeling is very nice , sticky and big , but not viscous and syrupy . really nice in that aspect . the carbonation was lively and enjoyable , made this one easy to drink .

the smell was earthy and of tart fruits .  this pours out as a red-hued amber color with good carbonation that creates a scattered , bubbly head that dissipated pretty fast .  the mouthfeel is full and warming , in fact , this beer is a huge belly warmer .

the smell is quite pleasant , kind of like a forest with a lot of wet leaves on the ground .  there was absolutely no head or carbonation and even a vigorous pour resulted only in some air bubbles on top .  m - medium body and low carbonation , so incredibly smooth . perfect mouthfeel .

the aroma is very weak . actually , i ca n't get any aroma , even with a big swirl .  served on a tulip glass . a - hazy straw to pale gold pour , unremarkable head , short retention , fair surface ring and some lacing .  super creamy mouthfeel , medium body and carbonation level .

s : somewhat subdued citrus & pine hops with a caramel sweetness . t : really well balanced and drinkable .  i have experienced a bad batch of this brew , which was cloudy , and `` off '' in flavor . not quite translucent , which is not a negative , imho . nice white head .  wonderfully smooth mouthfeel , but not much of anything else that would make this beer standout .

aroma - not much of aroma . taste - cola and lightly fruity flavors . nothing amazing , but nothing to be shy about .  part of a taster flight , about a 5oz pour to a funkwerks tulip . pours a nice medium yellow with only a hint of haze , small white head that dissipates fairly quickly and no lacing .  but what might be the true feats here are , on the one hand , the quality and sock of the flavors given the abv , and the insanely creamy mouthfeel on the other .

s= huge spices like a fruitcake , or maybe like a spiced vanilla tea . the lovely scents simply do n't follow through in the taste .  a refreshing light-bodied ale that goes down easy a- very clear amber-yellow with thin , big-bubbled head s- smells a bit like honey along with a bottle/metal hint .  t : the taste was about average for a stout , almost identical in flavor to guinness m : amazing mouthfeel , so creamy and so smooth .

it smelled of cheap beer , like grain and alcohol , with a bit of sourness .  pours a one finger yellow-tan head over a cloudy light-gold liquid . this beer is quite drinkable , the glass is already half gone already . really nice lacing on the inside of the glass . i had a glass of this on tap at the brewery and it was very much like this from a bottle .  mouthfeel : amazing . creamy and smooth , thick .

really quite pale - barely gold . mild grainy aroma with a mild yeast quality . drinking while cold i think kept off any excessive taste from adjuncts .  i 've had plenty of these in my day , but this is the first i 've actually sat down with to review ... a - pours a slightly cloudy , orangish copper color , a little darker than alot of ipas . head grows to about 1 inch before settling down to a thin outer layer .  m : wow ! just so damn smooth .

assertive citrus aroma features plenty of orange , backed by pine .  a- poured a amberish coppery orange color if that makes sense . one finger off white head that shows light retention .  rich roasty chocalaty with a fabulous creamy mouthfeel . mouth again is just amazing . another great brew by troegs .

my sense of smell is not the greatest so do n't want to bash it on this but the smell is not strong enough for me to really pick out much , just a pleasant grassy aroma . mouthfeel is very good with quite a lot of carbonation [ or so i thought ] followed by quite a solid hops kick and lingerng bitter aftertaste . is actually very hoppy for what is meant to be a english style pale ale , which i have often found quite subdued . this really is a nice enjoyable beer , admitedly it cost about as a imported english pale ale & i do think they have played with the style a little to make it this bitter but very nice indeed .  pours a clear orange with a two fingers worth of fluffy head that subsided quickly . a good bit of lacing down the glass . this is a highly drinkable beer that masks the alcohol well .  bitter black chocolate moves into the woodiness and finishes boozy m- creamy , full-bodied , coats the mouth and boozy heat d- really impressed with this one .

smell : a surprisingly faint aroma , which was somewhat of a turnoff since i love the big malty aroma of doppelbocks .  the body of the liquid was hazy , but i would hesitate to call it cloudy . as the head subsided , it left a very sticky lacing on the edges of the glass that looked like bar soap froth on a wash cloth . average for the style , but nice never-the-less .  mouthfeel is exceptional . very smooth , great carbonation , but not enough to distract from the flavors going on .

real nice looking here . very dirty and manure like smelling . this is kind of unexpected . overall nose seems slightly off putting , but the taste more than makes up for it .  a : it pours a bright orange color with a finger of white head that does n't last and does n't lace very well either .  the mouthfeel , though , was the best part . it fills your mouth with mousse like consistency with very round edges .

s : notes of bubblegum , a bit of pepper , and a hint of orange , very faint smelling beer . t : starts out like it smells with a bit of a sweet bubblegum flavor with a bit of a sharp pepper but then does a 180 and has a bit of a dry/bitter hop taste , it 's not too strong but it 's definitely there .  poured pretty dark for an ipa , kind of an ice tea brown , but there are some other darker ipas out there where that fact is considered part of their novelty . 1 '' head gradually dissipated to lace .  complexity is not disturbed by the great thick airy body . thick enough that the high carbonation appears just smooth and creamy . it feels like theyve brewed it with oatmeal .

this beer is faintly ripe with doppelbock scents of caramel , mixed dark and roasted malt , heated figs , and an end hint of port wine . smell is the weak point of maximator , but only because all its components are so weakly displayed .  6 % abv 45 ibu a : straw-red in color with a good amount of haze . there is a decent off-white head that floats atop this brew .  great mouthfeel and is smooth on the palate with a hoppy bitterness that lasts forever .

the smell is very mild with a bit of toasted bready malt coming through . while the smell was a bit small the flavor is the opposite , very big . huge fruity malts up front with a bit of sweet apricots and a touch of raisins , toasted malt and bread qualities linger as a strong juniper and grapefruit bitterness take over and linger on the tongue .  12 oz bottle , bottled 06/18/08 a : deep black under a small tan head . no lace , no retention .  wonderful full mouthfeel .

i am a hophead and i might as well have ordered a lite beer . no hoppiness at all- very bitter and a poor lingering aftertaste .  ) poured into a pint glass a : pours golden pale orange with less than a finger of thin white head . not great retention .  the feel is awesome . maybe it is the milk sugar , but something gives it an icy , silky feel that is wonderful . overall good , a beer that i would have one of on occasion .

aroma of burnt toffee - more like a brown ale to me . very tasty , hop flavor mixes well with the roasty , chewy grains . no yeast trub in this bottle .  pours a pale , clear , gold/yellow with almost zero head .  it seemed to just coat my whole mouth on its way down .

excellent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with rings , streaks and splotches of soapy lacing . earthy hop aroma with hints of soil and pine needle as well as some faint fruit character and a prominent malt backbone . there 's some faint pineapple and grapefruit in the nose but the hop profile mostly gives off an earthy scent .  a slight head forms which is bone white , but quickly fades to nothing .  has that totally coating feel like a warm thick cask draught , just almost oily in its feel and velvety ( aside from the alcohol ) . really like this about this beer .

s-yeasty , wheaty aromas , slight citrus with minimal phenols .  this bottle pours a hazy amber with little head . carbonation is a bit low , and it 's not the prettiest beer in the world .  m : incredibly creamy leaving a nice coating around the mouth that tingles slightly .
smell : yeasty . maybe some very mellow goldings or fuggles .  a - poured out a somewhat cloudy , copper color with a small , tan head that left no lace .  very full and creamy mouth . damn tasty .

s - slightly sour and horsey on the nose , somewhat saison-esque , with a brighter malt/hop aroma in the background .  appearance : burgundy amber orange body , clear as a sunrise with a sad , fizzy beige head that hardly lasts long enough even to describe it .  mouthfeel is truly wonderful , with a heavy , syrupy feel mixed in with a light tingle from some hidden carbonation and the alcohol itself .

s - i am hard pressed to find much in the nose beyond a light , pleasant flowery hop . very good beer , though i feel the appearance and aroma are weak for a bspa .  somewhat cloudy yellow-orange with a small white head .  very smooth and full bodied mouthfeel , with medium carbonation .

s - sweet raspberry , cherries and candied sugars . t - very sweet , like a slightly sour cherry soda , there is a bit of raspberry and light malt .  received one fat finger of head that quickly faded . brownish copper colored body was clear .  the mouthfeel as mentioned earlier , is very thick and creamy . very little carbonation .

what i liked most was that it was well balanced and not a hop bomb in my opinion . i love sierra nevada pale ale and i think fans of that will like this too if not more . very drinkable and probably could go through quite a bit on a warm sunny day .  2009 375ml bottle a : pours a murky chestnut brown with amber highlights near the edges . bottle gave a muted `` pop '' but not going on with the bubblies ; does n't offer more than a ring and a few swirls of carmel-colored head .  first gulp of this was outstanding.. nice creamy , mouthfeel to it that just bombards your mouth with sweet , delicious beer flavor .

another head scratcher ... .a wheat beer made with oven roasted beets ? a-gorgeous , brilliant red copper with a medium white head that hangs on and leaves nice lace .  currant jam . appearance : very hazy orange-copper . minimal head with some lacing .  the mouthfeel was exquisite . tiny bubbles caress , going a little foamy , opening the flavor as it hits the back of your mouth .

my first instinct was that the aroma was very faint ; but as i adjusted , the roasted malts smell followed by a yeasty , brown bread and caramel odors .  dense two finger head shows good retention but weak lacing .  mouthfeel- the texture of this beer in the mouth is stunning and absolutely *perfect* .

it has a nice colour and can easily be consumed on mass while watching either the maple leafs of the blue jays . i find that creemore does not have the best aroma and infact it greatly detracts from the flavour .  a - the low , poorly retained off-white head is disappointing as is the hazy golden yellow color .  m : nice light body on it with mild carbonation , which was perfect for this style of ale .

the aroma was the typical malty smell of a brown ale .  pours clear golden with a thin white head . the appearance is not much to write about .  this is one of the thickest beers i 've had . very heavy and smooth mouthfeel .

aroma : very complex . banana , clove , butter , bubblegum , and hints of alcohol .  this beer tastes like bacon if bacon = good and beer = good and this beer = bacon then for you , the beer = good if you do n't like bacon , do not get this beer .  mouth is very crisp and finishes clean , excellent carbonation . leaves a nice tingling on the tongue . drink is very good i usually would n't want an ipa for a session beer but this one i definetly would have a few more for the evening .

some thick lacing towards the top s : nose is probably the weakest part of this beer . not much too it ; some roasted oat and malt t : ah yes , the beer i remember . very flavorful and easy drinking .  cloudy , obviously , but golden amber color with a modest white head that left a ring pretty quickly .  excellent balance and mouthfeel , could be a great session beer .

the smell is that of a traditional lager with a little roasted malt to it .  it really reminds me of swamp water with little head to speak of .  exactly how i like my stouts to feel -- heavy and chewy .

smell is a little flat ... some burnt caramel and a little bit of orange citrus . taste is off the rocker , though ... this is basically dogfish head 90 minute without the bitterness .  either way this is a solid , if not spectacular , example of the style . slightly hazy and mild amber in color you can almost see the hops coming .  the mouthfeel is dry with a long and deep finish which is full of blackened malt and char . very very nice .

it did n't smell like much , which is dissapointing . i look forward to the roasted and hoppy aroma of russian stouts , but this one did n't come through very well .  pretty much the definitiion for an amber ale . poured at about the right temperature for a small to medium , light tan head that soon settled out .  ideal texture for an ipa .

a 1.5in foamy head builds as i pour-swish-pour-swish-pour my way through the last 4 ozs . lots of cloves and bread in the nose , but just as dominant is the smell of bier . perhaps a bit of citrus as well . the first few pulls are sublime , with big mouthfeel and a wonderful orange citrus mid palate .  bottleshare from darthkostrizer with bhobs and alucard4 pours a hazy reddish brown with a very quick dissipating bubbly head .  the way this tastes is absolutely nothing like the way it smells ... m - full , pleasing mouthfeel . the best part of this beer .
smell is weak , thankfully the taste is not .  bottle part of mixed 12-pack . has pale yellow color .  the mouthfeel is silky smooth and really rounds the beer out nicely .

smell has only a touch more cocoa and sweetness to it , still a disappointment as far as aroma . taste is milder and smoother , warmer and more rounded , softer , not quite as sharp with light roasty malts and bit more dryish chocolate and cocoa , some notes of nuttyness appear in there .  a straw-colored pilsner that pours with an initial frothiness that falls quickly leaving a little bit of lace .  they served it properly too - the temperature was perfect ( not co cold ) . pretty close to perfect .

tried to hold it up to some light , and managed to spill ( experimental error , or general incompetance ) i 'm finding it a little weak in the nose , generally unexpressive . solid dark roast , a little espresso , perhaps a little sarsaparilla . tastes deep , heavy , and satisfying .  i got just a little head in my chalice , and what i got did n't stay long .  the palate is delightfully smooth and creamy . overall , this is an outstanding dipa that is sure to fill anyones hop fix for the evening .

the aroma was subtle and i tried to pick up the smokiness but really could n't . mostly it smelled like a pale ale just not as hoppy and citrusy.the beer has a nice velvety mouthfeel but was a lot crisper than i thought it would be .  i heard such great things about this beer that i figured i should enjoy my first from the can . smooth ; very good for the summer . best canned beer i have ever had ( the rumors were true ) . recommended if you want a stronger pale ale for a backyard cook out , or a few beers doing house work .  perfect creamy mouthfeel .
s : typical lambic funky smell .  pretty much no lacing .  light carbonation , rich smooth mouthcoating sensation from the oatmeal .

s : toasted bread and grain , not as much caramel as the appearance might suggest , with some faint tangerine citrus occasionally emerging .  pours a very cloudy yellow with a very small white head that disapears to a thin white line immediatly .  mouthfeel was awesome . farily prickly carbonation with some slight drying on the finish due to the barrel aging .

smell : boozey , toasty malts . uh oh.. `` dirty nickels '' .. but not that much.. lets hope we dont taste them .  a - a quick-dissolving tan foam settles to ... nothing . lightly hazed dark ruby-brown body .  awesome mouthfeel .

smell : has a bit of a roasted malt smell , similar to a coffee smell , but it 's a little bland . almost watered down in smell .  pours with a black body topped by a thick , fizzy , quickly disappearing brown head with little lacing .  great mouthfeel .

s - not what i anticipated . lots and lots of booze along with some sweet malt characteristics . the hops i do smell are only a tad floral . t - as much as i wanted to throw this one away after smelling it , i took one drink and it was amazing . a huge beer , malty and bready and hoppy and piney and fruity at the same time .  dark brown but not black like i was expecting . decent one finger head that leaves quickly smells of rich chinook hops and a sugary malt sweetness .  m : one of the fullest and creamiest dipas i 've ever had .

s - muted floral notes , a certain meaty quality , and some of the malt is coming out in the nose - hints of nut and bread .  copper-orange pour with a small off-white head .  m-medium carbonation with a great creamy finish d-hmm i actually like this a lot ... .i 'm very confused by the other peoples ' reviews ... the taste is n't too complex but its otherwise a great drink .

probably our favorite beer from calgary beer fest 2009 so i may be a little biased . honestly 1 good looking ipa ... hazy copper color , excellent head with good retnetion and huge webs of lacing to boot . ahhh ... the let down ... as in aipa i have come to ecpect a bit more in the nasal dept . this offering certainly score on a nice balance between hop and sweet malt ... but does n't knock my socks off ... if it were an eipa i 'd score it higher . carbonation level is almost perfect ... allows all the flavours to come trhu without any fizzy bite . very drinkable and is now my goto ipa  poured from the bottle into a pint glass a - pours a dark copper with virtually no head . perhaps that explains the lackluster head ...  mouthfeel is superb . great level of spice , perfect carbonation , medium body .

s : smells hoppy , nothing special going on really . some citrus .  this is actually a very drinkable beer . it 's called a pale ale but it 's much drier with a lot less malt feel . the beer is a great , low-alcohol , hot weather alternative to a good lager or pilsner . the character is somewhere between a kolsch and an extra pale ale or even a bitter .  a nice chewy , creamy malt backbone makes each sip a pleasure .

it had a mild malty aroma with good lacing and a very smooth palate .  darkish amber in colour with a persistent head , albeit it quite thin in texture .  unbelievably smooth in mouthfeel - bittersweet chocolate and bitter roasted notes played effortlessly on your tongue .

a very faint smell , hard to put a nose on it but there 's some sweetness there .  it looks like a black colored ale . it doesnt look amazing who cares , inviting enough .  first sip reveals a smooth silky textured beer with a fairly thick body and gentle rolling carbonation . there is a sticky sweet residue on my lips after each sip and the boozy warmth lingers as well . the booze factor makes this a sipper and it is a little sweet and boozy to drink a full bomber .

n : lemon peel , citrus and some kiwi ( ? ) with some sweet malt smells . hops come and go in the aroma , knocked out a bit from the orange and coriander .  it poured opaque black , nearly zero foam .  great mouthfeel .

smell here is n't of really much . perhaps a bit of creaminess . it 's just kind of `` beery '' . an easy drinker ... at this low abv , you could drink these seemingly all day .  my pour created a finger of tawny head with decent retention . color was a slightly hazy orangish-amber .  mouthfeel was full and rich . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .

the aroma is coffeeish , bitter . this beer is a pretty masterful beer of the style , but it 's not quite exceptional ( for a stout ) . considering the fact there was as much flavor left as there was , this would probably be a beautiful beer if drawn from a cask with a handpump .  served in a flute . transparent amber-brown body with visible bubbles streams . no cap , lace , etc .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is full bodied with low carbonation , and oh so smooth .

almost no aroma , though the floral hops and lotus flowers do come through .  the color is very very dark brown , and a bit murky .  m : thin to medium viscosity , simultaneously wet and creamy on the palate developing into a sublime smoothness , with moderate carbonation that keeps the texture from becoming heavy or lifeless .

a translucent orange body , sorta lie copper or a slightly lighter orange blossom honey . a solid malty body , chewy and a bit hoppy , hell of a lot better than the nose . this is a solid english pale ale , solid body of hops and malts , nothing to let you down initial taste is a bit bitter with mostly malts .  slight film persists , but no real head retention or lacing s : sour & oaky notes t : sweet cherry , then sourness , oaky dryness & small hint of vanilla up front .  mouthfeel is damn near perfect for an o'fest , i think . impeccable balance .

the aroma is composed of citrus and yeast . i detect the slight prenence of hops in the aroma . the flavor is slight on the front of the tongue , but the hops are prevelent on the back of the tongue .  pours a straw yellow from a 12oz bottle to a standard pint glass . dissipating to a half finger head with good lacing .  some of the best damn mouthfeel you will ever get in a beer too .

the first versions were too heavy on the holiday spices and every year it seems to become more and more balanced . the smell is average , relative to a xmas style beer , which are usually loaded with spice and citrus . only the slightest hint of orange comes off the beer . the taste is excellent though . the spices and fruit are at a perfect balance with the malts and hops .  i was dissapointed with the appearance . when poured it did'nt reveal any type of head or lacing .  the mouthfeel is velvety and thick .

the aroma does n't seem so bad ; perhaps even pleasant - prairie grass , damp pollen , clean grains and hints of mild spice . there 's a lemon grass element as well , but i 'm concerned the lemon smells too ... pungent . yuck .  appearance : very effervescent . poured a absolutely clear golden yellow , very small off white head .  feel : low carbonation , medium body that is extremely smooth for so low abv , very nice drying finish .
s : aroma is reserved , with hints of dried fruit and spice . t : dried fruit , bananas , cloves , and ginger are well balanced .  great retention and poor lacing .  excellent in the mouth .

i think if i were to drink this out of a regular pint the aroma would have come off better . t : again chocolate and coffee .  pale gold and crystal clear . modest white head ( about one finger ) that becomes a thin film and then a ring . lacing is minor perhaps due to glass washed in the dishwasher . a perfect easy drinking summer pils .  body is n't the first thing you notice , but once the distraction of the sour wears off , you realize this brew is very smooth , neither tacky nor sticky , nor drying . carbonation can be swirled up , and compliments the feel of the sour in your cheeks quite well . all in all , a crazy departure from the normal dfh offerings and dang fine weissen .

the smell is faint spices , notably cinnamon .  on tap @ the brewery 03-26-09 pours a light hazy yellow , my friend ordered hefeweizen and i actually thought it was the dipa based on appearance .  deliciously smooth . coating the entire mouth with a lasting finish .

smell was zesty , definite hints of citrus and wheat .  tomos watkin osb pours a deep amber with just barely off-white two-finger foamy head .  m= smooth and crisp . feels resinous as well which is great for an ipa . d= super drinkable .

the aroma is very deep -- anise , fennel , mocha , coffee and a burning alcohol nose -- awesome . really a marvel . strange .  there is very little head on this beer ; the head leaves rather quickly .  the finish lingers for a while , almost spicy with a slight alcohol burn m - pretty ideal for this style i thought .

looks great , clear burnt orange/ harvest orange color that has hints of brown . smells has some vague fruity esters , lemons , a hint of pepper , almost a hint of tea leaves . upon re-drinking i can gladly up the score a bit but still feel there are better saisons out there .  pours a reddish amber with a quickly fleeting rocky off white head .  mouthfeel is smooth and creamy , with a lighter body , almost cask like .

the aroma is very enticing ... it 's fruity and easily smelled from afar..thankfully this is not overloaded with cinnamon as was my fear ... instead , there is a rich perfumy sourness of rotting apples , musty basement and faint tobacco . very nice , and not tainted with fusels as i have noted in ron 's prior entries .  nice head and golden beercolor with big particles in the beer . nose is strange for a white ; bretty , hoppy and sourness giving this brew a unfamiliar witbier nose .  m- full bodied and creamy . very smooth and silky in the mouth . full bodied but not heavy .

the aroma is of muted hops and barley . there is n't really much going on in the nose . after smelling this beer i thought it would be rather bland but the flavors pop off the tongue . i would n't call any 8.7 % alcohol beer extremely drinkable , but this is exceptional .  poured into a tulip glass . dark opaque effervescing with a slight reddish hue .  mouthfeel is amazing on this one .

the aroma was light as only some malts were detectable . overall a very nice brew that was very flavorful but not overwhelming for the food .  to say the least , this is a monster beer , a complete monster . loaded with vanilla , chocolate , figs , prunes..etc . a dark , opaque beer , with little head ( only drawback ) .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and smooth . an excellent feel .

the nose was surprisingly subtle ; could n't pick up much besides a distant chocolate and tartness .  poured slightly chilled in flared glass a : no head , decent beads , clear mead color s : honey , persistent smell of honeysuckle t : light ale , very floral , very complex ; lots of honey , lavender ; it 's like drinking a fancy handsoap ( meant to be a compliment ) ; buttery undertone ; ok , let 's call it soapy , but i think this flavor profile calls for that .  silky , creamy , and perfectly textured , this mouthfeel ca n't be beat .

original rating date : august 30 , 2008 pours an enticing dark gold , smells of a bit of hops but not as much as i expected , relatively weak on the nose which surprises me as most iipas i 've tried have a great nose . looking down the ratings already here , it seems like i 'm the only one who will score this weak on aroma- maybe my nose is too stuffed ? i want to give this a higher rating but the nose just was n't there for me . either way , excellent iipa , a far better effort than lagunitas ' regular ipa .  it poured clear until i hit the yeast at the bottom of the bottle - thus , a hazy auburn body topped by a very thin off-white head that drops almost immediately .  mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and creamy - almost reminded me of a nearly flat ginger ale , with more depth/body .
the smell has some peach aromas to it , but it 's much lighter than i expected .  there was very little head to speak of even with a vigorous pour .  m - smooth as silk .

aroma is amazing ... whisky , vanilla , smooth smoke , chocolate , big roasted notes and some oak . taste was a bit of a let down after the wonderful aroma . i picked up a lot of sweet chocolate , some booze , big on the bourbon flavor . this was a rare treat to enjoy i am very happy i had the chance .  i would prefer the appearance to be a little more hazy & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; but this stuff comes from germany so i guess these guys know good beer & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; the smell is reminiscent of banana i do n't get too much clove to it & gt ; & gt ; i also ge an earthy smell too & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; it tastes just like it smells & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; very easy to drink & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; watery mouthfeel not my favorite beer style but excellently true to style !  body is full but not heavy and has a great creamy smoothness . almost feels like an oatmeal stout .

malt scent with a feint fruitiness to it .  there was no lace .  this is so creamy and not too carbonated , its just enough to get both senses of substantial and refreshing . quite thick , not so much as syrup but a few steps under . one please , fills the stomach nicely , not too harsh on the throat or stomach . it has a nice balance between warmth and coolness in the stomach .

it also has a nice , scotchy aroma , appropriate to the style .  appearance was a bit light in color and with less head than i would 've expected , but you do n't taste with your eyes , so i 'm willing to forgive that this beer is not terribly photogenic .  this beer is on the lighter side of medium-bodied beers and boasts an exceptionally pleasant mouthfeel . carbonation is perfectly balanced , i could n't imagine any improvement here .

smells quite refreshing . t : fruit continues to be up front at first , followed by a touch of sweet malts and some wheat . o : this beer smelled delicious , and after enjoying their spring offering , i had high hopes .  appearance : pours an opaque bronze with a thin bubbly head that quickly disappears smell : a strong burst of malt and a bit of hops on the finish taste : toasted malt dominates , but there is a subtle spicy finish not apparent in the aroma .  body is full but not cloying . exceptional silky velvet mouthfeel that is full-bodied yet providing a smooth viscosity .

smell : not much , some yeast , some fruit taste : nice cherry flavour , not overly sweet by anymeans . mouthfeel : starts creamy and thick but finishes crisp with the carbonation coming in on the finish dinkability : quite good , i could certainly have more than one .  a- amber- orange with minimal head , but good retention of what head it has ... slightly cloudy ( chill haze ? ) not super-pretty .  m : creamy and delicious . everything is dead on here .

smell is a little off out of the bottle - a bit glassy , but the mouthfeel and drinkability are high .  the appearence was ok , looks just like everyother beer i have seen before .  excellent for it 's style .

s : extremely sweet candy aroma that overpowers any belgian yeast character that may be present . no hop aroma , not much nuance .  poured from 12oz bottle into 20oz brooklyn brewery branded tulip pint glass . appearance : dark cola color with a small tan head that dissipates quickly and leaves a ring of lace .  smooth grit with comfort .

aroma is very muted . i had a hard time picking anything up at all . unique , and very enjoyable .  it looks pretty much just like an ordinary old dark beer . its really really black , the head that rises with a pour is small and off white , there is really no retention at all , no lacing .  the mouthfeel was very very thick and creamy and not as thin as say a sierra nevada .

huh . ok , big punch in the mouth for flavor . lovely beer .  otter creek turns out some very drinkable beers , but often the brewery has been short on experimentation . unexpected notes of grapefruit and light burnt sugar open the nostrils . the taste is richly satisfying yet not overpowering , with a good balance of malt and hops . mouthfeel is quite good - in this case , a little bubbly , a little syrupy - and in all this is a beer one could drink at length .  amazingly smooth going down ; full bodied with light carbonation .

unfortunately the aroma is not so good . very weak and faint with only subtle leafy hops .  pours a light amber color with ruby low lights , a small puffy head , some clingy lacing and a moderate amount of visible carbonation .  nice touch of bitterness lingers as i contemplate the rich , full mouth feel . nice beer , much more approachable than the expedition .

s- not much happening here . a little hoppy , a little sweet . pretty balanced , leans more toward hops . the hops used taste a little different from other apa 's and ipa 's i 've tasted . d- because of the clean and crisp hops , i could drink it all day . it 's not the best out there , but is pretty good and worth trying .  dusky brown appearance , with ruby highlights at the edges , very slim and soon gone head , nothing to speak of .  mouthfeel : on the heavy side of the medium-bodied scale and creamy smooth .

light-medium carbonation . medium bodied . starts and finishes sweet this could be mistaken for a belgian . the high abv ( 9 % ) is not really noticeable . pricey - $ 4.50 for a 330ml bottle from wine society tyngsboro , ma .  a clear light orange with a dense yet soft off-white head with good retention , there 's also not much lacing present . decent in appearance , this is also quite enjoyable on the nose .  m- full , smooth mouthfeel .

s - mild chocolate aroma .  recieved this bottle froma friend at ab in st. louis . not a test bottle , but , a production bottle . a : milky brown , tan puffy head . nice lacing .  moutfeel : probably the best part of this beer is the mouthfeel . thick and sugary , with a ton of creaminess to start . a crisp , drying effect then takes over your throat and palate upon swallowing . then you are left with an alcohol bite that is both satisfying and warming .

no faults here ... s : citrus , roasted malt , cocoa , and chocolate malt . all very light aromas . t : acidic darker and roasted malt , the same cocoa as detected in the smell is present here as well .  this beer pours a clear tawny color . the head is half an inch in height , and recedes quickly into a thin cap of lacing .  s : smells like sweet malt , spices that i ca n't pick out , some red/dark fruits , vanilla t : tastes just like the smell with more vanilla and even bourbon but in a mellow way , like a fruity , sweet , light bourbon..some alcohol flavor too m : very full bodied , almost to the point of creamy d : highly drinkable for the flavor but less so for the alcohol kick

not a ton of aroma , some carmel notes there though .  appearance : hazy and somewhat cloudy yellow ... a decent head .  very nice feel in the mouth -- rich , thick , tingling bubbles , kind of evaporates on the tongue . medium-heavy body , quite a bit of honey , i get this apple quality .

rich malt lacing . drawback : only subtle hints of malt in the aroma , but with the quaff came a load of malts and an earthy , spicy finish .  a : dark orangish amber with a tannish hue . not much head to speak of and minimal lacing .  mouthfeel is full and rich , easy to sip and enjoy . sweetness hinders the drinkability a bit , one bottle at a time is enough for me .

smell is hops and very very little floral notes .  it pours pale , cloudy gold with a thin near-white head that really does n't hang around to party .  mouthfeel is perfect - smooth and velvety without being clingy or cloying .

smells mostly of sweet malt , with some fruit and wine-like oak . very nice complexity where the malt sweetness starts off , followed by fruit and some spices , then it has a crisp finish that 's malty and tails off with some more malt that 's roasted , delicious and dry . an overall great beer that is belgian in style and complexity , even though it 's a french beer ; clearly the belgian influence has dominated the taste of this beer , which i am thankful for .  a : muddy brown with limited tan head that quickly fades but leaves lace on he edge .  thick and creamy . everything i look for in an imperial stout . light carbonation .

very straight up pale lager smell , it does supply some decent scents of fruit and bread . much more flavorful than expected !  pours a bright , clear straw sunshine yellow . very quick , spongey head and one string of bubbles .  the mouthfeel was phenomenal . to have a cask conditioned beer is such a treat , and i 'm glad my neighborhood bar always has one beer on cask .

great lacing & head retention s : musty grain , herbal & woody hops t : follows the nose , rye peppery notes & crispness , plus a whisper of smoke & some grassy hops climbing up as well up front .  poured into a tulip . a soapy copper tinged head starts out very strong , but recedes to a ring at the beer 's edge fairly quickly .  m : the feel is excellent with fine carbonation lending a creaminess that is top-tier and a clean scrubbing finish with the right balance of crispness and aftertaste . d : an fine tripel with classic light fruit flavors mixed artfully with pepper and spice and a top-notch mouthfeel compose a very good brew .

very bitter citrus smell . sweet to the taste .  on tap and enjoyed at steve 's birthday bash , snifter : a- coppery red with a small head and spotty lace .  very nice rich and creamy full body on this one , super smooth on the palate .

some sweetish caramel malt . not much else in the nose but what 's there is tasty . overall it is very good .  pours a nice cloudy yellow as expected but this taste of it is just .  m : very soft carbonation and easy on the palate as a good session beer should be .

s awesome whiff of freshly brewed coffee and oats . bits of chocolate are also pleasing on the nose , as this is very simple but rather enjoyable . burnt roasts add to this smooth and creamy mixture of scents .  a - pours a very mirky yellow/orange color , small head that vanishes , no lace , cap , or retention .  m : so good i ca n't get enough . nice thickness with light carbonation and a good oily texture make this a delightful treat for my mouth .

pours a light brown with a reddish tint , it dosnt have much of a scent to it except for a slight cirtus .  of all of the seasonal brews the guys at cbc put out , this is by far their standout . simply put : this is an excellent beer out of the tap , but only average out of the bottle . it 's never given # 1 billing - this is not a perfect beer by any stretch - but it is an incredibly drinkable beer , especially on a warm spring day near a college campus if you know what i mean .  in addition , there are hop oils , caramel , some sweetness and perhaps molasses along with a medium body that is oh so smooth and coats the mouth well . delicious and well balanced .
the smell is hops , almost bitter , and faint malt .  could n't get a head going on it . no lacing . dark brown in color .  bear republic really , really nailed the mouthfeel on this one .

the smell does nothing for the beer , it is very light , made me not expect much from this beer .  bottle w/ some bad ass artwork on the label ( i love flying dog 's illustrations ) cloudy golden color w/ a very thin head that quickly dissappeared to nothing , no lacing to speak of .  the feel is very silky .

not much on the nose here , just an openness that has some light roasty tones and dryness to it . some small phenol and sweet notes sneak in as it warms . easy , clean feel , medium bodied , nice mild little sweetness and roasty tone . not much for the nose but it makes up for it with a nice , easy going pace with flavors and body .  on to the beer : there was no head on this beer when i received it in my tulip . the color is chocolate brown wih hues of caramel orange . very lightly carbonated , and no , this was n't from the infamous bottles of the 2008 vintage , but a keg ( sorry , do n't know what vintage ) .  i really this the mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .

n = some hints of alcohol , skunk , fruit , but not a good indication of the taste .  a : dark orange , very translucent . you can see that it 's quite fizzy . layer of golden foam quickly dissipates .  really wonderful . the mouthfeel is the most impressive and outstanding attribute of this beer .

aroma is very light , and consists mainly of citrus and light hops .  mmmm ... the appearance is n't anything abnormal/fantastic/special or anything else to write home about ... it looks like an ipa .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel .

no aroma to speak of , which is unfortunate , because it would complement the interesting flavors . somewhat malty , but this is obscured by the many flavors rolling around - sweet pear and apple , a bit of butterscotch , with gentle hops riding beneath .  a- dark amber with large off-white head that slowly dissipates to nothing .  mouthfeel is thick with smooth and creamy carbonation .

smell mildly sweet with a slight hop skunkness .  it looks much like a standard macro-brewers lager but the similarity ends there .  smooth and creamy , very soft carbonation . booze is extremely well hidden .

very clean aroma and taste , classic sammy smith . the complex grain profile makes it so delicious .  bottle a pale golden , yellowish straw color . aggressive pour yielded little head , but decent carbonation and some nice sediment .  medium bodied but carbonation is bright and exciting , reminiscent of deschutes ' black butte porter , very refreshing . ca n't say enough about how great the mouthfeel deschutes puts out on some of their beers , red chair fits that bill .

lacing got more impressive as the glass emptied . i quite enjoyed this beer and found it more interesting than the leffe blonde ; my only criticism might be that it 's a bit too rich at times , but that 's a minor distraction . my preferred leffe right now .  paid $ 15 even for the midwest taster ... the appearence was a cola colored base with a nice tannish head , minimal retention and no real lacing .  the mouthfeel is dead-on creamy .

smells mostly of citrus and light malt . floral notes . nothing too prominent .  poured a hazy straw color with 3 fingers of off-white head . average head retention & lacing s : slight straw with grassy & lemon notes t : lemon & orange hops up front .  m : thick and rich , with a nice amount of fine , late-developing carbonation . perfect for such a big beer .

i live in north carolina and love to get my hands on beer from my area back home . the smell is just fairly subtile but hinted of almost friuty . overall a very decent beer .  12oz bottle , no date , in sa glass a : black with a one finger tan head that goes to ring rather quick s : roasted malts , espresso , oats and a little chocolate t : coffee , faintly bitter chocolate like bakers m : full body , little carbonation quite creamy d : enjoyable could have more than one .  it 's definitely thick , but it does n't feel anywhere near as syrupy as it looks . o : this beer has a great appearance and mouthfeel .

s - nothing particularly special here , but what is most noticible is that there is no overpowering smell of alcohol ; just a bit of hops or some sort of plant material , let 's say it has a slight 'grassiness ' to it . aside from that there is a distinct fruitiness to the aroma which is most enticing , though mostly through its lissome appearance . nothing really jumps out at me for this beer ; though i must say the frutiness stays with me with an added dimension of spice .  pours a golden yellow with very little head .  m - medium bodied really smooth with perfect carbonation .
body is not heavy , smell is no special event . try it .  a- straw with some haze .  extremely satisfying in this regard .

rather subdued smells of hops and citrus and i 'm getting a bigger than expected malt .  pours a dark clear gold with a 1 inch foamy light brown head that fades to nothing . no lacing on this one .  full bodied , heavy on the palate and full of flavor . i love it .

a - clear , ruby red , aggressive poor produces no lacing s - not a lot going on here , maybe some figs or plums and vanilla or caramel t - wonderfully subdued representation of the same aromas in the nose m - very smooth and creamy with just enough carbonation for a clean finish d - impressive for 10 % .  poured into a snifter , with a half inch head that all but disappears in seconds . very dark , mostly opaque body , a shade browner than black , with a touch of red at the edges when held to light .  mouthfeel is big full and smooth very rich and easy drinking with a really satisfing warming in the gut .

i couldnt detect much aroma , but the flavor was a tasty mix of vanilla with a hint of malty chocolate .  pours a hazy mud brown with little to no head .  this has been sitting in the cellar for about a year and i am convinced it has the absolute perfect mouthfeel .

s : i smelled hops and some sweetness maybe from cinnamon , that 's about it . d : it is a great christmas ale .  pours a clear orange with a 1 inch white head that fades to an oily film .  m : the mouthfeel is delightful . fairly thick for an ipa , almost creamy with mild carbonation .

aroma is the only thing that falls a bit short here as the hops are in the back somewhere . the aroma does have a touch of burnt caramels which is coming through from the rye . nice job on this one , just missing a little on the aroma end for what i was expecting .  poured a hazy orange/dark peach color , providing not much of a head and leaving behind hardly any lacing to speak of .  perfect carbonation .

and now these famous waters are again being put to good use as the principle ingredient in local ales . spartesian is a soft , summer ale . it is exceptionally pale in a dramatic hue of sun-yellow . fortunately , my tastes stray far from `` timid '' and i was able to settle in to a satisfying appreciation of this very pale beer . it has low co2 , no smell , little forward hop flavor , and a vivid lemon color . but the smooth body makes it an easy drinker on a summer 's day and i was left wondering if that billowy mouthfeel was attributable to olympia 's famous artesian well water .  poured from a 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass . a : not-quite-black dark brown with a tiny wisp of a tan head that materializes with some delay but does n't stick around long and leaves a few dots of lace . the lack of head made me wonder about packaging issues , although the flavor was excellent .  ( m ) mouthfeel is perfect for this beer .

s : grainy malt , not too exciting . t : creamy smooth malt with bitter hops . o : well , you 'll get what you pay for , and this one came cheap .  pours a less than clear reddish brown . head only lasts a fleeting moment with no lacing to speak of .  mf - perfect ! soft carb .

the nose had some malt , and a light note of candy .  i 've had the bottle , and there is some weird floaters in there , but they did n't bother me . there is little head and is a nice amber in color .  just take a sip and get lost in the nearly overpowering flavor explosion and the creamy tingly mouthfeel of this wondrous scottish ale .

mostly malts , but a little caramel/toffee/sugar . t : sweet malty flavor throughout . very enjoyable , but maybe could have used a bit more hops . the eliot ness holds a special place in my heart .  it looks like they wo n't last long . half the head is gone within 1 minute .  great mouth feel on this one . no hops or bitterness present at first , but bitter in the finish .

a- pours chocolate milk color into black with the creamiest of tan heads . s- aroma is soft and roasted , not much going on . perfect amount of malt .  not bright and vivid like mirror pond , not at all cloudy . head was some what reluctant , white and thin with decent retention .  mouthfeel is perfect , my ideal belgian .

it 's supposedly a witbier heavily flavored with raspberries -- and just a touch of honey . the berry aroma is all-consuming . 8 inches from my nose , it 's attacking my nostrils like a schoolbully . if i 'm picking raspberry seeds out of my teeth with new glarus rapsberry tart or lindemans framboise , i 'm picking the raspberry jolly rancher wrapper out of my teeth with this one . intensely fruity .  1/8 '' white head that dissipates quickly with minimal slippery lacing .  the mouthfeel is amazing , thick and solid with a lingering savory finish .

aroma is pretty subdued .  small , short-lived white head tops a golden colored brew , slight haze but mostly clear .  silky silky smooth on the mouth , it makes it feel as light bodied but if you take the time to get a feel it 's almost medium . just fantastic . o- this is deffinitely a good saison , the mouthfeel is the highlight .

smell is very nice , probably the best part about this beer .  good lacing , poor head retention .  feel is really nice as well , lightly creamy and buttery with super calming smoothness and a bit of chewyness with a slightly bread dough drying in the finish .

ah ... sierra nevada pale ale ... . smell is mild and not tons of identity here . a bit of a metallic smell . nothing overpowering .  pours a light bronze with notable carbonation .  finishes fruitty & spicy mf : huge & well balanced this was bit ponderous , but tasty .

aroma was well restrained , with dark malt notes and roastiness coming forth . 3.9 look : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | feel : 4 | drink : 4 1267  preface - i always rate brews to style ... a - very average . no head . or lacing .  m - the mouthfeel is fantastic . medium and a little creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .

the smell was rather plain , hints of roasted grain and toaste , slight metallic nose , otherwise not much there , the taste however was great , a nice marshmellow smoothness up front followed by a warming dark roasted and coffee flavor with backing of chocolate , goes great with pie and ice cream , highly recommended .  ok retention with little fingers of lace .  m : light and refreshing with a perfect amount of carbonation .

aroma is faint or nil . sharply carbonated and very little up front hoppiness . a welcome refreshment from over-oaked beers that have been popular with us craft breweries the past couple years . i would have guessed oak aged english brown as much as german dunkel , though .  a - pours a deep brown with very distinct ruby highlights . thin off-white head and very little lacing .  mouthfeel : fantastic . rich without being syrupy . carbonation is just right .

metallic wet grain , corn sweetness , sulfurous malaise . bland and hollow , sweet corn flavor with club soda carbonation .  lots of sediment just waiting to get moved around in the bottom of this beer . not enough foam or head , or lacing for an ipa imho .  dark malts , some chocolate , medium to full bodied and very smooth from start to finish .

by the way , is a beer to drunk fast because the taste when it 's in a high temperature is very bad . the merchandise is greater than the taste but is better than other brazilian pilsen style beers .  pours a pale copper color with an off white head from a brown twist off bottle .  mouthfeel is fine and not heavy .

n : not much of anything . minimal fruitiness and spices climbing to mostly lemon as it warmed . t : definitely shined more when it was crisp and cold than when it warmed .  appears a hazy yellow color and a heavy pour yields a thin , large bubbled head that fades to a sheen rapidly .  mouthfeel was real good .

at first blush , it smells like rotten fruit and maple syrup .  pours an efferevescent bronze with a thumb of offwhite head . not a lot of head retention or lacing s : bready malt & aged or old hops .  very rich flavor of dark malts and smoke , with hints of coffee and chocolate as well . the finish is almost all smoke , much too intense for my liking . ive used this many times in making caribou pot roasts in the crockpot . they even have a recipe on their website , which is delicious . i was informed that this beer has won more medals at the great american beer festival than any other beer , quite an accomplishment .

smell was deep with plenty of sweet chocolate aromas and bitter grains .  theyre rumored to be in yakima now but no information is forthcoming and their system wont accept my email inquiries . the brew was deep crimson with fine sediment adrift throughout . this is ( was ) a regal , dignified ale that was oh so easy to drink . though neither the bottle nor the bear creek website mentions the abv , bearly barley wine didnt come across as overpowering or excessively strong .  m : smooth and medium bodied .

smell is chocolate with some burnt coffee tones and burnt bread crust smell as well .  it pretty much looks like muddy pond water , but this look in a beer is actually sort of exciting , because it signals me that i am in for an interesting experience .  it is bubbly on the tongue and does leave you dry . it 's smooth , but just kind of basic . it 's a very approachable stout .

the smell is mild , clean and neutral . or , to be frank , very boring .  this score might be a bit lower than appropriate , as i drank the beer in an opaque vessel , and in a dark room -- did n't get much of a look , so i just gave it a middle of the road score on appearance .  it is quite nice on the mouthfeel , almost enough to disguise the heavy-handed corn influence .

skunk on the nose , unavoidable skunk due to the bottle color . once it dies down it is a very malty smell , i would have like more hops .  courtesy of raindog , thanks sir body is dark brown and initially wears a tan head that fast becomes one of the quickest dissipating festival of bubbles i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel was good and very drinkable ; however , it was slightly bitter ... something i was n't expecting this to have considering the malts .

smell : no discernable aroma at all .  the beer pours a very deep brown , forming a thin 1/8 inch head .  the drink is carbonated a little more than average as well . mf- very crisp beer with little or no after taste . one of the smoother beers around .
