a : usually drink it in the can , so the view never changes s : it smells like many american macros , maybe a bit better , but that 's not saying much t : defnately not much going on , but overall smooth , well carbonated m : carbonation , foam , and a little flavor , nothing special d : you can easily knock a few of these back and not notice it overall : as i 'm apt to tell my more snobby beer friends , it won a blue ribbon in the past ( most recently 2006 ) , so something must be good about it .  pours a pale straw yellow color with a decent looking body and about two fingers of nearly pure white head . ample carbonation and the head is very fizzy , and as such it recedes quickly and leaves not a lick of stick or a trace of lace .  mouthfeel is fine . medium bodied with the right amount of carbonation .

it was n't yellow and it was n't pale . it had a unique smell that was hard to place . a slight sweetness that was maybe vaguely fruity , like a pear ? something else was present that i could n't quite place , sort earthy .  fluffy head features large bubbles quickly thins , leaving only a very thin top .  mouthfeel is medium to full . there 's a nice level of carbonation .
pretty boring and bland .  pours a caramel with a light tan froth , good retention , & average lacing .  mouthfeel : crisp and refreshing .

the smell is about half and half lager flavor does no tliv eup to the malt smell at all .  the beer 's appearance was a little bit of a letdown , there was almost no head at all even with an aggressive pour . below the beltline everything was all right , the beer was pale yellow and hazy , almost looked like a wit .  it as a quite full mouthfeel similar to a very sweet red wine , almost syrupy . it gives a good warming feeling .

smell is somewhat corny/metal ... not too tempting , but i dive in anyway .  the beer pours a dark copper , forming a 1/4 inch tan head . light spots of lace on the glass .  mouthfeel is nice , actually - light bodied , spritzy carbonation .

a big sniff presents brown sugar , molasses , a touch of butterscotch , and a tad of bittersweet chocolate .  ( a ) - pours a very thick cloudy caramel color .  the mouthfeel is good ; slightly thick and very smooth . however , it is a little bubble and will sting the recesses of your mouth .

very unimpressive .  an initial pleasantly sweet light malt aroma moves to phenol and other spiciness , finally settling with that mix . fizzy smallish head that leaves . richness to mouthfeel lends to the sense of fullness and a hefty carbonation helps too . contrary to crispness for style this has a very good ale smoothness .  taste is a very light malt sweetness upfront with a moderately bitter finish of good length and crispness . a pretty uncomplicated beer , good for the style , a good lawnmower beer .
s - hmm . mildew ?  pours a slighlty hazy amber with a pretty average head .  body is on the full side of medium . moderate carbonation .

head drops to a finger weird smells coming out of this one : crisp lemon & raspberry , but also a strange savory flavor , like overly sweet ketchup , which is a turn-off . it 's a shame : the peripheral aspects ( appearance , mouthfeel ) were impressive , but there was something off about the smell & taste which would make me avoid this one in the future .  this beer pours a mirky brown with a sizeable light tan head .  highly carbonated .
smell : sweet and grains and that lingering trademark skunk !  minimal head with an aggressive pour . minimal to no lacing at all .  mouthfeel : the bottle conditioning makes for a very smooth ride .

nothing of note on the nose , maybe a bit of burnt caramel or it could have been the glass , it was weak either way . unremarkable overall but nothing offensive by any means .  a hazy orangeish brown with a small head which quickly receded and left minimal lacing .  light and creamy mouth feel with obviously knocked down carbonation .

the aromas were really weak and could not get much character from it except the malts .  good bubbly , head . the variance in size of bubbles making up the head , almost give it a lumpy appearance .  good carbonation .

the scent is crap if this is an imperial ipa . the only scents i am getting is a estery apple scent . this one smells more like a poor belgian beer then a double ipa .  the pour was not what i would consider , um great . light amber in color , nearly golden with a very , very clear body to it . lots of carbonation could be seen streaming up towards the top of the glass which coalesced into a thin , but firm white cap at about a quarter of an inch , but this really did not stay long , fading with no real side glass lacing .  mouthfeel is very light and well carbonated .

i 'm not pulling much off this other than yeast and citrus . it 's not weak , but it 's not so pleasant . no citrus but comes to life in the middle third . full bodied , robust .  cola-like brown in appearance . carbonation is a bit high on this very fresh bottle , but i 'm sure aging a few of these will mellow that , in addition to allowing the flavors to meld and blend together . quite nice fresh though .  m - low carbonation , tiny bubbles , overall feels pretty good .

the aroma is sweet roasted grains and cola .  pours a cloudy amber topped with a two finger foamy tan head . a little too dark and too cloudy for the style - unless those are hop particles clouding it up , but as long as it tastes good i can look past it .  mouthfeel is medium , clean with a bitter hop aftertaste .

nose was very very mellow . very subtle malt and a crispness but beyond that i could n't smell much of anything .  very small tan head with minimal retention and lacing .  good , solid creamy feel with enough dryness to get you through .

hardly any smell , a little bit of malt maybe .  a : a murky , iced tea colour ... not much head at all , and whatever was there did n't stick around long .  if there is , then this ska brew is a prime example ... this is the second time i tasted a bottle of this brew . this is an extremely clean tasting brew which is a great quality i enjoy , but where are the hops ? the malt and ( not overwhelming ) bitterness serve as great supporting backbones to what should be a wonderful hoppy aroma and flavor . as it stands , this brew is severely lacking in hop flavor/aroma and comes across as a brew which should be named `` delicate '' rather than `` decadent '' imperial ipa .
s- 100 % hoppy nose . d- decent drinkability . very bitter . wanted more balance .  a- pale yellow and cloudy .  medium bodied and smooth .

pours golden clear with good carbontaion that provides an intial froathy white head that dissapates quickly . the smell and taste are bolstered by grain with some hop in an effort to balance the beer .  a : cloudy yellow/orange color with some suspended solids . broken , thin lacing ; none near the end .  nice mouthfeel .

the smell is that of boston lager , rather skunky with hints of hops and malts .  but i was in a pils-y mood today and picked up some budweiser ( the real budweiser ) today and drank it before this guy , so i was worried about how it would hold up to that greatness . but it really is like comparing apples to oranges . troegs is a very faint , almost macro-lager yellow , almost definately not decoction mashed . like biting into an apple on a summer 's day . it does n't taste like an apple at all , but that is what it makes me think of . the mouthfeel is good for a pils . it 's a well made pils man .  mouthfeel is sticky and sweet with a nice roundness and full character .

smell is pretty boring , a little old bananas and corn - eh , whatever taste is quite clean , warm , cereal grain flavour lingering on the off sweet side , but then finishing with a bit of artificial cherry on the end .  their saison pours a bright , rich , cloudy golden hue with a milky white , effervescent head . the pearly cap of foam recedes fairly quickly and leaves little or no lacing .  m : about the same consistency as the boston lager .

like most macros , its easy going down , and unappealing in scent or appearence .  poured from a 12oz bottled in 2009 a : pours a deep red orange color with a small white head that dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel : medium-plus body . medium carbonation . some oily viscosity to the mouthfeel .

s : peaches . need i say more ? t : lots of peach favor , with a big sour bite at the end .  some sediment and good lacing .  as is the case in many of the wilder beers out there it 's not as wacky on the palate as it is on the nose . even for a lover of brett and funk this is n't a highly drinkable beer . if the goal was just to see how far they could crank up the volume on the brett funk then they succeeded but if they were looking to brew something that tasted great i 'll have to say they fell a little short .

very little aroma , has a slight grassy smell i thought it was a drinkable beer that has a much different taste than it american counterparts .  a hazy dark yellow color with a head that i missed since i looked in another direction ( for 3 seconds ) while rvdoorn poured the beer .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a velvety texture , and appropriately low carbonation .

smells vaguely of hops . very faint odor .  clear gold with a small bubbling white head . very balanced and enjoyable ... perfect for sessioning anytime .  mouthfeel : light bodied beer . moderate carbonation .

pleasant smell of green bananas and citrus .  appearance is rather uninspiring , dark , little to no lace or head , no apparent carbonation .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .

under all of this , i can still smell some gumball and barnyard odors . an amazing smell and likely a very unique one . t - more grapefruit pith and that same pine , but i still ca n't figure it out .  color is a nice golden orange , much like an iced tea .  fairly thick body .

i't smells like a funky straw bale , some wet grassy notes as well .  poured into my guinness 20 oz glass , no idea when this was bottled ... there is no date listed on the bottle a-pale orange color with a small inch head s- sweet pale malt , flowery and fruity ( citrus ) hops t- very flowery , earthy , oily hops with a subtle citrus fruit taste .  light body with good carbonation .
slightly smokey malt aroma that is quit bland reall with faint hints of oak , toast , bbq , charcoal and bacon .  a very cloudy orange color .  very smooth without being too full bodied .

yeasty aroma with the funk of rotten fruit and full kitchen garbage can.. nasal accents of strong commonly-belgian hops work their way in as well .  pours a deep amber with very little carbonation . no head in trappist glass , just thin ring of white bubbles clinging to the sides for dear life .  taste is thin and adjuncty . mouthfeel is good , thick and creamy .

animal urine and feces . very sweet with pine overtones .  a - pours a semi-translucent deep brown hue , and is capped with a smallish bubbly head .  m- very little carbonation . very full syrupy body .

i honestly can not smell this beer at all . nothing . nada . zilch . taste is an interesting combination of cream and apricots .  eye candy : pours a transparent amber . plenty of rising carbonation . fizzy thin head , klacing lasted throughout session . otherwise , autumn is perfect for the fall , drinkable from early sept untill the snow starts a flying .  for a big mouthfeel , this simply does n't have a flavor to match . very nice mouthfeel , good bite up front , a bit of carbonation in middle that emphasises the rye flavors , and a crisp finish that is actual slightly ruined by the lingers smoked flavor .
aroma is strong with caramel malt , toffee , brown sugar , molasses , and a bit of alcohol .  presentation : on tap . appearance : hazy amberish brown .  there 's moderate carbonation to it as well .

a : pours a clear medium yellow with a thin white head that quickly vanishes s : hints of malt and corn , but weak overall t : simple basic lager taste that does not attract attention , neither too sweet nor too bitter m : smooth and easy on the tongue - moderately carbonated and well behaved d : easy to enjoy several , but may get a bit boring this would probably be a decent beer to enjoy on a hot day , with a sandwich and some chips .  22oz bottle a- pours an orangish amber color with a thin and fizzy off-white head that quickly disappears .  boiled pasta water finish . good carbonation . twinge of acid is perfect .

very pleasing . t - this beer smelled and looked so promising but the taste fell so short .  12oz brown bottle with a bottle code that i ca n't decipher . thin layer of tan head holds its own and leaves some lacing on the glass . opaque brown with amber hues when brought up to the light . coffee flavors comes in slow but becomes a dominant flavor middle to end .  creamy mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

the aroma was nonexistant . i was at a cajun restaurant so the smoke from the bar and the spices from the kitchen may have wiped out what little aroma there was in the beer .  big head with big bubbles like one , too . head dissipates fast to nothingness .  it has a very soft mouthfeel , a little like soda to be honest and you can barely notice the alcohol .

s - very nice . the aroma from the pecans is subtle but noticable and mingles well with the expected toasty , caramel , and slightly toffee aromas from the malt .  they get me all strung out on what becomes my go-to session beer -- like they did with the long-lamented cinder cone red -- and then like lucy van pelt , they snatch it away at the last second , leaving me flat on my back and yelling , `` aauugh ! '' red chair nwpa is a copper-colored pour with a sturdy , vanilla-tinted head that throws a nose of nice fragrant hops ; floral and citrus notes add some complexity to the usual pine/grapefruit assault . at around 55 ibus , red chair was the more balanced sibling of the more flamboyant bond street sisters . personally , i do n't care what they call it , it is a much better seasonal replacement for cinder cone than the buzzsaw brown was , and if they get it in their heads to make it year around , well , so much the better .  mouthfeel is medium with good level of carbonation .

the ginger was dry , powdery and muddled with no distinguishability . overall was muddled , flat , and bland . t : the flavor faired slightly better then the aroma .  painted 12oz purchased at merchant 's and poured into a tulip . dark chestnut with a bubbly head of light tan that dissipates to a ring of large bubbles .  m : nice and thick d : not something ill try again .

aroma is hard to detect , very mild malt/hops and paper .  dark , almost black with no head yet nice lacing .  dark brown/amber body . it is a very smooth and a sweet sipper . some hops , caramel , candy sugar and oak . not much bourbon . i was way excited to try this and actually find it to be rather average .

a : nice hazy copper color with lots of carbonation activity & little head retention s : difficult to detect anything specific in the aroma t : light sweetness and some roastiness m : good mouthfeel to start but loses it quickly - medium , smooth body , good carbonation to start d : this beer started off pretty well with aforementioned charactetistics , but lost its form too quickly .  first off , i thought this beer was very delicious ... and i will certainly buy another ! i do n't know if i poured mine incorrectly , but it was very cloudy ... which i thought oktoberfests are supposed to be clear ( i 'm thinking about spaten , sam adams , and the like ) . in fact , i loved it !  medium mouhfeel with some carbonation . smooth and buttery feel . pretty dry finish .

a : pours a hazy red , minimal head retention s : nose features acetone , paint , flashes of rye here and there , lots of herbal qualities t : taste features rye with hints at spiciness , the rye malt brings out a bitterness that does n't seem to be contributed from hops mf : high carbonation , medium body o : well this brew certainly features plenty of rye , but the supporting cast does not elevate the rye in any way .  pours a hazy straw yellow with a half finger head that fades somewhat quickly . not too impressive .  feels very creamy but that does n't make the beer more drinkable to me .

not a lot of aroma though , more of a faint `` beer-stink '' smell ... certainly not that impressive .  poured into a pint glass to give a nice clear golden ting witha 1/2 inch of white head thatlingered for a while but eventually dissipated to a thin film atop the beer .  mouthfeel : light-bodied but not watery . it had a nice feel to it .

it pours very light yellow , with a generous head ( of course , its beer out of a can , so there 's always head ) . there 's almost no nose to speak of . what is there is a light wheaty smell .  but it was a good spiritual experience anyway . the color was a bit darker than i expected , but i am not a bjcp judge , so screw it .  there 's also just a hint of citrus from the orange peel ( or orange oil extract ) the smooth mouthfeel and moderate body is not unlike that of a german hefeweizen .

s : a faint smell of malt without much of anything else . not a strong smell by any means .  a- cloudy golden tan topped with an off white head . the head fades quickly to a ring and leaves a little spotty lace on the glass .  this is my first review and hope it looks well , even if not my favorite beer . leaves a malt taste on the roof and tongue . this is the first scottish ale i 've tried . for comparison , i love dark ales , like ommegang abbey belgium ale and founders breakfast stout . bottle serving .

not much in the olfactory department , but it does have a nice , creamy medium body . it 's milky-bready malty and lightly toasted tasting . third coast beer ai n't bad , but seems to have a bit too much peppery spiciness for my enjoyment .  a - reddish brown brew with a big head and a little bit of scattered lacing .  maybe i could not taste the `` rare '' but this really sucked compared to the 2008 classic gueuze which is a fantastic gueuze .

s- there is no distinct smell to it , t- when it first hits your mouth you feel the creaminess of the beer .  hazy apricot-looking color , left a creamy light tan coating after the clean-up of the initial opening of the beer , left some spotty lacing and some slight traces of carbination .  m - great carbonation , finishes well .
the aroma was very light , i was barely able to pick out traces of malt and spice in the scent .  a lot of particles .  m - medium body and low carbonation .

aroma is kind of like dandelions , a little soap in there too .  appearance- pours out a muddy brown color with a small off white head . a good amount of particles floating around .  mouthfeel is crisp , the whole drink is refreshing due to the good carbonation .

nose : notes of coffee , chocolate and wood . roasted malt smells come through strongly . taste : tastes of roasted and chocolate malt , coffee and tangy flavors come through as well .  into a tulip , pours a decent head initially , with little lacing and no legs .  pleasantly carbonated on the palate , with a dry finish .

smell is faint with light adjunct , malt and hop . fairly light for the style acting and tasting more like a lager , the bottle does say ale , but ba style says dark lager which i would agree more with .  kind of cloudy hazy light golden color .  being of fan of bocks , i was fully prepared to love this ubiquitous doppelbock . it was kind of sweet and malty , smelled great , felt nice going down -- quite satisfying . there was a slightly funky smell to it , and an even funkier taste . i thought that was more common in highly hopped beers . at $ 10 for the four pack , i hate to try it again for fear of wasting my hard-earned beer money .

pours like strong coffee except it has virtually no aroma . as mentioned earlier , there is no nose with this beer .  another great offering from this great brewery . this is a great lambic . there is no mistaking it is a peach lambic . the peach is moderate to strong in flavor , somewhat sweet , a bit tart , but it balances well . again not all fruit beers are bad , were not talking about smirnoff or bacardi crap here , this isnt something sweet just to chug and get wasted , this is a beer to drink fo rthe enjoyment of drinking it , not just the buzz .  m- moderate/high carbonation , medium body , lager clean . crisp enough leaving a refreshing feel .

s - no idea what cardamom is , but smells like something that should be added to spaghetti not beer .  clear , pale golden with a quickly thinning white head with ok retention and alcing .  medium-full body and medium carbonation with good smoothness .

it was light and added character to the blonde ale , but it 's a little much in here and it make the aroma offensive . the flavor and aroma come off extra bready with a little rubber in the aroma .  golden-orange color , almost transparent and practically no head .  very creamy and full . very dry .

does n't smell like much . i get some malt , maybe some peach fuzz .  served in a hill farmstead tulip glass . a - minimal carbonation . thin-late rising wisp of bubbles that linger on top . not much of a looker here .  mouthfeel is about right for style , perhaps a touch undercarbed , but all else is acceptable , though it showcases a flavor profile best left behind the curtain .

smell is not impressive with watery dark malt and stale coffee .  it pours a lovely clear caramel brown with red highlights . very little head sits on top , and what little there is disappears almost immediately .  - well carbonated , dries the mouth a bit . nice smooth body , probably this beers highlight is the mouthfeel .

smells like dirt and honey . too dirty smelling and tasting to have more than one or two ( ever ) unless it was all that i had .  ayinger bru weisse pours a light golden color into my glass ; it has a perfect hefe haziness to it . moderate carbonation , no lacing . i was slightly disappointed by its initial appearance , but the taste is fantastic .  mouthfeel is light with a good spike of carbonation .

it smells like adjuncts honestly , not good at all . that smell is for suckers though .  this one pours very clear and almost `` light '' looking for an ipa , it 's a rather light amber with a puny head .  very light body , and highly carbonated and fuzzy .

a - clear red orange body with two finger for frothy tan head and excellent lacing s - a little pine and a little citrus . i would n't call this a ipa smell and is kind of faint t - nice mix of flavor and bitter hops with a little spice and citrus in the back m - medium body with medium carbonation d - easy to drink and kind of enjoyable but nothing really special  finally got some last night on tap at mad mex . looks average , served in a snifter , no head , mild lacing .  it was somewhat thick with some carbonation , and had a hot aftertaste .

smell theres almost no smell to this lager except for a hint of lemon and maybe grass .  this poured a clear medium golden , white foam head , that left broken lace all the way through , taste was nice , rather bold hops , up front , then mellows , to a bit of a sweet aftertaste , citrusy notes , fruit and hop nose , bit of apple , and lemon . mouthfeel was a little chewy , but fairly rich and full , drinkability is very good , nice summer brew !  a - opaque black color with a small head that disappears quickly s - rich chocolate-like aroma , mild yeast esters , some smokiness , no hop perceived t - roasted malt flavor dominates , some yeasty esters and mild hop flavors take a secondary role , very gentle mild hop finish with some lingering smokiness m - smooth creamy medium body with moderately low carbonation d - this is a decent enough oatmeal stout . the head and retention is disappointing , but the smell , taste and mouthfeel are acceptable .

crappy lime too .  poures a slightly hazy ... well hay/straw color with a white one finger head that leaves pretty quickly leaving no lace behind , nice lemony aroma very effervescent with just a light wheaty undertone.wow this beer suprises me a little not just a run of the mill american wheat ale here nice big wheat malt profile very sturdy but not heavy in the mouth , soft lemony tones round this out very nicely just enough to make you not think about the `` dreaded '' lemon wedge.could be one of the better american wheat beers out there wich might not be saying much but this is very good .  the mouthfeel is thick and oily with a mild burn going down . have a bottle of this is all i can handle , which is good because the full bottle would have me a little too buzzed .

the aroma was barely detectable due to the beer being served to cold and in a frozen mug . what nose there was showed some earthy biscuits and sweet malts .  it pours a dark beer with little head .  light-medium caramel malt sweetness up front , continued in the middle with a hint of earthy hop bitterness , finishing with a more of the same . medium mouthfeel .

the aroma is quite limited but offers some light malt and spicy hops , as well as some light sulfur ( which seems to be characteristic of the brewery ) . the maltiness has an odd , almost musty , bready note that 's fortunately overshadowed by a spicy , but indistinct , hop flavor .  a pour down the center gave an initial 2 fingers of tan head , which diminished rapidly to a little foam around the edges ... a little disappointing . the dark color is n't opaque , if held to a back light . dark hues of deep red/garnet highlight the edges . no lacing either ( also disappointing ) .  i 'm not sure what a `` baltic '' porter is supposed to taste like ; but this one is quite different from most porters i 've had . sweet molasses aroma that is greater than any chocolate or mocha that might be found . a strong level of metal present also . sweet , almost like brandy . reminds me far more of a double bock than a porter . i can not detect any hops at all . too sweet for me , making it more one-dimensional without any complexity .

not bad at all , pours a copper gold with a decent foamy head , rather weak in the nose , ajduncts plus some hop and grain come about . inexplicably though the taste is not bad , bitter-like light and refreshing , goes down smoothly and its aftertaste is not bad at all . still though , decent stuff .  a - pours cloudy dark amber with medium head . my glass had some dark particles in it .  it 's still fairly sturdy though , and carbonation is low but solid .
grainy/malty `` beer '' smell ; pretty common smelling .  a - its a real muddy brown with a light tan head and massive bubbles .  m : thick , chewy..medium carb .

a distinctly grainy malt greets you in the nose along with some skunky hops despite the brown glass bottle .  nice deep amber/copper color was topped by a thin head that left zero lacing .  good mouthfeel for this light body but the hops balance the feel .

smell is of grain , corn and a slight skunky smell .  poured from 750ml bottle into tulip glass . a : dark copper , head is generous and frothing but does n't live very long and leaves almost no lacing .  mouthfeel : good carbonation , nice medium body .
smell is weak , slight roasted barley and a little dark malt character but not much else .  served a crisp yellow with a thin diminishing head .  could be a bit less carbonated .

a - copper color with thin off white head s - light smell.. sweet malt.. little alcohol.. sort of a slight pukey smell too.. lol t - not very good , not all that bad .  glass with no head whatsoever .  m - full bodied and chewy with a moderately dry finish with some alcohol noticeable .

smell : diluted malts , anyone ?  a : crystal clear golden color with an appropriate sized head . i was expecting something a little more cloudy .  mouthfeel was nice smooth and easy to drink as far as body goes .

the smell is very faint , and i can hardly sense the beer at all .  brown color with tons of yeast floaters . very thin tan head . nothing special to look at but not terribly out of character for the style .  m : crisp and clean , moderate levels of carbonation and warmth . medium body .

12 ounce green bottle appearance : clear yellow color with little head and little to no lacing smell : a little hard to describe but would say it has a strong bitter almost skunky smell taste : has a lot better taste then smell which was a little surprising .  appearance : dark orange-copper color ; a little hazy ; very small head on the pour smell : a pleasant hoppy smell taste : excellent : fairly balanced ; mild hoppiness with a nice sweet malt flavor to balance ; very tasty ( not watered down at all ) mouthfeel : medium bodied ( im really surprised this is on 4.87 % alcohol ) ; its a lot thicker than other 4.87 % beers ; this must a have a lot of unfermentables in it drinkability : good flavor ; good body , so its going down pretty quick overall , an excellent beer .  mouthfeel was nice and thick ; you know you 're drinking a dipa .

smooth and balanced aroma . t/m- coffee flavor with some medicine mixed about .  pours - nothing spectacular here . moderate carbonation , moderate head - coarse , and fades rapidly , leaving some lace . looks thick - the bubbles seem pretty leisurely on the way up .  m - surprising carbonation fight with a medium bodied beer .

pours a really pretty cloudy orange color with a big white head , and some sediment floating around , smell is nearly non existent , some slight slight citrus scent but thats it .  appearance : medium carbonation , 1 inch head , dark brown smell : malt , chocolate syrup -- like bosco , and cream taste : chocolate , burnt malt , nut , and cream mouthfeel : sweet , medium bodied , smooth drinkability : this is a surprisingly sessionable stout .  mouthfeel was good , with plenty of carbonation and a nice smoothness to it .

very little head to speak of , thin collar of dense white bubbles s : deep notes of dark chocolate , carob , molasses , and a hint of coffee . the flavors are very mellow but well integrated . t : the taste does n't translate into being as good as the smell suggested , the smooth chocolate is there , but turns into a slightly sharp flavor by mid palate and has a slightly metallic finish .  small craft warning is a hazy golden lager with a somewhat diminishing , soft and splotchy , white head .  a little sticky and a very bitter aftertaste .

very faint hops ... .  rich antique golden ale , with a one finger head that gives way pretty quickly .  smells of raisins , a hint of semi-sweet choc ? mouthfeel is nice , thick , syrupy & smooth ... the way i want a barleywine .

almost no aroma in the nose . the appearances of cloudy lemonade .  33cl bottle poured into my gordons thistle glass a- 1 finger head post pour and reducing to non existancy immediately . held to the light , a hint of light gets through to show a very dark dark dark dark ruby body .  mouthfeel - medium bodied and smooth with a good carbonation level .

it was a pretty dark brown with a sweet hops and spices scent . it was n't very bitter at all .  nice light golden straw color with a slight haze appropriate for the style . head dissapears quickly to a light spotty blanket .  pleasantly effervescent mouthfeel .

smell is not much , sort of bland with a bit of skunk to it , small hints of malt and grains here and there .  the crystal clear mahogany red color was nice , but it only produced a -finger of beige head that dissipated quickly , and it left no lacing whatsoever .  mouthfeel is pretty good , goes well with the style of light and highly carbonated .

nose : very slight nose .  a pretty dull looking beer , but on the nose , there is a huge oatmeal presence that lays on top of the roasted coffee and bitter cocoa nubs .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and carbonation is moderate .

light straw golden color with an airy white head . light and sweet nose , with a bit of corn/cereal grains .  12 oz bottle a : deep amber under a small tan head . no lace , no retention .  the carbonation and mouthfeel were appropriate for this style .

nothing spectacular on the nose but for the typical belgian `` funk '' which was fine but i could distinguish nothing else . overall , a keeper , i just expected some more hop character to poke through but , then again , perhaps belgian darks are n't where we go for hop nirvana ?  deep dark brown color , little head and no lace .  thick and smooth mouthfeel .

served with a lemon , which i quickly removed and placed into my diet coke . a pale , cloudy yellow beer : the only brew they served that was n't crystal clear . no aroma .  pours an opaque orange/brown , thin tan head forms , disappears to a thin ring really fast , some lace spots .  m & d - this beer is great on its own , too light and carbonated and malty for me , but suits a nice dinner perfectly , goes well with food and that was its intention so i must review it within its intentions and the style , for which it is very good

light aromas of oak barrel , sweet malts , raisons , and a tad bitter sweet chocolate . i 've been enjoying the stout and ruby port mix , a.k.a velvet pussy , for some time now and imo a quality 12oz stout with a 1/2oz pour of quality port works better than ohanlons concoction .  pours a clear golden color with a big white head that diminishes quite quickly .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated , and nice and creamy . feels good on the tongue .

it smells faintly of roasted malt , and not much else .  appearence : poured a simple golden yellow without no head , smell : the smell is of grapes and some hints of spices .  this beer has noticeable viscosity and a big thick feel . minimal carbonation .

smell : reminiscent of cheese . but the smell is actually quite tame ... too much . you can hardly smell much at all .  it is cold and looks refreshing . the beer is a hazy gold pour with only a small white edge layer of head . hmm . was hoping for a little more froth . besides the lack of substantial head a good example of the style i think .  crisp , clean mouthfeel with flavors of dry , pale malt . at first , i found myself wanting more flavor , a la boston lager , but the mouthfeel and resulting drinkability really brought things back up for me in the end .

a - pale straw yellow , slight orange tint , and slightly cloudy . s - light malt , citrus , and wheat . t - taste upfront is a sweeping bitterness , fades to a light malty sweet banana clove aftertaste .  pours a brown amber color with a fairly weak head and very few lacings but does keep a nice brown film on top .  m : pretty creamy and lightly carbonated . easy to swallow a mouthful .
aroma reminds me of lemongrass or some kind of oriental vegetables like bok choy .  pours a clear yellow with a light head on top .  m - lighter side of heavy , pretty smooth .

the smell was not strong at all ... very light hints of earth and raisins . a mediocre ale .  it was bottled in april 2010 , so i think i 'm good ... duped by the standard brown longneck bottle , i poured this into a standard american pint glass , and it appears a cloudy dark iced-tea colour , with a bit of swirling sediment , and a half finger of soapy pale beige head , which disappears quickly , leaving some sparse spidery lace around the glass .  m : medium in both body and carbonation .

smell is a very subdued smoky chocolate , a bit earthy and a faint whiff of bbq sauce .  a- clear yellow gold color with a small head that stick and laces .  light mouthfeel with a good amount of carbonation when you drink it .

n : sweet malts and , uh , nothing else t : sweet bready malts , almost no hops , caramel .  brown bottle into a sam adams glass . the body was golden brown/amber with a pocked , off-white head .  m : light-bodied , crisp , very clean , refreshing .

s - smelled like it was light struck - a little skunky . otherwise , grassy aromas are present .  pours a clear , medium copper , very much like apple juice .  thick body is very good . it 's just passable for now .

the drink was described as light and long with a sweet taste that stays in your mouth but no `` haze '' more like the reminder of something like perfume sprayed in the air .  no problem though , taste is fine , colour is nice and although there is no head and very little in the way of lacings , the body is pretty nice .  mouthfeel : bitter . nice carbonation .

aroma is very nice , surprisingly fruity , almost like a belgian pale .  the bottle looks very picturesque and i love it . it pours a cloudy , hazy wheaty yellow color with a tint or orange . only a half finger lace of head rises to the top . it doesnt have too much staying power and is gone within seconds .  i felt that the mouthfeel was the best part of this brew .

smells : slightly sulfurous on opening , but not as bad as my last sample of pbr . maybe the pabst plant has a little sulfur in the water ? i 'd really like to compare this side-by-side with pbr since they 're both pabst beers .  pours a clear light amber color with a thin white head that dissipates quickly with no lacing .  mouthfeel is good , soft and tingly .
the nose is ale yeast and disapointing .  appearance was n't much . dark gold , big bubbles in the head , retained some , but not great lace .  mouthfeel - nice body , pretty crisp .

smell is , well , sauerkraut . it dominates the aroma and any sembelence of oakiness or caramel just get lost in the sauerkraut . needless to say , i do n't like sauerkraut . taste is significantly better than aroma , but still not all that amazing . definte caramel and burnt sugar flavors as well as lactic tartness and there 's that darn sauerkraut again .  appearance : lightly hazed pale golden straw . very volatile , fleeting white head .  it 's very creamy and goes down easy . i 'm really disappointed with this .

aroma is an intense , lightly parching cherried candy and sweet chocolate , however mildly artificial . cordial cherries dominate the initial flavor , in that sold at the counter , wrapped in red foil , in plastic trays , at a midwestern gas station , kind of way . stout character takes over with a salty and pithy stout run .  7.5 % abv bottle into my slender & top heavy rare vos glass . big powdery head , though quite faint & not big on sticking around . body is a glittery caramel amber with lots of floaties .  mouthfeel was smooth , light , though i do n't know i 'd go as far as crisp .

the smell is almost that of a macro lager but slightly less offensive .  it is a dark brown color with a brown head .  i like the thick , syrupy mouthfeel as it 's quite comforting but the taste gets old fast and just is n't complex .

the smell is barely perceptible ; i do n't pick up much other than a bit of dry dark malt . i guess it could be worse . add to that a creamy oiliness in the mouthfeel and you 've got a better-than-average mexican beer , but nothing stunning . still , it 's better than corona , better than bud , better than labatt 's blue .  it is a medium brown brew with an ivory head .  medium bodied ; good amount of carbonation .

a : pale straw , fizzy , some head retention s : stale cereal grains , corn , a hint of sweetness t : starts with a tinge of sweetness , big grainy bread profile , considerable amount of flavor for an adjunct lager , decent balance mf : light body , high carb o : better than most of what bmc offers , but only by a slim margin  slight amounts of sediment adds to the mild haziness . no lacing , and just about no head , but there is a slight cloud of head floating around . m- full and very smooth .  mouthfeel was really good for a light beer . liked the carbonation , and felt richer than it tasted .

smell is pretty weak .  bottle poured into a tulip a : pours a translucent amber color with an eggshell hued , fizzy thin head . the fact that it 's considered an american amber is truly an insult . it has the appearance of an amber , but the aroma of a belgian and the flavor of a porter .  the body and carbonation levels are appropriate .

not much happening here . clean and dry but not particularly flavoursome . faint traces of lemon both in aroma and palate , and some bitterness / aniseed in the latter . but , ultimately just doesnt offer much at all , like most local examples of the genre .  a- pours and looks more like a porter than an imperial stout . dark see-through brown with a quickly fading tan head .  the mouthfeel is very nice , it 's very carbonated which works with the ginger presence , and the mouthfeel is at about a medium thickness .

smell : very weak smell overall- some sweet pale malts and grain hints .  a & # 8211 ; it pours like a foamy glass of iced tea , with large soapy bubbles but not a huge head .  mouthfeel is heavier than i 'd anticipate . i wish i liked the flavor of this because its heaviness is spot on .

smell is where it breaks down . took forever to find any smell at all and then only some malt and light hops .  the aroma is mostly floral malty with some grassy hops and barely distinguishable yeast . taste is quite similar - soft and sweet maltiness in the beginning , maybe some caramel additionaly and nice bitter finish . pretty good beer , i will definitely buy some more of them  mouthfeel : light/medium with a tart , crisp finish drinkability : i really do n't crave another of these ; this certainly would n't be a lawnmower beer for me conclusion : just kind of unsorted ( also kind of an odd bitterness on the finish ) ... i tried this a year or two ago and was n't a huge fan ... now that i 'm reviewing it ... i 'm still not .

sharp grapefruit-like hops aromas dominate , with only hints of grain in the background .  whenever i drink magic hat # 9 i always have a happy buzz . it is great to get a fruit beer that tastes like beer and not so much a fruit stand in your mouth .  mouthfeel : full-bodied with a strong , expressive carbonation .

the smell is of overwhelming vanilla and roasted malt , there is a sweet malt smell as well .  this one pours a dark and murky , dirty gold in color .  the body was definitely heavy on this one . heavy for a dipa especially of this size .

s - it smells like a sour old beer .  i 'm reviewing this one as i sit at the desk drinking it . i 'm weary of drinking something from a clear bottle , but i 'll get through it . the beer itself poured a rich mahogany or chestnut color . the head was fizzy and dissipated right after pouring . the initial flavor was a caramel nuttiness and molasses .  mouthfeel is of alcohol . the brew itself is medium-heavy bodied , with a very clean finish . this beer is clean as far as mouth feel goes , but is not as forgiving to the throat on the way down .

s : unable to detect any strong aromas from this beer . t : taste is slightly better than the scent .  appearance - this is peculiarly shiny and clear , almost a bright orange , with little head .  good carbonation .

smell is distinctly metallic note , malt , subdued hops , vanilla and citrus . hard to detect with the overwhelming metallic smell .  2006 vintage . no head on the pour .  the mouthfeel is about right for a stout , a bit thick with low carbonation .

smell is nearly non-existent , just malt . decent complexity and balance but nothing for the nose . aftertaste is light especially for the style .  i was glad to see brew kettle still serving a pumpkin beer during my visit in late december ... seems like a lot of brewers plan to sell out of pumpkin beer by thanksgiving , and to me the flavor is appropriate through the new year . appearance-wise , it looked a great deal like the chief 's rye - not quite colorful enough in the amber body , and with a medium amount of head .  the mouthfeel is the most appealing part of this brew , unfortunately i just ca n't escape the sour flavour .

s : mild , notes of carbonic acid and husky grain , that 's about it . t : bittersweet grainy malt flavour , with a nice little hop balance .  somewhat murky , reddish and garnet in color . big hoppy and grassy aroma sort of `` locker room '' sweat which doesnt mean a bad thing . serious hop levels .  mouthfeel is light body , medium carbonation . fairly nice .

the appearance is average ( 3.0 ) , but i guess that 's good for an american adjunct lager with lots of tiny bubbles rising up through the yellow swill . the smell is neither good or bad , there just is n't any .  12oz bottle into pint glass pours a deep gold color , one finger off-white head , with a decent amount of chunky particulates .  golden in color , slight haze ( nothing wrong with that ) , definite aromas of honey sweetness . lingering sweetness in the palate with a slight funk . interesting beer and something that one might only need to consume once .

balanced malt and hop , but with strong notes of a fresh water stream ? almost a puzzling smell . taste - right away you can taste the complexity .  poured and hazy copper/orange color with very little head .  velvety . good amount of carbonation .

the smell was typical and under-whelming , but really not an important aspect of this kind of beer .  a : pours a light golden color with a big white head that does not quickly dissipate .  mouthfeel is nice and thick and well carbonated . the best part of the beer .

smell is mostly grain , little citrus zest .  upon pouring into my mirror mirror tulip , rock art 's golden tripple is a attractive hazy deep golden color , topped with a weak fine white head .  the mouth is thick and malty . as far as drinkability , i have to say that i would be really happy to have one of these if i was alive 4000 years ago but for now i 'm going to have to go for something else .

s- nail polish remover with a hint of vinegar and dark fruits .  the beer poured a hazy burnished amber with next to nothing of a head .  m : medium-light body ; moderate carbonation ; smooth and clean mouthfeel .

12 ounce green bottle appearance : clear pale yellow color with a thick head that diminished fairly quick but left alright lacing smell : slight skunky smell with very little malt smells taste : slight bready taste and less flavor then some pilsners , but similar with very little bitterness but the bitterness that is there stays as an aftertaste for a while comment : it seems that the less taste the more refreshing , and this is the same .  nice gold ... almost no head .  meidum bodied and relatively smooth .

almost no aroma when poured . easy to quaff but not much reward for doing so . if you really like this , just buy a bud and save yourself a few bucks .  drink a few of these on a cold winter 's day and you 'll be feeling like you 're sitting by the fire ! very sweet , with lots of caramel . good stuff . gon na be buying this one a lot this winter .  mouthfeel is light and refreshing making the beer overall a decent session beer .

appearance : light brown/gold , good clarity , not much head formation aroma : lightly skunky , malty caramel , feint strawberries , honey flavor : light initial malt sweetness before a somewhat acidic backwash riding a wave of herbally hops , green olives ( ? ) , finishes dryish with a lingering hop bitterness mouthfeel : light body , crisp texture , low carbonation other comments : an ok beer , but a bit timid and unexciting .  a ) amber in color , about 1/2 inch of head , which was gone before i could get my nose into the pint . no lacing . the smell is like pumpkin pie . in fact , i said to my wife , this smells like pumpkin pie .  smooth with a creamy but dry finish . i walked away thinking that the `` smoked vanilla , coffee , and birch '' was meant to be flavor descriptors rather than actual ingrediants . all of these elemtns were way too weak to be appreciated for what other beers can do with them . call it a single , nix the mention of the adjuncts , and this beer would be alright .

smell : citrusy , with hints of spices , very powerful if you can wait a minute or so before you drink it .  lovely little bottle , but i will say it looks much bigger in photographs . the head fades quickly and no head retention to be seen .  really nice body all around ... overall - i would really enjoy this beer if it were n't for the bubblegum flavor , it 's really off putting and not very pleasant .

it has a cloudy light brown body and a malty fruity combination . it 's a very well rounded brew and just a little different .  a- medium amber with a quarter inch white head that disappears very quickly , an inviting unfiltered cloud lingers as you continue to sip .  mouthfeel is fairly creamy , with a lighter , dry body .

a good hot weather outdoors session beer , can only get in a bottle , not available in a keg for my kegerator , a shame , need to add a lime and lots of salt , that way i can not taste the actual beer . this is a light beer but not as watery tasting as american light beers and the lime and salt make it something a little special .  deep gold/pale amber in colour . thin , foamy tan head fades to a respectable layer of foam . chill haze is very evident .  mouthfeel- medium mouthfeel ( for the style ) . carbonation level was perfect for bringing out the bittering hops .

smell : immediately after i popped off the cap i got a whiff of ... corona . the aroma is slight , but there is a hint of macro lager grains there . it 's a good anytime lager -- the pabst of mexico .  a - hazy , pale straw yellow color with less than a one finger white head . leaves little to no lacing . color is right on for a pilsener but the head/lacing is disappointing .  m & d : very good , sits well and fairly easy to drink once you get the first one down

s : malty smell , but not much really . t : a bit fruity with very small hints of fruits .  i got a growler to go to assess . pour is a slightly hazy darker golden color . nice carbonation nose is alot of spice with a hint of citrus . i 'm a big dopplebock fan , but i liked this more than their dopplebock , it 's that good .  m - oily , medium body with a fantastic amount of carbonation .

s : smells like it looks - almost non-existent .  appearence ... slight haze ( no big deal ) but the color is way off . looks like an amber .  first off , i can tell that this one is slightly skunked , but i ca n't really blame the brewer for this one as i am also able to pull out some nice mellow caramel malts and a touch of biscuity-bready goodness as well . nice mellow malts , not too sweet , but the hops come through for a bit too much bite from what i look for and love about english pales . the hops come on a little too strong and linger too long , not really allowing me the chance to savour the mellow malts as much as i would like . there is a slight sweetness about it that reminds me of fresh apples although not the biting green apple off taste . this is different , and nice , but not my first choice for an english pale .

i am a big ipa fan and had never heard of this beer , but when i saw it on tap at a local restaurant decided to give it a try . nice traditional amber color , slight citrus nose , decent malt to hop balance , very drinkable , and went great with my pizza .  appearance : light amber ... similar to an american lager but with more carbonation smell : like a cross between a budweiser and heineken .  medium bodied with lively fine carbonation .

however , i detected no aroma at all .  pours golden yellow with one finger white head when poured aggressively that subsides to none almost instantly .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly creamy and not too heavy . the drinkablity is pretty low , not from the booze , but extreme bitterness , which overwhelms the decent , but not exceptional malt .

smell : quite sweet , hints of fruit and a bit metallic with a hint of tomato . not a lot of hops here .  a- golden yellow little no white lace / head s- a slight skunky smell to it light hop odor t- tasted like your average heineken , nothing to really stand out m- went down smooth , slight aftertaste the beer skunk after taste very thin d- not bad would have been better on a hot day , not one i would run out and get again but might have it if i were out for italian .  char davies , the artist in 1998 , made a fully interactive immersive visual/aural virtual artwork called ephemere , which furthers the work begun in osmose started in 1995 and displayed in the national gallery of canada in ottawa on june 26 , 1998. who cares ? this beer is almost close to a champaign ( and i would think that the yeast probably is champaign ) . also there is bitterness , which is nice to know that at least there are some hops to the so called beer . it is not advisable to use apples with fermenting , as the yeast creates funky flavors from apples , but this is much better than expected . although i would not want to drink this beer on a regular bases , thus low score on drinkability , i think it has a great taste like a grandsmith apples i use to eat as a kid .

aroma was very pleasing . deep and rotund hop nose is neither too flowering , too citrusy , and definitely stops shy of being too grassy . really a unique aroma , something that has become kind of rare these last few years .  light gold color with a bubbly head that dissolves right away .  served in a pint glass mug a : pours a clear bronze color with about an inch of thick head s : a smell provides a nice rye scent with a very sweet undertone contributed by the honey addition t : very nice smooth tasting beer , has a slight hint of honey and perhaps a slight rye note but other than that there isnt much to comment on , smooth and slightly sweet but thats about it m : very smooth in the mouth with a slight bite on the tongue as it is drank d : high level of drinkability , very subdued taste that is great for a hot summer day but leaves the drinking looking for more otherwise .

faint grain adjunct smell , mostly clean .  a - pours a yellow-green color with light sediment , moderate carbonation evident , and one inch of white head . looks odd and off , though not as neon green as some bottles . appearance is very odd looking , but luckily it smells and tastes a ton better .  m - nice average mouthfeel .

s : not much here . some light chocolate maybe . t : sweet malt and fruits .  zero head . o : the lack of head and almost non-existent carbonation seems off .  starts off clean and finishes with metallic hops m : silky smooth , good carbonation d : why ?

slight herbal/maple scent , nothing memorable . m- same as the smell , nothing memorable , typical ale .  this unusually plain pale ale is a pee yellow , and has an aroma of musty basement inhabited by a cat . it is a little less than ideal for a standard american pale ale , but will certainly do in a pinch when decent beer is needed for mindless television watching .  i believe the bottle i got was 8.75 percent.. looked pretty good for a esl , smell and taste reminded me very much of great western extra gold.. very malty with a nice solventy sweet-like alcohol burn ... carbonated perfectly , making it halfway drinkable , still hangover juice as far as imports go.. cheers !
i agree , the smell was weak , a bit lacking , just a slight floral and citrusy hint .  from the bottle it poured a dirty gold color with about a 1 '' head .  adequate carbonation .

the nose is off . some citrus and a tone of off phenolic aromas . there is just a off yeast note that is not good .  after a few swigs , however , the can taste went away , and what was an honest-to-goodness lager with no strings attached . there 's nothing spectacular about this beer , but i believe it beats out most american and canadian lagers i 've had .  the body of this beer suits the style with the usual level of north coast drinkability and feel to it . definitely the best feature .

pours a 1 finger head with trace amounts of lacing smell - yeast and malts with a rather powerful skunky aroma . it 's an offensive smelling combination to say the least taste - it 's got a very yeasty and mild citrus flavors as well as some slight floral hops and sweet malts .  a- pours a clear yellowish color , almost the same shade as piss .  mouthfeel -pretty good . foamy , not spritzy . nice and full , for a lager .

the smell is amazing ! ! very nice indeed . mouthfeel is medium light with a healthy amount of carbonation and a dry finish .  pours yellow and very cloudy . one finger head , soapy but dense . poor lacing and a few specs of lace .  m - i find with sub-par beers such as this one , the mouthfeel usually gives them their only good qualities . good amount of carbonation and goes down smooth .

first off , i 've never had a beer that smelled this bad while tasting so good . it had a caramel scent , with very heavy undertones of wet dog .  a : pours a light yellow with a thin stark white head and not a lot of retention .  m : medium bodied , good amount of carbonation .

aroma : sour dough bread with emphasis on sour , as in old stale rags .  from a 12oz can , this pours a very light golden color , plenty of active carbonation , and a quickly dissipating head .  glass : new belgium globe aging notes : one year at ~60f in the dark bang for the buck ( oz* % / $ ) : 22*6.2/10 = 13.64 a : orange , white lacey head , slightly cloudy from yeast s : horse-y farmhouse brett with hints of orange t : brett dominates ( horse-stable hay , a little dung almost ) , notes of orange m : silky , coating , lingering , pleasant o : worth drinking , a little one-dimensional with the brett .

i could not get much out of the aroma with this one .  almost looks green in its pint glass on my computer desk . fairly aggressive pour that would have 99 % of all other hefes spilling over the sides of the glass , leaves me with only a mediocre head . body is lemon yellow when held to a lamp , and in lieu of the usual cloudiness , this is clear with 1000 's of individually recognisable particulates floating around .  the mouthfeel is good , but obviously does not improve the flavor !

s : pine hop bomb at first ... mouth-watering in its pungency . then a floral and cinnamon spice aroma that -- and i apologize for saying this -- reminds me of urinal cakes .  poured a very pale yellow color with monstrous white puffy head than was soon only a memory .  very nice feel .

to start off , good ole raspy on the front scares the crap out of me . i get a little rubbing alcohol in the nose . even as it warms , that alcohol smell sticks around . i think this one would be interesting to age to see if that mellows out a little bit . the alcohol is in the taste , but not as strong as it is in the nose . this stout is good . definitely something that should be sought after by stout lovers .  appearance : light straw-colored , little head and no lacing .  m - light to medium carbonation with medium carbonation .

i could n't smell anything . but i could taste a lot .  pours into a pint glass a very , very pale yellow with just a little bit of foam .  flavor is malty and sweet , and on the finish , bubble gum ! mouthfeel is firm , and drinkability is high .

it smells a bit skunky right off , but if you let it breath for a moment or two after you open the bottle , the smell goes away .  a little white in another pale lager . passable overall rather than a standard macro .  let me first say that the brugse tripel used to be one of my favorite beers . nowdays its called brugge tripel and the taste changed slowly ... but a lot of small steps make a big one and today this beer is nothing what it used to be . smell of spices and a little hops , not fresh at all and a dull taste make it just a drinkable beer but nothing great like it had in the past .

s-almost no aroma but what is there is mostly sweet with a hint of pine . t-somewhat watered down flavor overall . overall , not a great ipa especially when the label talks up the 120 minute boil and the hops . it 's actually quite watered down .  pours a dark copper color with no head . good clarity , but the complete lack of visual carbonation was a turn off .  m - crisp and refreshing o - overall pretty meh .

s : some spice notes in the aroma -- cloves , cinnamon , and nutmeg -- followed by sweet caramel and vanilla aromas . there are some floral notes in there as well as a touch of sweet citrus . t : similar to the aroma , spices come up front but do n't overwhelm .  bottle , a : pours almost an amber , a shade or 2 darker than an average pils , fizzy head with fair retention , no lacing .  m : light body with good carbonation .

if you get it in a bottle it 's not as good since they distribute this beer in green bottles and you start to get some skunkey flavors . this is a very grainy pilsner with a slight hop aroma and taste . this beer is very true to style . that said , if you like a hoppy beer then pass on this one .  poors out with hardly any head and has an amberbrown color with lots of white haze .  it is very finely carbonated , giving a tickle on the tongue .

s -pretty skunky eurolageryness . besides the skunk it 's not too bad .  this is an easy to drink ale , but there 's nothing really to write home about . be careful not to drink this right out of the refrigerator , as it is really surprisingly bad when cold with a terrible mouthfeel . still , i 'm impressed that goose island has so many beers to i find very drinkable , and they are able to do it in large quantities .  carbonation is right on par .

s : clover , grassy . cooked rice .  i bought this can at a nepali night shop . when poured only a small white head develops . the colour is golden pale . i emptied it & # 8230 ; not because it was good , but because you don & # 8217 ; t waste beer .  feels right in body , but the taste is just off .

the label on the bottle i 'm drinking has a coat of arms , 2 cherries and says the abv is 6.8 % . the smell was the first thing that weirded me out ; maybe i was expecting more of a lambic-ness , but the smell had a funk that i found hard to place . what the hell was that smell ? dirty underwear ? the taste started okay with a tart , bitter cherry flavor but followed by a metallic nastiness that almost pressed down on the back of my tongue .  this is typical beer of a brazilian macro brewery . a pale industrial lager as many other brazilian competitors , with a little more bitterness .  m : light-bodied on the palate , with a slightly creamy texture and average-to-lively carbonation . d : i just do n't think it tastes like a real lambic .

smell is weak , faint caramel malt and slight sugary adjunct aroma .  pours a clear , and very light golden color with barely any head .  - 3.0/5.0 feel - coats the mouth well , with a bit of pepperly aftertaste .

mmm , some nice simple roastiness ... some decent not embarrassing like naked in a dream lacing ... medium mouth for a porter ... '' m-i-l-l-s fuck off '' ... a low end-decent middle of the road $ 35 hooker kind of beer.. and by the way , who the hell is cole porter ?  uh , it 's lemonade . pale yellow , slightly cloudy . you know , like when it gets up to 79f in seattle .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated and good level of thickness - probably the best part of this beer .

the phenol aroma overpowers any bouquet the brewer may have tried to put forth .  appearance - the muddy water brown stout was cloudy and when put to the light did not have a distinct or appealing color smell - faint smell of whiskey and apricot taste - starts nice and finishes like a train wreck ... sickly sour at the end mouthfeel - not much to speak of drinkability - i would take many other mass produced stouts , i dont think i would pick this up again .  m : felt good going down had a nice thick feel to it .

the smell has nothing . this beer was light and crisp in taste !  a-cloudy yellow/golden color body with a thin head.no lacing and this looks like cloudy piss .  good mouthfeel , crisp , medium body , good carbonation which is refreshing for a warm weather beer .

the nose is a bit unpleasant .  the beer was so black my laser pointer would not shine through it ! the beer poured a poor head that was gone soon as i finished pouring .  it had a really good mouthfeel .

s - has a metallic caramel aroma ( pretty weird ) , crackery malt ... there 's barely any aroma to this beer !  the color is pale yellow with good carbonation .  mouthfeel is light to medium and has a soft feel .

s : very wine like . some cheap malty notes you usually find in cheap fruit flavored drinks . light vinegar . t : nice amount of raspberries and acid grapes .  not a very exciting beer . it poured with a dull yellow hue , approximate 1/2 head , but clung well to the glass .  the body is on the full side , though not quite as much as most stouts ( i suppose increased attenuation should have been expected with the switch in yeast strain ) , and has a solidly low key carbonation .

lots of lacing s prominent aroma is a hard to describe variety of hoppiness . there seems to be an almost plastic or soapy smell going on that is unpleasant .  appearance makes it seem like a wheat beer . in a clear glass looks a lot like cream soda which is , maybe , what the brewer intends with this cream ale .  m : well carbonated and thick , fairly heavy . fits the style .

smell : slightly aromatic . okay .  pours into a pint glass a very light golden yellow with a big foamy , but rapidly receding head . looks like a macro beer looks .  m - medium bodied with some soft carbonation .

s- smells very much like adjuncts to me .  poured into a tulip glass . the beer was a cloudy golden amber color , a bit darker than i expected , big white head that recedes quickly and left no lacing . drinkability is limited by the prominence of the alcohol and the disheartening sight of a glass of beer with absolutely no head and no lacing . it just looked dead in the glass .  this one is crisp and carbonation is at a good level . body is n't as light as i had expected ; this one 's medium-bodied .

standard aroma for a light beer -- but this is a pale ale ( ? ) .  pours a bright , clear yellow/light gold , with moderate white head about an inch thick . retains for a few minutes , then quickly vanishes , leaving no lacing . typical weak lager appearance .  m- medium bodied with a decent carbonation level .

there was no bad smell to this , but there was no good smell to it either . there was simply no aroma of any kind . this beer is pretty much odorless .  it looks like flat coke .  mouthfeel is nice and full and slippery without any carbonation .

my best description for the smell , and sorry if it seems like i am ripping on the beer , but it smelled like leaves that had been in the gutter after a couple of rains , with a touch of sugar added .  i 'll tell ya in college , if your drinking bud light that is a good night . it looks like your typical goldish yellow and smells like . . . well like bud light , im sure if your reading this you have had it so there isnt much to compare it to .  the mouthfeel at the start was mildly crisp and finished dry and smooth . the unbalanced flavors knock down the drinkability for me .

not much in the way of aroma , except for some caramel from the malts , some metallic hops qualities , and a hint of pine .  murky cola brown body with an exceedingly brief wisp of bubbles and a short-lived ring of bubbles providing the only signs of life . not too impressive looking , but things get better soon enough .  no complaints as the the mouthfeel , medium bodied with a pretty sharp carbonation .

pale in color , low in taste , high in making you run to the bathroom . i also can still drink it when it gets hot without wanting to vomit .  hazy golden color with no head and no lacing . it is not completely flat but nothing formed during the pour .  medium mouthfeel .

anyhow , it 's yet another rare euro pale that is apparently only sold in russia and iowa . smells light and weedy . nothing much going on here , though absolutely nothing is off .  a : pale straw color , looks like a macro . the carbonation looks weak but feels good on the tongue .  the mouthfeel was decent , medium with adequate carbonation .

something smelled off but the taste was good .  no carbonation really to speak of . no head forms at all , and therefore no lacing .  i like the feel with some prickly carbonation and moderately light feel and some creaminess from the head .

lots of carbonation in the pint glass i ca n't place the aroma , seems earthy . not the most pleasant smell . i do n't note much for aroma hops taste is malty , fairly light in taste , small bittering finish . not a great version of a munich style beer .  i knocked back a few of these at a restaurant the other night because all they had on tap was miller and bud products . appearance : poured slightly darker than a budweiser , but i could only tell when i held it right next to a bud . had no head but that 's no doubt the bartender 's fault .  the mouthfeel is crisp overall .

the smell lacks any character . it 's hard to distinguish anything from the nose .  pours a clear gold color with a thin white head . no real lacing to speak of and the head was short-lived .  mouthfeel is thick and smooth , no watery sensation at all .

s- aroma 's are actually very faint . hard to pick up on anything . some yeast and clove , but very faint . d- nothing overly special about this beer . best aspect may be how well the alcohol is hidden , which does contribute to some good drinkability .  it 's appearance is a fizzy , yellow colored average looking beer . thats this beer 's only huge upside .  m : medium-bodied and creamy ; high carbonation ; mouthfeel is this beer 's strongest attribute , in my opinion .

surprised to see a harvest ale categorized as an amber instead of apa or ipa , but the aroma confirms that style choice . put simply , this smells of nearly nothing . if i really concentrate i can pick out a little spice , ala a pumpkin beer .  not terribly impressed however . and i think the green bottle adds to a slight skunking of the beer . tasted like a typical american macro lager , not much now to add . i think i 'd order a bud over this in the future though .  mouthfeel : smooth and medium thick , low carbonation .

the aroma is not very nice . it 's incredibly boozy . a bit of solvent , nail polish remover aromas are in there as well . the taste is not as boozy as the aroma . the aroma hurts the drinkability and it does n't taste like a well made imperial stout .  a clear pinkish color , almost like cherry 7-up mixed with pale ale . no head to speak of .  nice creamy mouthfeel .

pours very clean and carbonated golden color.the smell was not to apparent and almost none at all.the taste was like strait carbonation i 'm talking like battery acid , but i loved it.i have never had something with so much carbon that tasted so sweet but strange at the same time.definitely a must for me and i would definitely recommend to anyone .  poured the carta blanca from a bottle to a pint glass . very , very thin looking .  medium carbonation .
smells of yeast and not much else .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  light to medium bodied , with a very smooth mouthfeel .
not much smell maybe a little malt .  pours yellow , clear , small white head .  m : creamy and spot-on carbonation .

the smell is oddly like dirty river water , which kind of turned me off at first .  pours an amber color with reddish hues , looks more like a red ale than anything else , not much of a head and what there is fades fast , no lacing on the glass .  m - good mouthfeel , coats a bit like oil but smooth .

the smell was almost completely absent .  1995 lambic bottled in 2000 and drank in 2004 . poured a pale hazy yellow beer with almost no carbonation , which was to be expected .  mouthfeel : medium body , medium carbonation overall : this beer has almost no taste , pity

utterly without a hint of sweetness , and very lemony-tart . from past tastings i seem to remember some fruit aroma , but i do n't get any fruit except the tartness that makes me think of lemons .  good thing they told me this was a hefeweizen on the label , because otherwise i would n't have been able to tell . golden yellow color with an awful lot of clarity for a hefe . do n't think i 've ever seen a hefeweizen that 'd been filtered this much .  but , also an odd smell kind of like salami . this must be some nasty phenol created by the yeast . a bad yeast flavor here and a lot of it . i usually love unibroue brews for that complex yeasty quality but for some reason this one tastes a little off . that lunchmeat aroma and now this bad oily yeasty taste make this beer almost undrinkable . i doubt it considering it 's called edition 2004 , we 're in 2005 , and it 's 10.5 abv .

smells interesting and fun . the taste is floral and spicey .  a - pours a clear orange color with decent carbonation . the head fizzled out before i could even look at it long enough to see what color it was . obviously no lacing here .  mouthfeel is fine for the style .

it 's yellow . smell : it has an unusual smell . not skunky , but funky .  sprecher 's version uses real bananas . orange hazed brew is nearly cloudy . fizzy at pour and fizzy from the head , which drops down to a minimal ring around the glass .  the mouthfeel was quite good , though . well carbonated and it felt good going down .

it just smells like beer .  pour was boring , even for the style , as the beer had little head that vanished quickly and left not lacing on the glass as it was being consumed . color and body are yellow and looks fairly thin . as for budweiser , i would advise ab to make sure they keep the flavor in bud , and leave it to bud light to cater to the people that do n't like the taste of real beer .  this beer feels almost delicate .

there lacked a adequate smell here . there was a malty smell , but very slight .  for a white ale , this is pretty translucent . not terribly impressed -- looks somewhat like a cloudy average big brew ale .  the mouthfeel is smooth and oily and the carbonation is alright .

the smell had a hint of bread and fruit , but just a hint .  but today , i finally decided to try it , and though its appearance is not good , it 's got a strong taste .  it is medium bodied and smooth in the mouth .

slightly sweet aroma . light , sweet malt , bit of corn . no hops . immensely drinkable . i 'm still convinced that corn is a much more acceptable adjunct than rice .  a-pours with no head , no carbonation , and just some white bubbles around the rim .  pretty refreshing , not overwhelmed with carbonation .

reviewed from notes : appearance : orange copper with a 1 finger head smell : bourbon , vanilla , fruity taste : sour fruit , something went wrong in this bottle mouthfeel : mild carbonation , medium body , overall : i think i 'm going to need to try it again .  well the appearance is rather limp .  the palates leads with a thick , malty mouthfeel up front and a sticky , resiny bitterness in the back .

smell was intense and unpleasant .  appearance : light , clear straw color with a medium sized white head that dissipates very quickly and leaves no lacing behind .  m : mouthfeel is crisp , light-medium bodied and pretty dry .

even after serious swirling , this beer smells like nothing but cocoa puffs and pale malt . but i wish i could try it on cask , maybe then it would have some complexity and real aroma .  a painfully flat and lackluster appearance .  still for such a big beer it had a great body , just not sure if i would want more , until it got about 5 years on it .

i am not impressed with the smell , as it reminds me of a wet morning in a cornfield .  12 oz bottle into a rare vos 3/4 pint glass appears murky and super-light in the glass . not much head but alot of slow-moving crazy carbonation .  mouthfeel : soft creaminess , light to medium carbonation , with a medium to full body .

s- smells grainy , little bit of corn , little metallic , almost white wine smelling .  it is a light straw colour with little to no aroma . there is yeast floaties which adds to the ugliness of the beer .  pours a cloudy , almost 'chunky ' looking way -- looks a bit similar to an apple cider ( non alcoholic kind ) . caramelly sweet too . vanilla . taste is what kind of throws me - again , both the oak ( taste of whisky barrel ) and smokiness are there . i like both of those favors in my beers , but combined , my jury is still out : like they are competing for my affection . alcohol is quite present too , which seems to go well with the aforementioned whisky oak . a lot going on in this brew .

not too impressed , as others in 6-pack had poor smells but also tasted fine . t : sweet , malty , biscuity m : carbonation , good lingering mouthfeel for golden o : a decent , very drinkable golden .  pours fizzy yellow gold with alot of pbr type nose .  mouthfeel is good and thick , finish is dry with a moderate dose of alcohol present .

smells amazing . chocolate and some buttery , boozy notes emerge with warming .  litle head and a amberbrown beercolor with white haze and big flocks floating .  aroma : hops . the crystal hops dominate the aroma . the malt is there , but overpowered by hops . but i do n't taste the balance that an esb should have . the hops weigh far more than the malt in this beer . notes : this tasted like a very good ipa , but did not have the balance i was expecting , for an esb . a great beer , but did n't fit the style as well as i would have liked .

very clear brassy color s - smells like two skunks fighting in an old oil drum .  pours a clear darkish iced tea color with a fizzy 1 inch beige head that fades to nothing . no lacing whatsoever either . i was expecting something disgustingly gross but i actually really enjoy drinking this one .  oily mouthfeel with next to no carbonation . quite thick and heavy , coating every area of the mouth .

smell is of fresh hop , so fresh.just layers of vegetal , cirtusy hops with a slight hint of pine and pale malt .  lots of bubbles . no head what-so-ever , no lacing either . looks like sparkling lemon koolaid .  everything about this beer was pretty light - light , crisp malt scent ; light fruity taste ; light body . feel - 4.0/5.0 - refreshing , which was really nice .

excellent . sweet and sour fruits cominate the taste , but caramel malts creep slowly in , along with alcohol , honey , and even some wood . the feel ends up pleasantly sweet and smooth .  pours a lot like the american macros - pale yellow and a very small head that disappears quickly .  smells sour , big nodes of orange and very tart lemon juice . there 's a bit of a funky hop in there , as well . no real spice of which to speak , nor any hint of wheat . very sour , almost cidery . starts more tart , like lemon juice , moves into a dryer , white wine middle , and ending on a more of a light , semi-sweet orange sour . a unique beer , to say the least . could benefit from a bit of something at the end , but is drinkable enough as it is .

the beer was poured into a weizen glass and looked the business : murky , dull amber with the usual huge head sat on top , just like all the best hefeweizen . where was the normal aromas of vanilla and banana , no cloves or anything else for that matter .  now i am stuck with with the remaining 5 bottles with no one to try and pawn them off on . this beer was a terrible dissapointment and had really no pumpkin flavor at all to it . it had quite a bit of cinnamon to it but no pumpkin flavors .  mouthfeel is nice & creamy .
