the nose , however , is rather unpleasant . rather prominently hoppy in the english vein , this initially has a very noticeable soapy , mildly cleaning-solution like aroma . once it breathes for a bit , it does become better , changing to a rather pungent ekg aroma . a mild toasted white bread-like malt sweetness is present as well .  a - pours just the lightest clear gold with a thin white head that dissipates quickly , leaving nothing but a steady stream of carbonation bubbles . a bit better then your average adjunct , but an adjunct nonetheless .  m : fuller side of medium-bodied with moderate carbonation that tickles the tongue and throat . this aspect of the beer is really nice .

smell is quite tart smelling , bit of sweetness , can easily make out the raspberry aroma .  a : pours light golden with a white soapy head that dissapears quckliy with a sizziling sound . no lace . d : a rather uneven beer ; looks crappy and smells below average but tastes ok and has a really nice aftertaste .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a soft prickly creaminess , along with some easy slickness in the body that helps that raw feeling finish go down . just a smidge of alcohol is felt but it is n't overly noticeable .

in the world of light ales , this one wins the color award : yellow , even bright yellow hue under decent head . ah , that somewhat skunky hop aroma that is much more pronounced in a rolling rock . lack of malt or sweet in aroma had me prepared for the worst .  this beer simply looks awful . i try not to judge beer by its outward appearances but since the ba ratings system includes a weighted 20 % value based on visual appearances , ill just play along and call em like i see em . and this beer looks awful . ) in fact , this beer is hideous to look at , but delightful to drink . it has a very active measure of carbonation , a bright honey-apricot color , and a strong aroma that is distinctly belgian and musty .  m - nice and creamy in the mouth , goes down smooth .

almost no aroma . creamy nitro texture .  undated bottle , but these just arrived on the shelf at a street wines , so it shouldnt be too old . head is small , rapidly fizzling to a ring of bubbles , beer is copper to very light auburn-amber and though the bottle has no sediment left in it whatsoever , the beer does have a decent chill haze . no lacing on the glass , head is off-white .  the mouthfeel of this beer ( outside of taste ) was great . great carbonation , bitter hop aftertaste , medium bodied .

not much aroma , but what is there is a little wheat and breadiness , and a dash of grassy hop aroma . taste is bready , with a nice grassy , floral hop bite and bitterness . miles better than the aroma . feel is light and crisp , clean and has a nice refreshing quality about it . drink ability is high , though it 's nothing particularly stellar .  with the 5.9 abv , this is equivalent to putting down around 9-10 macro lights , like coors or bud light .  mouthfeel - good smoothness , a medium body on par with the style , crisply carbonated .

o : well , this one was all over the place ; the smell reminded of euro pale lager , the taste was more like german pilsener but way to mild .  black color turning to a yellow gold around the top . once again it looks very thin and watery . low marks are in order here .  mouthfeel is quite nice and full .

a very faint , very vague fruity aroma . a nice lead malt caramel taste .  appearance is wholly lacking in any kind of head - so obviously no retention or lacing .  m- felt just about right on not too thick .

very blond to light gold in color . slightly unpleasant vegetal , crackery aroma with a hint of coriander . medium-medium light body .  soft white to off white head begins at two and three quarters inches falling to one quarter of an inch within five minutes leaving no lace on the glass . hazy dirty gold in color . large quantity of sediment entered glass despite careful pouring efforts .  m - good carbonation and it finishes clean . good light to medium mouthfeel .
looking and smelling the beer wo n't do much for you .  poured a typical macro pee-yellow .  m : easy drinking with medium-body and low-moderate carbonation .

the aroma is not good at all . it smells like corn with some chlorine mixed in for good measure .  zero lacing . color was very dark brown , almost black .  as i drink more my palate adjusts but it does n't ever really get over the off flavors m - pretty thick , not too carbonated , nice mouth coating qualities d - burnt coffee does not go down very well , plust the thickness of the beer limits my ability to quaff this completely i like coffee , i like stouts , and i like a lot of coffee stouts ( new glarus and founders breakfast stout for instance ) .

s : sweet malt for sure . moldy wood and cooked veggies .  clear piss/apple juice color with a bit of chill haze . thin fizzy white head that fades to a sickly smattering of froth .  m : moderate carbonation with a decently viscous mouthfeel .

smells like tin foil .  pours out of the bottle with just a thing layer of foam that disappears almost immediately . the body is really a dull amber body with not much going on .  finish is very grainy and `` off '' lol mouthfeel : full-medium , creamy body with moderate carbonation .

s - my first reaction from the smell was a bag of crushed malt . it just smelled like 2-row pale malt . the aroma also threw me off a bit . the can does say `` all malt '' on it so i 'm assuming they tried to get it to be more malty than normal ipas , i just think they overdid it . the aroma is nothing but malt , and not even specialty malt , it 's all base malts .  clear yellow filtration victim of a beer screams anything but quad . first sip reveals corn syrup and chardonnay .  mouth feel is more medium bodied than the wheats i 'm used to , a nice change and the full blast carbonation leaves one a happy advocate overall it is lacking smell , good in flavor , great in feel .

the aroma , however , was weak and suggested skunky cardboard to me . not inviting .  on tap brigantine seafood restaurant poway , ca pale straw yellow with a pitiful white head that dissipates almost immediately .  m : lots of carbonation , but a pretty smooth medium body nonetheless .
there was next to no aroma , perhaps a hint of malt , no more .  a hard pour produced nothing ! very interesting color .  mouthfeel : medium body with smooth carbonation and a dry finish .

overall , nothing all that great here , especially with that odd smell . it goes down easy enough , but i really do n't wan na put too much more in me .  still feel this is easily the best us macro-brewed light beer . this is my go to beer if i 'm out tailgating or watching sports and need something cold , refreshing and in a quantity that wo n't have me draining the wallet . i will take this over bud or coors , everytime .  m : creamy to a crisp finish with a good carbonation throughout .

smells sort of like wet hay or grassy . body is fairly light with a thicker coating on the mouth feel than i was expecting . otherwise leaves little aftertaste , and not as watery as many similar brews .  appearance low head . looks uninviting .  i did n't want to buy this because i do n't trust twisted pine to sell me a good beer . since i am a sucker and i love hoppy beers i bought it anyway . the smell was very hoppy citrus , pine and something off i could n't place until i tasted it , butter . this beer was quite disappointing and i poured out the remaining 13 or so ounces after i finished my first glass .

aroma : weird fruit , obvious guess would be peach , but alas it is not obvious .  pours a hazy 24 karat gold color , with considerable amounts of chunkiness floating in it , despite a very slow pour . protein flakes everywhere in the beer , makes this truly disgusting to look at . no head and no lacing to speak of .  fine mouthfeel , nothing objectionable , but it 's not a stand-out lager either .

after hearing such good reviews about this malt i decided to give it a shot . and after finding a 24-pack of 16 ounce cans for under $ 12 at my favorite local distributor , i couldnt resist . i must say that this is by far the best malt liquor i have ever tried . it is much lighter in the mouth , without the repulsive taste of familiar malts ; it is also smoother in the throat , as well as being lighter in the stomach than any other malt liquor i have tried .  appearance : orange-amber color , clear . little to no head , no lacing .  mouthfeel -- nice , an initial carbonate bite followed by a foamy smoothness . , molasses , pepper/spice .

t : hugely ( and distractingly ) sweet . almost medicinal o : a very complex sipper of a beer that i found overly sweet . enjoyed the non-ba version much better .  mother lager- magic hat `` you 're never alone with a bone '' mother lager poured a light yellow with no head .  mouthfeel - some creamy smoothnes , well-carbonated .

i have tried this beer two ways ... ..with and without lime in it . my advice is to definatly drink this with a lime . a lime improves the taste significantly . thats why i rated the taste and drinkability higher than i would have if i would have reviewed this without adding anything . this beer appears pale with a small head that dissapears in the blink of an eye .  a - pours pink with half an inch of white foam and soda-like carbonation . looks an awful lot like some kind of fanta .  lighter body and a nice lively carbonation .

a : straw lager coloring , half finger head with nice lacing . s : not much on the nose at all , nothing negative but nothing really positive to say either . d : very drinkable , i wish i had tried this brew before and will definitely be having again to support my local brewery .  poured into a .2l stange , this brew is a clear gold with a negligible white head . no retention or lacing .  mouthfeel is nice and light , with adequate carbonation for the style .

it is an odd aroma , there is n't much there , but it smells a bit sour .  i am a little concerned about the complete and total lack of head on this one . there is no head , no carbonation and no body .  m : smooth and round .

ok malt scent , not an aromatic beer really . starts out mildly sweet with a decent herbal hop assault .  this beer being a macro lager , still is a very good beer , is nothing to be impress about , this beer have a light gold color with a little bit of head.very easy to drink , not a hard taste or a hard feeling on the mouth .  creamy mouthfeel with the addition of oatmeal in the mix .

... smell needs major improvement ... heads abit low for my liking ... golden copper in colour ... hides the abv quite well ... lacing is very nice ... smooth and drinkable but lacks that special something to make it stand out ... 'jiminy jilikers ' ''  pours a pale straw yellow with a soda like head that recedes fairly quickly . mouthfeel and drinkability make this beer , like most macros .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and crisp . good carbonation , but the overall trainwreck of flavor in the brew makes this one hard to take down .

smells grainy but little else of note .  it poured a murky , yellow-white color . very hard to describe . it also was corn .  mouthfeel is medium , well carbed , nice on all fronts but where it needs to be . big failure , in my opinion .

pours a nice clear golden with an average head that dissapated before i took a drink smelled a bit skunky ( surprise surprise ) with some sweetness in there .  a good hot weather outdoors session beer , can only get in a bottle , not available in a keg for my kegerator , a shame , need to add a lime and lots of salt , that way i can not taste the actual beer . this is a light beer but not as watery tasting as american light beers and the lime and salt make it something a little special .  the body is nice and thick , with a flavorful malt profile : sweet medium caramel malts with a bit of roast character . hops , by the way , are almost nonexistent , which would n't be bad if not for the oxidation , which makes the faint floral flavor seem dull . overall not bad , but has the same type of oxidized or maybe just oversparged flavor common to other corporate breweries like gordon-biersch .

good clean , refreshing scent . taste = good taste upfront but too much sourness comes through .  it 's all over the place in canada , but i 've never seen it here ... very light yellow , clear body with half inch offwhite head . similar to a macro lager . i 'd drink this again .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with almost no carbonation .

smell is pleasantly malty and sweet .  poured chilled in scotch glass ( all that was handy ) a : cloudy , dark orange ; thin-to-no head ; dead carbonation ; no lacing s : sweet , malty , savory spicing t : very well spiced ale ( to push the amber/red into october ) ; complex ; moderately hopped m : carbonation should be better one of the better october brews i 've had .  medium body , almost non existent carbonation , sweet sticky syrupy mouthfeel . i think the lack of carbonation ruins the mouthfeel and makes this taste and smell overly sweet .

has a nice light and crispness to it . hops are present with a nice bouquet aroma .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass , beer is a slightly hazy , straw color with a pure white , fizzy head . other than the small bits of sediment actively swimming around throughout the glass , looks like a macro lager .  overall , feels unbalanced , too much carbonation and a little too dull .

the smell was pretty good . i was intrigued actually .  i poured my first bottle and poured it out because there were lots of floaties . poured a second glass and still lots of floaties . the color was a sick orange , with a thin head that receded to the edges .  flavor is rather plain , roasty , sweet , a bit of coffee and coco , the hops seem to be hiding somewhere , i detect little to none , little carbonation , short finish , with a bit of dark bread , and rasins , very thin body.drinkable but not very memoriable .

the aroma is sweet and malty with a slight coffee/chocolate undertone .  if you pour it good you can get absolutely no head on it , looks like apple juice when you do .  m : this was the most dissapointing . aside from the lingering dry finish this was a very thin porter .
pleasant aroma is light and spicy , clean fresh ginger .  appearance- cloudy , absolutely no head , and no lacing .  mouthfeel was poor .

aroma is excellent . it 's full of fresh hops , citrus and pine .  12oz bottle a- pours a clear golden yellow color with a fizzy white head that quickly disappears .  body is depressingly light . very nonexistent in the finish . taking bigger an bigger sips just to capture some flavor . smooth , but light . bitterness in the aftertaste follows a big gulp .

yep , it 's a black beer . it started well with a nice head and aroma . sweet fruit and coffee flavors , not too heavy .  magic hat # 9 was left at my house after a party . # 9 pours a very clear yellow with tons of bubbles , but only a very slight head that soon reduces to nothing . the maltiness does come out a bit more in the taste , but unfortunately , it is drowned out by the overbearing fruit .  the mouthfeel is disappointing with absolutely no carbonation and mild flavors lingering around . overall , i could have possibly gotten a flat beer but this beer had potential ( when carbonated ) but it didnt come through in my bottle .

you can smell and taist the black berry .  a : the beer is clear pale yellow in color and has no visible signs of carbonation .  mouth is thin and watery . too simple and too one dimensional and thin .

smell is nice wheat , spice , sweet malt .  i poured this strange brew into my tumbler at 50 degrees . the beer ? had no head whatssoever . it looked like beer other than that .  mouthfeel is thin for the style .
good . t : watery banana upfront with some bitter sugared malts .  a - straw yellow , clear with no head .  2.5 m very light , i am not impressed . it is very close to water in feel .

s- lots of coffee , and *tons* of that smoky flavor you 'd expect from the title . i actually ... do n't like the way they jive as much as i thought i would , but it 's still nice . t- this is actually ... kind of disgusting . very nice d- not a fan .  three of some of the great brewers together to produce a lovely , artistic bottle with minute text on the back outlining the mikkeller history from loving the pale yellow american macro-beers of the past . the first thing noticed was that it poured much like the `` fizzy yellow '' macro-beers mentioned ; but this soon darkened a bit with a 1-2 finger white head that soon disappeared without a lace !  the mouthfeel is syrupy and shows none of the carbonation that the pour hinted at .

nose is devoid of any real hop presence , clean caramel malt , hint of ethanol , perhaps a light floral presence . lots of piney bitterness but lacking much aroma hop presence - not shocking considering the aroma . sticky caramel and bread malt base , resiny pine bitterness with a long finish , alcohol present in the finish .  not very beer like . more like a sparkling apple juice . color is a somewhat dull gold . no head .  aside from that , the taste , like the smell , is unremarkable mouthfeel is borderline watery .
the nose is full of notes of raisiny notes as well as distinct hoppy character .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  the mouhfeel is weak , watery , thin .

smells good , like lindeman 's framboise lambic .  a : pours a deep brown with a soda-like head that quickly fizzes away to nothing . zero lacing .  taste is weak , almost watery , has to be drank ice cold or has a taste like vomit . bottom line is compared to other cheap beers pbr excels in taste , quality , and conveniently the price , 7 bucks a 12 pack .

very fresh and clean smell , hardly any yeast aroma .  the appearance was an opaque golden yellow that left a thin white head that dissipated quickly . obviously , little of the head was left clinging to the glass . on the second pour in the same glass , there was more of a head , and more apparent carbonation , but still was not impressive .  smells basically like apple juice . watery . also , the carbonation that was so present during the pour now seems dulled . for all its faults , in the end rogue makes a malt liquor that achieves what you usually want out of the style .

aroma is strongly chocolaty , with a hint of alcohol . taste is a let down after the nice aroma . roasty cold coffee with maybe a smidgeon of bitter chocolate and metallicness .  on tap , looks unimpressive , same with smell .  m - thin , watery , overly carbonated .

i had not heard of this kristalweizen style before , so i thought i was reviewing a straight wheat , but here goes . aroma is really hefty considering the low abv and general weakness of the flavor . there 's a great bit of bready yeast and a big malted wheat aroma . exactly what you would expect .  very pale yellow and not much head . minimal bubbles floating to the top .  mf : it 's medium-bodied at best despite the label 's claims of `` full bodied . '' speaking of which , it has a soda watery type carbonation , not at all the `` luxuriously smooth '' of the label . i have to say that they could get the mouthfeel under control ( i 'd imagine this is less of an issue on tap ) , it would be hands-down my favorite irish stout .

smell is cherries , sour , rather pleasant . smells like a sour beer .  i was lured into the purchase by the pretty pink cherry blossoms on the can and my desire for the neverending hokkaido winter to end.. the beer is a thin yellow , with light , fast-fading bubbles . there 's a light , roasted grain taste which appeals ... until ... the incredibly nasty aftertaste hits , which sends shivers through the body .  mouthfeel is equally watery .

such a teaser the nose- complex and swirling with sweet notes of cocoa powder , toffee , freshly ground coffee , raisin , prune , brown sugar , peach and apricot . ) with a low carbonation , a mild and poorly integrated sourness , and a bigtime cloying sweetness upfront- the unfortunate result of the beer 's sweet chocolate flavors clashing head on with the brown sugary fruitiness . like i said , the nose is nice , but it really ends there .  a : one finger head devoid of cream , of bad thickness , and average retention . cloudy lemon-yellow colour .  very thin , and barely any head .
smell : cocoa , as expected , along with some good roasted malt . smells like a promising porter .  it really reminds me of drinking zima .  it 's highly carbonated , and extremely astringent .

sfruit and caramel jumps out right away , faint alcohol , plums , some spices , but not sure what they are , mildly sweet and floral tlike drinking fresh flowers , also spicy , some sweet honey and caramel notes , starts mildy sweet like candy , then sucks all of the spit out of your mouth with its dry , perfume like finish .  the head was very disappointing . the beer looks filtered like most of stone 's beers . it is a dark amber color .  mouthfeel : terrible . after drinking half of this bomber , my mouth is completely numb and i am starting to feel comatose .
s - this beer smells pretty good . resiny , tropical goodness .  it appearance is awfully light in color to have blueberry flavors .  mouthfeel is thin and weak .

aroma : an amazing , complex aroma which far exceeds any other pils aroma i have smelled . lemony , peppery , summery , yeasty and malty all zipping around my nose . taste : does n't live up to the aroma but is n't bad .  very weak yellow color.. bordering on clear/yellow , with a head that adjusts well to pour speed , stays very white and leaves a cute belgian to look at .  mouthfeel : absolutely no carbonation .

original rating date : august 28 , 2008 pours a nice copper , almost no aroma present . smells like almost nothing , more like fizzy lager than an actual pumpkin ale .  pours a peachy , almost lemonade in color and fizzy clarity .  the mouthfeel was thin and not terribly hoppy on the palate .

aroma is husky corn some sour hops and a bit of skunk i think . not the most appealing scent ever .  this one pours a pale gold color with a hint of malt in the smell .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is very high , way too high , for a milk stout . the body is thin . drinkability : just an ok beer , the mouthfeel also hurts the drinkability .

dark thick brown/black , and i even managed to get an good tan brown head out of the pour despite the alcohol s - smells of pure sweetness , syrup , dark barley , coffee , chocolate , and a touch of the booze all together t - here 's where the `` no thanks '' comes in . complex indeed , but ugly and overpowering .  pours clear pale straw with a small head . overall a very average macro .  m - thin , a little harsh and a bit drying .
seemed nice for the style .  my least favorite of their beers ... this pours a super light straw , watery color .  mouthfeel is excedingly thin and watery .

smell = lots of alcohol and zest . a candy like sweetness , smell almost exaclty like strawberry twizzlers . intesesting scent . taste = too sweet and syrupy with the alcohol packing quite a punch to boot .  clear yellow color , brighter even than many other light beers .  really thin for an imperial stout .

s : sour aroma with apple , citrus , and raisin notes . d : this brew looked and smelled good but is way off the mark on taste .  appearance : pours a medium viscous piss yellow color .  tastes first of caramel , then of grain , and finally thin , fizzy bitterness . for all its color , finishes bone dry with a tragically meager mouthfeel .

strong caramel & malt aroma with some floral hints .  i drink miller light because it 's lower in carbs and calories then other beers yet still has a good beer taste without a bad `` light beer '' aftertaste . it might not be a premium beer for special occasions but it 's a great everyday-beer for the everyday drinker .  mouthfeel is watery . this style needs more body - the maltiness is there , but there is very little roasted character & not enough creaminess .

smell - apples , citrus , yeast and alcohol .  the weakest 'imperial ' anything ___ a : deep , dingy clear ruby body with essentially no head .  maybe a little dusty , but i probably dislike the low carbonation & tackiness more . my tongue feels like i just drank a pot of black tea .

the beer poured an amazing color to be expected from a good stout . very dark , with a slight head . the smell was very obvious of cherries , with a slight hint of coffee and chocolate . i was happy with this beer until the first taste . well the initial taste is definitely cherries , and the typical stout taste was lost on me .  review from notes pours copper/auburn with a pinky of cream colored head . zero head retention & lacing s : apricots & leafy hops , persimmons as this warms t : much dark fruittyness ; figs & apricots , plus breadyness & leafy hops & a touch of butterscotch up front .  the mouthfeel was then utterly unimpressive . overall , the drink looks good but the taste and feel are way too thin and watery .

s - cherries , duh ? but what smelled like very sweet cherries .  appearance - super clear pale and yellow , looks like discolored water .  very pale straw yellow color , hazy but filtered look no aroma noted water like very light bodied taste and looks like water ... . however better than most would give credit to seeing how its bud .

aroma is a nice spicy hops with a good bready , roasted malt to it .  thos brew pours out as a clear yellow color with a fizzy whit sheaf that last only a few seconds .  with a near-white head , very little in the way of roasted quality in the nose or taste , and a very thin body , this reminds me of a weak porter with a slight coffee aroma .

it 's aroma is a schnauzola full of banana & cloves . this is a very easy to drink & refreshing german wheat .  pours copper amber , with a quickly vanishing cream colored collar .  palate scraping astringency . the lack of carbonation particularly makes me wonder if i should have given this more time in the cellar to condition .

very nice . smells light , not expecting much malt in the flavor . where are all those delicious hops i smelled ? as with many ipas , i find that it smells better than it tastes .  appearance : very pale yellow .  the carbonation and the bitterness overpower the toasty flavors .

o : a pumpkin ale that smells good , but is overall just too bland .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1 inch head .  the lack of body really disappointed me . while surprisingly drinkable , this beer needs to be heavier to match the taste , so more body and more alcohol are needed .

back in the aroma i am digging the rich toasty bready stuff . there is a bit of the aroma 's promise for maybe a quarter second , then , `` wham ! i would imagine that if the flavor held to the aroma this would be a nice red ale that i could drink a ton of , but this one just is n't right .  the wife wanted to try a fun fruit beer , my choices were limited , so i grabbed a sixer of this ... neat 12 ounce bottle with silly dog cartoon thingy on the label . let 's see how `` wild '' this blueberry beer is ... a : poured in traditional pint glass at 40 degrees . holy fruit beer , batman , this one 's a clear , purplish red with a light purple fizzy head that fades quickly leaving no lacing and a small purple/off-white collar .  very light bodied , an ok mouthfeel.. just way too watery and thin , not much for taste , just some lemon zest on the after taste .
lots of citrusy , hoppy aromas a bit of good barnyard funk .  yellow-brown beer with a fizzy head that dissolves right away .  on top of that , the beer tasted a bit flat and felt thin .

a bit muted , but in a nice direction . t : low hop bitterness , low hop flavor for style .  had one the other night , but this actually tastes better on a fresh set of taste buds imo ... pours an effervescent ebony with a finger+ of brown/chestnut colored head . zero head retention & lacing s : chocolate , coffee & iron t : coffee , dark chocolate , & iron up front .  the feel is fizzy and watery thin .

not a whole lot stood out in the aroma . flavors : spices with ginger , some bitterness , and a roasted malt and coffee finish and aftertaste .  pours out coppery , with no head to speak of . their are a few bubbles , but no real foam .  as many others have said , i 'm not liking the extra carbonation .

the aroma is very belgian with lots of sour fruit lacto , weaker raspberries and cherries , dusty basement .  it is n't as big ( or swillish ) as bud and is heavier than bud light ( no pun intended ) , but there 's nothing here . i can get watery chug beers lacking flavor that are cheaper .  it is entirely too thin for a stout .

s - nice hop aroma with a few floral notes .  a-poured yellow with mild cloudiness and a thick head that quickly faded . carbonation was strong initially , but also slackened off rapidly . no lacing . this is my go-to cheap stuff .  mouthfeel was pretty watery and went down quickly .

s : very tart , almost of a peach mixed with lemon . t : just ok . extremely peachy , but in a sour/tart sort of way .  poured out a darker yellow with maybe a half pinky head that dissapeared immediately .  thin to medium mouthfeel with zero carbonation -- lifeless .

smell is wonderfully floral and hoppy . not floral or hoppy , but more like perfumy .  this was a golden yellow , and my bottle looked different than the label on the site here . very thin head , even tried to pour a little harder at the end to see what would happen ... nada .  the mouthfeel is quite disappointing due to carbonation that is much too high for a stout and a body which is not thick or creamy .

does n't look like much , more like a cheap domestic pilsner , but smells pretty inviting .  there is absolutely no head to be found on this beer when i receive it .  smell is not overwealming , but seems sweet with hints of yeast and hop . watery , yeasty , sweet ... more corn than i thought there would be ... taste relatively one-dimensional , unfortunately . fairly drinkable though ... inoffensive and cheap ...

very malted , to hide the spices ? very corriander , hoppy , and yeast with a bananna aroma and taste , and all of this adding to mouthfeel .  a- hazey pale orange . if i ignored the small foamy cap i 'd swear it was some sort of orange soda made with juice . i would n't buy a 6-pack , and if i had a choice of this macro and blue moon i 'd choose blue moon .  in body and taste , this is so akin to water that i find it very drinkable .

smells very nice , with strong citrus/lemon/fruitiness , and a good dose of floral .  it was the lightest colored beer i have ever seen with an average head and lace .  feel : active , assaulting carbonation and a light , watery body .

s : very heavy on the mint , with some alcohol and roasted malt . smells like a peppermint patty . t : initial punch of mint followed by chocolate malt .  a : pours a clear weak yellow with a thin white head which does not last long at all .  it actually smells more like a belgian dubbel . it does n't have much complexity and it drinks very watery . this is by far the thinnest quad i 've ever come across .
the aroma is surprisingly subdued .  near zero head . not an attractive beer . it looks dead .  although the mouthfeel is thin for a stout , the flavor is pretty good .
it has a deep coppery crystal appearance and an invitingly crisp , sweet , floral scent .  it 's a pale clear yellow with little head or carbonation .  carbonation is too high .

s - coffee with with a hint of sweetness . t - a solid coffee taste in the beginning ... and that is where it left off .  very small head , particularly for a wheat . it dies to literally no bubbles and therefore no lace . the finish is milky and short lived .  very little mouthfeel , this beer is meant to be drank ice cold as implied with the cold indicator on the can unlike most beers that i drink .

sherry-like oxidation is unfortunately , very profound in the aroma . nuts and ripe fruits are present in the aroma as well , with hints of peanut brittle , caramel corn and mocha . the mouth experience is quite tame , considering the style . unfortunate oxidation initially on the palate , while on the mid-palate ripe fruity esters and mocha hints are present , which leads into a caramel , port-like finish .  a : pours a copper body with a very small off-white head with extremely poor retention and no lacing .  very thin , and watery . lower carbonation .

aroma : a pleasant smell of grapefruit like hops , with some malt coming through .  appearance : very cloudy , much more so than an average wheat beer . the head was almost nonexistent , but had decent lacing for whatever was there .  color very pale green or lemon odor , which suggests more concentrated lemon juice only freshly cut lemon slices , but preserving a small mouth , perhaps a bit too much . the lager that is the basis must be extremely low in taste because the body is still very watery , just a few hints of lemon , no sugar but not bitter unfortunately .

i had the sour face when you suck on a lemon . the aroma is good and very profound with strong notes of figs , raisins , and heavy malts .  pours a cloudy and murky light urine color with a slight head that dies quick and doesnt lace .  mouthfeel was stingy and watery .

aroma is malty with pleasant notes of bananas .  pours a light yellow with minimal head and lacing .  the mouthfeel on this one fluctuates but it has one of the worst finishes i can recall in a beer . the thin body and soda-like carbonation ( and some wheaty texture ) save this some , but the finish is just harsh . artificial flavor , sticks to the teeth , chewing on cardboard , something is wrong here finish to the mouthfeel .

i poured this beer into my tumbler at 45 degrees the beer was a amber color that had a big caramel smell .  a - this beer was light . almost transparent . a clear as sprite , but less bubbly . s - corn , mild hops , mild algae smells , a bit sweet . mostly because the pilzner hops are cut back and other flavors of the corn barley and local water come out .  m : water thin , light side of champagne-like carbonation .

smells nice , a bit fruity , with a refreshing effervescent quality . does smell a bit on the citrus side .  alright , enough flack from all you real men who dont drink light beer . sometimes drinking 5 imperials of barley wine and washing it down with 10 plates of nachos is a little overkill . theres nothing wrong with enjoying a light beer every now and then . im not in love with it , but hey , i dont like soda and this is a good pick for lunch or after the gym when you dont really need the full impact of a heavyweight brew but need a little refresher . it is somewhat enjoyable , a lil funky and it tastes better than the usual na beer . so all in all , i think its a decent stab at a low cal/alch .  its rather thin in the mouth , and doesnt ready leave me wanting more drinkabilty - with its high alcohol , and bitter mocha overload , this beer doesnt do it for me .
this smells delicious , close to pumpkin pie . some good , some bad on the taste .  pretty plain-jane . very light color a real pale yellow .  feel is thin , dribbly and loose .

the aroma is similar to homebrewing wort with hints of cereal grains and corn syrup . it smells good but its way to sweet for my taste .  this was always my emergency beer ; the cheapest sixer at the one place that stayed open latest . tastes pretty cheap and watery and best served ice-cold-as-possible .  mouthfeel is painfully carbonated . light bodied , way way to much carbonation .

the aroma was semi-sweet , a blend of slightly doughy malt , caramel malt , floral hops and herbal hops .  pours an unexciting see-through straw colour with minimal fizzy head despite my vigorous pouring efforts .  it was very thin bodied as well .

fruity aroma of pinnaple , banana , carmelised candy sugars , some peppery spice , and a touch of warm alcahol fumes .  well , it gets really hot down here , so i figured a caribbean beer would be good yard beer for the summer . anyway , this was a decent one , definitely a good one for the heat , maybe one to take fishing with me . maybe it 'll show up here this summer .  the palate is not unpleasant , with plenty of that molasses , clove , and dried fruit and some decent maltiness , but this beer is very light in body ( hence my unusually low `` mouthfeel '' score - i rarely dock or add points here unless there is significant deviation from stylistic expectations ) .

smells really nice , with a flowery and wine like bouquet , with a sweet slightly malty aroma .  pours a bright orange color , not much of a head at all , some carbonation is visible ... looks like cider instead of beer .  very thin feel , little oily .

s - instantly linseed and lemon peel smells entered the room when the cap was popped . some honey-comb sweet waxy smells and a bit of powdered sugar .  it appears clear , and with a fairly pathetic looking tan color head , that is very thin , and settles to a patchy looking film . not an enticing looking brew ... s- this area is better , with aromas of sweet caramel , coffee bean , and dark chocolate dominating the smell .  m : thin , watery , light-bodied , not something you 'd expect with the smell .

s - not very aromatic , but smells fairly sweet and malty . t - biscuity and bready .  served in a nonic pint glass , the beer pours a hazy gold color with about a 1/4 inch white head that went away pretty quickly . no lacing whatsoever .  the mouthfeel needs work . it is n't creamy at all , it is just really watery and lacking carbonation .

a : pours a hazy orange color , good sized head with nice lacing down the glass s : smell is of sweet ripe citrus fruits .  the pour is flat and the head is dismal . due to their being no head , there 's subsequently no retention or lacing .  it 's low in carbonation and a little thin and watery , which is a real shame .

i do n't like stinky beer and this one stinks , literally , like cabbage farts . pale clear gold color . the aroma shows up in the flavor too , but not as bad .  a : a head that lasts for an average time , that left no lacing nor foam at the edge atop a beer that 's a red-brown ?  for some reason i do n't taste the citrus like everyone else does ... m - thin and flat . propagates through the mouth pretty easily though .

smell is lots of walnuts and figs ; it actually smells a lot like a spanish sherry . not as complex as some but this has a powerful sweet nutty odor like a port or sherry wine . taste is not as good as the scent i am afraid .  very little head and no lacing to speak of . not a great looking beer , frankly .  carbonation is much too high .

honey is very pronounced edging near a braggat . both in the aroma and the taste . the hops are non-existent until the finish were they are quite strong . overall i think it 's too sweet and i could barely finish the sample . too cloying .  only a tiny bit of apple juice yellow color . corn and rice but slightly malty m - it 's surprisingly viscous for this type of cheap canned adjunct .  for a russian imperial this is even for 9.7 incredibly weak and watery it 's the first thing i notice . the mouthfeel on this is not good , it 's even weaker than most american stouts i 've had .

the aroma was gingerbread spice and cinnamon spice with some light caramel maltiness . almost the aroma of allspice one finds in a pumpkin beer .  pours out a light , pale yellow that gives the impression of a basic beer . almost no head , even from the tap .  very light in body with a slick mouthfeel at first that becomes almost slimy .

s- the smell is strong . its one of those beers that can be smelled half way across the room . there will be no fooling the officers at the check point on your way home from having a glass of this . it has a milky , chocolatey smell with a touch of roast and grain . its appealing and quintessentially stout .  12 oz bottle : aroma light wheat , tart , acidic , lemon and lime , very very slight cardboard aroma . pours a clear golden with the slightest hint of amber and a small sized white head that diminishes into a soapy film . flavors are going all over the place , but not in the layered ... mmmm , complex sort of way . overall , it 's drinkable but nothing stellar to say the least .  m : watery , very light-bodied , body of a light lager .

s - incredibly complex smell . fruity , hoppy , and a smell of a cleaning solution ( from the copious amount of alcohol no doubt ) .  bought this as part of 12 pack variety down ar kure beach , nc , bbd of 1 sep 07 , consumed mid-july poured a hazed amber with 1 ' of offwhite head . zero head retention or lacing s : slight sour notes & some apricots t : apricots & apples with some hop bitterness up front .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a fizzy carbonation .

s - coffee ( duh ) , cocoa powder , and a mild pleasant sweetness t - initially hoppy followed briefly by mocha .  it pours a very transparent yellowish gold into a glass , it 's not much to look at .  the mouth feel is very thin for a stout this big and has almost no sweetness .
well , it smells pretty good at least .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  fizzy carbonation and no body .

this is one of the sweeter smelling stouts that i have had ... its got a milk chocolate backbone along with some other sweet fruity notes . it smells rather sugary and sweet for a stout , but i like that . beyond a pour and a couple good whiffs this beer goes downhill fast , this beer is extremely watery , and not rich like the smell would suggest .  lacing is sparse to nil . too bad the appearance is hum-drum .  very watery . the mouthfeel was thin and watery as well .

the scent is very good ... roast and espresso ... .unfortunately the taste was like coffee ground in water ... .was n't creamy or had body ... which is what i like in my stouts .  s- served from a chilled 12 oz bottle into a pint glass . a- light , almost clear with a yellow tinge .  the body is very thin and watery and the carbonation level is medium low which does not compliment this beer at all .

sour flemish aroma , sour apple , somewhat like a wild ale . numbing sour mouthfeel , with significant carbonation , refreshing . not for a newbie .  almost no head , a tiny rim of almost non-existant film . not very impressed .  fizzy ... gross . m- watery , thin , minimal carbonation , and nothing lingering .

the aroma is what one might expect from a northwest ipa . it has plenty of citrus hop character and only a rumor of malt .  half finger tan head that shows poor retention overall . no lacing at all sticks to the sides of the glass which made me a little sad .  the body is a bit thin and feels too bubbly .

sweet and fruity aroma with cloves and a little bit of funk .  pours a very pale , clear yellow color with an airy white foam that fades in a matter of seconds to nothingness . even for an aal , this one does not look great .  s. nonexistent . m. also nonexistent . just plain and unoffensive . light beer on amber side ? nothing to brag about but goes down like water . above average in it 's class .

smell , while better then grasshopper is dissapointing for the style , wet grass and wheat , not much else of anything .  `` the circus is the place for me with bears and clowns and noise . '' - phish despite a hearty rousing circus boy pours a mostly clear gold . 1 finger white head that does n't do too much . poor showing for a wheat . light grain , grass and lots of butter .  it seemed to have very high carbonation .

the smell is fresh and hoppy with some sour hints of wheat .  a : pours a flat straw-gold ; zero head , zero lacing .  i do n't taste any pecan ... m : thin . not to impressive in this dept o : do i love it ?

smells of roasted hopps with mild hints of chocolate .  it pours red-orange with suspended red particles . the head dies down quickly and leaves no lacing .  the sweetness died out in the taste , however , which was flat and slightly watered-down . a weird bitterness gave an unpleasant mouthfeel but still not difficult to drink .

laces well throughout process s-smells like a coffee stout ( what a shocker ) . smell the roasted coffee up front with a slight chocolate malt i think t/m-eh , it does its job well , it tastes like it should .  a- super pale straw .  mouthfeel is too thin for me .

nose is pleasant , full of citrus and wheat , and an undefined spiciness .  a - classic green bottle . pours a dark gold with a fizzy soda-like head that goes away quickly .  mouthfeel is awfully watery , though not completely distasteful .

smell : ah , now we 're getting somewhere . super saturated bock aroma , fusels , brown sugar , surprisingly sharp citrus notes . as it opens up , cherry and vanilla become more assertive .  almost no head , carbonation or lacing observed .  medium bodied , but watery .

while i am a huge barleywine fan , i just do not like this beer at all . smell is that of apricot an fruit .  with fairly aggressive pouring i got a small to medium sized off white head that quickly faded to almost nil and no lace .  still has some things that i 'd consider defects that define budweiser 's trademarks ; it 's got plenty of personality but not enough charm . overall seltzer water vibe , which shoots beer right up your nose like soda pop . do n't pass it up if you 're at the brewery , simply because it 's not too shabby when it 's this fresh .

smelled great very rich and malty . unfortunantly that aroma did not carry over in the taste which was on the weak side .  if you cant drink beer out of a mug its not a beer ! appearance- pale clear yellow smell - not much more than a hint of beer odor taste- clean . very light and clean . drinkability- easy to drink .  the mouthfeel is thin , with excessive carbonation that gives it a slight harsh feeling on the tongue .

had a very hoppy aroma upon first sniff . second whiff hints at fruity aromas that almost smell like a fruit salad .  i think on the right day with the right food it 'd be a fair beer - like a hot summer day doing some yard work . the beer seemed lighter than miller or bud light to me .  ( m ) thin mouthfeel with some bitterness loosely gripping at the tongue , barely holding on .

the smell is malty with distinct notes of alcohol . not very pleasant . the taste is a little better ; it is very malty with lots of bread-like flavours .  poured a very light gold colour that was extremely transparent . it looks thin , if that 's possible .  the mouthfeel was a bit thin and watery .

s : the weakest aspect of this beer for me . general maltiness is all i get . t : the key here is balance ; a supremely well-crafted beer .  kind of a cloudy greyish color . not very appealing to the eyes .  m : despite its creamy appearance , the head feels thin on the palate . the brew itself is thin and watery , especially as it warms . the carbonation barely registers .

this beer is nothing like a farmhouse . d : the aroma was the only really likeable characteristic of this beer .  a - pours a pale straw colour , finger of head with little retention or lacing .  taste : decidedly like its nose , only more so ; large notes of bittersweet chocolate and espresso rule the roost , here ; not nearly as sweet as you might imagine ; total lack of carbonation left the impression of a somewhat light , thin mouthfeel .

an impressively hoppy aroma . some citrus aromas , some biting alcohol , and caramel malt . not particularly interesting and relatively one-note , but certainly hoppy .  pours a very light , very clear yellow colour , with a minimally weak head of white , which dissipates almost immediately to a loose collar around the edges of the glass , despite a pretty vigorous pour . minimal lacing . looks very insipid .  mouthfeel was very watery and not smooth in the slightest .

love the idea of a beer from utah being called polygamy anything , although i 'm not sure how the people who run that state would feel . anyway , at first glance this is a beautiful dark red porter in the glass with a nice chocolate milk head that did dissapate a little quick . the taste of chocolate malt is very mild , if fact you have to wait 5-6 seconds after you swallow to really taste anything . i could drink this porter but for a purist , this would not hold up . a nice try , and not a bad brew , but not worth any extra effort either .  with the last `` porterish '' day before summer actually kicks in upon me , i rate this from a 12-pack sampler ... chocolate-vanilla notes adorn a mocha-soda tint with flatlining head and zero lacing ... like experiencing a cologne bottle ... malty punch ... obtrusive , almost as `` no shit '' as flying dog provokes on its label ... a too smooth ( oily ?  m : very overly carbonated to the point where it was difficult to drink early on , mild acidity , medium-bodied .

the lightest `` light '' beer ever ] for my taste but my friend , let me tell ya ... it will get ya drunk .  a - poured out a straw yellow color with a bubbly , white , two-finger head .  3.0 m thin .

dusky crimson-glinting brown adorned with a fat gob of buttercreme suds . rum-steeped fruit nose , a la fruit punch with cherries , pineapples , and apples , then backed with a stanch vanillin oak character . begins with a tepid fruitiness . again with the cherries , pineapple , and apples . yeast come in and sprinkles slate and sandalwood earthiness . it leaves a semi-acrid and astringent burnt coconut essense mixed with a tannic and lingering sense of black cherry skins as it rides out forcefully vinous . light bodied , but it feels fatter with some element of clinginess . the barrel-aging really just ruins this .  very pale yellow colour with surprisingly thick head .  way too carbonated here , which hurts the mouthfeel quite a bit .

hobgoblin is a very easy going down brown ale that is a perfect session beer .  next time , i 'll have the server recommend some sake to try ... it seems asian macros are rather predictable . i like the bottle design , for what its worth ... beer poured a clear straw into the glass , which was provided ( kudos ) .  pretty nice . the body is as thin as water . that leads to a very drinkable beer , actually , since it goes down ... well , like water .

s : a nice hop smell with aromas of pine needles and citrus .  i actually like this beer with a nice slice of lemon or lime . taste pretty good when it is ice cold but do n't let it warm down or the skunkiness comes through .  feel of almost flat carbonated water .

pale , cloudy body with little white head that fades quickly s. a cirtusy lemon , banana scent . nice t. sharp zesty taste , leaving a weird lemon aftertaste .  my father is a bartender . he works at an `` old man bar '' where the options are pretty limited and there is n't much to do but bs and drink and maybe watch some tv . heineken is not a pretty beer , but do n't let it 's asthetics get it the way of your enjoyment . i would never turn down a free heineken , but if i needed to pay for it i would likely select something else .  m- thin highly carbonated .
the is such ah wonderful ber to watch as it 's poured .  appearance - murky witbeer like appearance . not very presentable appearance at all .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

smell is sweetly malty , definite dark fruit edges ... quite appealing .  i see this currently ranks 202 out of 205 for the style ... no way this is that bad ... there are many macros worse ... with that said , i am not a big a-b fan ( used to work for a miller distributor ) ..this is at least as good as bud and cheaper ... it pours a light straw color ... .about a 1 inch head settles to virtunally nothing ... .no lacing evident ... .nose is cooked corn and cereal grains ... body is on the lighter side of medium but defnitely not watery or thin like some ... .slick ... not real charged up ... flavor is basically adjuncty sweet cereal grains and corn meal ... .relatively sweet for the style ... .no hop bite at all ... .  the body is light and really deters the taste .

smells really good for a belgian strong dark so i 'll give it that , but the brett and sour cherry components were just not there as i thought they would be . could have been but the aroma was n't bad so i have my doubts .  cloudy golden color body topped by a thin white head that quickly fades . a hefe with a quick-fading head ?  the herbal hops will become medicinal with traces of alluminum and will become a bit less appealing as it goes from a zippy feel to rather stagnent . a flat and bitter hop flavor is the finish .

the smell is also quite pleasant and interesting . apple skins , lemon zest , belgian candi sugar , complex alcohols , malt backing , and dry-ish . it is a terrible combination .  the color is moderate golden . something is wrong with the color on this one . no head and no lacing on the glass .  the presence of tannin explains how , while quite watery , satan red is also quite drying .

s - smells of citrus and bananas . very strong fruity smell . no hops or malts in the aroma . smells like a very strong soda .  a - light yellow straw color .  the finish is lightly sweet rather than crisp , and the mouthfeel , which started out thin , ends on a watery , undercarbonated note . zywiec is an average epl , making it a below average beer in general .

the smell was fragrant and very boozey . it wafted cough syrup memories .  pours a pale gold colour - almost looked silvery coming out of the bottle . looks like a dull impersonation of beer .  thin and watery .

the smell was nice . tobacco , chocolate , caramel , molasses , dried plums , brown sugar , and a hint of soy sauce .  a : very pale yellow with literally no head or lacing at all .  alcohol is very well masked for a 6.5 % way too much carbonation for my liking .

smell leaves scets of caramel and roasted coffee , and a very sweet smelling milk scent . very appetizing .  pours light golden , but the head is extremely bad , disappears within one minute and there almost is no lacing as well .  the mouthfeel is pretty thin and watery .

smell- smell is eathy herbal , a hint of brett is present , i am getting the sweaty horse blanket aromas that are present in belgians , i havent had too many english ipas i am not sure if this fits the profile t- is not what you would expect from a stone beer , im getting a strong grapefruit bitterness , with a lingering sour note in the back of the palate .  it was a light , translucent yellow in the glass with a filmy head . a thick lace would form as i sipped , but it would quickly slide back down into the beer . but it was not as wheaty as a hefeweizen .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .

n : citrus , pine and light caramel notes . t : lemon citrus and pine upfront followed by hints of navel orange and some very light grains in the background .  pours a clear , unassuming yellow , with a minimal , filmy white head , and an exceptionally light body . fine carbonation and decent lacing , but it 's hard to ignore the fact that this looks like a big pile of nothingor at least , it looks like any other pale american adjunct lager .  i thought that the mouthfeel was kind of watered down ... it needed more `` oommff '' .

not much in the aroma department , a bit of faint roasted malt .  a=pours a thin , wispy , nearly headless yellow straw color , nearly the same color as a lot of bmc adjunct lagers . very , very weak appearance . i have seen some amazing looking hefeweizens but this it not on the same level .  mouthfeel sucks . the viscosity is where it should be , which is the only reason this gets anything above a 1 for mouthfeel . low carbonation is acceptable in a beer like this , but no carbonation is inexcusable . drinkability is ok , but the alcohol heat definitely shows up , and the poor mouthfeel does not help either . alot of promise in this one though , would be quite tasty if it was carbonated , and not quite so hot .

appearance : dark brown , not ebony , slight retention , no lacing smell : some roasted and coffee aroma taste : flat , low on taste , just not much there .  weal yellowy macro-ish pour with white fluff head that disappears in a blink leaving little to no lace . this would be fine at a show with cheap taps or as a cheap can of hipster irony .  flavor : then , i drank some & everything went downhill . it was watery & disappointing .

dark roasted malts , espresso , bitter chocolate , vanilla bean , and some black currant . very one dimensional with little complexity . you mainly get a big slap in the face of dark roasted malt , with some bitter chocolate , and coffee in the finish .  head forms at two fingers , lots of bubbles that fade quickly to a thin foam on the surface . zero lacing whatsoever .  tastes like someone put artificial flavoring in carbonated water .

color is a brilliant ruby/amber with minimal haziness , smells of honeyed ginger and spice exactly as promised on the label , flavors of gingerbread and spiced christmas cookies come through cleanly just as promised by the nose , fresh , sharp , and clean flavors overall that really make me feel like the holidays ... if only there was carbonation , it could have been something stellar .  typical coors characteristics : dissappearling head , pale color , low bitterness .  the flavor was spicy and malty and the mouthfeel was tingly along with a burning sensation as it is swallowed .
restrained aroma of toasted coconut and rich cocoa .  a- pours clear orange , no head at all , no lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel was very light bodied and again , watery .

nose is pretty simple and straightforward with pale bready malts and a light hop profile . yeast notes that draw me to this style are seriously absent , instead you get a lot of gummy nothingness . the aroma is n't bad , it just plain is n't , save a subtle spice and a hint of grain .  clear yellow with a mediocre white head . no retention , no lace .  m- this is precisely the opposite mouthfeel that i want . it feels like it wants to be sweet and sticky , but it really just falls watery on the tongue .

the smell was good .  had bottle of this which revealed a light gold-yellow color . disappointing overall for a brewery with so much god damned hype around it . a very forgettable beer unfortunately .  overall feel was very thin , not impressive and not terribly satisfying .

smells pretty good .  corona light , abv=4.5 % , cals~~109 , light lager reviewed 10/20/08 @ home , bottle & gt ; pilsner glass a 2.0 - very pale straw in color , little to no head at all s 2.0 - minor hop & malt notes , semi skunky smell in background t 3.5 - pretty good taste for a light beer , crisp on palate , minor hop finish mf 2.5 very thin body as expected , super carbonated d 4.0 - pretty enjoyable for light beer in taste & drinkability .  body is pretty watery .

there is no doubt about it , it smells like blueberry syrup mixed with malt liquor and it smells good . of course , malt liquor mixed with blueberry syrup can only taste so good .  not attractive head , with big bubbles and falling . not compact .  m - crisp start but the finish ends up being very watery .

overall : nice smell , average taste but the rest is forgettable .  appearance : this brew is classified and a standard american adjunct beer , and thas is exactly how is should be classified .  taste is that of a standard belgian wit , but the body was off-puttingly thin . it was watered down , far too light for my tastes of wit beers .

s - spicy , fruity hops . pepper and lemon with some floral hints of jasmine and a bit of basil . the hop character is fantastic , especially in the nose , and the bitterness is neither harsh nor overwhelming , but rather refreshing .  so i pour ... very clear hay yellow color with a quickly-dissolving soap bubble head . now it looks like diluted apple juice .  no attempt whatsoever to hide the alcohol and the addition of the heavy acidic espresso taste and a watery mouthfeel make this hard to down .

s - nice aroma of cider ... that seems to be a recurring theme for me with this beer .  dark brown with some read hues . no head with just some carbonation lacing .  empty , chalky mouthfeel , not much going on here .

the aroma is exceptional as you can smell this ale when you pour it out of the bottle . deep dark fruity ester mingle with a citrussy coriander spiciness make for an excellent aroma , this is the first beer i have tried in which the aroma exceeds the flavor . the rich aroma led me to a letdown as the flavor was much more subdued than i expected . the body of this ale is an immense letdown as a scotch wee heavy imo should have a bit more viscosity and sweetness but this is a rather thin ale in terms of body . the scotch ales always throw me off due to the lack of hops and for some reason i have a hard time enjoying tha malt flavors unless they are balanced by a signifigant amount of hops .  pours a pale straw without much head .  good lacing down the glass s : coffee , sweet bready malts t : coffee , slight harsh maltiness also slight hint of chocolate m : light very thin bodied beer .

s - fruity and sweet and alcoholic . very different than a raspberry lambic .  this poured the palest yellow i have seen in a very long time . the head was bright white with very small bubbles .  better than expected , but as someone who despises ab products + light beer i was n't expecting much trouble is , within the same can it tasted like lemonade in some sips , water in others . giving it a 4 on drinkability because it 's light , so one could drink a lot of these if they chose to .

super cru appears like it should , starting out with a leather-mahogany color , frothy head . does n't smell too bad either ; nice belgian yeasty notes and the added pear .  sitting at a grass and bamboo bar in honduras , one is told to reach for another brand of drink . this beer blends well with the salty brine that has infiltrated your mouth and sinuses . the rejuvenating characteristics of a cold port royal feel great to a body that has been pickling in the briny deep all day .  the palate is way too thin for a stout .

a bit too sweet ( confectionery-like ) but still nice . flavours suggest that unibroue has got a perfectly acceptable wheat beer and then dumped a truckload of apple lollipops into it .  appearance : pours amberish brown in color with a surprising amount of sediment in the beer .  2.5 m thin , with only the grain tastes and the slightest stickiness keeping it from being water itself .

highly aromatic nose of fruity , herbal resiny hops .  pours as a cloudy orangeish color . resembles frankiszer but has some sediment floating around in it - probably just active yeast culture . definitely wonky - has a smell like that of wheat beer but it is n't a wheat beer . has kind of a coriander-orange peel aroma with a touch of wheat ( appears and smells like a blue moon but with a lot more color ) .  this is a drinkable brew that definatly packs a punch , but it 's kind of one dimensional and thin .

odd sweetness behind the tartness , still had no problem drinking a few glasses of it at la mort subite cafe in brussels though .  pours a really bright golden straw color , no head at all . it 's super transparent and looks basically like a bud , not very inviting at all .  the mouthfeel is confusing as it feels too thin for the amount of sweetness on the taste buds .

aroma is actually quite good . sweet rasberry aroma , mixed with a nice lager like smell .  a : pours a mahogany color , very very flat . absolutely no head , no lacing .  the mouthfeel is astringent .
smell - the scent of brown sugar and slight spice .  zero foam , head or texture .  skimpy in body , vapidly dextrinous and approaching watery in mouthfeel .

s - a rich and very fine woody scent , malts there too , and a sort of cheap candied fruit aroma as well . t - quite poor actually considering its pleasing aromatic character .  this beer is everything i feel an oktoberfest should n't be ... mild flavor , light color , poor head retention and lacing , not much by way of malty goodness .  appearance : golden with extremely high head with low head retention smell : sublte hop aroma , taste : light and refreshing , herbal with some decent hop flavor mouthfeel : light bodied , way too much carbonation , jeez ... drinkability : great flavor belgian pale but its overcarbonated .

smell : mild to relativley unpronounced aroma . faint trace of both fruity hops and bready malt .  for export only fill 12 12 02 the appearance when poured into the glass was of a plain yellow color , nothing fancy , and it boosted some carbonation .  m - too thinned out , would guess this is medium bodied but seems like they cut this one with a little bit of water or something .

s - a little barley and some tangy fruits like orange/pear/apricot t - starts off with that specific fruity flavor that came from the nose and leads into a good amount of alcohol and finishes with a sweetness and very little hops .  at just 7oz , this beer will only fill up your glass about 2/3 full , so feel free to give it a hard pour right down the middle . even with a hard pour this pale yellow beer only made a finger white head that disappeared in about 30 seconds . this beer was skunked beyond belief and i was n't sure i would even be ale to drink it , but after i let it sit and breath a bit , most of the skunkiness wore off and i was able to pick out a sweet grainy corn smell .  seemed flat and had a flat taste .

s : a rich toastiness . the sweetness has a faint caramel that is reminiscent to a lightened wee heavy . d : okay , but really nothing to go crazy about .  this beer is lighter than light . pours very light gold .  m - way too much carbonation for my taste .

s : this is an obvious german pilsener - pure malt together with nice bitter hops in balance with the slight fainter floral hops .  12oz brown bottle ( not metal ) into pint glass . crystal clear light hay color with a thin head that does n't last long . almost no lacing . very clean light malt aroma .  m - light bodied , very thin feeling , and very little carbonation o - not too impressed with this beer .

s : hops , herbs , tangerine , yeast t : toffee , bread , flowers , lemon peel . this disappointed me a bit .  pours a pale golden colour with a good creamy white head , very densely compacted and fed by steady carbonation . lots of very thick lacing . looks like a lager should .  mouthfeel is indeed excessively thin , leaving a slight tingle of carbonation , but otherwise going down like iced water .

lots of lacing . smell : big vanilla and caramel with a slight hint of roasted malt . i was ready for sweet , but this is easily the sweetest beer ive ever had .  pours a brassy yellow with a solid foamy head that laces the glass nicely .  the mouthfeel was flat and very dissapointing .

smells very different than any amber i have had but still smells good . t - i get some of the spices and hops but tastes very watered down , really disappointing .  big , black , thick and sludgy looking . nice looking half a finger of leather head . some visual spotty lacing .  taste is rich and sweet , slightly nutty , but this beer really sufferes from it 's thin and watery mouthfeel .

the smoky aroma was evocative of a tantalizing backyard bbq wafting my direction , but that merely hinted at the in-yo-face smokiness of the brew itself .  a- the head is bubbly bubbly slightly creamy brown with a reddish tinge . holds nice to the glass . the body is dark again brown with a red hue- murky .  chocolately , dark . dry chalky taste , sweet . some warming . watery porter-like .

sour fruit to the nose .  we seem to get a lot of rogue out here in south bend and im glad to see that we get some of the special releases like this one too . poured brown , clear dark earthy color .  mf- watery and too light bodied for a red ale . mouthfeel lacking .

a- 3 very light blonde color reminiscent of a cider , with a minimal white head which dissipates to practically nothing quickly . s- 4 the aroma of this is more like white grapes to me , similar to a wine , but the peach is definitely there in the background . it smells as if it will be refreshing ... t- 3 it is hard for me to get past the tartness of this brew .  daark brown body with plenty of carbonation , topped by a hefty medium to dark tan frothy head . good lacing .  m - flat , uninteresting , a little oily .

a- deep brown with mahogany hues , 1/4 '' tan head with little retention and films of lacing s- coffee , roasted malts , rich , alcohol , strong scents t- sweet caramel and buttery malts flavor but balanced by strong burnt astringencies , alcohol evident throughout , strong at finish , some chocolate m- somewhat creamy , stiff carbonation with ho alcohol at finish and in after d- complex malt flavor but alcohol is to strong and carbonation comes off as awkward .  appearance : pours a clear golden with a fluffy white head that thins to a persistent layer .  m - extremely carbonated .

aroma is quite subdued . subtle citrus and toasted malt about sums it up . taste follows suit , but offers a bit more .  poured a nice garnet hue with a slight off white head that barely lingers with minamal lacing going on .  the mouthfeel was flat leaving a watery feel in the mouth .

s : lots of oak and bourbon . big bourbon smell really dominates . it 's followed nicely by a big chocolately middle , and a dry coffee finish .  beer pours a very nice hazy light amber color with a nice but not lingering white head .  far too thin and light for a bock . carbonation was assertive , but the body just felt thin and watery .

everything from the nose is lost to sweetness , very disappointing .  alex keeps feeding the beast ... a sexy can served in my darkness glass ... pours a super clear medium gold with about three fingers of head . the head just looks weak , watery and whispy but it actually hangs for a bit and has surprisingly full lacing ... a medium skunk aroma , rice , alcohol .  starts with fruit taste , looses interest with a thin mouthfeel and water middle although helped by a supporting co2 texture and some tartness ( carbondated water ) ending with lactic acid and dry pucker on the back of the tongue and esophagus .

a-black , thin light tan head s-surprisingly i 'm not picking up not much more than a light hint of sweet potato , and possibly some cream . very very unique for stout t-i 'm getting some coffee notes with a sweet potato after-taste but more than anything this beer is just watery . it is absolutely a terrible stout .  appearance seemed good , super pale golden yellow with a billowy head of white foam just over a finger high , not bad for a lager .  flavor is of arange , and body is highly carbonated . prickly mouthfeel , and a bit boring overall

s - tart cherries right away with maybe just a tad of artificial cherry candy smell , and some dark chocolate . i like it . i wanted to like this because it looked and smelled very good but just took a bad turn after that .  close to black . fizzy , airy big brown head .  too thin .

aromas of sweet caramel , brown sugar , clove and other spices . nice , very sweet malt up front , caramel with some chocolate in the middle . looks , smells and starts out good but the finish ruins the drinkability in this one , not balanced at all .  330ml bottle poured into a pilsner glass appearance- light and golden , bright and transparent . good 2 fingers of head , which dissipates very slowly .  md - thin and not much of a body to it .

smelled of sweet malt , rich and heavy .  an average pour with a little too much head presented a nice clear amber color .  biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel which lacked any crispness/carbonation at all ; practically flat and way too light .

smell figs , sweet molasses alcohol .  a- nice deep-amber body with a good head and great retention .  smell- sweet malt and grains ( sunflower seeds and barley ) taste- watery with a touch of malt acidic hops . mouthfeel- acidic and bitter .

s : bready malts balanced with piney hops , which are hard to separate from the traditional pumpkin beer aromas and flavors . cardamom is the dominant spice . t & m : lightly sweet . d : overall , i 'd like to say that post road pumpkin ale is an average pumpkin beer but it was my least favorite of 2010 .  a : the pour is dark amber/red-brown with a thin tan head forming .  high carbonation and a continental hop aroma mixed with corn . light , watery body with a vegtable-grainy taste . dry , crisp finish . strictly unsatisfying .

s - very strong aromas of tangerine , it smells like i just peeled the skin off of a fresh piece of fruit . d - this is a very strange beer with some over the top tangerine character . it really smells like a piece of fruit , which works well in the aroma but not so much flavor wise .  25cl into a tulip . unexceptional head , nice lacing .  fairly watery on the tongue . i was exited for this one after smelling , but the lack complexity on the palate coupled with the watery mouthfeel made this one a disappointment .

s : a really interesting mix , i get a strong strawberry aroma mixed with a heavy caramel smell . there is also a nice hop/citrus aroma in the middle , some tangerine maybe . overall a really nice beer , very drinkable .  pours a clear august-afternoon sunshiny amber with a small amount of head , about one skinny finger .  high gravity beer , this one is king . drink alot of water when drinking or a major headache occurs . so drink with caution .

s- interesting mix of sourness and sweetness . picking up the barnyard , lemon sourness , with a bit of apple skins and oak . decent , but the sweetness was a bit out of a place .  perfectly clear amber orange . big frothy head .  a thin mouthfeel . extremely drinkable . but that 's all i can really say good about it , the taste is n't great , and the mouthfeel is too thin .

this looks like cough syrup . smells of citrusy hops , hops , and more hops .  the ruination and bastards are extremely well made beers ; beers that i 've converted bpr drinkers with . the colour was nice , looked on par for the style .  m - weak and thin . lifeless .

the smell of yeast and citrus filled the nose . the smell of banana is also there .  had on tap at willimantic cafe in ct. a - pours copper colored with a white foam on top .  mouthfeel : pretty thin , with sharp carbonation and a watery finish .

s : ton of grapefruit , citrus , lemon , pine in the background , smells sweet t : there 's something that just tastes off and soapy . there 's almost a cloying sweetness that adds to the off-taste .  poured a deep amberish brown with lots of carbonation and abid dirty white head that took a while to simma down .  crisp to the point of being overdone , loads and loads of soda like carbonation . notes : ho hum , average , run of the mill , mediocre ... etc .

smell is very spicy , orange , ginger and cinnamon as mentioned on the label , and a bit sweet . taste is plenty spicy and not sweet at all , more roasty , some toffee and a bit acrid .  a : pours black with two fingers of brown head that recedes into a thin layer with a little lacing .  it tastes ok. kind of watered down . cant taste any malt or hops . it was too bubbly , seemed over-carbonated .

s : a nice roasty bitter chocolate scent upfront followed by some hints of vanilla and raisin . a nice cocoa on the backend . good .  pours a deep dark brown , hints of burnt amber in the light .  m- thin and watery this could be improved greatly , but then it would probably be too sweet .

okay , so the nose is a bit disconcerting , perhaps like washing your socks in stewing wort , but the taste more than makes up for it .  a : it looks dark , just like coffee with some redish . i like the color , since it remind me of red wines . i have signed up here because i want to write a review of this horrible beer .  mouthcoating is chewy , tacky and fairly unpleasant . the mouthfeel was distracting but it does become a bit more tolerable and almost smooth once the mouthcoating becomes entrenched .

aroma of sour cherries jumps out while being poured .  looks great on a bar top . amber red with a decent enough head but little retention , surprised to see some good lacings .  m : medium bodied beer but it is a bit light on carbonation . feels dull and flat .

s : strong notes of malt and caramel , sugary smell .  pours a really nice dark red colour , which reminded me of some of the better belgian ales , but there was absolutely no head , though i tried to get some as i quite like it .  mouthfeel feels thin and weak ; this is my only real complaint with this beer .

deep chocolote , caramel , raison , fig and nuts in the aroma . while i enjoy them , i 'm not a huge fan of irs 's , but if i were to compare to version i do enjoy , like abyss or stone irs , this is not very impressive at all . the mouthfeel is too thin , the bitterness is out of whack , and the beer just comes across unbalanced .  has a pretty nice look actually .  mouthfeel is very thin , again very soda like .

strong coffee aroma has me salivating , it is mixed with a lighter chocolate aroma , this beer smells rich with hints of bourbony alcohol . the taste is where i was thrown , there is an extremely lemony tartness in the flavor which may be fine in another style , but not what i was expecting here , especially after the inviting aromas . i 'm not sure if the tartness is a result of roasting the malts and the tangy acidity that follows or something else , but it masked most of the flavors and was very prevalent .  was really looking forward to this brew , but sad to have tried it .  one thing about this beer is it feels extremely watery .

a pleasant aroma with a medium body .  a : nice , clear golden color . very foamy and lasting head with some small lacing .  the body is kind of thin , and there 's too much carbonation , which brings the drinkability down a fair bit .

has a unique floral-like almost medicinal band-aid brett character to it . a different aroma , but an intriguing one . ( t ) - very different from the smell . very dry and bitter with tons of clay . a bit disjointed and surprisingly thin even for the style .  appearance this one had a nicely carbonated orange body with some cool-looking sediment and a promising head .  the mouthfeel leans toward the thin and watery side .

aroma : dark roasts produce mild dark chocolate and black coffee robust tones with an air of nuttiness and tart cherries blended in there .  a : pours pretty dark , near black but not quite , with deep brown hues when held to light .  i 'm no fan of bud , and probably have n't had a bmc beer in 2 years , but this is not one of the worst 50 beers in the world . it 's far better than many of the cheap , crappy pale lagers in many parts of the world . although it had little taste to speak of , it was exceedingly easy to drink , which , for bmc swill , ai n't that terrible .
smell was sweet cherries , dark . toffee .  a : cloudy amber color with a decent creamy head that left decent lacing and remained throughout .  mouthfeel - one of the most water beers i 've had .
