t - surprisingly nice given the weak smell and my general lack of knowledge about the style .  poured from a 12oz bottle into a nonic . pours a clear golden color with a sizeable head that leaves nice lacing down the glass .  definative lack of carbonation , maybe this one blew it 's top at one time or another . body wise to thin to stand on its own without more carbonation , lacking in complexity .

aroma : a great mix of sour and vinegary notes over a sweet malt body . mouthwatering . unfortunately , this is nowhere near as intense as the nose and ends up way too subdued for my tastes .  pours a clear , golden colour with plenty of bubbles . it forms a nice white head at the top that settles to leave a half centimeter of lacing around the rim of the pint which lasts for the duration of the beer leaving a little lacing on the glass although not a lot .  slightly watery body and bland carbonation .

s - the initial smells were malty , yeasty , and complex . i noticed coffee and sweet cake smells in there too . the pleasant malty smells died down after a few min and left the bitter hoppy smell of an ipa t - initial taste was sour and yeasty .  ap- this beer actually looks pretty damn good sititing in the glass .  mouthfeel is very thin and overly carbonated .

very dark yellow , really cloudy , almost looks to be , if it was n't liquid , a good bread . does n't have much smell i 'm afraid to say , there is the slight hefe scent . chew on and let the fruity taste go down and leave you with juicy fruit aftertaste , but this aftertaste is not fakey , it tastes like the real fruit . it 's the most natural flavor in a hefe i 've had . great stuff .  greatful red pours a amber color with strong red and light brown hues . good head and lacing .  mouthfeel very flat for a belgian dubbel .

yeast totally non-flocculating , so even a careful pour would have left 1/2 the bottle behind if i didnt take some yeast . aroma was typical ommegang , sour and spicy with vapors of peach and cherry . palate was less sour than aroma and about 1/2 way between duvel and ommegang ommegang . the `` fine dose of yeast '' did cause massive rumbling in my plumbing later that night though .  pours a deep , dark , slightly orangish brown color with plenty of creamy light tan head that fades pretty quickly , but makes it 's mark on the glass .  taste : carbonated water , with hops and light malt thrown in . mouthfeel : light and quickly fading .

smells great . t - malt initially .  on-tap at bruery provisions the pour is bright orange in color with a finger of white head .  the mouthfeel is unbalanced as if the carbonation and the liquid will not merge . for as much noise the carbonation made on opening the bottle , it seems quite on the palate .

smell : very sweet smell . very malty .  22oz bottle poured into weyerbacher tulip . bottle reads `` best by 12/11/11 a : clear golden honey that paints my palm in an amber hue , with a 1 1/2 finger of soapy white head that clings to the glass as the beer arches downward when the glass is tilted .  m - light bodied and bordering on watery . a little too carbonated imo .

smell is of grains and mustard seeds . this is very weird .  it shows a bone-white head with heavy lace , and a sassy , vivid yellow color with low co2 .  a : it 's still carbonated , that 's something at least . too fizzy .

this is exactly what you want in an american macro lager .  the beer poured very dark brown with a nice tannish head .  heard great things about this , found it in buffalo bought a 96 vintage.started promising i liked the color and the nice head , after that all downhill.had little to no smell , the taste was peppery ( overpoweringly so ) and way to sour ! the beer was way to thin and watery to go along with that taste.didnt finish the bottle just to peppery and thin for me , waiste of six bucks .
s- it does have a nice smell of oranges .  the beer pours dark , very dark , a slight hint of dark brown in the black makes this look similar to a pint of guinness .  tingly , thin watery feel .

this amber ale has a huge sweet caramel aroma with a bit of spice .  appearance : pours a super large 3+ finger thinner off-white head . actually poured relatively clear for a dunkelweizen , then quickly turned cloudy after a few seconds .  m : very thin and watery -- it has a consistency not far from kool-aid .

i love the smell of a good lambic though .  crystal clear , straw yellow with a finger of bright white foam on top . clumpy lacing stuck to the top of the glass , decent head retention .  the mouthfeel lacks more . and flat .

s- strong hops aromas , but blended with sweet barley malt sugars . bright and uplifting scents . lots of stone trademark hops aromas . if so this is the absolute worst amber beer i 've ever had . and the strange mishmash of bad , unlike tastes and contrasts . d- very poor .  almost opaque black with deep ruby highlights . nice creamy tan head looks like nitro to me .  sweet crackery finish , m - thin with very low carbonation .

i also get a sort of hospital sanitation aroma . i always think sahti smells very interesting and inviting as well as completely authentic . t - quite mild .  dark golden look . head was about an inch and a half that left a quarter-inch ( or more ) film . reminded me of that candy that fizzes in your mouth .  not so much the taste as it had a good belgian style wheatiness to it but the body was extremely thin and almost watery . i was looking for more in the way of the mouthfeel .

hoppy aroma as expected , decent amount of it i 'd say .  a : nice coloration with some light lacing .  body is a nip thin . a bit too still , but more carbonation would have blasted through the empty body of the beer , making it even less desirable .

smell is a beautiful bouquet of tangy/citrus hops .  appearance : this was a very dark , ruby-brown lager with a light tan head . a thin layer of foam was left capping the beer , leaving a decent amount of lace behind .  mouthfeel : way too big-bodied , way too carbonated , and way too uneven .

s : the smell is nice . whiskey , booze , malts , molasses , really deep and balanced .  pale copper in color with a well established white head that is mostly lasting .  feels thin and watery on the tongue with a low level of carbonation . bitterness is harsh and detracts from drinkability , mouthfeel is unsatisfying , and the flavors are n't interesting and complex enough to yield repeated enjoyment .

s- floral apricot , with touch of light orange , light hopiness , and decent balance of malt and hops . t- pretty austere here . w/ just a hint of maltiness .  mythos from greece : a hellenic lager , in a 11.5 ounce green bottle . strong euro-skunk aroma . thick white head , long lasting , with pronounced belgian lace . light bodied , deep golden color .  a little thin overall . mouthfeel : light-bodied and lacking . way too light and delicate of a beer to have an abv of 7.5 % .

strongly flavoured nose with herbs and nettles .  a : this beer pours a nice deep , translucent , bronze color with a khaki colored sudsy head .  i must say this beer is best on tap as everywhere i 've tried it otherwise all of its carbonation seems to be non-existant .
interesting aroma . very floral with slight hints of spice and citrus .  the pour is promising .  the mouthfeel is way thin , but drinkability is ok .

smell : loads of spicy/mint hop aromas , with a casual sweetness on the backend .  ultramour pours in fine and has a nice with staying head and a deepredbrown beercolor .  the body was disappointingly thin for such a big beer , allowing the unwelcome alcohol notes to really come through .

it has a really nice , spicy aroma with a solid grain backbone .  while it has a deep clear amber color , it seems lighter than i would expect for a `` dark '' ale ? very nice initial carbonation and rocky head and sticky lacing . while nice , the carbonation fades quickly .  thin mouthfeel with average macro carbonation . touch of caustic mouthfeel in the middle with the bitterness and petrol notes .

largely based on a sweet malt base . its well brewed just not for me . too much of the sticky sweet side of things .  pours out to a clear , deep mahogany , forming a modest light yellow , off-beige head of microbubbles with decent retention and good lacing .  m - kind of flat on the palate with very little carbonation . hop profile caught me off guard and the mouthfeel is pretty weak .

smell is milk chocolate sweet and it also has traces of black fruit .  it pours nicely and the nitro tap gives it that cool lava lamp effect .  it 's drinkable , but the body and carbonation are really lacking .

s : smells tangy - slightly stings the nostrils , in a good way . ginger simple syrup , orange peel , graham cracker crust , peaches ? something a tad off lurks , almost like a liqueur . tastes like it was once great though .  this nearly opaque brown pint arrived with a huge , cloudy head .  m- not a lot of carbonation , kind of syrupy actually . i feel if it would have been carbonated more it would have helped a lot .

nose is dark malt with some nice subtle estery notes of banana , raisin and pear .  appearance was nice . decent head .  i recently bought a bottle and had it at home and was supprised to find that it really was not much better than the average super brewery light beer . the taste is almost nonexistant and unlike some mega beers has almost no aftertaste at all which for this beer is actually a benefit . i would compare is most to a pbr .

s : distinct and delicious aroma of butter rum leads off . honestly , this smells like angel 's share should have smelled .  labeled scaldis , pours a nice brown amber with a huge head that stays throughout drinking the beer .  m : mild , almost weak or watery . does not have stout presence at all ; feels like flat cola , if anything .

nice . the liberator is n't quite my bag of tea .  poured from a bottle into a pilsner glass , beer is what you might expect from a `` black '' beer , very dark in color although not quite black and a root beer colored head .  the mouthfeel was watery , the body medium/light and the carbonation average .

s : has a sweet smell of caramel .  smell is heavy with cooked vegetables - carrots and peas . accidents happen , and the reviews for this beer seem quite good , but at over 10.00 a bottle , i feel mistakes must be mentioned when they occur .  mouthfeel was thin and tingly , and the initial flavor was sour fruit , which was fine , but then it too was quickly overtaken by the taste of grains .

s - the rich caramel and malty nose is unleashed on the pour . a light kiss of hops compliments the very malty nose . smells almost like a dopplebock . very sweet .  pours out to a clear medium amber with ruby highlights , forming a modest off light yellow head with ok retention and nice sheets of lace .  mouthfeel : seltzer drinkability : would be good but the mouthfeel sucks .

s : raspberry and lemons with a hint if mint .  this apa has a nice copper color and foamy head , but from there it goes downhill .  the mouthfeel is flat , but predictable as there are virtually no bubbles in the glass after the first minute or so . as far as drinkability goes , i 'd save it for the hot summer days , the ballpark and the cheap 30 pack for the party .

looks like honey , smells like honey , very sweet , almost no head in either pour out of a 22 oz .  a : this sour brown ale , true to its name , pours deep ruby-tinted brown , with a quickly-vanishing two-finger head that is also a rich burnt-straw-brown mahogany . maybe i 'm just not a sour beer drinker , as this is perhaps a well-crafted beer for its style , but not what i like to experience when tasting a fourteen-dollar bottle of beer .  mostly smells and tastes like a lager pretending to be an ale . that hint of lager ( as in yuengling lager ) sits there in the background , but then there 's a nice hit of hops in there too . it 's odd , but not necessarily bad ( although certainly not a good american pale in any sense of the word ... it 's a cheap beer masquerading as an american pale ) . not great , but one to try if you 're tired of lager as your cheap beer for the minute .

dark brown with a bit of a reddish hue when held to the light , about one finger thick head in the pour left tight lacing on the glass sweet caramel and coffee notes gives a little burnt coffee favor , sweetness counteracted by a little sour . this poured and smelled like a porter but drinking did n't really feel like a porter .  very dark brown , almost black with a thin mocha coloured head .  thin on the mouthfeel and the carbonation is way too high on this one making the thinnes hard to handle .

usa says , `` batch # 56 '' this looked and smelled quite nicely , but everything else was rather ho-hum . the smell was nice , as well , consisting of caramel and roasted grains , but no really discernable , specific profile .  a- actually looked nice after the pour . red in appearance , nice head retension s- smell is where it really falls out .  mouthfeel is rather thin for a scotch ale .

s : bourbon , a little chocolate , coffee , and a little smoke .  i poured the beer into my favorite laser etched pint . the head is a little more bubbly than the stout , but other than that it looked like a pint of the draught .  m : dammit , i hate porters like this . light , watery body , slightly oily , and slick on the palate . this would have been so much better with more body to it .
smell is fruity with a nice yeast kick at the end .  a : it looked good . nice head , nice color , nice texture .  the body was very thin and the beer lacked substance .

corn and cereal . t-tastes like the normal as well but a bit more flavorful .  the pour into 180 ml chimay chalice delivers a garnet reddish-brown body overlain by light tan head that slowly sets to a bubbly island encircled by an elevated peripheral ring .  strong roasted malt character with a twang of hop bitterness , but really light and pale in the mouth with a watery body . no creamy mouthfeel , which was somewhat disappointing , but it was overall enjoyable . clean , pure and watery finish was n't quite what i had hoped for , as i was expecting something a little more milky/creamy/smooth .

o : the beer smells great , but pales in other categories , especially taste , which is a terrible place to have the weakest link .  poured the 12oz bottle into a pilsener glass . small bubble rising up to the top where a three finger spongy bright white head rests . o : this lager is a good cheap option since it 's very drinkable and decent .  pours a clear golden copper hue which leaves a creamy fast vanishing two finger head and creamy lacing , the smell is herbal grassy hops and some honey malts thats it , the mouthfeel is light and watery and has tastes of honey malts , herbal grassy hops , fresh cut grass , pale malts and finished with a mix of herbal grassiness and toffee and overall i definately would not buy again and the bitterness is only very light avoid cheers .

nose is kind of odd , dirty , but also sweet and honey-like . overall this is a smooth , easy-drinking beer , but the aroma was a little odd .  the appearance is a porter but that is about it . dark black with a tan head .  for the level of alcohol , there is hardly any hotness at all and a bizarrely watery and light body for a barleywine . could also stand some more hops , as i could hardly detect any at all .

dales ' has a mildly hoppy bite and leaves little aftertaste - due to storage , i think . all-in-all , an exceptional quaff , though i do prefer oskar blues scotch ale `` old chubb .  a-tan and spongy head with a black body .  m - thin , watery body , moderate carbonation , slight bitterness in the finish .
nose is really great . a lot going on in there .  slightly hazy gold body with pure white active head .  m - watery , light carbonation .

interesting . d : smells good but the taste is a little off .  pours out to a clear ( i.e-filtered ) pale golden , forming a tall , poofy white head with excellent retention and nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly flat .

has an interesting unique look , very cloudy with a hint of ruby color , alot like cranberry juice ( duh ) smell is good , has a classic belgian wit aroma , spicy yeast dominates taste is ok , easy to drink , but the fruit really ruins the beer in imo just an unnecessary addition  if you just handed this to me i would guess belgian dubbel . really has the belgian aspects right up front just like in the nose ; strong banana and clove , really dominates and considering i expected malt because this is a `` scottish '' i am very dissapointed .  that being said i want to keep track of beers i have tried and will start to try reviewing beers i drink ) from a sampler pack found at specs liquor . tastes flat to me . no alcohol taste that i can tell of and not a whole lot of flavor . goes down easy and not much of an aftertaste .
nice roasty aroma . but it 's downhill from here .  it 's a really nice , orange color , with bubbles set up in just the right way .  mouthfeel is thin .

the smell is nothing special . with my eyes closed , i would swear i was smelling regular budweiser the taste is good . i had to remind myself of what i had in my hand -- a new style `` american ale '' . i say this is a very drinkable beer , though i do not think this will be on the shelf very long since the budweiser market may not find this enjoyable .  pours a nice deep amber with a good one fingered fluffy white head that fades real quick , leaving a bit of lacing .  thin , harsh , and astringent- the mouthfeel is where the beer suffers the most .

attractive lacing . smell is a rich combination of herbs and spices , with sassafras , vanilla , and wintergreen being detected . there are others there , but i am unable to specifically identify them taste also shows lots of spices and herbs and while they combine nicely , they also have there own separate taste sensations .  served on tap , this pours a pleasing clear amber color .  it has a below average mouthfeel - boring , too watery and macro-brewish .

the first smell was of licquorice , then coffee , then dark chocolate . the flavours in the taste followed very closely to the aromas , but a whole lot sweeter .  poured slightly heady with a very cloudly light brown color .  thin , watery , overcarbonated .

fresh aroma , fruity , with notes of peach , nectarine , citrus . once a favorite , before i discovered what the revivalists among american craftbrewers have been doing with this style . apparently , the american version , bottled and draft , is weakened some for `` our '' taste , and i 'm profoundly disappointed .  gee , i hate to write a bumming report on my favorite brewery but ... this beer taste like it got scorched at some point . big scorched coffeee tatse , and hints of molasses . very dark and again the recipe has changed from last year ( last years was very piney ) .  mouthfeel is like most others ... flat .

odd , but oddly good . taste follow suit and starts out good , but a pretty strong metallic aftertaste ruins this beer .  a- deep dark browen/black . light tan head . i think that they literally dumped vanilla extract into this beer once it finished fermenting .  m - watery and sticky . its almost a thin beer .

this beer looks good , and it smells good too , but in the end beer is not drunk for the way it looks or smells .  pours black with a very light tan head . nice retention and dotted lacing covers my glass .  a bit bland for the style . body is a bit like soda water , and fades really fast .
pleasant aroma of amarillo hops with notes of mandarin/tangerine .  pours from the bottle into an imperial pint with an amber color and a decent head .  thin and tingly mouthfeel .

burnt brown head poured pretty thick , foamy and meringue like then faded to light covering with thick edging ... some light lines of lacing ring the glass ... aroma - dark toasted malts , metallic notes , black coffee , some dark brown sugar sweetness , light nuttiness , some blackcurrant and raisin fruitiness , faint liquorice traces , some graininess coming through , dusty hints ... taste - watered down roasted maltiness mixed with nutty notes , some molasses / treacle sweetness , light chocolate mixed with black cherry and blackcurrant fruits , light nutmeg and pepper spiciness , some light vegetal traces just noticeable , cola hints ... feel - way too over carbonated this one which really spoils it both in terms of flavour and drinkability ... overall - a bit disappointing as all the other les fous beers i 've had have been very good ... sort out the carbonation and this could be very good..  pours a nice dark brown , similar to the color of cola , with slight hints of auburn .  horrible macro version of the style .
the blueberries floating in it drove the aroma of fruit in the nose , like cereal fake blueberries .  poured a thick foamy head on a solid red body .  the mouthfeel is light bodied and watery .

very pleasing . taste is really subdued .  i know there are tons of people who rave about guinness ... but for what reason , i do n't know ... a : bartender did not perfect pour this one for sure , but it still looked good s : smells like burnt coffee t : tastes like it smells , burnt coffee m : like cold burnt thick coffee .  the mouthfeel is light and watery , not much substance . a very watered down dunkel , i would skip this in the future .

s - truly not a lot of nose to this but you can pick up small tones of coffee and malt . it even smells dry .  hmm , i got ta try it . a : cola black , some head , nice lace .  finish really kills me as bad oaks comes off ... mouthfeel is the true downfall of this beer , watery light with no depth ... easy to drink but not good enough that i would .

nice notes on the nose - lots of toffee and caramel with a pleasant citric fruit character piping through , perhaps a little pineapple which stops the rich malt and caramel from becoming overpowering .  pours a golden color with a big head .  a thin mouthfeel and not a lot of carbonation .

sweet fruity aroma with a little bit of maltiness .  i wasnt sure i would get the $ 6.50 that i wanted so i could buy the local growler i had my eye on , and i didnt . ) the beer itself ( seen easily through the clear glass 40 bottle , ) seems darker than many other 40s like st ides and steel reserve , which boast the same 8.2 abv .  mouthfeel is very flat and is not impressing at all .

aromas of black current , butter , black coffee , some malted milk and alcohol.first thing i notice about this beer is the fact that it is a bit too carbonated for the style . there are way better brews out there .  appearance : dark-brown/black color with a huge tan head that gradually collapses , leaving thick lacing .  the problem is that the beverage is thin and flat on the palate and leaves a really unpleasant metallic aftertaste .

smell- roasty and malty with much hop presence . hops are pretty strong , but not overpowering .  once things settled down , the presentation was nice , with a foamy tan head that left lots of lace over a very cloudy reddish-brown brew .  m : flat . way too sweet for the ( non-existant ) level of carbonation .

s - heavy on the grains , both hops and malt , with a note of something floral there , too . d - the appearance and the smell had me really pumped on this beer initially but the taste killed it for me . and afterall , it 's about the taste in the end ... very disappointed in this entry into one of my favorite genres of brewdom .  the color of this beer is quite good . light yellow with a small white head .  mouthfeel is way watery and i feel like it is slightly udnercarbonated .

average lacing & head retention s : coffee & a bit of chocolate , grows stronger as this warms t : coffee grounds , black patent malt , a bit of mocha & herbal hops up front .  appearance : this pours a maple brown , nearly mahogany , with an eggshell colored head that retains nicely . strangely light appearance for a double cda , though .  it does bring vanilla to mind . the sweetness almost removes it from the style of beer . far to thin for a brown ale .

a = pours a nice copper color with a 1/2 '' white head s = smells slightly hoppy with citrus undertones t = very much a citrus taste with slight clove undertones .  appearance- black with little tan head .  t : cheap carbonated corn . m : if it werent for the bottle this beer would have sunk years ago .
pretty classic pilsener nose .  poured dark amber , clear , with a good head .  not sourdough , but sour-smelling dough . taste is very flat and bland . malty and earthy , but with a dry finish .
aroma was appropriate for the style - hoppy , not much malt .  this beer pours a cloudy amber hue with a thick head that slowly settles .  mouthfeel is overly carbonated .

i still say that there 's nothing like the `` original '' pilsner -- as the marketers would say -- and that is pilsner urquell . sure the hop aroma has faded a bit over the years , but the fluffy head has n't . i know the green is pretty , and i even know that some people ( like an old friend of mine ) like that skunky aroma , but why could n't they at least put some of the beer in brown bottles ?  a : pours an extremely dark brown with a little bit of light passage when the glass is held to a lamp . there is about a 1 finger creamy looking head with decent retention and some lacing .  mouthfeel is disappointing ; thin and watery , with too much carbonation for my taste .

smell : very malty with strong hints of chocolate .  appearance : same great creamy looking head and leaves rings of lace all the way down ... the color is not as black as it used to be , its more of a very dark brown .  a - light , clear , yellow color with a thick head that dissipated quickly s - beer , cheap beer t - beer from a can , cheap beer from a can m - thin , flat , not much d - went down smooth , probably because i 'd wisely iced it down with some ice and rock salt so it would get really cold .

aromas are surprisingly floral , nectar-like , and a bit perfumy from the boquet of aromatic hops . these compliment the softer pilsner malt aromas and mask the grainy-sharp sensation in the nose that usually accompany pilsner grains .  pours a nice `` pale-golden '' yellow , nice head , that last fairly long .  the body was water and medium light .

smelled or just about every spice you would associate with fall ; nutmeg , cinnamon , all spice , etc . overall decent but not in my top 5 of pumpkin ales that i 've had so far .  i must admit i was suprised to see this new offering from coopers as i have never heard of it , it pours a pale golden see thru champagne colour with a nice frothy one finger head , sparkling carbonation and bubbly clingy lacing , it has a green , grassy hop aroma with a malty background , it has a thin mouthfeel even thinner for the style for my liking and the taste isnt as pleasant as it looks it has tastes of watery hops with a feint grainish aftertaste not as great as i was hoping for but definately better than the other macro swill out there .  m : bubbly and very thin .

i was expecting this ... s- very oaky smelling with a copious amount of bourbon presence t- bourbon is overwhelming vs the sweet malts of the flat beer .  pours a nice light gold colour with light fluffy head .  very thin mouthfeel , almost tasted flat , nothing special .

smell : right up front and in your face is yeast . upon closer inspection citrus and honey come through giving way to spice , malts , floral hops , apple cider and pear . mouthfeel : i bit over carbonated and a bit too yeasty . the complexity of the aroma surpasses the simplicity of the taste .  appearance : nice looking dark beer with carmel color head .  tasting it my first impression was how thin the body was for an english porter , compared to , for instance , the excellent fuller 's london porter or young 's double chocolate .

smell : sweet roasted malt , vanilla and french oak .  a - rusty orange ; vibrant and bright . off-white head - pillowy and high . nice !  mouthfeel : very carbonated with a thin , almost watery feeling .

nose is molasses and licorice with some hints of smoke ; sweet dried plums and cherries in the background . it looks like a stout . the low taste rating is simply because i did n't enjoy this beer , and i 'm very jealous of the reviewer who managed to taste this on draft because i 'm stuck with five bottles i do n't want : - )  this beer looked great , but was otherwise very unimpressive . it poured out of the bottle a very pretty hazy orange with a perfect amount of what appeared to be velvety-smooth head .  m - this bottle was flat . this gave the beer a thick and somewhat unenjoyable mouthfeel .

s : aromas of piney hops , almost like an ipa .  appearance - dark amber , a shade or two darker than a vienna lager and with a reddish tint . head retention is moderately good , leaving a spotty lace on the glass .  slightly watery body with adequate carbonation . mouthfeel is slick and thin with a metallic and astringent finish as it dries .

the whisky barrel smell hits you immediately , and like a ton of bricks . it continues from there , slapping you with a mouthful of roasty malt and alcohol . the nastiness continues in the aftertaste , and the best part is when you ca n't taste it any more .  this beer looks very good , but as a light japanese beer , it is indeed light and lacking in what one expects of one 's beer . however , it 's a nice golden , sunflower color , and it is extraordinarily easy to drink .  it 's watery on the palate , surprisingly so - i 've had beers of 3 to 4 % alcohol that had more body . the finish is lightly astringent and bitter .

the aroma is pleasant . it 's semi-tart , which makes it appealing to me , and a little sugary from the beets .  reviewed 2/7/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a golden yellow colored body , with a huge creamy white head , lasting , with okay lacing .  zero carbonation .

( s ) - a dry oaky profile with caramel and bourbon notes . ( t ) - nice vanilla notes with wet cardboard and sawdust aspects .  actually looked pretty good in the glass . nice and dark with a pretty decent head .  the first thing i notice with this beer is the watery mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is terrible .

s : dominated by citrus , get a lot of tangerine , citrus , pineapple , and an earthy belgian yeast kick , light pepper .  the appearance is pretty good . it is mostly foam but the head is thick and cloudy and rocky and dense .  the mouthfeel was very thin for a stout .

s : abundant floral hops , definately some cascade . the perfect combination of floral , bittering , aroma , in a showcasing of hops that is presented beautifully , well balanced and tame but not lame .  this was n't lager at all , but something more like alcoholic grape soda . it looks great and smells delicious , and right after pouring it i was actually very hopeful .  it has a difficult time making a favorable impression though since the body/mouthfeel is way too light for the style . what makes it to the taste buds is washed away in seconds as the anemic body collapses into nothingness . as a result , it 's hard to appreciate any depth or complexity in the beer at all .

s : oranges and cream , honey , lemon , heather . d : the aroma was so promising , but overall this beer is shooting for typical and falls just shy of that .  appearance : the beer looks really good . nice sized white head which lingers shortly , leaving small bubbles and minimal lacing .  mouthfeel : thin and watery body , medium carbonation overall : highly overrated .

aroma is very pleasant . sweet .  bomber , a : pours black with a medium mocha coloured head . good retention , light lace .  mouthfeel is very thin with low carbonation , almost watery , drinkability is poor , huge bitterness and watery mouthfeel is a disappointment .

the smell is good , and in fact is the strongest attribute in my opinion .  northwoods lager pours a clear golden color with a finger of white head .  the mouthfeel is pretty sad on this one . very watery and thin .

interesting . the taste is very smoky and has maybe a beer/bacon grease flavor to it .  came out of the can looking okay , clear golden colour with a moderate white head .  feels really dry and grainy , very prickly in my mouth and sand papery , not impressed . there 's some interesting flavor components playing which eachother , but ultimately the mouthfeel and the harsh finish really let it down , shame that wo n't be reflected so well in the overall score with the way the weighting system works .

head is almost tan , but too white to deserve the label . aroma is like a 60-minute ipa that 's gone off its meds . a blast of hops juice . but , i could not drink your 120 minute ipa .  appears a dark amber/red color . with a small white head .  however , extremely thin for a beer , and not very carbonated either .

a - looks like dr. pepper or even a cherry coke s - caramel popcorn up front and bold , hint of caramel t - it tastes like caramel popcorn , candy , hazelnut and then finishes with a little coffee m - average on carbonation and finishes dry d - this beer is quite different but gets a little old because the smell and taste is like candy when i first opened this beer it hit me right away with all the popcorn .  looks good as per the style .  mouthfeel is thin .

smell was n't very attractive . the malt smelt like it had been roasted , and poorly . thankfully the beer is much better than the atrocious smell .  '' a-poured a nice clear amber-golden color w/rich frothy off-white head , good retention , and some sticky bits of lacing .  it is a bit bland , the mouthfeel is way too watery .

2010 vintage thanks to j47paco look : pitch black and totally opaque with a 1/4 inch tan head and no real retention smell : hints of dark chocolate molasses and fudge taste : i am not sure why everyone praises the flavor of this beer because the beer is a sweet sugary mess .  transparent medium gold capped by a large , off-white head that persists acceptably well . a fair amount of lace sticks to the glass , lending the appearance of quality .  mouthfeel is also watery with not much body and no carbonation but essentially pretty drinkable due to the fact that is just resembles colored water .

not that strong of an aroma , some sitrusy hops but otherwise very laid back . soft malty start blending into a spicy hop finish , a bit bitter . not the best ipa but this is very drinkable compared to some of the overhopped ipa that have come into style .  pours dark reddish brown , the color of cola , beige head retreats leaving a thin ring .  the body is thin and watery ; one hardly notices the beer until it is gone .

smell is very nice and enticing . t - here 's where this one starts letting me down a bit .  tommyknockers imp nut brown a 4-4.5 somewhat aggressive pour yields a one-finger tan head above a cocoa body with orange highlights . the ring holds well and leaves spotty lace .  lack of carbonation , and this beer 's thin , watery mouthfeel combine to make a less-than-awesome drinking experience .
s-chocolate milk mix , rich , earthy cigar tobacco , nutty malts .  solid white head sits above a gold bodied beer . produces some decent lacing .  mouthfeel is overyly fizzy and thin .

this smells of ipa and initially it tastes of ipa with strong pink grapefruit and copper malt backbone ... but then there 's a little bite of fake-fruity-artificialsweetness ... reminds me of leiny 's sunset wheat ... almost like somebody dropped a shot of that in here ... which is not a good thing ... it really hits in the aftertaste and really turns me in the wrong direction on this beer ... i give it props for the taste up front ... and for the fact that it completely hides it 's alcohol content ... in that aspect i 'm not sure if i 've ever had a 7 % 'er that did n't have some alcohol bite ... but that off-put-taste of fake sweetener is just turning me off of this one and it will be my last .  appearancewise , it delivers a solid score of 4 due to its golden , clear and warm colour and its generous compact and tenacious cap of foam that clings admirably .  m - no staying power .

smell was very sweet and alcohol ( rummy ) rich . candied and brown sugar with alcohol soaked fruit and spices ( alcohol soaked fruit cake possibly ?  nice retention and incredibly solid lace adorns the glass .  3.0 m too thin for my taste and my experience with better scottish ales ( like oskar blues ) .

roasted coffee nose .  the only reason i gave the appearance a 4 is because the bottle looks kind of cool and it is corked which is unusual .  m - too thin , light body , fizzy carbonation . the mouthfeel on this beer is no good .

very nice aroma . hmm , not sure about the taste .  hazy orange copper body , topped by four fingers of rocky frothy white micro bubbles .  too much alcohol , comes of chemically ... the taste is slightly better than the aroma , but the mouthfeel is way over-carbonated and distracting and really detracts .

strong nut aroma . flavor was not very rich but was nutty with some malt .  im just gon na say , pepper in beer is obviously not for me.this beer looked great , nice amber color with a fluffy white head.the smell of this beer just reminded me of ground pepper , something i like on food.just not something i like in beer.my sister poured me a small sample into a glass , and i had about two sips and gave her the rest .  thin watery feel .

s : super sweet chocolate is the main thing that i get at first . the beer is sitting a foot away from me and all i can smell is cocoa puffs .  looks nice . has a dark , almost gingerbread like color .  `` simple '' is the best word i can use to describe the taste , but it does deliver with scorched malts with a touch of lactose . my biggest complaint with this beer is the mouthfeel- it 's way too watery .

smell : dry , musty and earthy , with clove , banana and black pepper .  pours pale yellow and settles light amber in the glass . impressive , frothy head .  caramel , coffee and cocoa are there , but overall balance is towards the dry and bitter mouthfeel - 2.0 lightly carbonated , bordering on flat and a little watery .
it was nice . taste was primarily strong rich malt .  nice auburn with yellow highlights .  mouthfeel was slightly thick and flat .

drinkability : the strong alcohol , of my opinion , does n't go well with the refreshing smell and taste .  it poured a deep , cherry red with minimal head which foamed a bit when swirled .  watery mouthfeel .

nose shows loads of treacle fudge and brown sugar with cloves showing in the background .  i like beers brewed with rye and love ipa 's , but this was a beer that i could n't stomach .  the mouthfeel is very watered down like an american pale ale but i thought the pumpkin taste was enjoyable .

the beer has a very spicy odor , maybe a hint of cloves or something similar in the nose .  the pour is dark brown , almost black , with a khaki head .  has a malty aroma , enticing , maybe some wheat too ? fizzy palate , mallty taste , fruity , not very lingering . thirst-quenching .

the nose , however , brings in a harsh metallic scent which is rather unpleasent , though it 's the sort of thing that 's possibly more indicative of a bad batch . luckily , the metallic scent does n't carry over too much into the flavor , which is actually quite enjoyable . the brew 's a bit more weighty than the light red hue might have you think , and malty to the core .  pours with light brown , two-fingered bubbly head , fades slowly and leaves a good lace .  this beer reminds me greatly of sol , corona , and modelo . i would n't be surprised if all mexican beer came from the same place ... dirty t-shirts squeezed out into a horse trough and then 'pasteurized ' by the horse before making its way into the bottle , but hey what do i know about cervezas .

smell is of spices , black pepper , and lemons .  a- pours a deep hazy red/orange with a nice fluffy , crispy white head that disappears kinda quickly leaving a nice amount of sticky lacing . loads of carbonation !  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and very watery .

can into pint glass a - big 2 finger eggshell head , slightly hazy medium orange/brown coloring on the beer , relatively large bubbles s - quite robust hops and citrus control the doughy scent , surprisingly bold smell t - bready start transforms smoothly to a citrus to a bitter and a slightly sour finish .  pours a very cool orange color with a pretty dense head with very tiny bubbles .  a : hazy dark yellow , very nice head , carb ok s : sweet , wet , doughy aroma t : hard to place this as a pale lager ; a pale something , yes ; tinny , rather hoppy for a lager , but not enough to do the tongue any favors ; mid-sweet m : flat , watery overall , not a terrible beer , but it is rather strange .

s- coriander and orange peel dominate the nose . sour yeast round out the nose .  the beer is beautiful golden and looks damn good but yuck w the taste ... .  m : i was disappointed in the mouth feel . the light mouth feel really hurt for me .

aroma is malty with breads and burnt sugars . i did n't care for it , but my roommates gf said its good for girls and she really likes it .  copper colored with a decent light tan head , very active carbonation -- a bit too much -- possibly aged ( ?  the carbonation seems artificial , which really brings down the quality of this lager to something like a henry weinhards ( goes for a good taste , but it all seems somewhat fake ) . without the strong carbonation this would have been a common sight in my fridge , but as it is sieraa nevada summerfest will only make occassional appearences .

falls surprisingly fast for a hefe and does not leave a whole lot of lace behind . overripe bananas , cloves and bubblegum galore ! there is some nice wheat tang to offset some of the sweeter , fruity yeast esters .  that taste mitigates after a while , leaving a more pleasant nose of dark coffee . in other words , a lagered stout . the waitress said it may be off because the batch was just tapped the day i can in .  the mouthfeel is way to under carbonated and watery for the style .

( s ) - a spicy apple & honey with bits of cranberry . ( t ) - very dry with a musky-like honey & cranberry . has a big corn husk background . ( d ) - a basically good beer to have around for the holidays .  a : pours a dark golden yellow with a couple fingers worth of fairly oily looking bright white head that took its time fading into a thin film that left a pretty good layer of sticky lace down the glass .  i feel like i have now experienced the true port/lost abbey experience , this is the first one i 've had that is flat ... a : pours dark brown with caramel highlights , zero head even after stiff pour , some clarity s : nose is predominantly oak and vanilla , some char quality in there , stout base takes a back seat t : vanilla and bourbon again dominate , some ashy character in there along with light notes of leather and tobacco , a bit of of boozieness on the finish mf : low carbonation is an understatement , medium body o : good flavors here , the lack of carbonation takes away from the quality a bit , for the premium price tag , i would expect carbonation .
spicey , fruity , and perfumey nose .  bottle into a pint glass pours black in color with a bit of red highlighting along the edges of the glass .  mouthfeel : way too carbonated .

s - very goodly smell of malts and some faint raspberry juice in the background , biscut qualities too .  it looks pretty enough , with its amber body and nice tan head , but the heavy mouthfeel did n't sit too well with me .  head falls into the liquid way too quickly and seems to look more like bubble bath suds that the typical beautiful belgian head . certainly is the high point of the beer . alcohol comes a little too strong on the palate and seems to take over the other flavors . flat on the tonque . outrageously overpriced and overrated .

nice chocolate and coffee in the nose , surprisingly good when compared to the last pioneer brew i had .  a : a strange deep red color with both pink and brownish hues .  thin and watery for a dark beer . little carbonation . needless to say , i was disapointed in this beer .

very little aroma , mouthfeel 's watery .  kind of an odd lager ... pours a clear , good looking rich gold color ... 1/2 inch frothy head ... .nose is sweet ... .almost a hint of barley..body is light and lacks substance ... .taste is bland..there are macros with more flavor than this ... no hops to speak of and the malt profile borders on an adjunct style beer ... has a corny , adjunct like mouthfeel ... .  mouthfeel : a bit on the fizzy side - really scrubs the tongue .

s - the very dark roasted coffee is actually one of the last places my mind goes after a whiff of this .  the beer has an overall nice appearance .  coppery colored amber with a sudsy froth top that subsides to a foam slick , no lacing , body is very thin and under-carbonated . perhaps as an effect of my bottle not being quite as fresh as it ought to be , i am detecting absolutely none of the fruity notes commonly perceived by other ba members ... .and this really hurts my overall impression quite a bit .
very nice .  a - hazy ( for a pale lager ) yellow with a big frothy head that lingers .  body is thin and flat .

huge fruity nose with lots of pineapple . pretty sour which also makes me think it may have been a bad bottle . hugely disappointing considering how much i had heard about hair of the dog .  very dark mahogany brown colour with a tanned brownish white head that is quite foamy . retention is good with some lacing too .  mouthfeel on both is not much , just clear water with a bit of beer bubbles .

where the smell was certainly nothing to write home about , everything else was quite impressive , especially for this style . the smell was a nice mix of malt and hops , but again , typical . not striking or unusual in anyway .  it looks pretty nice .  the palate is thin .

s : scent quite good , grapefruit & melon , hops .  tastes extremely bitter , reminded me of chinook on steroids . grapefruit city . normally bitter beers i can deal with but not enough sweet malt to counter balance for me . one and done for taste buds .  m : taste was below average for me , but the mouthfeel is even worse . super thin . light carbonation and no body make this almost watery .

the first thing i smell is an off-putting burnt rubber aroma that continues to decline the more i smell it . beer smell is pretty absent here .  bottle : poured a golden color lager with a big foamy head with good retention and some minimal lacing .  limp bodied and watery , with no real aftertaste .

the aromas are loaded with dank hop earthiness and woodiness from the oak aging . defintely also some citrus/pine and the alcohol notes finish out the smells . the tastes are good , with apple brandy-like alcohol that is hot on the tongue right off the bat , but this one is too syprupy for me . the oak is there , but not in a good way , and the thickness/syrup qualities , detract from the hops .  slightly hazy amber , with a tan head that foams up and laces .  mouthfeel : very very thin .

smell-a nice nutty and sweet aroma . nice hints of roasted malts and caramel .  appalachian trail blaze brown is a clear red ale with a thin beige head that fades and leaves nice lacing .  carbonation appears low . beer is thin and boring , not much there at all . mild sweetness very water like . bummer .

the initial aroma is promising- delivering a crisp maltiness , low-lying sweetness , and a good helping of cascade hops for a grapefruity , lightly piney aroma . fair and balanced throughout the nose . flavors is where the beer begins to give way .  initial head that rises a half inch or so , then fades to a broken ring around the edge . mahogany color when poured , appears black in the glass .  the taste is similar , just a little sweeter , with more wateriness and less hops . i could n't get over how watery this beer tasted and felt . maybe i 'm rating it a little low because of that , but it has a lot of strikes against it : watery , bland , and definitely not a bargain .

the aroma is promising -- it smells like it could be a rich but balanced stout .  a - pours a one a half finger head with a hazy golden straw body . the head fades to a decent lace as time passes .  has a bit of a sweet maltiness and maple flavor does come out more as it warms m : very thin feel for a porter and leaves an odd buttery coating d : nothing really appauling , and nothing overpowering so it is drinkable , but i probably wo n't get another

aroma : there is a strong smell of malt and hops . the hops has a citrus aroma .  dark brown to black color with ruby red highlights and an inch of light beige head .  hard to slam the beer that got my through college but ... . the twelfth tasted like the first . not really whatt i consider beer anymore but my in-law says it is more of a beer than budweiser ? could there be a reason you can by `` cooler-packs '' in multiples of 6 !

i have never had a pumpkin ale before . it smells of spices ; nutmeg , ginger and clove . it begins deceptively cleanly with a metallic taste before the spices take over with nutmeg to the fore .  the santa fe pale ale poured a copper-orange with an thick and creamy off-white head that laced the glass .  the mouthfeel is medium-light bodied with a watery texture , and a little too much carbonation .

smells like fucking nothing . this `` beer . '' it barely , barely has an aroma of faint grain husk .  pours a orange almost amber color with a less than finger head .  taste is malty to start , but very thin . the body leaves one wanting more . dry finish with an almost soda-like feel . despite the lack of body , this beer is rather drinkable .

aroma is hoppy , with some sweet malt .  this filled the pint glass with a densely black color with a little red at the edges .  m. thin with no carbonation at all . d. i thought the flavors were interesting , but this beer was much too thin and flat for my taste .

snifter s -- very funky smell with apples , pears , oranges , and white grapes creating a nice complexity t -- totally caught me off guard , i may not be ready for this yet .  looks like a nice beer .  m : light carbonation with a very light watery body .

not much of an aroma on this but picked up some slight floral hints and a bit of caramel .  this bell 's porter was dark brown and had a tan head which went away .  m : this feels fairly thin ; the flavors fall quickly off the tongue , resulting in a watery finish .

4.0 s : surprisingly grainy , which i like . roastiness , some toffee , and a touch of coffee . fairly simple , but pleasant nonetheless .  poured from a 22oz bottle into a magners glass the beer pours a nice golden color with a slight amount of haziness to it . there is a big 1-2 inch head that falls back to about 1/4 inch and statys .  the taste is cloyingly sweet , viscous , the aromas transfer , and turn very bready on the finish , the middle has cherries candies , almost medicinal the mouth feel is vaguely reminiscent of cough syrup , but watered down . there is no bitterness and even less carbonation .

aroma is bad eggs . definitely had some green bottle funk . really couldnt smell much else besides that .  after getting the contents under contol , it poured out a dark and murky brilliant amber colour , with a huge meringue-like head that shows no sign of receding .  m - one of the first things that i noticed was how thin this beer was . unfortunately , this definitely felt watered down .
s : floral & citrus hops .  the pour on the beer was very nice , proper stout black with a thick tan head on top .  almost no body present .

aroma is fruity with white grapes , brewady yeast and a bit of cloves .  i really enjoy most st offerings a -- nice amber/copper color s -- very surprising nutty aroma .  mouthfeel was quite thin and highly over carbonated .

s : very candy sweet with buttery caramel , cocoa , cola , toasted dark grain aromas t : the taste is a major disappointment , but the butter in the aroma unfortunately is the foreshadowing of diacetyl bomb .  looks can be deceiving . this beer looked fine , sporting a rich copper hue .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and just way too thin and watery for an oatmeal stout .

s : nice nose . lots of vanilla and caramel , with well integrated bourbon . this is about a 4.25 in the nose , but i 'm feeling generous . t : not as good . the second half of this beer is just unpleasant : hot , overly bitter , and astringent .  barnyard in a bottle . but uniquely so . if for no other reason than to go back to a differing style .  watery and flat in my mouth .

good aroma , lace , but sour and strong carbonation .  it poured a dark brown-copper color with a nice off-white head and good lacing .  the beer was entirely too light bodied for a stout , this really was one of the most disappointing elements of the beer .

nice copper color with a slightly off white head that shows good carbonation but is also quite frothy . the aromas on this o-fest are sweet butterscotch all the way . sweet caramel malt with the slightest floral hop .  12 oz bottle poured into a pilsner - fridge - 2009 appearance : pours a transparent golden color with lots of flowing carbonation . the head is white and rises 1 '' tall , showing a good amount of foaminess and retention . a coating of lace remains behind . nice !  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

a - poured a black color with no head to leave any lace s - is of roasted malt with chocolate some smoke and a little pepper t - follows the nose with some smoke and chocolate but the pepper is the dominant flavor but not overpowering m - this beer has a thin watery body with no carbonation to it d - i still liked it but the lack of carbonation killed this beer to me it was an interesting experiment that tasted good but literally fell flat  black with brown highlights and an enormous soapy light tan head that leaves scattered patches of lacing .  beer is black in color , with very little light showing through when held up to the ceiling s- after some swirls , gives off a boozy sweet aroma with notes of wood t- well , it has a very good flavor starting out malty sweet with dark fruits , then gets an added booziness a with notes of wood m- has a full body but there 's pretty much no carbonation d- its a shame , if this had at least a hint more carbonation , it would have been a pretty stellar beer because the flavor is there .
good ! taste is similar to smell but a bit strong for my tastes .  this pours a nice almond color , little head , no lacing .  not thick at all , but lacking carbonation .

smell : huge yeasty smell reminiscent of the finest ales from belgium . a vague aroma of bready funk comes through . hop aroma is non-existant . taste : incredible flavors come through all at once . goes down so incredibly easy and hides the 7.7 % pretty well .  pours a large white head with fair retention and some lace .  but it seemed way too flat and thin . the favor is there , but the body is not . unless you have a pathological obsession with oatmeal stouts , look elsewhere for your beer drinking needs

the best way for me to try and describe this beer is if you would take a blueberry muffin , ferment it , and then bottle it .  it is a nice amber color , much darker than most miller products .  taste is very light and mouthfeel is weak .

our group thought this was not bad for a blueberry ale , and in fact some thought it was the best they 'd had . its main advantage is a drier taste than the sweet nose suggests .  a= the pour is a nice deep golden color with a crispy white head on it that holds some decent retention and lacing .  mouthfeel - watery .

the smell was probably what i liked most about this olde style ale .  this beer pours a dark mahogany with a normal-ish 2 inch tan head that leaves just a bit of lacing .  m - watery . too thin , especially for a beer so strong , and meant to be malt-forward .

s : brown sugar , plums , figs and toffee . i like the way this smells . some notes of tea and honey .  poured a bright copper color with a large tan head that dissolved away quickly . looked nice .  unfortunately it takes on flat , syrupy , and warm qualities from the cask . it needs more carbonation to lift it .
a very sweet and fruity smell . sweet malts with apple and pear highlights . not very subtle but quite fine .  i do like the appearance , nice amber color .  mouthfeel is very flat .

amber color with a huge orangey , frothy head that leaves crusty peaks like meringue as it dissipates . aroma is of hop , citrus , and pine .  appearance : i must say by taking a look at it , its a very pretty orange/ honey color with minimal head ... so far so good .  m - maybe i 've had too many rises recently , but this is thin , very very thin .

quite a nice aroma . tastes like it smells but with a bit of sweetness . was light and crisp with a slight dryness at the end .  this is my second try with a high-alcohol beer ; the first time was at a party years ago and i was too drunk to remember whether or not i enjoyed whatever it was that i drank , i just remembered that it was really strong . this comes in an absolutely beautiful bottle and pours a thick , very dark red .  a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher

smells of overly spiced pumpkin pie , which is a good thing . cinnamon and clove come out straight away . the smell was completely misleading ; i think i found pumpkin in this one somewhere , but the spices are glaringly absent ( with the exception of cinnamon which comes through the nose ) it kind of leaves an off flavor behind that i do n't like .  pours out to a slightly hazy light amber with orange accents , forming a large light beige head after a vigorous pour . head is sea-foam in consistency and has ok retention with sparse lacing .  mouthfeel is flat but this is the only disappointment .

sampled from a 12oz bottle at the falcon 's christmas in july tasting sharp citrusy aroma with a grapefruit rind approach with some dry toasty malt notes . it 's unfortunate , but i i 'm cerrtain this was a well travelled bottle of what feels like it should be an otherwise fine beer .  stroh 's in a can , why not let 's do this ... appears a golden clear bubbly quote , unquote beer look to it with large heavily carbonated bright white head floating above body dwindling at a moderate pace leaves some nice patches of sporadic lacing around my duvel chalice ... sorry duvel .  smells and tastes bland and grain like . almost stale . it is a good beer to party with if all your doin is playin beer pong or circle .

the aroma is of cocoa and grapefruit , orange and floral notes .  appearance - golden yellow , very carbonated , very pretty -- looks appetizing .  mouthfeel is somwhat thin for a baltic porter , with more carbonation then i 'd like .

s : honestly , smell like vomit . maybe some passion fruit and maybe some wheat , but it 's bad and smell liked some puked up a beer .  pours a dark brown with ruby highlights . tan head that fades quickly .  m - very thin and watery with flat carbonation .

the smell is defiantly banana bread , a welcoming aroma .  black pour with a two tone mocha head that is several fingers thick .  m - syrupy , mouth coating body with an obnoxious amount of carbonation . carbonation is prickly and really too much as i feel like i ca n't taste everything because of it . it does get better the more you let it warm and let the carbonation die down .

golding hops , great hoppy aroma . some barley initially .  pours from the bottle a dark brown with a light tan head and settling quickly into a thin filmy froth .  the mouthfeel is very thin and highly carbonated , very reminiscent of your typical macro lager .

s - pretty good aroma . chocolate and coffee are both strong but not overpowering .  served in a stone vertical epic glass that can be described as stemless martini-like . pours a dark golden-copper color with a good white head and some lacing .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . it took much diligence to see my way to the end of this beer , and , were it not for the runaway carbonation , it could 've been far better . one to revisit , provided they clear up the carbonation issue .

aroma starts with a tropical fruit note , some fruit salad and then turns into pine . smell is the best part , downhill from there .  drank from a bottle . i first had to rid myself of the expectations of guiness extra stout in a bottle ( what i 'm used to ) . chocolately and coffee-ish , appropriately bitter , no noticeable hops .  almost watery .

nose is sweet milk chocolate , cookie dough , and roasted malt with hints of vanilla and black cherry in the background . this is a fairly enjoyable brew , but i could n't see drinking more than a couple without wanting to go onto something else with a bit more complexity in flavor . perhaps with a little more carbonation the rich flavors hinted at in the nose could really come through .  the pour was highly carbonated , with thick tan , lingering head .  the flavor was both too light and 'way too bitter for a pils . it was watery and lacking in aroma . not much foam - what there was disappeared quickly . the word i 'd use to describe this beer is `` insubstantial . ''

rolling the beer around the glass shows off some very nice legs and leaves some really nice lacing . nose - i could smell this beer across the room while setting up the pictures , it is strong . lots of roasted barley notes , alcohol and really dark coffee . very bitter and very aggressive .  poured a dark reddsih-brown . creamy looking head 1 '' high . slightly cloudy .  m - light and fizzy , thin bodied .

the aroma is intense in a pine-tree-sap , lemon-pepper , oily hop way . little yeast and meaty fruit underneath , but it just didnt seem to come together for me .  deep cherrywood or chestnut body with white fluffy head .  mouthfeel : this beer is almost watery yet with a hint to tannins that leave my mouth dry and scratchy . the beer had a watery texture in my mouth and the flavors were not in balance with the nose . while it did have a light mouthfeel and i am used to drinking hoppy dry beers , this beer would have had an easy drinkabilty yet with its unbalanced flavors i had very little desire to do so .

the nose is sweet malts with hints of golden fruit and a smattering of spiciness . it'sa shame , too , because i have had some really good beers from green flash ( the double stout is really good .  in the glass the beer looks fine , amber in color .  it lacks a big full mouthfeel , and is actually very watery and disappointing .

it looked extremely appetizing . smell was caramel/chocolate , but a little weak .  appearance is very good . a nice dark red brown but not black like so many american porters . clean and transparent . dirty socks maybe ? a cheap macro would do this for you .  mouth : enters the mouth with very light carbonation that flattens as it goes back . overall , it 's not a bad brew , it 's got a great hop flavor but not enough depth or balance , and the weak mouthfeel ruins the experience .

the aroma is pleasing with a dominant smell of overripe peaches backed by toasty malt and pecans .  bad sign , but i ordered it anyway a - looked fine , medium golden , mildly hazy s - mild citric hop smell quickly hidden behind malty/bisquity sweet smell . can still smell the yeast on it as well , which makes me wonder if they filter at all .  mouthfeel is weak and watery .

the smell reminds me of peaches in a can with syrup and is slightly interesting . the taste is oily hops on top of a decent amount of malts but is just not very good .  pours a three finger cream head that fades slowly leaving a trace of lace . chrystal clear amber color . good carbonation and medium bodied .  mouthfeel - very light and dry .

nice bitter chocolate and roast malt aroma , some earthy hop spiciness taste was black and roasted malt with loads of caramel to smooth a touch of pnw hops for balance but somewhat soapy in the swallow ?  a= pours a nice cloudy golden copper hue , sits hazy golden orange in glass . a good foamy white head forms and lingers pretty well .  body is way too thick , sweet , and syrupy .

smell - cherries with a subtle hint of chocolate , as well as a mild oak tinge . all very muted .  poured a entirely opaque dark brown color that yielded nothing when held up to light . big , creamy tan head that required two pours . lots of lace on the sides of the glass .  but i felt i owed it to myself to see if smaller carbonation meant bigger taste .

mariestad porter looks like a glass of coke and does n't really smell much except a little roasted malts and fish ( ! ) .  pours a clear copper color with a mostly white with light tan head .  carbonation is way too strong .

you can immediately pick up some fruity tones upon popping the cap .  poured from a brown bottle into a weizen glass . has a rich amber color with a 1 inch head .  mouthfeel is thin for a ris , almost watery .

the aroma is nice and sweet , but that 's about all this has going for it .  appearance : looks pretty good .  taste : largely dry ; bland notes of roast upfront and throughout ; slightly sour with a mildly bitter finish ; hints of chocolate ; somewhat light bodied ; thin mouthfeel .

it carries a sweet , tart , caramel aroma with a bit of chocolate , roast , a bit of spruce ... and maybe chai . a very rich aroma , indeed .  pours a light brass color with very active carbonation . the head has good retention and leaves sticky patches of lace behind .  i 'm going to have to go against the gimmick and with the style here , the mouthfeel just is n't there . i 'm not impressed at all , it 's like a half flat beer that you 've left on your desk whilst reviewing a beer and forgotten about it only to come back to it 30 mins later . the shining point of this beer is it 's drinkability .

aroma is rich in smoky , roasted chocolate malts , and fresh brewed coffee ( better java flavor than some java stouts ) .  a-cloudy gold , nice white head s-fairly gross smelling , like a very tangy orange with wheat t-orange and wheat upfront that quickly fades in to a tanginess . sam adams , thank you for changing the spring seasonal to the noble pils , you still should 've left this out of the winter package and never made this again .  mouthfeel/ drinkability : the carbonation isnt stinging and seems appropriate . the body of the beer seems far too thin .

the pour ... .no ... the pop of the cork ... did n't happen . it 's cloudy partly because of a chill haze i assume . the cork came out too easily and it was n't tight . this brewery makes good beer and this does n't make the cut . i 'm dissappointed .  the pour was ok , nice hazy reddish amber color .  a nice chocolatey finish that lingers for a while on the palate is the best part about this beer . m : poor .

5.0 s : wow ! this is n't the strongest smelling dipa i 've had ( it 's up there ) , but it is the most harmonious mixture of citrus i 've ever experienced . pineapple and mango are the most intense , followed by orange , tangerine , and grapefruit . 3.5 t : the taste is a bit disappointing after the nose . 3.0 m : lighter medium body , but it strangely lays heavy on the tongue . 3.5 d : pretty good , but one of the reason i really like dipas are for the awesome creamy mouthfeels .  well , it looks good - coppery gold with plenty of creamy head .  nose : it 's aroma is a little bit malty , a little bit citrusy flavor : the taste has some lemon/citrus notes w/ some hints of maltiness , but the big thing that you notice is how fizzy this beer is . it 's far too fizzy for me .

looks like maple syrup i think . some grape , plums , burnt caremel perhaps . taste- not like the smell at all . sour at first .  a- has a nice amber color to it . nice and clear .  mouthfeel is kind of thin and not very pleasant as the carbonation dies down and leaves a sort of flat cola sensation , without the stickiness .

the aroma is of roasted/ chocolate malts and grainy alcohol hints .  it pours a pale and perfectly clear straw-yellow . a two finger head rests on top , retaining nicely and leaving a bit of lacing behind .  d-a little rough on the palate with the huge carbonation and extremely grainy feel .

as others may have observed , this is more like `` pumpkin pie ale '' than `` pumpkin ale '' . picture a nut brown ale , with a pumpkin flavor , and the nose of cinnamon & nutmeg and you have this one .  i really want to like this local brewery but something about every beer i try ends up being below average . this beer , for a stout , is great looking but the taste is something very strange .  mouthfeel is boring and watery .

smells not like a red ale at all , very sweet , malt pouring out of the glass , pretty enticing .  the color was very appealing , but that was all . when i gathered the nerve to take a drink and really sink my teeth into this beer , it felt like i was drinking a beef jerky smoothie .  on first taste the mouthfeel seems a little thin . all in all tasty , but quite thin and seriously lacking in body .

smell is really spicy and slightly malty .  first appearance is pretty good with that awesome head that just keeps coming , but the color just seems to be too light and clear , something else is going on here .  watery mouthfeel in terms of a stout .

s : smells great for a pale ale , smells like hops and hoping the taste measures up .  a- this one pours out of the bottle a glowing golden orange colored body with a small eggshell colored head on top .  medium body . nearly flat .

the nose had a decent malt front line backed by strong fresh hops , a little citrusy , more piney .  a - pours a nice clear amber colour with a white large bubbled head that dies quickly to a film .  m - the body is vanishingly thin and i feel the carbonation is too high for an english porter .

aromas of bread ( it looks like he is grilled ) and cinnamon sweet very pleasant .  the beer poured a clear medium gold color with a four finger fluffy white head that lasted awhile and left lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is overly fizzy , making an already light beer even fluffier . overall , this is an interesting beer that could be very refreshing if less carbonated .

smelled pretty good , hops & grain filled the nose immediately . after sitting for a moment , the smell faded slightly , but still nice . tasted some hops , but not nearly as dominant as i prefer .  bottle poured into a tulip glass . appearance-pale to medium gold , with a slight cast of haze , and a moderate white frothy head with decent retention .  neither was the taste - a bit bitter , no real aftertaste , with a weak , watery mouth feel .

the aroma is lacking . it is n't unpleasant , it 's just very weak . although the look and the smell were n't promising , bell 's lager proved to be a quality lager with a good bit of hops .  lacy rich foamy light tan lasting head . cloudy bright rich red ruby brown shade color . loose sediment dust .  not the worst tasting beer ever , but very thin and watery .
it smells quite fruity ( apples ) and a bit astringent .  appearance-dark golden color , nice white head that dissapears slowly .  mouthfeel was thin like water , very little body .

s- smell is sour , raspberries , slight peach .  but now , 2,500 miles from the source , and from it 's 25.4 oz oil can , i get the opportunity to try it again : poured into a stange , it 's golden color is attractive along with its well built head that does n't fizz .  m- spritzy , carbonation fills your mouth swelling your cheeks slightly . rough , bubbly and thin .

aroma is screaming butterscotch candy in my face . taste is not quite as bad as i thought it might be based on the aroma . this stuff is just way too sweet and butterscotchy .  pours black with brownish edges , feeble foam rises and leaves a thin ring at the edge of the glass .  2/5 m : thin and watery with medium carbonation .

good head s : roasty , fruity , over all not bad t : garbage .  served in a tulip . pours a light copper color with a single-finger white head and a bit of lacing as it slowly falls down my glass .  good for a lager , but way too much carbonation really throwing this beer off .

s : when i opened the bottle i thought i was about to eat an apple . really smells like you are about to drink apple juice , with a hint of alcohol t : to me it tastes just like an an apple beer should taste .  a pretty golden orange color in the glass but the fragrance was musty to me and actually unpleasant .  thin body looked nice in the glass , but was over carbonated . kind of a watery finish .

aromas of strong piney hops and roasted malts with hints of caramels and toffee , however the hops dominate the nose . i have had good , bad and average black ales .  ca n't really knock this beer for it 's appearance , it looks pretty good .  was excited to see this one.. but again newcastle has let me down again ... on the bottle it says `` blood red ale '' .. it pours a reddish-brown color.. smells a little funky ... way too carbonated for my liking .

aroma smelled strongly of fresh strawberries ; very nice .  it has good color , but beyond that that this ipa is not a pleasant one to drink .  really fizzy ( like coca-cola fizzy ) on the tongue , with a metallic finish , not really what i was hoping for , dissapointing .
